var P_HTM = [];
P_HTM[1]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa* **";
P_HTM[2]="*Saṃyuttanikāyo* **";
P_HTM[3]="*Khandhavaggo* **";
P_HTM[4]="*22. Khandhasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[5]="*sn/sn22.001.xhtml==1. Nakulapituvagga==1. Nakulapituvaggo**Nakula’s Father*";
P_HTM[6]="*1. Nakulapitusuttaṃ**Nakula’s Father*";
P_HTM[7]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[8]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā bhaggesu viharati susumāragire bhesakaḷāvane migadāye.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Bhaggas on Crocodile Hill, in the deer park at Bhesakaḷā’s Wood.*";
P_HTM[9]="*Atha kho nakulapitā gahapati yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho nakulapitā gahapati bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then the householder Nakula’s father went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[10]="*“Ahamasmi, bhante, jiṇṇo vuḍḍho mahallako addhagato vayoanuppatto āturakāyo abhikkhaṇātaṅko.**“Sir, I’m an old man, elderly and senior. I’m advanced in years and have reached the final stage of life. My body is ailing and I’m constantly unwell.*";
P_HTM[11]="*Aniccadassāvī kho panāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato manobhāvanīyānañca bhikkhūnaṃ.**I hardly ever get to see the esteemed mendicants.*";
P_HTM[12]="*Ovadatu maṃ, bhante, bhagavā;**May the Buddha please advise me,*";
P_HTM[13]="*anusāsatu maṃ, bhante, bhagavā;**and instruct me. It will be for my lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[14]="*yaṃ mamassa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[15]="*“Evametaṃ, gahapati, evametaṃ, gahapati.**“That’s so true, householder! That’s so true, householder!*";
P_HTM[16]="*Āturo hāyaṃ, gahapati, kāyo aṇḍabhūto pariyonaddho.**For this body is ailing, trapped in its shell.*";
P_HTM[17]="*Yo hi, gahapati, imaṃ kāyaṃ pariharanto muhuttampi ārogyaṃ paṭijāneyya, kimaññatra bālyā?**If anyone dragging around this body claimed to be healthy even for a minute, what’s that but foolishness?*";
P_HTM[18]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[19]="*‘āturakāyassa me sato cittaṃ anāturaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘Though my body is ailing, my mind will be healthy.’*";
P_HTM[20]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[21]="*Atha kho nakulapitā gahapati bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho nakulapitaraṃ gahapatiṃ āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**And then the householder Nakula’s father approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right. Then he went up to Venerable Sāriputta, bowed, and sat down to one side. Sāriputta said to him:*";
P_HTM[22]="*“vippasannāni kho te, gahapati, indriyāni;**“Householder, your faculties are so very clear,*";
P_HTM[23]="*parisuddho mukhavaṇṇo pariyodāto.**and your complexion is pure and bright.*";
P_HTM[24]="*Alattha no ajja bhagavato sammukhā dhammiṃ kathaṃ savanāyā”ti?**Did you get to hear a Dhamma talk in the Buddha’s presence today?”*";
P_HTM[25]="*“Kathañhi no siyā, bhante.**“What else, sir, could it possibly be?*";
P_HTM[26]="*Idānāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā dhammiyā kathāya amatena abhisitto”ti.**Just now the Buddha anointed me with the deathless ambrosia of a Dhamma talk.”*";
P_HTM[27]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, gahapati, bhagavatā dhammiyā kathāya amatena abhisitto”ti?**“But what kind of ambrosial Dhamma talk has the Buddha anointed you with?”*";
P_HTM[28]="*“Idhāhaṃ, bhante, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃ. Ekamantaṃ nisinno khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ etadavocaṃ:**So Nakula’s father told Sāriputta all that had happened, and said,*";
P_HTM[29]="*‘ahamasmi, bhante, jiṇṇo vuḍḍho mahallako addhagato vayoanuppatto āturakāyo abhikkhaṇātaṅko.* **";
P_HTM[30]="*Aniccadassāvī kho panāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato manobhāvanīyānañca bhikkhūnaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[31]="*Ovadatu maṃ, bhante, bhagavā;* **";
P_HTM[32]="*anusāsatu maṃ, bhante, bhagavā;* **";
P_HTM[33]="*yaṃ mamassa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[34]="*Evaṃ vutte, maṃ, bhante, bhagavā etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[35]="*‘evametaṃ, gahapati, evametaṃ, gahapati.* **";
P_HTM[36]="*Āturo hāyaṃ, gahapati, kāyo aṇḍabhūto pariyonaddho.* **";
P_HTM[37]="*Yo hi, gahapati, imaṃ kāyaṃ pariharanto muhuttampi ārogyaṃ paṭijāneyya, kimaññatra bālyā?* **";
P_HTM[38]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[39]="*āturakāyassa me sato cittaṃ anāturaṃ bhavissatīti.* **";
P_HTM[40]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabban’ti.* **";
P_HTM[41]="*Evaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā dhammiyā kathāya amatena abhisitto”ti.**“That’s the ambrosial Dhamma talk that the Buddha anointed me with.”*";
P_HTM[42]="*“Na hi pana taṃ, gahapati, paṭibhāsi bhagavantaṃ uttariṃ paṭipucchituṃ:**“But didn’t you feel the need to ask the Buddha the further question:*";
P_HTM[43]="*‘kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, āturakāyo ceva hoti āturacitto ca, kittāvatā ca pana āturakāyo hi kho hoti no ca āturacitto’”ti?**‘Sir, how do you define someone ailing in body and ailing in mind, and someone ailing in body and healthy in mind’?”*";
P_HTM[44]="*“Dūratopi kho mayaṃ, bhante, āgaccheyyāma āyasmato sāriputtassa santike etassa bhāsitassa atthamaññātuṃ.**“Sir, we would travel a long way to learn the meaning of this statement in the presence of Venerable Sāriputta.*";
P_HTM[45]="*Sādhu vatāyasmantaṃyeva sāriputtaṃ paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho”ti.**May Venerable Sāriputta himself please clarify the meaning of this.”*";
P_HTM[46]="*“Tena hi, gahapati, suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, householder, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[47]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho nakulapitā gahapati āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Nakula’s father.*";
P_HTM[48]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[49]="*“Kathañca, gahapati, āturakāyo ceva hoti, āturacitto ca?**“And how is a person ailing in body and ailing in mind?*";
P_HTM[50]="*Idha, gahapati, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the qualities of a noble one. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the qualities of a good person.*";
P_HTM[51]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[52]="*‘Ahaṃ rūpaṃ, mama rūpan’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re obsessed with the thought: ‘I am form, form is mine!’*";
P_HTM[53]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ rūpaṃ, mama rūpan’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**But that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[54]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[55]="*Vedanaṃ attato samanupassati, vedanāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā vedanaṃ, vedanāya vā attānaṃ.**They regard feeling as self, self as having feeling, feeling in self, or self in feeling.*";
P_HTM[56]="*‘Ahaṃ vedanā, mama vedanā’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re obsessed with the thought: ‘I am feeling, feeling is mine!’*";
P_HTM[57]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ vedanā, mama vedanā’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, sā vedanā vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**But that feeling of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[58]="*Tassa vedanāvipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[59]="*Saññaṃ attato samanupassati, saññāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā saññaṃ, saññāya vā attānaṃ.**They regard perception as self, self as having perception, perception in self, or self in perception.*";
P_HTM[60]="*‘Ahaṃ saññā, mama saññā’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re obsessed with the thought: ‘I am perception, perception is mine!’*";
P_HTM[61]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ saññā, mama saññā’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, sā saññā vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**But that perception of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[62]="*Tassa saññāvipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[63]="*Saṅkhāre attato samanupassati, saṅkhāravantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā saṅkhāre, saṅkhāresu vā attānaṃ.**They regard choices as self, self as having choices, choices in self, or self in choices.*";
P_HTM[64]="*‘Ahaṃ saṅkhārā, mama saṅkhārā’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re obsessed with the thought: ‘I am choices, choices are mine!’*";
P_HTM[65]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ saṅkhārā, mama saṅkhārā’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, te saṅkhārā vipariṇamanti aññathā honti.**But those choices of theirs decay and perish,*";
P_HTM[66]="*Tassa saṅkhāravipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[67]="*Viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[68]="*‘Ahaṃ viññāṇaṃ, mama viññāṇan’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re obsessed with the thought: ‘I am consciousness, consciousness is mine!’*";
P_HTM[69]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ viññāṇaṃ, mama viññāṇan’ti pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**But that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[70]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[71]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, āturakāyo ceva hoti āturacitto ca.**That’s how a person is ailing in body and ailing in mind.*";
P_HTM[72]="*Kathañca, gahapati, āturakāyo hi kho hoti no ca āturacitto?**And how is a person ailing in body and healthy in mind?*";
P_HTM[73]="*Idha, gahapati, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto**It’s when an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[74]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[75]="*‘Ahaṃ rūpaṃ, mama rūpan’ti na pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re not obsessed with the thought: ‘I am form, form is mine!’*";
P_HTM[76]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ rūpaṃ, mama rūpan’ti apariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**So when that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[77]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[78]="*Na vedanaṃ attato samanupassati, na vedanāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā vedanaṃ, na vedanāya vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard feeling as self, self as having feeling, feeling in self, or self in feeling.*";
P_HTM[79]="*‘Ahaṃ vedanā, mama vedanā’ti na pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re not obsessed with the thought: ‘I am feeling, feeling is mine!’*";
P_HTM[80]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ vedanā, mama vedanā’ti apariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, sā vedanā vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**So when that feeling of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[81]="*Tassa vedanāvipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[82]="*Na saññaṃ attato samanupassati, na saññāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā saññaṃ, na saññāya vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard perception as self, self as having perception, perception in self, or self in perception.*";
P_HTM[83]="*‘Ahaṃ saññā, mama saññā’ti na pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re not obsessed with the thought: ‘I am perception, perception is mine!’*";
P_HTM[84]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ saññā, mama saññā’ti apariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, sā saññā vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**So when that perception of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[85]="*Tassa saññāvipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[86]="*Na saṅkhāre attato samanupassati, na saṅkhāravantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā saṅkhāre, na saṅkhāresu vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard choices as self, self as having choices, choices in self, or self in choices.*";
P_HTM[87]="*‘Ahaṃ saṅkhārā, mama saṅkhārā’ti na pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re not obsessed with the thought: ‘I am choices, choices are mine!’*";
P_HTM[88]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ saṅkhārā, mama saṅkhārā’ti apariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, te saṅkhārā vipariṇamanti aññathā honti.**So when those choices of theirs decay and perish,*";
P_HTM[89]="*Tassa saṅkhāravipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[90]="*Na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā viññāṇaṃ, na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[91]="*‘Ahaṃ viññāṇaṃ, mama viññāṇan’ti na pariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyī hoti.**They’re not obsessed with the thought: ‘I am consciousness, consciousness is mine!’*";
P_HTM[92]="*Tassa ‘ahaṃ viññāṇaṃ, mama viññāṇan’ti apariyuṭṭhaṭṭhāyino, taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**So when that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[93]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[94]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, āturakāyo hoti no ca āturacitto”ti.**That’s how a person is ailing in body and healthy in mind.”*";
P_HTM[95]="*Idamavoca āyasmā sāriputto.**That’s what Venerable Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[96]="*Attamano nakulapitā gahapati āyasmato sāriputtassa bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Nakula’s father was happy with what Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[97]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[98]="*2. Devadahasuttaṃ**At Devadaha*";
P_HTM[99]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[100]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati devadahaṃ nāma sakyānaṃ nigamo.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, where they have a town named Devadaha.*";
P_HTM[101]="*Atha kho sambahulā pacchābhūmagamikā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants who were heading for the west went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[102]="*“icchāma mayaṃ, bhante, pacchābhūmaṃ janapadaṃ gantuṃ, pacchābhūme janapade nivāsaṃ kappetun”ti.**“Sir, we wish to go to a western land to take up residence there.”*";
P_HTM[103]="*“Apalokito pana vo, bhikkhave, sāriputto”ti?**“But mendicants, have you consulted with Sāriputta?”*";
P_HTM[104]="*“Na kho no, bhante, apalokito āyasmā sāriputto”ti.**“No, sir, we haven’t.”*";
P_HTM[105]="*“Apaloketha, bhikkhave, sāriputtaṃ.**“You should consult with Sāriputta.*";
P_HTM[106]="*Sāriputto, bhikkhave, paṇḍito, bhikkhūnaṃ anuggāhako sabrahmacārīnan”ti.**He’s astute, and supports his spiritual companions, the mendicants.”*";
P_HTM[107]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[108]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā sāriputto bhagavato avidūre aññatarasmiṃ eḷagalāgumbe nisinno hoti.**Now at that time Venerable Sāriputta was meditating not far from the Buddha in a clump of golden shower trees.*";
P_HTM[109]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā sāriputtena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**And then those mendicants approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. They got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right. Then they went up to Venerable Sāriputta, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[110]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side and said to him,*";
P_HTM[111]="*“icchāma mayaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, pacchābhūmaṃ janapadaṃ gantuṃ, pacchābhūme janapade nivāsaṃ kappetuṃ.**“Reverend Sāriputta, we wish to go to a western land to take up residence there.*";
P_HTM[112]="*Apalokito no satthā”ti.**We have consulted with the Teacher.”*";
P_HTM[113]="*“Santi hāvuso, nānāverajjagataṃ bhikkhuṃ pañhaṃ pucchitāro—**“Reverends, there are those who question a mendicant who has gone abroad—*";
P_HTM[114]="*khattiyapaṇḍitāpi brāhmaṇapaṇḍitāpi gahapatipaṇḍitāpi samaṇapaṇḍitāpi.**astute aristocrats, brahmins, householders, and ascetics—*";
P_HTM[115]="*Paṇḍitā hāvuso, manussā vīmaṃsakā:**for astute people are inquisitive:*";
P_HTM[116]="*‘kiṃvādī panāyasmantānaṃ satthā kimakkhāyī’ti, kacci vo āyasmantānaṃ dhammā sussutā suggahitā sumanasikatā sūpadhāritā suppaṭividdhā paññāya, yathā byākaramānā āyasmanto vuttavādino ceva bhagavato assatha, na ca bhagavantaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkheyyātha, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākareyyātha, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgaccheyyā”ti?**‘But what does the venerables’ Teacher teach? What does he explain?’ I trust the venerables have properly heard, learned, attended, and remembered the teachings, and penetrated them with wisdom. That way, when answering you will repeat what the Buddha has said and not misrepresent him with an untruth. You will explain in line with the teaching, with no legitimate grounds for rebuke and criticism.*";
P_HTM[117]="*“Dūratopi kho mayaṃ, āvuso, āgaccheyyāma āyasmato sāriputtassa santike etassa bhāsitassa atthamaññātuṃ.**“Reverend, we would travel a long way to learn the meaning of this statement in the presence of Venerable Sāriputta.*";
P_HTM[118]="*Sādhu vatāyasmantaṃyeva sāriputtaṃ paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho”ti.**May Venerable Sāriputta himself please clarify the meaning of this.”*";
P_HTM[119]="*“Tena hāvuso, suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, reverends, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[120]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[121]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[122]="*“Santi hāvuso, nānāverajjagataṃ bhikkhuṃ pañhaṃ pucchitāro—**“Reverends, there are those who question a mendicant who has gone abroad—*";
P_HTM[123]="*khattiyapaṇḍitāpi … pe … samaṇapaṇḍitāpi.**astute aristocrats, brahmins, householders, and ascetics—*";
P_HTM[124]="*Paṇḍitā hāvuso, manussā vīmaṃsakā:**for astute people are inquisitive:*";
P_HTM[125]="*‘kiṃvādī panāyasmantānaṃ satthā kimakkhāyī’ti?**‘But what does the venerables’ Teacher teach? What does he explain?’*";
P_HTM[126]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, āvuso, evaṃ byākareyyātha:**When questioned like this, reverends, you should answer:*";
P_HTM[127]="*‘chandarāgavinayakkhāyī kho no, āvuso, satthā’ti.**‘Reverend, our Teacher explained the removal of desire and lust.’*";
P_HTM[128]="*Evaṃ byākatepi kho, āvuso, assuyeva uttariṃ pañhaṃ pucchitāro—**When you answer like this, such astute people may inquire further:*";
P_HTM[129]="*khattiyapaṇḍitāpi … pe … samaṇapaṇḍitāpi.* **";
P_HTM[130]="*Paṇḍitā hāvuso, manussā vīmaṃsakā:* **";
P_HTM[131]="*‘kismiṃ panāyasmantānaṃ chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā’ti?**‘But regarding what does the venerables’ teacher explain the removal of desire and lust?’*";
P_HTM[132]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, āvuso, evaṃ byākareyyātha:**When questioned like this, reverends, you should answer:*";
P_HTM[133]="*‘rūpe kho, āvuso, chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā,**‘Our teacher explains the removal of desire and lust for form,*";
P_HTM[134]="*vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[135]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[136]="*saṅkhāresu …**choices,*";
P_HTM[137]="*viññāṇe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā’ti.**and consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[138]="*Evaṃ byākatepi kho, āvuso, assuyeva uttariṃ pañhaṃ pucchitāro—**When you answer like this, such astute people may inquire further:*";
P_HTM[139]="*khattiyapaṇḍitāpi … pe … samaṇapaṇḍitāpi.* **";
P_HTM[140]="*Paṇḍitā hāvuso, manussā vīmaṃsakā:* **";
P_HTM[141]="*‘kiṃ panāyasmantānaṃ ādīnavaṃ disvā rūpe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā,**‘But what drawback has he seen that he teaches the removal of desire and lust for form,*";
P_HTM[142]="*vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[143]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[144]="*saṅkhāresu …**choices,*";
P_HTM[145]="*viññāṇe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā’ti?**and consciousness?’*";
P_HTM[146]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, āvuso, evaṃ byākareyyātha:**When questioned like this, reverends, you should answer:*";
P_HTM[147]="*‘rūpe kho, āvuso, avigatarāgassa avigatacchandassa avigatapemassa avigatapipāsassa avigatapariḷāhassa avigatataṇhassa tassa rūpassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**‘If you’re not free of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for form, when that form decays and perishes it gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[148]="*Vedanāya …**If you’re not free of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for feeling …*";
P_HTM[149]="*saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[150]="*saṅkhāresu avigatarāgassa … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[151]="*avigatataṇhassa tesaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.* **";
P_HTM[152]="*Viññāṇe avigatarāgassa avigatacchandassa avigatapemassa avigatapipāsassa avigatapariḷāhassa avigatataṇhassa tassa viññāṇassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**consciousness, when that consciousness decays and perishes it gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[153]="*Idaṃ kho no, āvuso, ādīnavaṃ disvā rūpe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā,**This is the drawback our Teacher has seen that he teaches the removal of desire and lust for form,*";
P_HTM[154]="*vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[155]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[156]="*saṅkhāresu …**choices,*";
P_HTM[157]="*viññāṇe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā’ti.**and consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[158]="*Evaṃ byākatepi kho, āvuso, assuyeva uttariṃ pañhaṃ pucchitāro—**When you answer like this, such astute people may inquire further:*";
P_HTM[159]="*khattiyapaṇḍitāpi brāhmaṇapaṇḍitāpi gahapatipaṇḍitāpi samaṇapaṇḍitāpi.* **";
P_HTM[160]="*Paṇḍitā hāvuso, manussā vīmaṃsakā:* **";
P_HTM[161]="*‘kiṃ panāyasmantānaṃ ānisaṃsaṃ disvā rūpe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā,**‘But what benefit has he seen that he teaches the removal of desire and lust for form,*";
P_HTM[162]="*vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[163]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[164]="*saṅkhāresu …**choices,*";
P_HTM[165]="*viññāṇe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā’ti?**and consciousness?’*";
P_HTM[166]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, āvuso, evaṃ byākareyyātha:**When questioned like this, reverends, you should answer:*";
P_HTM[167]="*‘rūpe kho, āvuso, vigatarāgassa vigatacchandassa vigatapemassa vigatapipāsassa vigatapariḷāhassa vigatataṇhassa tassa rūpassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**‘If you are rid of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for form, when that form decays and perishes it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[168]="*Vedanāya …**If you are rid of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for feeling …*";
P_HTM[169]="*saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[170]="*saṅkhāresu vigatarāgassa vigatacchandassa vigatapemassa vigatapipāsassa vigatapariḷāhassa vigatataṇhassa tesaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**choices …*";
P_HTM[171]="*Viññāṇe vigatarāgassa vigatacchandassa vigatapemassa vigatapipāsassa vigatapariḷāhassa vigatataṇhassa tassa viññāṇassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**consciousness, when that consciousness decays and perishes it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[172]="*Idaṃ kho no, āvuso, ānisaṃsaṃ disvā rūpe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā, vedanāya …**This is the benefit our Teacher has seen that he teaches the removal of desire and lust for form, feeling,*";
P_HTM[173]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[174]="*saṅkhāresu …**choices,*";
P_HTM[175]="*viññāṇe chandarāgavinayakkhāyī satthā’ti.**and consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[176]="*Akusale cāvuso, dhamme upasampajja viharato diṭṭhe ceva dhamme sukho vihāro abhavissa avighāto anupāyāso apariḷāho, kāyassa ca bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugati pāṭikaṅkhā, nayidaṃ bhagavā akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānaṃ vaṇṇeyya.**If those who acquired and kept unskillful qualities were to live happily in the present life, free of anguish, distress, and fever; and if, when their body breaks up, after death, they could expect to go to a good place, the Buddha would not praise giving up unskillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[177]="*Yasmā ca kho, āvuso, akusale dhamme upasampajja viharato diṭṭhe ceva dhamme dukkho vihāro savighāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho, kāyassa ca bhedā paraṃ maraṇā duggati pāṭikaṅkhā, tasmā bhagavā akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānaṃ vaṇṇeti.**But since those who acquire and keep unskillful qualities live unhappily in the present life, full of anguish, distress, and fever; and since, when their body breaks up, after death, they can expect to go to a bad place, the Buddha praises giving up unskillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[178]="*Kusale cāvuso, dhamme upasampajja viharato diṭṭhe ceva dhamme dukkho vihāro abhavissa savighāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho, kāyassa ca bhedā paraṃ maraṇā duggati pāṭikaṅkhā, nayidaṃ bhagavā kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadaṃ vaṇṇeyya.**If those who embraced and kept skillful qualities were to live unhappily in the present life, full of anguish, distress, and fever; and if, when their body breaks up, after death, they could expect to go to a bad place, the Buddha would not praise embracing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[179]="*Yasmā ca kho, āvuso, kusale dhamme upasampajja viharato diṭṭhe ceva dhamme sukho vihāro avighāto anupāyāso apariḷāho, kāyassa ca bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugati pāṭikaṅkhā, tasmā bhagavā kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadaṃ vaṇṇetī”ti.**But since those who embrace and keep skillful qualities live happily in the present life, free of anguish, distress, and fever; and since, when their body breaks up, after death, they can expect to go to a good place, the Buddha praises embracing skillful qualities.”*";
P_HTM[180]="*Idamavocāyasmā sāriputto.**This is what Venerable Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[181]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[182]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[183]="*3. Hāliddikānisuttaṃ**With Hāliddikāni*";
P_HTM[184]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[185]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā mahākaccāno avantīsu viharati kuraraghare papāte pabbate.**At one time Venerable Mahākaccāna was staying in the land of the Avantis near Kuraraghara on Steep Mountain.*";
P_HTM[186]="*Atha kho hāliddikāni gahapati yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho hāliddikāni gahapati āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etadavoca:**Then the householder Hāliddikāni went up to Venerable Mahākaccāna, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[187]="*“vuttamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā aṭṭhakavaggiye māgaṇḍiyapañhe:**“Sir, this was said by the Buddha in the Chapter of the Eights, in ‘The Questions of Māgandiya’:*";
P_HTM[188]="*‘Okaṃ pahāya aniketasārī,**‘After leaving shelter to become an unsettled migrant,*";
P_HTM[189]="*Gāme akubbaṃ muni santhavāni;**a sage doesn’t get close to anyone in town.*";
P_HTM[190]="*Kāmehi ritto apurakkharāno,**Rid of sensual pleasures, expecting nothing,*";
P_HTM[191]="*Kathaṃ na viggayha janena kayirā’ti.**they don’t argue with anyone.’*";
P_HTM[192]="*Imassa nu kho, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa kathaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti?**How should we see the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[193]="*“Rūpadhātu kho, gahapati, viññāṇassa oko.**“Householder, the form element is a shelter for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[194]="*Rūpadhāturāgavinibandhañca pana viññāṇaṃ ‘okasārī’ti vuccati.**One whose consciousness is shackled to greed for the form element is called a migrant going from shelter to shelter.*";
P_HTM[195]="*Vedanādhātu kho, gahapati, viññāṇassa oko.**The feeling element is a shelter for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[196]="*Vedanādhāturāgavinibandhañca pana viññāṇaṃ ‘okasārī’ti vuccati.**One whose consciousness is attached to greed for the feeling element is called a migrant going from shelter to shelter.*";
P_HTM[197]="*Saññādhātu kho, gahapati, viññāṇassa oko.**The perception element is a shelter for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[198]="*Saññādhāturāgavinibandhañca pana viññāṇaṃ ‘okasārī’ti vuccati.**One whose consciousness is attached to greed for the perception element is called a migrant going from shelter to shelter.*";
P_HTM[199]="*Saṅkhāradhātu kho, gahapati, viññāṇassa oko.**The choices element is a shelter for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[200]="*Saṅkhāradhāturāgavinibandhañca pana viññāṇaṃ ‘okasārī’ti vuccati.**One whose consciousness is attached to greed for the choices element is called a migrant going from shelter to shelter.*";
P_HTM[201]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, okasārī hoti.**That’s how one is a migrant going from shelter to shelter.*";
P_HTM[202]="*Kathañca, gahapati, anokasārī hoti?**And how is one a migrant without a shelter?*";
P_HTM[203]="*Rūpadhātuyā kho, gahapati, yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā ye upayupādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā te tathāgatassa pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṃkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**The Realized One has given up any desire, greed, relishing, and craving for the form element; any attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendencies. He has cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[204]="*Tasmā tathāgato ‘anokasārī’ti vuccati.**That’s why the Realized One is called a migrant without a shelter.*";
P_HTM[205]="*Vedanādhātuyā kho, gahapati …**The Realized One has given up any desire, greed, relishing, and craving for the feeling element …*";
P_HTM[206]="*saññādhātuyā kho, gahapati …**the perception element …*";
P_HTM[207]="*saṅkhāradhātuyā kho, gahapati …**the choices element …*";
P_HTM[208]="*viññāṇadhātuyā kho, gahapati, yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā ye upayupādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā te tathāgatassa pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṃkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**the consciousness element; any attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendencies. He has cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[209]="*Tasmā tathāgato ‘anokasārī’ti vuccati.**That’s why the Realized One is called a migrant without a shelter.*";
P_HTM[210]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, anokasārī hoti.**That’s how one is a migrant without a shelter.*";
P_HTM[211]="*Kathañca, gahapati, niketasārī hoti?**And how is one a migrant going from settlement to settlement?*";
P_HTM[212]="*Rūpanimittaniketavisāravinibandhā kho, gahapati, ‘niketasārī’ti vuccati.**Being attached to migrating from settlement to settlement in pursuit of sights, one is called a migrant going from settlement to settlement.*";
P_HTM[213]="*Saddanimitta … pe …**Being attached to migrating from settlement to settlement in pursuit of sounds …*";
P_HTM[214]="*gandhanimitta …**smells …*";
P_HTM[215]="*rasanimitta …**tastes …*";
P_HTM[216]="*phoṭṭhabbanimitta …**touches …*";
P_HTM[217]="*dhammanimittaniketavisāravinibandhā kho, gahapati, ‘niketasārī’ti vuccati.**thoughts, one is called a migrant going from settlement to settlement.*";
P_HTM[218]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, niketasārī hoti.**That’s how one is a migrant going from settlement to settlement.*";
P_HTM[219]="*Kathañca, gahapati, aniketasārī hoti?**And how is one an unsettled migrant?*";
P_HTM[220]="*Rūpanimittaniketavisāravinibandhā kho, gahapati, tathāgatassa pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**The Realized One has given up attachment to migrating from settlement to settlement in pursuit of sights. He has cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[221]="*Tasmā tathāgato ‘aniketasārī’ti vuccati.**That’s why the Realized One is called an unsettled migrant.*";
P_HTM[222]="*Saddanimitta …**The Realized One has given up attachment to migrating from settlement to settlement in pursuit of sounds …*";
P_HTM[223]="*gandhanimitta …**smells …*";
P_HTM[224]="*rasanimitta …**tastes …*";
P_HTM[225]="*phoṭṭhabbanimitta …**touches …*";
P_HTM[226]="*dhammanimittaniketavisāravinibandhā kho, gahapati, tathāgatassa pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**thoughts. He has cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[227]="*Tasmā tathāgato ‘aniketasārī’ti vuccati.**That’s why the Realized One is called an unsettled migrant.*";
P_HTM[228]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, aniketasārī hoti.**That’s how one is an unsettled migrant.*";
P_HTM[229]="*Kathañca, gahapati, gāme santhavajāto hoti?**And how does one get close to people in town?*";
P_HTM[230]="*Idha, gahapati, ekacco gihīhi saṃsaṭṭho viharati sahanandī sahasokī, sukhitesu sukhito, dukkhitesu dukkhito, uppannesu kiccakaraṇīyesu attanā tesu yogaṃ āpajjati.**It’s when someone mixes closely with laypeople, sharing their joys and sorrows—happy when they’re happy and sad when they’re sad—and getting involved in their business.*";
P_HTM[231]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, gāme santhavajāto hoti.**That’s how one gets close to people in town.*";
P_HTM[232]="*Kathañca, gahapati, gāme na santhavajāto hoti?**And how does one not get close to people in town?*";
P_HTM[233]="*Idha, gahapati, bhikkhu gihīhi asaṃsaṭṭho viharati na sahanandī na sahasokī na sukhitesu sukhito na dukkhitesu dukkhito, uppannesu kiccakaraṇīyesu na attanā tesu yogaṃ āpajjati.**It’s when a mendicant doesn’t mix closely with laypeople, not sharing their joys and sorrows—not happy when they’re happy or sad when they’re sad—and not getting involved in their business.*";
P_HTM[234]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, gāme na santhavajāto hoti.**That’s how one doesn’t get close to people in town.*";
P_HTM[235]="*Kathañca, gahapati, kāmehi aritto hoti?**And how is one not rid of sensual pleasures?*";
P_HTM[236]="*Idha, gahapati, ekacco kāmesu avigatarāgo hoti avigatacchando avigatapemo avigatapipāso avigatapariḷāho avigatataṇho.**It’s when someone isn’t rid of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[237]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, kāmehi aritto hoti.**That’s how one is not rid of sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[238]="*Kathañca, gahapati, kāmehi ritto hoti?**And how is one rid of sensual pleasures?*";
P_HTM[239]="*Idha, gahapati, ekacco kāmesu vigatarāgo hoti vigatacchando vigatapemo vigatapipāso vigatapariḷāho vigatataṇho.**It’s when someone is rid of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[240]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, kāmehi ritto hoti.**That’s how one is rid of sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[241]="*Kathañca, gahapati, purakkharāno hoti?**And how does one have expectations?*";
P_HTM[242]="*Idha, gahapati, ekaccassa evaṃ hoti:**It’s when someone thinks:*";
P_HTM[243]="*‘evaṃrūpo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃvedano siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃsañño siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃsaṅkhāro siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃviññāṇo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānan’ti.**‘In the future, may I be of such form, such feeling, such perception, such choices, and such consciousness!’*";
P_HTM[244]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, purakkharāno hoti.**That’s how one has expectations.*";
P_HTM[245]="*Kathañca, gahapati, apurakkharāno hoti?**And how does one expect nothing?*";
P_HTM[246]="*Idha, gahapati, ekaccassa na evaṃ hoti:**It’s when someone doesn’t think:*";
P_HTM[247]="*‘evaṃrūpo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃvedano siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃsañño siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃsaṅkhāro siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃviññāṇo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānan’ti.**‘In the future, may I be of such form, such feeling, such perception, such choices, and such consciousness!’*";
P_HTM[248]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, apurakkharāno hoti.**That’s how one expects nothing.*";
P_HTM[249]="*Kathañca, gahapati, kathaṃ viggayha janena kattā hoti?**And how does one argue with people?*";
P_HTM[250]="*Idha, gahapati, ekacco evarūpiṃ kathaṃ kattā hoti:**It’s when someone takes part in this sort of discussion:*";
P_HTM[251]="*‘na tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāsi; ahaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāmi. Kiṃ tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānissasi? Micchāpaṭipanno tvamasi; ahamasmi sammāpaṭipanno. Pure vacanīyaṃ pacchā avaca; pacchā vacanīyaṃ pure avaca. Sahitaṃ me, asahitaṃ te. Adhiciṇṇaṃ te viparāvattaṃ. Āropito te vādo; cara vādappamokkhāya. Niggahitosi; nibbeṭhehi vā sace pahosī’ti.**‘You don’t understand this teaching and training. I understand this teaching and training. What, you understand this teaching and training? You’re practicing wrong. I’m practicing right. You said last what you should have said first. You said first what you should have said last. I stay on topic, you don’t. What you’ve thought so much about has been disproved. Your doctrine is refuted. Go on, save your doctrine! You’re trapped; get yourself out of this—if you can!’*";
P_HTM[252]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, kathaṃ viggayha janena kattā hoti.**That’s how one argues with people.*";
P_HTM[253]="*Kathañca, gahapati, kathaṃ na viggayha janena kattā hoti?**And how does one not argue with people?*";
P_HTM[254]="*Idha, gahapati, bhikkhu na evarūpiṃ kathaṃ kattā hoti:**It’s when a mendicant doesn’t take part in this sort of discussion:*";
P_HTM[255]="*‘na tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāsi … pe … nibbeṭhehi vā sace pahosī’ti.**‘You don’t understand this teaching and training … get yourself out of this—if you can!’*";
P_HTM[256]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, kathaṃ na viggayha janena kattā hoti.**That’s how one doesn’t argue with people.*";
P_HTM[257]="*Iti kho, gahapati, yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā aṭṭhakavaggiye māgaṇḍiyapañhe:**So, householder, that’s how to understand the detailed meaning of what the Buddha said in brief in the Chapter of the Eights, in ‘The Questions of Māgandiya’:*";
P_HTM[258]="*‘Okaṃ pahāya aniketasārī,**‘After leaving shelter to become an unsettled migrant,*";
P_HTM[259]="*Gāme akubbaṃ munisanthavāni;**a sage doesn’t get close to anyone in town.*";
P_HTM[260]="*Kāmehi ritto apurakkharāno,**Rid of sensual pleasures, expecting nothing,*";
P_HTM[261]="*Kathaṃ na viggayha janena kayirā’ti.**they don’t argue with anyone.’”*";
P_HTM[262]="*Imassa kho, gahapati, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[263]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[264]="*4. Dutiyahāliddikānisuttaṃ**Hāliddikāni (2nd)*";
P_HTM[265]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[266]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā mahākaccāno avantīsu viharati kuraraghare papāte pabbate.**At one time Venerable Mahākaccāna was staying in the land of the Avantis near Kuraraghara on Steep Mountain.*";
P_HTM[267]="*Atha kho hāliddikāni gahapati yenāyasmā mahākaccāno … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho hāliddikāni gahapati āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etadavoca:**Then the householder Hāliddikāni went up to Venerable Mahākaccāna … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[268]="*“vuttamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā sakkapañhe:**“Sir, this was said by the Buddha in ‘The Questions of Sakka’:*";
P_HTM[269]="*‘ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā taṇhāsaṅkhayavimuttā, te accantaniṭṭhā accantayogakkhemino accantabrahmacārino accantapariyosānā seṭṭhā devamanussānan’ti.**‘Those ascetics and brahmins who are freed due to the ending of craving have reached the ultimate goal, the ultimate sanctuary, the ultimate spiritual life, the ultimate end, and are best among gods and humans.’*";
P_HTM[270]="*Imassa nu kho, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa kathaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti?**How should we see the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[271]="*“Rūpadhātuyā kho, gahapati, yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā ye upayupādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā, tesaṃ khayā virāgā nirodhā cāgā paṭinissaggā ‘cittaṃ suvimuttanti’ vuccati.**“Householder, consider any desire, greed, relishing, and craving for the form element; any attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendencies. With the ending, fading away, cessation, giving away, and letting go of that, the mind is said to be ‘well freed’.*";
P_HTM[272]="*Vedanādhātuyā kho, gahapati …**Consider any desire, greed, relishing, and craving for the feeling element …*";
P_HTM[273]="*saññādhātuyā kho, gahapati …**the perception element …*";
P_HTM[274]="*saṅkhāradhātuyā kho, gahapati …**the choices element …*";
P_HTM[275]="*viññāṇadhātuyā kho, gahapati, yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā ye upayupādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā, tesaṃ khayā virāgā nirodhā cāgā paṭinissaggā ‘cittaṃ suvimuttanti’ vuccati.**the consciousness element; any attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendencies. With the ending, fading away, cessation, giving away, and letting go of that, the mind is said to be ‘well freed’.*";
P_HTM[276]="*Iti kho, gahapati, yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā sakkapañhe:**So, householder, that’s how to understand the detailed meaning of what the Buddha said in brief in ‘The Questions of Sakka’:*";
P_HTM[277]="*‘ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā taṇhāsaṅkhayavimuttā te accantaniṭṭhā accantayogakkhemino accantabrahmacārino accantapariyosānā seṭṭhā devamanussānan’ti.**‘Those ascetics and brahmins who are freed due to the ending of craving have reached the ultimate goal, the ultimate sanctuary, the ultimate spiritual life, the ultimate end, and are best among gods and humans.’”*";
P_HTM[278]="*Imassa kho, gahapati, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[279]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[280]="*5. Samādhisuttaṃ**Development of Immersion*";
P_HTM[281]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[282]="*… pe … sāvatthiyaṃ …**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[283]="*tatra kho … pe … etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[284]="*“samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha;**“Mendicants, develop immersion.*";
P_HTM[285]="*samāhito, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A mendicant who has immersion truly understands.*";
P_HTM[286]="*Kiñca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti?**What do they truly understand?*";
P_HTM[287]="*Rūpassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca, vedanāya samudayañca atthaṅgamañca, saññāya samudayañca atthaṅgamañca, saṅkhārānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca, viññāṇassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca.**The origin and ending of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[288]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, rūpassa samudayo, ko vedanāya samudayo, ko saññāya samudayo, ko saṅkhārānaṃ samudayo, ko viññāṇassa samudayo?**And what is the origin of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness?*";
P_HTM[289]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**It’s when a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging.*";
P_HTM[290]="*Kiñca abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati?**What do they approve, welcome, and keep clinging to?*";
P_HTM[291]="*Rūpaṃ abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**They approve, welcome, and keep clinging to form.*";
P_HTM[292]="*Tassa rūpaṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**This gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[293]="*Yā rūpe nandī tadupādānaṃ.**Relishing forms is grasping.*";
P_HTM[294]="*Tassupādānapaccayā bhavo;**Their grasping is a condition for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[295]="*bhavapaccayā jāti;**Continued existence is a condition for rebirth.*";
P_HTM[296]="*jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā sambhavanti.**Rebirth is a condition that gives rise to old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[297]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa samudayo hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering originates.*";
P_HTM[298]="*Vedanaṃ abhinandati … pe …**They approve, welcome, and keep clinging to feeling …*";
P_HTM[299]="*saññaṃ abhinandati …**perception …*";
P_HTM[300]="*saṅkhāre abhinandati …**choices …*";
P_HTM[301]="*viññāṇaṃ abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**consciousness.*";
P_HTM[302]="*Tassa viññāṇaṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**This gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[303]="*Yā viññāṇe nandī tadupādānaṃ.**Relishing consciousness is grasping.*";
P_HTM[304]="*Tassupādānapaccayā bhavo;**Their grasping is a condition for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[305]="*bhavapaccayā jāti;**Continued existence is a condition for rebirth.*";
P_HTM[306]="*jātipaccayā … pe …**Rebirth is a condition that gives rise to old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[307]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa samudayo hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering originates.*";
P_HTM[308]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpassa samudayo;**This is the origin of form,*";
P_HTM[309]="*ayaṃ vedanāya samudayo;**feeling,*";
P_HTM[310]="*ayaṃ saññāya samudayo;**perception,*";
P_HTM[311]="*ayaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ samudayo;**choices,*";
P_HTM[312]="*ayaṃ viññāṇassa samudayo.**and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[313]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, rūpassa atthaṅgamo, ko vedanāya …**And what is the ending of form, feeling,*";
P_HTM[314]="*ko saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[315]="*ko saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices,*";
P_HTM[316]="*ko viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo?**and consciousness?*";
P_HTM[317]="*Idha, bhikkhave, nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**It’s when a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, or keep clinging.*";
P_HTM[318]="*Kiñca nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati?**What don’t they approve, welcome, or keep clinging to?*";
P_HTM[319]="*Rūpaṃ nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**They don’t approve, welcome, or keep clinging to form.*";
P_HTM[320]="*Tassa rūpaṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato yā rūpe nandī sā nirujjhati.**As a result, relishing of form ceases.*";
P_HTM[321]="*Tassa nandīnirodhā upādānanirodho;**When that relishing ceases, grasping ceases.*";
P_HTM[322]="*upādānanirodhā bhavanirodho … pe …**When grasping ceases, continued existence ceases. …*";
P_HTM[323]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering ceases.*";
P_HTM[324]="*Vedanaṃ nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**They don’t approve, welcome, or keep clinging to feeling …*";
P_HTM[325]="*Tassa vedanaṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato yā vedanāya nandī sā nirujjhati.* **";
P_HTM[326]="*Tassa nandīnirodhā upādānanirodho;* **";
P_HTM[327]="*upādānanirodhā bhavanirodho … pe …* **";
P_HTM[328]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[329]="*Saññaṃ nābhinandati … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[330]="*saṅkhāre nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**choices …*";
P_HTM[331]="*Tassa saṅkhāre anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato yā saṅkhāresu nandī sā nirujjhati.* **";
P_HTM[332]="*Tassa nandīnirodhā upādānanirodho;* **";
P_HTM[333]="*upādānanirodhā bhavanirodho … pe …* **";
P_HTM[334]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[335]="*Viññāṇaṃ nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**consciousness.*";
P_HTM[336]="*Tassa viññāṇaṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato yā viññāṇe nandī sā nirujjhati.**As a result, relishing of consciousness ceases.*";
P_HTM[337]="*Tassa nandīnirodhā upādānanirodho … pe …**When that relishing ceases, grasping ceases. …*";
P_HTM[338]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering ceases.*";
P_HTM[339]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpassa atthaṅgamo, ayaṃ vedanāya atthaṅgamo, ayaṃ saññāya atthaṅgamo, ayaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ atthaṅgamo, ayaṃ viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo”ti.**This is the ending of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.”*";
P_HTM[340]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[341]="*6. Paṭisallāṇasuttaṃ**Retreat*";
P_HTM[342]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[343]="*“Paṭisallāṇe, bhikkhave, yogamāpajjatha.**“Mendicants, meditate in retreat.*";
P_HTM[344]="*Paṭisallīṇo, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A mendicant in retreat truly understands.*";
P_HTM[345]="*Kiñca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti?**What do they truly understand?*";
P_HTM[346]="*Rūpassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca, vedanāya samudayañca atthaṅgamañca, saññāya samudayañca atthaṅgamañca, saṅkhārānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca, viññāṇassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca … pe …**The origin and ending of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness. …”*";
P_HTM[347]="*(yathā paṭhamasutte tathā vitthāretabbo.)**(Expand in detail as in the previous discourse.)*";
P_HTM[348]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[349]="*7. Upādāparitassanāsuttaṃ**Anxiety Because of Grasping*";
P_HTM[350]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[351]="*“Upādāparitassanañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi anupādāaparitassanañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you how grasping leads to anxiety, and how not grasping leads to freedom from anxiety.*";
P_HTM[352]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[353]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti, kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[354]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[355]="*“Kathañca, bhikkhave, upādāparitassanā hoti?**“And how does grasping lead to anxiety?*";
P_HTM[356]="*Idha, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[357]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[358]="*Tassa taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**But that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[359]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā rūpavipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.**and consciousness latches on to the perishing of form.*";
P_HTM[360]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmānuparivattijā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.**Anxieties occupy their mind, born of latching on to the perishing of form, and originating in accordance with natural principles.*";
P_HTM[361]="*Cetaso pariyādānā uttāsavā ca hoti vighātavā ca apekkhavā ca upādāya ca paritassati.**So they become frightened, worried, concerned, and anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[362]="*Vedanaṃ attato samanupassati, vedanāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā vedanaṃ, vedanāya vā attānaṃ.**They regard feeling as self …*";
P_HTM[363]="*Tassa sā vedanā vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[364]="*Tassa vedanāvipariṇāmaññathābhāvā vedanāvipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[365]="*Tassa vedanāvipariṇāmānuparivattijā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.* **";
P_HTM[366]="*Cetaso pariyādānā uttāsavā ca hoti vighātavā ca apekkhavā ca upādāya ca paritassati.* **";
P_HTM[367]="*Saññaṃ attato samanupassati … pe …**They regard perception as self …*";
P_HTM[368]="*saṅkhāre attato samanupassati, saṅkhāravantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā saṅkhāre, saṅkhāresu vā attānaṃ.**They regard choices as self …*";
P_HTM[369]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā vipariṇamanti aññathā honti.* **";
P_HTM[370]="*Tassa saṅkhāravipariṇāmaññathābhāvā saṅkhāravipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[371]="*Tassa saṅkhāravipariṇāmānuparivattijā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.* **";
P_HTM[372]="*Cetaso pariyādānā uttāsavā ca hoti vighātavā ca apekkhavā ca upādāya ca paritassati.* **";
P_HTM[373]="*Viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[374]="*Tassa taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**But that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[375]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā viññāṇavipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.**and consciousness latches on to the perishing of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[376]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmānuparivattijā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.**Anxieties occupy their mind, born of latching on to the perishing of consciousness, and originating in accordance with natural principles.*";
P_HTM[377]="*Cetaso pariyādānā uttāsavā ca hoti vighātavā ca apekkhavā ca upādāya ca paritassati.**So they become frightened, worried, concerned, and anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[378]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, upādāparitassanā hoti.**That’s how grasping leads to anxiety.*";
P_HTM[379]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, anupādāaparitassanā hoti?**And how does not grasping lead to freedom from anxiety?*";
P_HTM[380]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto, sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto**It’s when an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[381]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[382]="*Tassa taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**When that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[383]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā na rūpavipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.**consciousness doesn’t latch on to the perishing of form.*";
P_HTM[384]="*Tassa na rūpavipariṇāmānuparivattijā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.**Anxieties—born of latching on to the perishing of form and originating in accordance with natural principles—don’t occupy their mind.*";
P_HTM[385]="*Cetaso apariyādānā na cevuttāsavā hoti na ca vighātavā na ca apekkhavā, anupādāya ca na paritassati.**So they don’t become frightened, worried, concerned, or anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[386]="*Na vedanaṃ attato samanupassati, na vedanāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā vedanaṃ, na vedanāya vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard feeling as self …*";
P_HTM[387]="*Tassa sā vedanā vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[388]="*Tassa vedanāvipariṇāmaññathābhāvā na vedanāvipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[389]="*Tassa na vedanāvipariṇāmānuparivattijā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.* **";
P_HTM[390]="*Cetaso apariyādānā na cevuttāsavā hoti na ca vighātavā na ca apekkhavā, anupādāya ca na paritassati.* **";
P_HTM[391]="*Na saññaṃ … pe … na saṅkhāre attato samanupassati,**They don’t regard perception as self …*";
P_HTM[392]="*na attani vā saṅkhāre, na saṅkhāresu vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard choices as self …*";
P_HTM[393]="*na saṅkhāravantaṃ vā attānaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[394]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā vipariṇamanti aññathā honti.* **";
P_HTM[395]="*Tassa saṅkhāravipariṇāmaññathābhāvā na saṅkhāravipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[396]="*Tassa na saṅkhāravipariṇāmānuparivattijā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.* **";
P_HTM[397]="*Cetaso apariyādānā na cevuttāsavā hoti na ca vighātavā na ca apekkhavā, anupādāya ca na paritassati.* **";
P_HTM[398]="*Na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ … pe …**They don’t regard consciousness as self …*";
P_HTM[399]="*tassa taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**When that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[400]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā na viññāṇavipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.**consciousness doesn’t latch on to the perishing of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[401]="*Tassa na viññāṇavipariṇāmānuparivattijā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.**Anxieties—born of latching on to the perishing of consciousness and originating in accordance with natural principles—don’t occupy their mind.*";
P_HTM[402]="*Cetaso apariyādānā na cevuttāsavā hoti na ca vighātavā na ca apekkhavā, anupādāya ca na paritassati.**So they don’t become frightened, worried, concerned, or anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[403]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, anupādā aparitassanaṃ hotī”ti.**That’s how not grasping leads to freedom from anxiety.”*";
P_HTM[404]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[405]="*8. Dutiyaupādāparitassanāsuttaṃ**Anxiety Because of Grasping (2nd)*";
P_HTM[406]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[407]="*“Upādāparitassanañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi anupādāaparitassanañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you how grasping leads to anxiety, and how not grasping leads to freedom from anxiety.*";
P_HTM[408]="*Taṃ suṇātha … pe …**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.*";
P_HTM[409]="*kathañca, bhikkhave, upādāparitassanā hoti?**And how does grasping lead to anxiety?*";
P_HTM[410]="*Idha, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano rūpaṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassati.**It’s when an uneducated ordinary person regards form like this: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self.’*";
P_HTM[411]="*Tassa taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**But that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[412]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[413]="*Vedanaṃ etaṃ mama … pe …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[414]="*saññaṃ etaṃ mama …**perception …*";
P_HTM[415]="*saṅkhāre etaṃ mama …**choices …*";
P_HTM[416]="*viññāṇaṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassati.**consciousness like this: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self.’*";
P_HTM[417]="*Tassa taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**But that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[418]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[419]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, upādāparitassanā hoti.**That’s how grasping leads to anxiety.*";
P_HTM[420]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, anupādāaparitassanā hoti?**And how does not grasping lead to freedom from anxiety?*";
P_HTM[421]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassati.**It’s when an educated noble disciple regards form like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[422]="*Tassa taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**When that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[423]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[424]="*Vedanaṃ netaṃ mama …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[425]="*saññaṃ netaṃ mama …**perception …*";
P_HTM[426]="*saṅkhāre netaṃ mama …**choices …*";
P_HTM[427]="*viññāṇaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassati.**consciousness like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[428]="*Tassa taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati aññathā hoti.**When that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[429]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā nuppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**it doesn’t give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[430]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, anupādāaparitassanā hotī”ti.**That’s how not grasping leads to freedom from anxiety.”*";
P_HTM[431]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[432]="*9. Kālattayaaniccasuttaṃ**Impermanence in the Three Times*";
P_HTM[433]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[434]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ atītānāgataṃ;**“Mendicants, form of the past and future is impermanent,*";
P_HTM[435]="*ko pana vādo paccuppannassa.**let alone the present.*";
P_HTM[436]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako atītasmiṃ rūpasmiṃ anapekkho hoti;**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple doesn’t worry about past form,*";
P_HTM[437]="*anāgataṃ rūpaṃ nābhinandati;**doesn’t look forward to enjoying future form,*";
P_HTM[438]="*paccuppannassa rūpassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.**and they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present form.*";
P_HTM[439]="*Vedanā aniccā … pe …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[440]="*saññā aniccā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[441]="*saṅkhārā aniccā atītānāgatā;**Choices …*";
P_HTM[442]="*ko pana vādo paccuppannānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[443]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako atītesu saṅkhāresu anapekkho hoti;* **";
P_HTM[444]="*anāgate saṅkhāre nābhinandati;* **";
P_HTM[445]="*paccuppannānaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.* **";
P_HTM[446]="*Viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ atītānāgataṃ;**Consciousness of the past and future is impermanent,*";
P_HTM[447]="*ko pana vādo paccuppannassa.**let alone the present.*";
P_HTM[448]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako atītasmiṃ viññāṇasmiṃ anapekkho hoti;**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple doesn’t worry about past consciousness,*";
P_HTM[449]="*anāgataṃ viññāṇaṃ nābhinandati;**doesn’t look forward to enjoying future consciousness,*";
P_HTM[450]="*paccuppannassa viññāṇassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hotī”ti.**and they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present consciousness.”*";
P_HTM[451]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[452]="*10. Kālattayadukkhasuttaṃ**Suffering in the Three Times*";
P_HTM[453]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[454]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ atītānāgataṃ;**“Mendicants, form of the past and future is suffering,*";
P_HTM[455]="*ko pana vādo paccuppannassa.**not to mention the present.*";
P_HTM[456]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako atītasmiṃ rūpasmiṃ anapekkho hoti;**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple doesn’t worry about past form,*";
P_HTM[457]="*anāgataṃ rūpaṃ nābhinandati;**doesn’t look forward to enjoying future form,*";
P_HTM[458]="*paccuppannassa rūpassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.**and they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present form.*";
P_HTM[459]="*Vedanā dukkhā …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[460]="*saññā dukkhā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[461]="*saṅkhārā dukkhā …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[462]="*viññāṇaṃ dukkhaṃ atītānāgataṃ;**Consciousness of the past and future is suffering,*";
P_HTM[463]="*ko pana vādo paccuppannassa.**let alone the present.*";
P_HTM[464]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako atītasmiṃ viññāṇasmiṃ anapekkho hoti;**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple doesn’t worry about past consciousness,*";
P_HTM[465]="*anāgataṃ viññāṇaṃ nābhinandati;**doesn’t look forward to enjoying future consciousness,*";
P_HTM[466]="*paccuppannassa viññāṇassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hotī”ti.**and they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present consciousness.”*";
P_HTM[467]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[468]="*11. Kālattayaanattasuttaṃ**Not*";
P_HTM[469]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[470]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, anattā atītānāgataṃ;**“Mendicants, form of the past and future is not-self,*";
P_HTM[471]="*ko pana vādo paccuppannassa.**let alone the present.*";
P_HTM[472]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako atītasmiṃ rūpasmiṃ anapekkho hoti;**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple doesn’t worry about past form,*";
P_HTM[473]="*anāgataṃ rūpaṃ nābhinandati;**doesn’t look forward to enjoying future form,*";
P_HTM[474]="*paccuppannassa rūpassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.**and they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present form.*";
P_HTM[475]="*Vedanā anattā …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[476]="*saññā anattā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[477]="*saṅkhārā anattā …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[478]="*viññāṇaṃ anattā atītānāgataṃ;**Consciousness of the past and future is not-self,*";
P_HTM[479]="*ko pana vādo paccuppannassa.**let alone the present.*";
P_HTM[480]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako atītasmiṃ viññāṇasmiṃ anapekkho hoti;**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple doesn’t worry about past consciousness,*";
P_HTM[481]="*anāgataṃ viññāṇaṃ nābhinandati;**doesn’t look forward to enjoying future consciousness,*";
P_HTM[482]="*paccuppannassa viññāṇassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hotī”ti.**and they practice for the disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present consciousness.”*";
P_HTM[483]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[484]="*Nakulapituvaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[485]="*Nakulapitā devadahā,* **";
P_HTM[486]="*Dvepi hāliddikāni ca;* **";
P_HTM[487]="*Samādhipaṭisallāṇā,* **";
P_HTM[488]="*Upādāparitassanā duve;* **";
P_HTM[489]="*Atītānāgatapaccuppannā,* **";
P_HTM[490]="*Vaggo tena pavuccati.* **";
P_HTM[491]="*sn/sn22.012.xhtml==2. Aniccavagga==2. Aniccavaggo**Impermanence*";
P_HTM[492]="*1. Aniccasuttaṃ**Impermanence*";
P_HTM[493]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[494]="*sāvatthiyaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[495]="*Tatra kho … pe …* **";
P_HTM[496]="*“rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ, vedanā aniccā, saññā aniccā, saṅkhārā aniccā, viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**“Mendicants, form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[497]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi nibbindati, saññāyapi nibbindati, saṅkhāresupi nibbindati, viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[498]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[499]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[500]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[501]="*2. Dukkhasuttaṃ**Suffering*";
P_HTM[502]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[503]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ, vedanā dukkhā, saññā dukkhā, saṅkhārā dukkhā, viññāṇaṃ dukkhaṃ.**“Mendicants, form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are suffering.*";
P_HTM[504]="*Evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[505]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[506]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[507]="*3. Anattasuttaṃ**Not*";
P_HTM[508]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[509]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, anattā, vedanā anattā, saññā anattā, saṅkhārā anattā, viññāṇaṃ anattā.**“Mendicants, form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are not-self.*";
P_HTM[510]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi nibbindati, saññāyapi nibbindati, saṅkhāresupi nibbindati, viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[511]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[512]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[513]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[514]="*4. Yadaniccasuttaṃ**That Which is Impermanent*";
P_HTM[515]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[516]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ.**“Mendicants, form is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[517]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[518]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[519]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[520]="*Vedanā aniccā.**Feeling is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[521]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[522]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;* **";
P_HTM[523]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[524]="*Saññā aniccā … pe …**Perception is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[525]="*saṅkhārā aniccā …**Choices are impermanent …*";
P_HTM[526]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**Consciousness is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[527]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[528]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[529]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[530]="*Evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[531]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[532]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[533]="*5. Yaṃdukkhasuttaṃ**That Which is Suffering*";
P_HTM[534]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[535]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ.**“Mendicants, form is suffering.*";
P_HTM[536]="*Yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[537]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[538]="*Vedanā dukkhā …**Feeling is suffering …*";
P_HTM[539]="*saññā dukkhā …**Perception is suffering …*";
P_HTM[540]="*saṅkhārā dukkhā …**Choices are suffering …*";
P_HTM[541]="*viññāṇaṃ dukkhaṃ.**Consciousness is suffering.*";
P_HTM[542]="*Yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[543]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[544]="*Evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[545]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[546]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[547]="*6. Yadanattāsuttaṃ**That Which is Not*";
P_HTM[548]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[549]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, anattā.**“Mendicants, form is not-self.*";
P_HTM[550]="*Yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[551]="*Vedanā anattā …**Feeling is not-self …*";
P_HTM[552]="*saññā anattā …**Perception is not-self …*";
P_HTM[553]="*saṅkhārā anattā …**Choices are not-self …*";
P_HTM[554]="*viññāṇaṃ anattā.**Consciousness is not-self.*";
P_HTM[555]="*Yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[556]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[557]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[558]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[559]="*7. Sahetuaniccasuttaṃ**Impermanence With Its Cause*";
P_HTM[560]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[561]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ.**“Mendicants, form is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[562]="*Yopi hetu, yopi paccayo rūpassa uppādāya, sopi anicco.**The cause and condition that gives rise to form is also impermanent.*";
P_HTM[563]="*Aniccasambhūtaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ kuto niccaṃ bhavissati.**Since form is produced by what is impermanent, how could it be permanent?*";
P_HTM[564]="*Vedanā aniccā.**Feeling is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[565]="*Yopi hetu, yopi paccayo vedanāya uppādāya, sopi anicco.* **";
P_HTM[566]="*Aniccasambhūtā, bhikkhave, vedanā kuto niccā bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[567]="*Saññā aniccā …**Perception is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[568]="*saṅkhārā aniccā.**Choices are impermanent …*";
P_HTM[569]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo saṅkhārānaṃ uppādāya, sopi anicco.* **";
P_HTM[570]="*Aniccasambhūtā, bhikkhave, saṅkhārā kuto niccā bhavissanti.* **";
P_HTM[571]="*Viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**Consciousness is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[572]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo viññāṇassa uppādāya, sopi anicco.**The cause and condition that gives rise to consciousness is also impermanent.*";
P_HTM[573]="*Aniccasambhūtaṃ, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ kuto niccaṃ bhavissati.**Since consciousness is produced by what is impermanent, how could it be permanent?*";
P_HTM[574]="*Evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[575]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[576]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[577]="*8. Sahetudukkhasuttaṃ**Suffering With Its Cause*";
P_HTM[578]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[579]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ.**“Mendicants, form is suffering.*";
P_HTM[580]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo rūpassa uppādāya, sopi dukkho.**The cause and condition that gives rise to form is also suffering.*";
P_HTM[581]="*Dukkhasambhūtaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ kuto sukhaṃ bhavissati.**Since form is produced by what is suffering, how could it be happiness?*";
P_HTM[582]="*Vedanā dukkhā …**Feeling is suffering …*";
P_HTM[583]="*saññā dukkhā …**Perception is suffering …*";
P_HTM[584]="*saṅkhārā dukkhā …**Choices are suffering …*";
P_HTM[585]="*viññāṇaṃ dukkhaṃ.**Consciousness is suffering.*";
P_HTM[586]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo viññāṇassa uppādāya, sopi dukkho.**The cause and condition that gives rise to consciousness is also suffering.*";
P_HTM[587]="*Dukkhasambhūtaṃ, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ kuto sukhaṃ bhavissati.**Since consciousness is produced by what is suffering, how could it be happiness?*";
P_HTM[588]="*Evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[589]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[590]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[591]="*9. Sahetuanattasuttaṃ**Not*";
P_HTM[592]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[593]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, anattā.**“Mendicants, form is not-self.*";
P_HTM[594]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo rūpassa uppādāya, sopi anattā.**The cause and condition that gives rise to form is also not-self.*";
P_HTM[595]="*Anattasambhūtaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ kuto attā bhavissati.**Since form is produced by what is not-self, how could it be self?*";
P_HTM[596]="*Vedanā anattā …**Feeling is not-self …*";
P_HTM[597]="*saññā anattā …**Perception is not-self …*";
P_HTM[598]="*saṅkhārā anattā …**Choices are not-self …*";
P_HTM[599]="*viññāṇaṃ anattā.**Consciousness is not-self.*";
P_HTM[600]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo viññāṇassa uppādāya, sopi anattā.**The cause and condition that gives rise to consciousness is also not-self.*";
P_HTM[601]="*Anattasambhūtaṃ, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ kuto attā bhavissati.**Since consciousness is produced by what is not-self, how could it be self?*";
P_HTM[602]="*Evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[603]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[604]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[605]="*10. Ānandasuttaṃ**With Ānanda*";
P_HTM[606]="*Sāvatthiyaṃ … ārāme.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[607]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[608]="*“‘nirodho nirodho’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘cessation’.*";
P_HTM[609]="*Katamesānaṃ kho, bhante, dhammānaṃ nirodho ‘nirodho’ti vuccatī”ti?**The cessation of what things does this refer to?”*";
P_HTM[610]="*“Rūpaṃ kho, ānanda, aniccaṃ saṅkhataṃ paṭiccasamuppannaṃ khayadhammaṃ vayadhammaṃ virāgadhammaṃ nirodhadhammaṃ.**“Ānanda, form is impermanent, conditioned, dependently originated, liable to end, vanish, fade away, and cease.*";
P_HTM[611]="*Tassa nirodho ‘nirodho’ti vuccati.**Its cessation is what ‘cessation’ refers to.*";
P_HTM[612]="*Vedanā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā khayadhammā vayadhammā virāgadhammā nirodhadhammā.**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[613]="*Tassā nirodho ‘nirodho’ti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[614]="*Saññā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[615]="*saṅkhārā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā khayadhammā vayadhammā virāgadhammā nirodhadhammā.**Choices …*";
P_HTM[616]="*Tesaṃ nirodho ‘nirodho’ti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[617]="*Viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ saṅkhataṃ paṭiccasamuppannaṃ khayadhammaṃ vayadhammaṃ virāgadhammaṃ nirodhadhammaṃ.**Consciousness is impermanent, conditioned, dependently originated, liable to end, vanish, fade away, and cease.*";
P_HTM[618]="*Tassa nirodho ‘nirodho’ti vuccati.**Its cessation is what ‘cessation’ refers to.*";
P_HTM[619]="*Imesaṃ kho, ānanda, dhammānaṃ nirodho ‘nirodho’ti vuccatī”ti.**When they speak of ‘cessation’, its the cessation of these things that this refers to.”*";
P_HTM[620]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[621]="*Aniccavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[622]="*Aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ anattā,* **";
P_HTM[623]="*yadaniccāpare tayo;* **";
P_HTM[624]="*Hetunāpi tayo vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[625]="*ānandena ca te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[626]="*sn/sn22.022.xhtml==3. Bhāravagga==3. Bhāravaggo**The Burden*";
P_HTM[627]="*1. Bhārasuttaṃ**The Burden*";
P_HTM[628]="*Sāvatthiyaṃ … tatra kho …**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[629]="*“bhārañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi bhārahārañca bhārādānañca bhāranikkhepanañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the burden, the bearer of the burden, the picking up of the burden, and the putting down of the burden.*";
P_HTM[630]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[631]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, bhāro?**And what is the burden?*";
P_HTM[632]="*Pañcupādānakkhandhā tissa vacanīyaṃ.**The five grasping aggregates, it should be said.*";
P_HTM[633]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[634]="*Rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho;**The grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[635]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhāro.**This is called the burden.*";
P_HTM[636]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, bhārahāro?**And who is the bearer of the burden?*";
P_HTM[637]="*Puggalo tissa vacanīyaṃ.**The person, it should be said;*";
P_HTM[638]="*Yvāyaṃ āyasmā evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto;**the venerable of such and such name and clan.*";
P_HTM[639]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhārahāro.**This is called the bearer of the burden.*";
P_HTM[640]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, bhārādānaṃ?**And what is the picking up of the burden?*";
P_HTM[641]="*Yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobhavikā nandīrāgasahagatā tatratatrābhinandinī, seyyathidaṃ—**It’s the craving that leads to future lives, mixed up with relishing and greed, taking pleasure in various different realms. That is,*";
P_HTM[642]="*kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā.**craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[643]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhārādānaṃ.**This is called the picking up of the burden.*";
P_HTM[644]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, bhāranikkhepanaṃ?**And what is the putting down of the burden?*";
P_HTM[645]="*Yo tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodho cāgo paṭinissaggo mutti anālayo.**It’s the fading away and cessation of that very same craving with nothing left over; giving it away, letting it go, releasing it, and not adhering to it.*";
P_HTM[646]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhāranikkhepanan”ti.**This is called the putting down of the burden.”*";
P_HTM[647]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[648]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[649]="*“Bhārā have pañcakkhandhā,**“The five aggregates are indeed burdens,*";
P_HTM[650]="*bhārahāro ca puggalo;**and the person is the bearer of the burden.*";
P_HTM[651]="*Bhārādānaṃ dukhaṃ loke,**Picking up the burden is suffering in the world,*";
P_HTM[652]="*bhāranikkhepanaṃ sukhaṃ.**and putting the burden down is happiness.*";
P_HTM[653]="*Nikkhipitvā garuṃ bhāraṃ,**When the heavy burden is put down*";
P_HTM[654]="*aññaṃ bhāraṃ anādiya;**without picking up another,*";
P_HTM[655]="*Samūlaṃ taṇhamabbuyha,**and craving’s pulled out from the root,*";
P_HTM[656]="*nicchāto parinibbuto”ti.**you’re hungerless, extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[657]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[658]="*2. Pariññasuttaṃ**Complete Understanding*";
P_HTM[659]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[660]="*“Pariññeyye ca, bhikkhave, dhamme desessāmi pariññañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the things that should be completely understood, and complete understanding.*";
P_HTM[661]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[662]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, pariññeyyā dhammā?**And what things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[663]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, pariññeyyo dhammo, vedanā pariññeyyo dhammo, saññā pariññeyyo dhammo, saṅkhārā pariññeyyo dhammo, viññāṇaṃ pariññeyyo dhammo.**Form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[664]="*Ime vuccanti, bhikkhave, pariññeyyā dhammā.**These are called the things that should be completely understood.*";
P_HTM[665]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, pariññā?**And what is complete understanding?*";
P_HTM[666]="*Yo, bhikkhave, rāgakkhayo dosakkhayo mohakkhayo.**The ending of greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[667]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, pariññā”ti.**This is called complete understanding.”*";
P_HTM[668]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[669]="*3. Abhijānasuttaṃ**Directly Knowing*";
P_HTM[670]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[671]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, anabhijānaṃ aparijānaṃ avirājayaṃ appajahaṃ abhabbo dukkhakkhayāya;**“Mendicants, without directly knowing and completely understanding form, without dispassion for it and giving it up, you can’t end suffering.*";
P_HTM[672]="*vedanaṃ anabhijānaṃ aparijānaṃ avirājayaṃ appajahaṃ abhabbo dukkhakkhayāya;**Without directly knowing and completely understanding feeling …*";
P_HTM[673]="*saññaṃ anabhijānaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[674]="*saṅkhāre anabhijānaṃ aparijānaṃ avirājayaṃ appajahaṃ abhabbo dukkhakkhayāya;**choices …*";
P_HTM[675]="*viññāṇaṃ anabhijānaṃ aparijānaṃ avirājayaṃ appajahaṃ abhabbo dukkhakkhayāya.**consciousness, without dispassion for it and giving it up, you can’t end suffering.*";
P_HTM[676]="*Rūpañca kho, bhikkhave, abhijānaṃ parijānaṃ virājayaṃ pajahaṃ bhabbo dukkhakkhayāya;**By directly knowing and completely understanding form, having dispassion for it and giving it up, you can end suffering.*";
P_HTM[677]="*vedanaṃ abhijānaṃ …**By directly knowing and completely understanding feeling …*";
P_HTM[678]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[679]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[680]="*viññāṇaṃ abhijānaṃ parijānaṃ virājayaṃ pajahaṃ bhabbo dukkhakkhayāyā”ti.**consciousness, having dispassion for it and giving it up, you can end suffering.”*";
P_HTM[681]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[682]="*4. Chandarāgasuttaṃ**Desire and Greed*";
P_HTM[683]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[684]="*“Yo, bhikkhave, rūpasmiṃ chandarāgo taṃ pajahatha.**“Mendicants, give up desire and greed for form.*";
P_HTM[685]="*Evaṃ taṃ rūpaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati ucchinnamūlaṃ tālāvatthukataṃ anabhāvaṃkataṃ āyatiṃ anuppādadhammaṃ.**Thus that form will be given up, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated, and unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[686]="*Yo vedanāya chandarāgo taṃ pajahatha.**Give up desire and greed for feeling …*";
P_HTM[687]="*Evaṃ sā vedanā pahīnā bhavissati ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṃkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[688]="*Yo saññāya chandarāgo taṃ pajahatha.**perception …*";
P_HTM[689]="*Evaṃ sā saññā pahīnā bhavissati ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṃkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[690]="*Yo saṅkhāresu chandarāgo taṃ pajahatha.**choices …*";
P_HTM[691]="*Evaṃ te saṅkhārā pahīnā bhavissanti ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṃkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[692]="*Yo viññāṇasmiṃ chandarāgo taṃ pajahatha.**consciousness.*";
P_HTM[693]="*Evaṃ taṃ viññāṇaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati ucchinnamūlaṃ tālāvatthukataṃ anabhāvaṃkataṃ āyatiṃ anuppādadhamman”ti.**Thus that consciousness will be given up, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated, and unable to arise in the future.”*";
P_HTM[694]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[695]="*5. Assādasuttaṃ**Gratification*";
P_HTM[696]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[697]="*“Pubbeva me, bhikkhave, sambodhā anabhisambuddhassa bodhisattasseva sato etadahosi:**“Mendicants, before my awakening—when I was still unawakened but intent on awakening—I thought:*";
P_HTM[698]="*‘ko nu kho rūpassa assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ?**‘What’s the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form …*";
P_HTM[699]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ?**feeling …*";
P_HTM[700]="*Ko saññāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ?**perception …*";
P_HTM[701]="*Ko saṅkhārānaṃ assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ?**choices …*";
P_HTM[702]="*Ko viññāṇassa assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan’ti?**and consciousness?’*";
P_HTM[703]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etadahosi:**Then it occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[704]="*‘yaṃ kho rūpaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ rūpassa assādo.**‘The pleasure and happiness that arise from form: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[705]="*Yaṃ rūpaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, ayaṃ rūpassa ādīnavo.**That form is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[706]="*Yo rūpasmiṃ chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for form: this is its escape.*";
P_HTM[707]="*Yaṃ vedanaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ vedanāya assādo.**The pleasure and happiness that arise from feeling …*";
P_HTM[708]="*Yaṃ vedanā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā, ayaṃ vedanāya ādīnavo.* **";
P_HTM[709]="*Yo vedanāya chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ vedanāya nissaraṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[710]="*Yaṃ saññaṃ paṭicca uppajjati … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[711]="*yaṃ saṅkhāre paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ assādo.**choices …*";
P_HTM[712]="*Yaṃ saṅkhārā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā, ayaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ ādīnavo.* **";
P_HTM[713]="*Yo saṅkhāresu chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ nissaraṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[714]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ viññāṇassa assādo.**consciousness: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[715]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, ayaṃ viññāṇassa ādīnavo.**That consciousness is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[716]="*Yo viññāṇasmiṃ chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ’.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for consciousness: this is its escape.’*";
P_HTM[717]="*Yāvakīvañcāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ evaṃ assādañca assādato ādīnavañca ādīnavato nissaraṇañca nissaraṇato yathābhūtaṃ nābbhaññāsiṃ, neva tāvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, ‘sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**As long as I didn’t truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ gratification, drawback, and escape in this way for what they are, I didn’t announce my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[718]="*Yato ca khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ evaṃ assādañca assādato ādīnavañca ādīnavato nissaraṇañca nissaraṇato yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ;**But when I did truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ gratification, drawback, and escape in this way for what they are, I announced my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[719]="*athāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddhoti paccaññāsiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[720]="*Ñāṇañca pana me dassanaṃ udapādi:**Knowledge and vision arose in me:*";
P_HTM[721]="*‘akuppā me vimutti; ayamantimā jāti; natthi dāni punabbhavo’”ti.**‘My freedom is unshakable; this is my last rebirth; now there are no more future lives.’”*";
P_HTM[722]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[723]="*6. Dutiyaassādasuttaṃ**Gratification (2nd)*";
P_HTM[724]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[725]="*“Rūpassāhaṃ, bhikkhave, assādapariyesanaṃ acariṃ.**“Mendicants, I went in search of form’s gratification,*";
P_HTM[726]="*Yo rūpassa assādo tadajjhagamaṃ.**and I found it.*";
P_HTM[727]="*Yāvatā rūpassa assādo paññāya me so sudiṭṭho.**I’ve seen clearly with wisdom the full extent of form’s gratification.*";
P_HTM[728]="*Rūpassāhaṃ, bhikkhave, ādīnavapariyesanaṃ acariṃ.**I went in search of form’s drawback,*";
P_HTM[729]="*Yo rūpassa ādīnavo tadajjhagamaṃ.**and I found it.*";
P_HTM[730]="*Yāvatā rūpassa ādīnavo paññāya me so sudiṭṭho.**I’ve seen clearly with wisdom the full extent of form’s drawback.*";
P_HTM[731]="*Rūpassāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nissaraṇapariyesanaṃ acariṃ.**I went in search of form’s escape,*";
P_HTM[732]="*Yaṃ rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ tadajjhagamaṃ.**and I found it.*";
P_HTM[733]="*Yāvatā rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ paññāya me taṃ sudiṭṭhaṃ.**I’ve seen clearly with wisdom the full extent of form’s escape.*";
P_HTM[734]="*Vedanāyāhaṃ, bhikkhave …**I went in search of the gratification of feeling …*";
P_HTM[735]="*saññāyāhaṃ, bhikkhave …**perception …*";
P_HTM[736]="*saṅkhārānāhaṃ, bhikkhave …**choices …*";
P_HTM[737]="*viññāṇassāhaṃ, bhikkhave, assādapariyesanaṃ acariṃ.**and consciousness,*";
P_HTM[738]="*Yo viññāṇassa assādo tadajjhagamaṃ.**and I found it.*";
P_HTM[739]="*Yāvatā viññāṇassa assādo paññāya me so sudiṭṭho.**I’ve seen clearly with wisdom the full extent of consciousness’s gratification.*";
P_HTM[740]="*Viññāṇassāhaṃ, bhikkhave, ādīnavapariyesanaṃ acariṃ.**I went in search of consciousness’s drawback,*";
P_HTM[741]="*Yo viññāṇassa ādīnavo tadajjhagamaṃ.**and I found it.*";
P_HTM[742]="*Yāvatā viññāṇassa ādīnavo paññāya me so sudiṭṭho.**I’ve seen clearly with wisdom the full extent of consciousness’s drawback.*";
P_HTM[743]="*Viññāṇassāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nissaraṇapariyesanaṃ acariṃ.**I went in search of consciousness’s escape,*";
P_HTM[744]="*Yaṃ viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ tadajjhagamaṃ.**and I found it.*";
P_HTM[745]="*Yāvatā viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ paññāya me taṃ sudiṭṭhaṃ.**I’ve seen clearly with wisdom the full extent of consciousness’s escape.*";
P_HTM[746]="*Yāvakīvañcāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ assādañca assādato ādīnavañca ādīnavato nissaraṇañca nissaraṇato yathābhūtaṃ nābbhaññāsiṃ … pe …**As long as I didn’t truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ gratification, drawback, and escape for what they are, I didn’t announce my supreme perfect awakening …*";
P_HTM[747]="*abbhaññāsiṃ.**But when I did truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ gratification, drawback, and escape for what they are, I announced my supreme perfect awakening …*";
P_HTM[748]="*Ñāṇañca pana me dassanaṃ udapādi:**Knowledge and vision arose in me:*";
P_HTM[749]="*‘akuppā me vimutti; ayamantimā jāti; natthi dāni punabbhavo’”ti.**‘My freedom is unshakable; this is my last rebirth; now there are no more future lives.’”*";
P_HTM[750]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[751]="*7. Tatiyaassādasuttaṃ**Gratification (3rd)*";
P_HTM[752]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[753]="*“No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpassa assādo abhavissa nayidaṃ sattā rūpasmiṃ sārajjeyyuṃ.**“Mendicants, if there were no gratification in form, sentient beings wouldn’t love it.*";
P_HTM[754]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, atthi rūpassa assādo, tasmā sattā rūpasmiṃ sārajjanti.**But because there is gratification in form, sentient beings do love it.*";
P_HTM[755]="*No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpassa ādīnavo abhavissa nayidaṃ sattā rūpasmiṃ nibbindeyyuṃ.**If form had no drawback, sentient beings wouldn’t grow disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[756]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, atthi rūpassa ādīnavo, tasmā sattā rūpasmiṃ nibbindanti.**But because form has a drawback, sentient beings do grow disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[757]="*No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ abhavissa nayidaṃ sattā rūpasmā nissareyyuṃ.**If there were no escape from form, sentient beings wouldn’t escape from it.*";
P_HTM[758]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, atthi rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ, tasmā sattā rūpasmā nissaranti.**But because there is an escape from form, sentient beings do escape from it.*";
P_HTM[759]="*No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, vedanāya … pe …**If there were no gratification in feeling …*";
P_HTM[760]="*no cedaṃ, bhikkhave, saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[761]="*no cedaṃ, bhikkhave, saṅkhārānaṃ nissaraṇaṃ abhavissa, nayidaṃ sattā saṅkhārehi nissareyyuṃ.**choices …*";
P_HTM[762]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, atthi saṅkhārānaṃ nissaraṇaṃ, tasmā sattā saṅkhārehi nissaranti.* **";
P_HTM[763]="*No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, viññāṇassa assādo abhavissa, nayidaṃ sattā viññāṇasmiṃ sārajjeyyuṃ.**consciousness, sentient beings wouldn’t love it.*";
P_HTM[764]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, atthi viññāṇassa assādo, tasmā sattā viññāṇasmiṃ sārajjanti.**But because there is gratification in consciousness, sentient beings do love it.*";
P_HTM[765]="*No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, viññāṇassa ādīnavo abhavissa, nayidaṃ sattā viññāṇasmiṃ nibbindeyyuṃ.**If consciousness had no drawback, sentient beings wouldn’t grow disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[766]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, atthi viññāṇassa ādīnavo, tasmā sattā viññāṇasmiṃ nibbindanti.**But because consciousness has a drawback, sentient beings do grow disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[767]="*No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ abhavissa, nayidaṃ sattā viññāṇasmā nissareyyuṃ.**If there were no escape from consciousness, sentient beings wouldn’t escape from it.*";
P_HTM[768]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, atthi viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ, tasmā sattā viññāṇasmā nissaranti.**But because there is an escape from consciousness, sentient beings do escape from it.*";
P_HTM[769]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, sattā imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ assādañca assādato ādīnavañca ādīnavato nissaraṇañca nissaraṇato yathābhūtaṃ nābbhaññaṃsu;**As long as sentient beings don’t truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ gratification, drawback, and escape for what they are, they haven’t escaped from this world—with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—and they don’t live detached, liberated, with a mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[770]="*neva tāva, bhikkhave, sattā sadevakā lokā samārakā sabrahmakā sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya nissaṭā visaṃyuttā vippamuttā vimariyādīkatena cetasā vihariṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[771]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, sattā imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ assādañca assādato ādīnavañca ādīnavato nissaraṇañca nissaraṇato yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññaṃsu;**But when sentient beings truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ gratification, drawback, and escape for what they are, they’ve escaped from this world—with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—and they live detached, liberated, with a mind free of limits.”*";
P_HTM[772]="*atha, bhikkhave, sattā sadevakā lokā samārakā sabrahmakā sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya nissaṭā visaṃyuttā vippamuttā vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharanti”.* **";
P_HTM[773]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[774]="*8. Abhinandanasuttaṃ**Taking Pleasure*";
P_HTM[775]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[776]="*“Yo, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ abhinandati, dukkhaṃ so abhinandati.**“Mendicants, if you take pleasure in form, you take pleasure in suffering.*";
P_HTM[777]="*Yo dukkhaṃ abhinandati, aparimutto so dukkhasmāti vadāmi.**If you take pleasure in suffering, I say you’re not exempt from suffering.*";
P_HTM[778]="*Yo vedanaṃ abhinandati …**If you take pleasure in feeling …*";
P_HTM[779]="*yo saññaṃ abhinandati …**perception …*";
P_HTM[780]="*yo saṅkhāre abhinandati …**choices …*";
P_HTM[781]="*yo viññāṇaṃ abhinandati, dukkhaṃ so abhinandati.**consciousness, you take pleasure in suffering.*";
P_HTM[782]="*Yo dukkhaṃ abhinandati, aparimutto so dukkhasmāti vadāmi.**If you take pleasure in suffering, I say you’re not exempt from suffering.*";
P_HTM[783]="*Yo ca kho, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ nābhinandati, dukkhaṃ so nābhinandati.**If you don’t take pleasure in form, you don’t take pleasure in suffering.*";
P_HTM[784]="*Yo dukkhaṃ nābhinandati, parimutto so dukkhasmāti vadāmi.**If you don’t take pleasure in suffering, I say you’re exempt from suffering.*";
P_HTM[785]="*Yo vedanaṃ nābhinandati …**If you don’t take pleasure in feeling …*";
P_HTM[786]="*yo saññaṃ nābhinandati …**perception …*";
P_HTM[787]="*yo saṅkhāre nābhinandati …**choices …*";
P_HTM[788]="*yo viññāṇaṃ nābhinandati, dukkhaṃ so nābhinandati.**consciousness, you don’t take pleasure in suffering.*";
P_HTM[789]="*Yo dukkhaṃ nābhinandati, parimutto so dukkhasmāti vadāmī”ti.**If you don’t take pleasure in suffering, I say you’re exempt from suffering.”*";
P_HTM[790]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[791]="*9. Uppādasuttaṃ**Arising*";
P_HTM[792]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[793]="*“Yo, bhikkhave, rūpassa uppādo ṭhiti abhinibbatti pātubhāvo, dukkhasseso uppādo rogānaṃ ṭhiti jarāmaraṇassa pātubhāvo.**“Mendicants, the arising, continuation, rebirth, and manifestation of form is the arising of suffering, the continuation of diseases, and the manifestation of old age and death.*";
P_HTM[794]="*Yo vedanāya … pe …**The arising, continuation, rebirth, and manifestation of feeling …*";
P_HTM[795]="*yo saññāya … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[796]="*yo saṅkhārānaṃ … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[797]="*yo viññāṇassa uppādo ṭhiti abhinibbatti pātubhāvo, dukkhasseso uppādo rogānaṃ ṭhiti jarāmaraṇassa pātubhāvo.**consciousness is the arising of suffering, the continuation of diseases, and the manifestation of old age and death.*";
P_HTM[798]="*Yo ca kho, bhikkhave, rūpassa nirodho vūpasamo atthaṅgamo, dukkhasseso nirodho rogānaṃ vūpasamo jarāmaraṇassa atthaṅgamo.**The cessation, settling, and ending of form is the cessation of suffering, the settling of diseases, and the ending of old age and death.*";
P_HTM[799]="*Yo vedanāya … pe …**The cessation, settling, and ending of feeling …*";
P_HTM[800]="*yo saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[801]="*yo saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices …*";
P_HTM[802]="*yo viññāṇassa nirodho vūpasamo atthaṅgamo, dukkhasseso nirodho rogānaṃ vūpasamo jarāmaraṇassa atthaṅgamo”ti.**consciousness is the cessation of suffering, the settling of diseases, and the ending of old age and death.”*";
P_HTM[803]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[804]="*10. Aghamūlasuttaṃ**The Root of Misery*";
P_HTM[805]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[806]="*“Aghañca, bhikkhave, desessāmi aghamūlañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you misery and the root of misery.*";
P_HTM[807]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[808]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, aghaṃ?**And what is misery?*";
P_HTM[809]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aghaṃ, vedanā aghaṃ, saññā aghaṃ, saṅkhārā aghaṃ, viññāṇaṃ aghaṃ.**Form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are misery.*";
P_HTM[810]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, aghaṃ.**This is called misery.*";
P_HTM[811]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, aghamūlaṃ?**And what is the root of misery?*";
P_HTM[812]="*Yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobhavikā nandīrāgasahagatā tatratatrābhinandinī;**It’s the craving that leads to future lives, mixed up with relishing and greed, taking pleasure in various different realms. That is,*";
P_HTM[813]="*Seyyathidaṃ—kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā.**craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[814]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, aghamūlan”ti.**This is called the root of misery.”*";
P_HTM[815]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[816]="*11. Pabhaṅgusuttaṃ**The Breakable*";
P_HTM[817]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[818]="*“Pabhaṅguñca, bhikkhave, desessāmi appabhaṅguñca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the breakable and the unbreakable.*";
P_HTM[819]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[820]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, pabhaṅgu, kiṃ appabhaṅgu?**And what is the breakable? What is the unbreakable?*";
P_HTM[821]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, pabhaṅgu.**Form is breakable,*";
P_HTM[822]="*Yo tassa nirodho vūpasamo atthaṅgamo, idaṃ appabhaṅgu.**but its cessation, settling, and ending is unbreakable.*";
P_HTM[823]="*Vedanā pabhaṅgu.**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[824]="*Yo tassā nirodho vūpasamo atthaṅgamo, idaṃ appabhaṅgu.* **";
P_HTM[825]="*Saññā pabhaṅgu …**perception …*";
P_HTM[826]="*saṅkhārā pabhaṅgu.**choices …*";
P_HTM[827]="*Yo tesaṃ nirodho vūpasamo atthaṅgamo, idaṃ appabhaṅgu.* **";
P_HTM[828]="*Viññāṇaṃ pabhaṅgu.**consciousness is breakable,*";
P_HTM[829]="*Yo tassa nirodho vūpasamo atthaṅgamo, idaṃ appabhaṅgū”ti.**but its cessation, settling, and ending is unbreakable.”*";
P_HTM[830]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[831]="*Bhāravaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[832]="*Bhāraṃ pariññaṃ abhijānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[833]="*chandarāgaṃ catutthakaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[834]="*Assādā ca tayo vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[835]="*abhinandanamaṭṭhamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[836]="*Uppādaṃ aghamūlañca,* **";
P_HTM[837]="*ekādasamo pabhaṅgūti.* **";
P_HTM[838]="*sn/sn22.033.xhtml==4. Natumhākavagga==4. Natumhākaṃvaggo**It’s Not Yours*";
P_HTM[839]="*1. Natumhākaṃsuttaṃ**It’s Not Yours*";
P_HTM[840]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[841]="*“Yaṃ, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**“Mendicants, give up what’s not yours.*";
P_HTM[842]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[843]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ?**And what isn’t yours?*";
P_HTM[844]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**Form isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[845]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[846]="*Vedanā na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[847]="*Sā vo pahīnā hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[848]="*Saññā na tumhākaṃ …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[849]="*saṅkhārā na tumhākaṃ, te pajahatha.**Choices …*";
P_HTM[850]="*Te vo pahīnā hitāya sukhāya bhavissanti.* **";
P_HTM[851]="*Viññāṇaṃ na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**Consciousness isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[852]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[853]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yaṃ imasmiṃ jetavane tiṇakaṭṭhasākhāpalāsaṃ taṃ jano hareyya vā ḍaheyya vā yathāpaccayaṃ vā kareyya.**Suppose a person was to carry off the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves in this Jeta’s Grove, or burn them, or do what they want with them.*";
P_HTM[854]="*Api nu tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Would you think:*";
P_HTM[855]="*‘amhe jano harati vā ḍahati vā yathāpaccayaṃ vā karotī’”ti?**‘This person is carrying us off, burning us, or doing what they want with us?’”*";
P_HTM[856]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[857]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[858]="*“Na hi no etaṃ, bhante, attā vā attaniyaṃ vā”ti.**Because that’s neither self nor belonging to self.”*";
P_HTM[859]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**“In the same way, mendicants, form isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[860]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[861]="*Vedanā na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[862]="*Sā vo pahīnā hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[863]="*Saññā na tumhākaṃ …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[864]="*saṅkhārā na tumhākaṃ …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[865]="*viññāṇaṃ na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**Consciousness isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[866]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissatī”ti.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[867]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[868]="*2. Dutiyanatumhākaṃsuttaṃ**It’s Not Yours (2nd)*";
P_HTM[869]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[870]="*“Yaṃ, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**“Mendicants, give up what’s not yours.*";
P_HTM[871]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[872]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ?**And what isn’t yours?*";
P_HTM[873]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**Form isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[874]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[875]="*Vedanā na tumhākaṃ …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[876]="*saññā na tumhākaṃ …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[877]="*saṅkhārā na tumhākaṃ …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[878]="*viññāṇaṃ na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**Consciousness isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[879]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[880]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ taṃ pajahatha.**Give up what’s not yours.*";
P_HTM[881]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissatī”ti.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[882]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[883]="*3. Aññatarabhikkhusuttaṃ**A Mendicant*";
P_HTM[884]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[885]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[886]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu;**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[887]="*yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho, appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[888]="*“Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, anuseti, tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**“Mendicant, you’re defined by what you have an underlying tendency for.*";
P_HTM[889]="*yaṃ nānuseti, na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchatī”ti.**You’re not defined by what you have no underlying tendency for.”*";
P_HTM[890]="*“Aññātaṃ, bhagavā, aññātaṃ, sugatā”ti.**“Understood, Blessed One! Understood, Holy One!”*";
P_HTM[891]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsī”ti?**“But how do you see the detailed meaning of my brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[892]="*“Rūpañce, bhante, anuseti tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**“If you have an underlying tendency for form, you’re defined by that.*";
P_HTM[893]="*Vedanañce anuseti tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**If you have an underlying tendency for feeling …*";
P_HTM[894]="*Saññañce anuseti tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**perception …*";
P_HTM[895]="*Saṅkhāre ce anuseti tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**choices …*";
P_HTM[896]="*Viññāṇañce anuseti tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**consciousness, you’re defined by that.*";
P_HTM[897]="*Rūpañce, bhante, nānuseti na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**If you have no underlying tendency for form, you’re not defined by that.*";
P_HTM[898]="*Vedanañce …**If you have no underlying tendency for feeling …*";
P_HTM[899]="*saññañce …**perception …*";
P_HTM[900]="*saṅkhāre ce …**choices …*";
P_HTM[901]="*viññāṇañce nānuseti na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**consciousness, you’re not defined by that.*";
P_HTM[902]="*Imassa khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**That’s how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.”*";
P_HTM[903]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
P_HTM[904]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsi.**It’s good that you understand the detailed meaning of what I’ve said in brief like this.*";
P_HTM[905]="*Rūpañce, bhikkhu, anuseti tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**If you have an underlying tendency for form, you’re defined by that.*";
P_HTM[906]="*Vedanañce …**If you have an underlying tendency for feeling …*";
P_HTM[907]="*saññañce …**perception …*";
P_HTM[908]="*saṅkhāre ce …**choices …*";
P_HTM[909]="*viññāṇañce anuseti tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**consciousness, you’re defined by that.*";
P_HTM[910]="*Rūpañce, bhikkhu, nānuseti na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**If you have no underlying tendency for form, you’re not defined by that.*";
P_HTM[911]="*Vedanañce …**If you have no underlying tendency for feeling …*";
P_HTM[912]="*saññañce …**perception …*";
P_HTM[913]="*saṅkhāre ce …**choices …*";
P_HTM[914]="*viññāṇañce nānuseti na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**consciousness, you’re not defined by that.*";
P_HTM[915]="*Imassa kho, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena, bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti.**This is how to understand the detailed meaning of what I said in brief.”*";
P_HTM[916]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then that mendicant approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[917]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Then that mendicant, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[918]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[919]="*Aññataro ca pana so bhikkhu arahataṃ ahosīti.**And that mendicant became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[920]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[921]="*4. Dutiyaaññatarabhikkhusuttaṃ**A Mendicant (2nd)*";
P_HTM[922]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[923]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[924]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[925]="*“Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, anuseti taṃ anumīyati;**“Mendicant, you’re measured against what you have an underlying tendency for,*";
P_HTM[926]="*yaṃ anumīyati tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re defined by what you’re measured against.*";
P_HTM[927]="*Yaṃ nānuseti na taṃ anumīyati;**You’re not measured against what you have no underlying tendency for,*";
P_HTM[928]="*yaṃ nānumīyati na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchatī”ti.**and you’re not defined by what you’re not measured against.”*";
P_HTM[929]="*“Aññātaṃ, bhagavā, aññātaṃ, sugatā”ti.**“Understood, Blessed One! Understood, Holy One!”*";
P_HTM[930]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsī”ti?**“But how do you see the detailed meaning of my brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[931]="*“Rūpañce, bhante, anuseti taṃ anumīyati;**“If you have an underlying tendency for form, you’re measured against that,*";
P_HTM[932]="*yaṃ anumīyati tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re defined by what you’re measured against.*";
P_HTM[933]="*Vedanañce anuseti …**If you have an underlying tendency for feeling …*";
P_HTM[934]="*saññañce anuseti …**perception …*";
P_HTM[935]="*saṅkhāre ce anuseti …**choices …*";
P_HTM[936]="*viññāṇañce anuseti taṃ anumīyati;**consciousness, you’re measured against that,*";
P_HTM[937]="*yaṃ anumīyati tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re defined by what you’re measured against.*";
P_HTM[938]="*Rūpañce, bhante, nānuseti na taṃ anumīyati;**If you have no underlying tendency for form, you’re not measured against that,*";
P_HTM[939]="*yaṃ nānumīyati na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re not defined by what you’re not measured against.*";
P_HTM[940]="*Vedanañce nānuseti …**If you have no underlying tendency for feeling …*";
P_HTM[941]="*saññañce nānuseti …**perception …*";
P_HTM[942]="*saṅkhāre ce nānuseti …**choices …*";
P_HTM[943]="*viññāṇañce nānuseti na taṃ anumīyati;**consciousness, you’re not measured against that,*";
P_HTM[944]="*yaṃ nānumīyati na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re not defined by what you’re not measured against.*";
P_HTM[945]="*Imassa khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**That’s how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.”*";
P_HTM[946]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
P_HTM[947]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsi.**It’s good that you understand the detailed meaning of what I’ve said in brief like this.*";
P_HTM[948]="*Rūpañce, bhikkhu, anuseti taṃ anumīyati;**If you have an underlying tendency for form, you’re measured against that,*";
P_HTM[949]="*yaṃ anumīyati tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re defined by what you’re measured against.*";
P_HTM[950]="*Vedanañce, bhikkhu …**If you have an underlying tendency for feeling …*";
P_HTM[951]="*saññañce, bhikkhu …**perception …*";
P_HTM[952]="*saṅkhāre ce, bhikkhu …**choices …*";
P_HTM[953]="*viññāṇañce, bhikkhu, anuseti taṃ anumīyati;**consciousness, you’re measured against that,*";
P_HTM[954]="*yaṃ anumīyati tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re defined by what you’re measured against.*";
P_HTM[955]="*Rūpañce, bhikkhu, nānuseti na taṃ anumīyati;**If you have no underlying tendency for form, you’re not measured against that,*";
P_HTM[956]="*yaṃ nānumīyati na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re not defined by what you’re not measured against.*";
P_HTM[957]="*Vedanañce nānuseti …**If you have no underlying tendency for feeling …*";
P_HTM[958]="*saññañce nānuseti …**perception …*";
P_HTM[959]="*saṅkhāre ce nānuseti …**choices …*";
P_HTM[960]="*viññāṇañce nānuseti na taṃ anumīyati;**consciousness, you’re not measured against that,*";
P_HTM[961]="*yaṃ nānumīyati na tena saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**and you’re not defined by what you’re not measured against.*";
P_HTM[962]="*Imassa kho, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti … pe …**This is how to understand the detailed meaning of what I said in brief.” …*";
P_HTM[963]="*aññataro ca pana so bhikkhu arahataṃ ahosīti.**And that mendicant became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[964]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[965]="*5. Ānandasuttaṃ**With Ānanda*";
P_HTM[966]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[967]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando … pe …**And then Venerable Ānanda …*";
P_HTM[968]="*ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**sitting to one side, the Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[969]="*“Sace taṃ, ānanda, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Ānanda, suppose they were to ask you:*";
P_HTM[970]="*‘katamesaṃ, āvuso ānanda, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyatī’ti?**‘Reverend Ānanda, what are the things for which arising is evident, vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident?’*";
P_HTM[971]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho tvaṃ, ānanda, kinti byākareyyāsī”ti?**How would you answer?”*";
P_HTM[972]="*“Sace maṃ, bhante, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Sir, suppose they were to ask me:*";
P_HTM[973]="*‘katamesaṃ, āvuso ānanda, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyatī’ti?**‘What are the things for which arising is evident, vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident?’*";
P_HTM[974]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhohaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyaṃ:**I’d answer like this:*";
P_HTM[975]="*‘rūpassa kho, āvuso, uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.**‘Reverend, the arising of form is evident, its vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident.*";
P_HTM[976]="*Vedanāya …**The arising of feeling …*";
P_HTM[977]="*saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[978]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices …*";
P_HTM[979]="*viññāṇassa uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.**consciousness is evident, its vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident.*";
P_HTM[980]="*Imesaṃ kho, āvuso, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyatī’ti.**These are the things for which arising is evident, vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident.’*";
P_HTM[981]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhohaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyan”ti.**That’s how I’d answer such a question.”*";
P_HTM[982]="*“Sādhu sādhu, ānanda.**“Good, good, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[983]="*Rūpassa kho, ānanda, uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.**The arising of form is evident, its vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident.*";
P_HTM[984]="*Vedanāya …**The arising of feeling …*";
P_HTM[985]="*saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[986]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices …*";
P_HTM[987]="*viññāṇassa uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.**consciousness is evident, its vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident.*";
P_HTM[988]="*Imesaṃ kho, ānanda, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyatīti.**These are the things for which arising is evident, vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident.*";
P_HTM[989]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho tvaṃ, ānanda, evaṃ byākareyyāsī”ti.**That’s how you should answer such a question.”*";
P_HTM[990]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[991]="*6. Dutiyaānandasuttaṃ**With Ānanda (2nd)*";
P_HTM[992]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[993]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Sitting to one side, the Buddha said to Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[994]="*“Sace taṃ, ānanda, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Ānanda, suppose they were to ask you:*";
P_HTM[995]="*‘katamesaṃ, āvuso ānanda, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha?**‘Reverend Ānanda, what are the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting were evident?*";
P_HTM[996]="*Katamesaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati?**What are the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting will be evident?*";
P_HTM[997]="*Katamesaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyatī’ti?**What are the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting are evident?’*";
P_HTM[998]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho tvaṃ, ānanda, kinti byākareyyāsī”ti?**How would you answer?”*";
P_HTM[999]="*“Sace maṃ, bhante, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Sir, suppose they were to ask me:*";
P_HTM[1000]="*‘katamesaṃ, āvuso ānanda, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha?**‘Reverend Ānanda, what are the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting were evident?*";
P_HTM[1001]="*Katamesaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati?**What are the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting will be evident?*";
P_HTM[1002]="*Katamesaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyatī’ti?**What are the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting are evident?’*";
P_HTM[1003]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhohaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyaṃ:**I’d answer like this:*";
P_HTM[1004]="*‘yaṃ kho, āvuso, rūpaṃ atītaṃ niruddhaṃ vipariṇataṃ;**‘Whatever form has passed, ceased, and perished,*";
P_HTM[1005]="*tassa uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting were evident.*";
P_HTM[1006]="*Yā vedanā atītā niruddhā vipariṇatā;**Whatever feeling …*";
P_HTM[1007]="*tassā uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitāya aññathattaṃ paññāyittha.* **";
P_HTM[1008]="*Yā saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1009]="*ye saṅkhārā atītā niruddhā vipariṇatā;**choices …*";
P_HTM[1010]="*tesaṃ uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha.* **";
P_HTM[1011]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ atītaṃ niruddhaṃ vipariṇataṃ;**consciousness has passed, ceased, and perished,*";
P_HTM[1012]="*tassa uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting were evident.*";
P_HTM[1013]="*Imesaṃ kho, āvuso, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha.**These the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting were evident.*";
P_HTM[1014]="*Yaṃ kho, āvuso, rūpaṃ ajātaṃ apātubhūtaṃ;**Whatever form is not yet born, and has not yet appeared,*";
P_HTM[1015]="*tassa uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting will be evident.*";
P_HTM[1016]="*Yā vedanā ajātā apātubhūtā;**Whatever feeling …*";
P_HTM[1017]="*tassā uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitāya aññathattaṃ paññāyissati.* **";
P_HTM[1018]="*Yā saññā … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1019]="*ye saṅkhārā ajātā apātubhūtā;**choices …*";
P_HTM[1020]="*tesaṃ uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati.* **";
P_HTM[1021]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ ajātaṃ apātubhūtaṃ;**consciousness is not yet born, and has not yet appeared,*";
P_HTM[1022]="*tassa uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting will be evident.*";
P_HTM[1023]="*Imesaṃ kho, āvuso, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati.**These are the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting will be evident.*";
P_HTM[1024]="*Yaṃ kho, āvuso, rūpaṃ jātaṃ pātubhūtaṃ;**Whatever form has been born, and has appeared,*";
P_HTM[1025]="*tassa uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting is evident.*";
P_HTM[1026]="*Yā vedanā jātā pātubhūtā … pe …**Whatever feeling …*";
P_HTM[1027]="*yā saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1028]="*ye saṅkhārā jātā pātubhūtā;**choices …*";
P_HTM[1029]="*tesaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.* **";
P_HTM[1030]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ jātaṃ pātubhūtaṃ tassa uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.**consciousness has been born, and has appeared, its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting are evident.*";
P_HTM[1031]="*Imesaṃ kho, āvuso, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyatī’ti.**These are the things for which arising is evident, vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident.’*";
P_HTM[1032]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhohaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyan”ti.**That’s how I’d answer such a question.”*";
P_HTM[1033]="*“Sādhu sādhu, ānanda.**“Good, good, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[1034]="*Yaṃ kho, ānanda, rūpaṃ atītaṃ niruddhaṃ vipariṇataṃ;**‘Whatever form has passed, ceased, and perished,*";
P_HTM[1035]="*tassa uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting were evident.*";
P_HTM[1036]="*Yā vedanā …**Whatever feeling …*";
P_HTM[1037]="*yā saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1038]="*ye saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1039]="*yaṃ viññāṇaṃ atītaṃ niruddhaṃ vipariṇataṃ;**consciousness has passed, ceased, and perished,*";
P_HTM[1040]="*tassa uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting were evident.*";
P_HTM[1041]="*Imesaṃ kho, ānanda, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyittha, vayo paññāyittha, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyittha.**These the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting were evident.*";
P_HTM[1042]="*Yaṃ kho, ānanda, rūpaṃ ajātaṃ apātubhūtaṃ;**Whatever form is not yet born, and has not yet appeared,*";
P_HTM[1043]="*tassa uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting will be evident.*";
P_HTM[1044]="*Yā vedanā …**Whatever feeling …*";
P_HTM[1045]="*yā saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1046]="*ye saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1047]="*yaṃ viññāṇaṃ ajātaṃ apātubhūtaṃ;**consciousness is not yet born, and has not yet appeared,*";
P_HTM[1048]="*tassa uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting will be evident.*";
P_HTM[1049]="*Imesaṃ kho, ānanda, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyissati, vayo paññāyissati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyissati.**These are the things for which arising, vanishing, and change while persisting will be evident.*";
P_HTM[1050]="*Yaṃ kho, ānanda, rūpaṃ jātaṃ pātubhūtaṃ;**Whatever form has been born, and has appeared,*";
P_HTM[1051]="*tassa uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting are evident.*";
P_HTM[1052]="*Yā vedanā jātā pātubhūtā …**Whatever feeling …*";
P_HTM[1053]="*yā saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1054]="*ye saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1055]="*yaṃ viññāṇaṃ jātaṃ pātubhūtaṃ;**consciousness has been born, and has appeared,*";
P_HTM[1056]="*tassa uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyati.**its arising, vanishing, and change while persisting are evident.*";
P_HTM[1057]="*Imesaṃ kho, ānanda, dhammānaṃ uppādo paññāyati, vayo paññāyati, ṭhitassa aññathattaṃ paññāyatīti.**These are the things for which arising is evident, vanishing is evident, and change while persisting is evident.*";
P_HTM[1058]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho tvaṃ, ānanda, evaṃ byākareyyāsī”ti.**That’s how you should answer such a question.”*";
P_HTM[1059]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1060]="*7. Anudhammasuttaṃ**In Line With the Teachings*";
P_HTM[1061]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1062]="*“Dhammānudhammappaṭipannassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ayamanudhammo hoti**“Mendicants, when a mendicant is practicing in line with the teachings, this is what’s in line with the teachings.*";
P_HTM[1063]="*yaṃ rūpe nibbidābahulo vihareyya, vedanāya nibbidābahulo vihareyya, saññāya nibbidābahulo vihareyya, saṅkhāresu nibbidābahulo vihareyya, viññāṇe nibbidābahulo vihareyya.**They should live full of disillusionment for form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1064]="*Yo rūpe nibbidābahulo viharanto, vedanāya … saññāya … saṅkhāresu nibbidābahulo viharanto, viññāṇe nibbidābahulo viharanto rūpaṃ parijānāti, vedanaṃ … saññaṃ … saṅkhāre … viññāṇaṃ parijānāti,**Living in this way, they completely understand form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1065]="*so rūpaṃ parijānaṃ, vedanaṃ … saññaṃ … saṅkhāre … viññāṇaṃ parijānaṃ parimuccati rūpamhā, parimuccati vedanāya, parimuccati saññāya, parimuccati saṅkhārehi, parimuccati viññāṇamhā,**Completely understanding form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness, they’re freed from these things.*";
P_HTM[1066]="*parimuccati jātiyā jarāmaraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi, parimuccati dukkhasmāti vadāmī”ti.**They’re freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress. They’re freed from suffering, I say.”*";
P_HTM[1067]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1068]="*8. Dutiyaanudhammasuttaṃ**In Line with the Teachings (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1069]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1070]="*“Dhammānudhammappaṭipannassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ayamanudhammo hoti yaṃ rūpe aniccānupassī vihareyya … pe …**“Mendicants, when a mendicant is practicing in line with the teachings, this is what’s in line with the teachings. They should live observing impermanence in form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness. …*";
P_HTM[1071]="*parimuccati dukkhasmāti vadāmī”ti.**They’re freed from suffering, I say.”*";
P_HTM[1072]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1073]="*9. Tatiyaanudhammasuttaṃ**In Line with the Teachings (3rd)*";
P_HTM[1074]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1075]="*“Dhammānudhammappaṭipannassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ayamanudhammo hoti yaṃ rūpe dukkhānupassī vihareyya … pe …**“Mendicants, when a mendicant is practicing in line with the teachings, this is what’s in line with the teachings. They should live observing suffering in form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness. …*";
P_HTM[1076]="*parimuccati dukkhasmāti vadāmī”ti.**They’re freed from suffering, I say.”*";
P_HTM[1077]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1078]="*10. Catutthaanudhammasuttaṃ**In Line with the Teachings (4th)*";
P_HTM[1079]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1080]="*“Dhammānudhammappaṭipannassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ayamanudhammo hoti yaṃ rūpe anattānupassī vihareyya, vedanāya … saññāya … saṅkhāresu … viññāṇe anattānupassī vihareyya.**“Mendicants, when a mendicant is practicing in line with the teachings, this is what’s in line with the teachings. They should live observing not-self in form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness. …*";
P_HTM[1081]="*Yo rūpe anattānupassī viharanto … pe … rūpaṃ parijānāti, vedanaṃ … saññaṃ … saṅkhāre … viññāṇaṃ parijānāti, so rūpaṃ parijānaṃ, vedanaṃ … saññaṃ … saṅkhāre … viññāṇaṃ parijānaṃ parimuccati rūpamhā, parimuccati vedanāya, parimuccati saññāya, parimuccati saṅkhārehi, parimuccati viññāṇamhā, parimuccati jātiyā jarāmaraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi, parimuccati dukkhasmāti vadāmī”ti. Dasamaṃ.**They’re freed from suffering, I say.”*";
P_HTM[1082]="*Natumhākavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[1083]="*Natumhākena dve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[1084]="*bhikkhūhi apare duve;* **";
P_HTM[1085]="*Ānandena ca dve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[1086]="*anudhammehi dve dukāti.* **";
P_HTM[1087]="*sn/sn22.043.xhtml==5. Attadīpavagga==5. Attadīpavaggo**Be Your Own Island*";
P_HTM[1088]="*1. Attadīpasuttaṃ**Be Your Own Island*";
P_HTM[1089]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1090]="*“Attadīpā, bhikkhave, viharatha attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā.**“Mendicants, be your own island, your own refuge, with no other refuge. Let the teaching be your island and your refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[1091]="*Attadīpānaṃ, bhikkhave, viharataṃ attasaraṇānaṃ anaññasaraṇānaṃ, dhammadīpānaṃ dhammasaraṇānaṃ anaññasaraṇānaṃ yoni upaparikkhitabbā ‘Kiṃjātikā sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā, kiṃpahotikā’ti?**When you live like this, you should examine the cause: ‘From what are sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress born and produced?’*";
P_HTM[1092]="*Kiṃjātikā ca, bhikkhave, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā, kiṃpahotikā?**And, mendicants, from what are sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress born and produced?*";
P_HTM[1093]="*Idha, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto,**It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[1094]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[1095]="*Tassa taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati, aññathā ca hoti.**But that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[1096]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[1097]="*Vedanaṃ attato samanupassati, vedanāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā vedanaṃ, vedanāya vā attānaṃ.**They regard feeling as self …*";
P_HTM[1098]="*Tassa sā vedanā vipariṇamati, aññathā ca hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1099]="*Tassa vedanāvipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparideva … pe … pāyāsā.* **";
P_HTM[1100]="*Saññaṃ attato samanupassati …**They regard perception as self …*";
P_HTM[1101]="*saṅkhāre attato samanupassati …**They regard choices as self …*";
P_HTM[1102]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1103]="*Tassa taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati, aññathā ca hoti.**But that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[1104]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**which gives rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[1105]="*Rūpassa tveva, bhikkhave, aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmaṃ virāgaṃ nirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva rūpaṃ etarahi ca sabbaṃ rūpaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhamman’ti, evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato ye sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā te pahīyanti.**Sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress are given up when you understand the impermanence of form—its perishing, fading away, and cessation—and you truly see with right understanding that all form, whether past or present, is impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[1106]="*Tesaṃ pahānā na paritassati, aparitassaṃ sukhaṃ viharati, sukhavihārī bhikkhu ‘tadaṅganibbuto’ti vuccati.**When these things are given up there’s no anxiety. Without anxiety you live happily. A mendicant who lives happily is said to be extinguished in that respect.*";
P_HTM[1107]="*Vedanāya tveva, bhikkhave, aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmaṃ virāgaṃ nirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva vedanā etarahi ca sabbā vedanā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā’ti, evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato ye sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā te pahīyanti.**Sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress are given up when you understand the impermanence of feeling …*";
P_HTM[1108]="*Tesaṃ pahānā na paritassati, aparitassaṃ sukhaṃ viharati, sukhavihārī bhikkhu ‘tadaṅganibbuto’ti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[1109]="*Saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1110]="*saṅkhārānaṃ tveva, bhikkhave, aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmaṃ virāgaṃ nirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva saṅkhārā etarahi ca sabbe saṅkhārā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā’ti, evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato ye sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā te pahīyanti.**choices …*";
P_HTM[1111]="*Tesaṃ pahānā na paritassati, aparitassaṃ sukhaṃ viharati, sukhavihārī bhikkhu ‘tadaṅganibbuto’ti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[1112]="*Viññāṇassa tveva, bhikkhave, aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmaṃ virāgaṃ nirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva viññāṇaṃ etarahi ca sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhamman’ti, evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato ye sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā te pahīyanti.**consciousness—its perishing, fading away, and cessation—and you truly see with right understanding that all consciousness, whether past or present, is impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[1113]="*Tesaṃ pahānā na paritassati, aparitassaṃ sukhaṃ viharati, sukhavihārī bhikkhu ‘tadaṅganibbuto’ti vuccatī”ti.**When these things are given up there’s no anxiety. Without anxiety you live happily. A mendicant who lives happily is said to be extinguished in that respect.”*";
P_HTM[1114]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1115]="*2. Paṭipadāsuttaṃ**Practice*";
P_HTM[1116]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1117]="*“Sakkāyasamudayagāminiñca vo, bhikkhave, paṭipadaṃ desessāmi, sakkāyanirodhagāminiñca paṭipadaṃ.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the practice that leads to the origin of identity and the practice that leads to the cessation of identity.*";
P_HTM[1118]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[1119]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyasamudayagāminī paṭipadā?**And what is the practice that leads to the origin of identity?*";
P_HTM[1120]="*Idha, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto,**It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[1121]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[1122]="*Vedanaṃ attato …**They regard feeling as self …*";
P_HTM[1123]="*saññaṃ …**They regard perception as self …*";
P_HTM[1124]="*saṅkhāre …**They regard choices as self …*";
P_HTM[1125]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1126]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ‘sakkāyasamudayagāminī paṭipadā, sakkāyasamudayagāminī paṭipadā’ti.**This is called the practice that leads to the origin of identity.*";
P_HTM[1127]="*Iti hidaṃ, bhikkhave, vuccati ‘dukkhasamudayagāminī samanupassanā’ti.**And that’s why it’s called a way of regarding things that leads to the origin of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1128]="*Ayamevettha attho.* **";
P_HTM[1129]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**And what is the practice that leads to the cessation of identity?*";
P_HTM[1130]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto, sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto,**It’s when an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[1131]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[1132]="*Na vedanaṃ attato …**They don’t regard feeling as self …*";
P_HTM[1133]="*na saññaṃ …**They don’t regard perception as self …*";
P_HTM[1134]="*na saṅkhāre …**They don’t regard choices as self …*";
P_HTM[1135]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā viññāṇaṃ, na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1136]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ‘sakkāyanirodhagāminī paṭipadā, sakkāyanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti.**This is called the practice that leads to the cessation of identity.*";
P_HTM[1137]="*Iti hidaṃ, bhikkhave, vuccati ‘dukkhanirodhagāminī samanupassanā’ti.**And that’s why it’s called a way of regarding things that leads to the cessation of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[1138]="*Ayamevettha attho”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1139]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1140]="*3. Aniccasuttaṃ**Impermanence*";
P_HTM[1141]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1142]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ.**“Mendicants, form is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1143]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[1144]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[1145]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1146]="*Evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato cittaṃ virajjati vimuccati anupādāya āsavehi.**Seeing truly with right understanding like this, the mind becomes dispassionate and freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1147]="*Vedanā aniccā …**Feeling is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[1148]="*saññā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[1149]="*saṅkhārā …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[1150]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**Consciousness is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1151]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[1152]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[1153]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1154]="*Evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato cittaṃ virajjati vimuccati anupādāya āsavehi.**Seeing truly with right understanding like this, the mind becomes dispassionate and freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1155]="*Rūpadhātuyā ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno cittaṃ virattaṃ vimuttaṃ hoti anupādāya āsavehi, vedanādhātuyā … pe …**If a mendicant’s mind is dispassionate towards the form element, the feeling element,*";
P_HTM[1156]="*saññādhātuyā …**the perception element,*";
P_HTM[1157]="*saṅkhāradhātuyā …**the choices element,*";
P_HTM[1158]="*viññāṇadhātuyā ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno cittaṃ virattaṃ vimuttaṃ hoti anupādāya āsavehi.**and the consciousness element, it’s freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1159]="*Vimuttattā ṭhitaṃ. Ṭhitattā santusitaṃ. Santusitattā na paritassati. Aparitassaṃ paccattaññeva parinibbāyati.**Being free, it’s stable. Being stable, it’s content. Being content, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1160]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1161]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1162]="*4. Dutiyaaniccasuttaṃ**Impermanence (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1163]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1164]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ.**“Mendicants, form is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1165]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[1166]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[1167]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1168]="*Vedanā aniccā …**Feeling is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[1169]="*saññā aniccā …**Perception is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[1170]="*saṅkhārā aniccā …**Choices are impermanent …*";
P_HTM[1171]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**Consciousness is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1172]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[1173]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[1174]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1175]="*Evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato pubbantānudiṭṭhiyo na honti.**Seeing truly with right understanding like this, they have no theories about the past.*";
P_HTM[1176]="*Pubbantānudiṭṭhīnaṃ asati, aparantānudiṭṭhiyo na honti.**Not having theories about the past, they have no theories about the future.*";
P_HTM[1177]="*Aparantānudiṭṭhīnaṃ asati, thāmaso parāmāso na hoti.**Not having theories about the future, they don’t obstinately stick to them.*";
P_HTM[1178]="*Thāmase parāmāse asati rūpasmiṃ …**Not misapprehending, the mind becomes dispassionate towards form,*";
P_HTM[1179]="*vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[1180]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[1181]="*saṅkhāresu …**choices,*";
P_HTM[1182]="*viññāṇasmiṃ cittaṃ virajjati vimuccati anupādāya āsavehi.**and consciousness; it’s freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1183]="*Vimuttattā ṭhitaṃ. Ṭhitattā santusitaṃ. Santusitattā na paritassati. Aparitassaṃ paccattaññeva parinibbāyati.**Being free, it’s stable. Being stable, it’s content. Being content, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1184]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1185]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1186]="*5. Samanupassanāsuttaṃ**Ways of Regarding*";
P_HTM[1187]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1188]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā anekavihitaṃ attānaṃ samanupassamānā samanupassanti, sabbete pañcupādānakkhandhe samanupassanti, etesaṃ vā aññataraṃ.**“Mendicants, whatever ascetics and brahmins regard various kinds of things as self, all regard the five grasping aggregates, or one of them.*";
P_HTM[1189]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1190]="*Idha, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[1191]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[1192]="*Vedanaṃ …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[1193]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1194]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1195]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1196]="*Iti ayañceva samanupassanā ‘asmī’ti cassa avigataṃ hoti.**So they’re not rid of this way of regarding things and the conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[1197]="*‘Asmī’ti kho pana, bhikkhave, avigate pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ avakkanti hoti—**As long as they’re not rid of the conceit ‘I am’, the five faculties are conceived—*";
P_HTM[1198]="*cakkhundriyassa sotindriyassa ghānindriyassa jivhindriyassa kāyindriyassa.**the eye, ear, nose, tongue, and body.*";
P_HTM[1199]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, mano, atthi dhammā, atthi avijjādhātu.**The mind, thoughts, and the element of ignorance are all present.*";
P_HTM[1200]="*Avijjāsamphassajena, bhikkhave, vedayitena phuṭṭhassa assutavato puthujjanassa ‘asmī’tipissa hoti;**Struck by feelings born of contact with ignorance, an uneducated ordinary person thinks ‘I am’,*";
P_HTM[1201]="*‘ayamahamasmī’tipissa hoti;**‘I am this’,*";
P_HTM[1202]="*‘bhavissan’tipissa hoti;**‘I will be’,*";
P_HTM[1203]="*‘na bhavissan’tipissa hoti;**‘I will not be’,*";
P_HTM[1204]="*‘rūpī bhavissan’tipissa hoti;**‘I will have form’,*";
P_HTM[1205]="*‘arūpī bhavissan’tipissa hoti;**‘I will be formless’,*";
P_HTM[1206]="*‘saññī bhavissan’tipissa hoti;**‘I will be percipient’,*";
P_HTM[1207]="*‘asaññī bhavissan’tipissa hoti;**‘I will not be percipient’,*";
P_HTM[1208]="*‘nevasaññīnāsaññī bhavissan’tipissa hoti.**‘I will be neither percipient nor non-percipient’.*";
P_HTM[1209]="*Tiṭṭhanteva kho, bhikkhave, tattheva pañcindriyāni.**The five faculties stay right where they are.*";
P_HTM[1210]="*Athettha sutavato ariyasāvakassa avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjati.**But an educated noble disciple gives up ignorance about them and gives rise to knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1211]="*Tassa avijjāvirāgā vijjuppādā ‘asmī’tipissa na hoti;**With the fading away of ignorance and the arising of knowledge, they don’t think ‘I am’,*";
P_HTM[1212]="*‘ayamahamasmī’tipissa na hoti;**‘I am this’,*";
P_HTM[1213]="*‘bhavissan’ti …**‘I will be’,*";
P_HTM[1214]="*‘na bhavissan’ti …**‘I will not be’,*";
P_HTM[1215]="*rūpī …**‘I will have form’,*";
P_HTM[1216]="*arūpī …**‘I will be formless’,*";
P_HTM[1217]="*saññī …**‘I will be percipient’,*";
P_HTM[1218]="*asaññī …**‘I will be non-percipient’,*";
P_HTM[1219]="*‘nevasaññīnāsaññī bhavissan’tipissa na hotī”ti.**‘I will be neither percipient nor non-percipient’.”*";
P_HTM[1220]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1221]="*6. Khandhasuttaṃ**Aggregates*";
P_HTM[1222]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1223]="*“Pañca, bhikkhave, khandhe desessāmi, pañcupādānakkhandhe ca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the five aggregates and the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1224]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[1225]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, pañcakkhandhā?**And what are the five aggregates?*";
P_HTM[1226]="*Yaṃ kiñci, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, ayaṃ vuccati rūpakkhandho.**Any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: this is called the aggregate of form.*";
P_HTM[1227]="*Yā kāci vedanā … pe …**Any kind of feeling at all …*";
P_HTM[1228]="*yā kāci saññā …**Any kind of perception at all …*";
P_HTM[1229]="*ye keci saṅkhārā atītānāgatapaccuppannā ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikā vā sukhumā vā … pe … ayaṃ vuccati saṅkhārakkhandho.**Any kind of choices at all …*";
P_HTM[1230]="*Yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, ayaṃ vuccati viññāṇakkhandho.**Any kind of consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: this is called the aggregate of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1231]="*Ime vuccanti, bhikkhave, pañcakkhandhā.**These are called the five aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1232]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, pañcupādānakkhandhā?**And what are the five grasping aggregates?*";
P_HTM[1233]="*Yaṃ kiñci, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ … pe … yaṃ dūre santike vā sāsavaṃ upādāniyaṃ, ayaṃ vuccati rūpupādānakkhandho.**Any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near, which is accompanied by defilements and is prone to being grasped: this is called the aggregate of form connected with grasping.*";
P_HTM[1234]="*Yā kāci vedanā … pe … yā dūre santike vā sāsavā upādāniyā, ayaṃ vuccati vedanupādānakkhandho.**Any kind of feeling at all …*";
P_HTM[1235]="*Yā kāci saññā … pe … yā dūre santike vā sāsavā upādāniyā, ayaṃ vuccati saññupādānakkhandho.**Any kind of perception at all …*";
P_HTM[1236]="*Ye keci saṅkhārā … pe … sāsavā upādāniyā, ayaṃ vuccati saṅkhārupādānakkhandho.**Any kind of choices at all …*";
P_HTM[1237]="*Yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ … pe … yaṃ dūre santike vā sāsavaṃ upādāniyaṃ, ayaṃ vuccati viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**Any kind of consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near, which is accompanied by defilements and is prone to being grasped: this is called the aggregate of consciousness connected with grasping.*";
P_HTM[1238]="*Ime vuccanti, bhikkhave, pañcupādānakkhandhā”ti.**These are called the five grasping aggregates.”*";
P_HTM[1239]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1240]="*7. Soṇasuttaṃ**With Soṇa*";
P_HTM[1241]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1242]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[1243]="*Atha kho soṇo gahapatiputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe …**Then the householder Soṇa went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[1244]="*ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho soṇaṃ gahapatiputtaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[1245]="*“Ye hi keci, soṇa, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā aniccena rūpena dukkhena vipariṇāmadhammena ‘seyyohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;**“Soṇa, there are ascetics and brahmins who—based on form, which is impermanent, suffering, and perishable—regard themselves thus: ‘I’m better’,*";
P_HTM[1246]="*‘sadisohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;**or ‘I’m equal’,*";
P_HTM[1247]="*‘hīnohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;**or ‘I’m worse’.*";
P_HTM[1248]="*kimaññatra yathābhūtassa adassanā?**What is that but a failure to see truly?*";
P_HTM[1249]="*Aniccāya vedanāya dukkhāya vipariṇāmadhammāya ‘seyyohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;**Based on feeling …*";
P_HTM[1250]="*‘sadisohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;* **";
P_HTM[1251]="*‘hīnohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;* **";
P_HTM[1252]="*kimaññatra yathābhūtassa adassanā?* **";
P_HTM[1253]="*Aniccāya saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1254]="*aniccehi saṅkhārehi dukkhehi vipariṇāmadhammehi ‘seyyohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;**choices …*";
P_HTM[1255]="*‘sadisohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;* **";
P_HTM[1256]="*‘hīnohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;* **";
P_HTM[1257]="*kimaññatra yathābhūtassa adassanā?* **";
P_HTM[1258]="*Aniccena viññāṇena dukkhena vipariṇāmadhammena ‘seyyohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;**consciousness, which is impermanent, suffering, and perishable, they regard themselves thus: ‘I’m better’,*";
P_HTM[1259]="*‘sadisohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;**or ‘I’m equal’,*";
P_HTM[1260]="*‘hīnohamasmī’ti vā samanupassanti;**or ‘I’m worse’.*";
P_HTM[1261]="*kimaññatra yathābhūtassa adassanā?**What is that but a failure to see truly?*";
P_HTM[1262]="*Ye ca kho keci, soṇa, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā aniccena rūpena dukkhena vipariṇāmadhammena ‘seyyohamasmī’tipi na samanupassanti;**There are ascetics and brahmins who—based on form, which is impermanent, suffering, and perishable—don’t regard themselves thus: ‘I’m better’,*";
P_HTM[1263]="*‘sadisohamasmī’tipi na samanupassanti;**or ‘I’m equal’,*";
P_HTM[1264]="*‘hīnohamasmī’tipi na samanupassanti;**or ‘I’m worse’.*";
P_HTM[1265]="*kimaññatra yathābhūtassa dassanā?**What is that but seeing truly?*";
P_HTM[1266]="*Aniccāya vedanāya …**Based on feeling …*";
P_HTM[1267]="*aniccāya saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1268]="*aniccehi saṅkhārehi …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1269]="*aniccena viññāṇena dukkhena vipariṇāmadhammena ‘seyyohamasmī’tipi na samanupassanti;**consciousness, which is impermanent, suffering, and perishable, they don’t regard themselves thus: ‘I’m better’,*";
P_HTM[1270]="*‘sadisohamasmī’tipi na samanupassanti;**or ‘I’m equal’,*";
P_HTM[1271]="*‘hīnohamasmī’tipi na samanupassanti;**or ‘I’m worse’.*";
P_HTM[1272]="*kimaññatra yathābhūtassa dassanā?**What is that but seeing truly?*";
P_HTM[1273]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, soṇa,**What do you think, Soṇa?*";
P_HTM[1274]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1275]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1276]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1277]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1278]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1279]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1280]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1281]="*“Vedanā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[1282]="*“Aniccā, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[1283]="*“saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1284]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1285]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1286]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1287]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1288]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1289]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1290]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1291]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1292]="*“Tasmātiha, soṇa, yaṃ kiñci rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ rūpaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**“So, Soṇa, you should truly see any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1293]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**You should truly see any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[1294]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1295]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1296]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1297]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, soṇa, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi nibbindati, saññāyapi nibbindati, saṅkhāresupi nibbindati, viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1298]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1299]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1300]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1301]="*8. Dutiyasoṇasuttaṃ**With Soṇa (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1302]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1303]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[1304]="*Atha kho soṇo gahapatiputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho soṇaṃ gahapatiputtaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then the householder Soṇa went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[1305]="*“Ye hi keci, soṇa, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā rūpaṃ nappajānanti, rūpasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, rūpanirodhaṃ nappajānanti, rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti;**“Soṇa, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t understand form, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1306]="*vedanaṃ nappajānanti, vedanāsamudayaṃ nappajānanti, vedanānirodhaṃ nappajānanti, vedanānirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti;**They don’t understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[1307]="*saññaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1308]="*saṅkhāre nappajānanti, saṅkhārasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, saṅkhāranirodhaṃ nappajānanti, saṅkhāranirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti;**choices …*";
P_HTM[1309]="*viññāṇaṃ nappajānanti, viññāṇasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, viññāṇanirodhaṃ nappajānanti, viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti.**consciousness, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1310]="*Na me te, soṇa, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā, na ca pana te āyasmanto sāmaññatthaṃ vā brahmaññatthaṃ vā diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[1311]="*Ye ca kho keci, soṇa, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā rūpaṃ pajānanti, rūpasamudayaṃ pajānanti, rūpanirodhaṃ pajānanti, rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti;**There are ascetics and brahmins who do understand form, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1312]="*vedanaṃ pajānanti … pe …**They do understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[1313]="*saññaṃ pajānanti …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1314]="*saṅkhāre pajānanti …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1315]="*viññāṇaṃ pajānanti, viññāṇasamudayaṃ pajānanti, viññāṇanirodhaṃ pajānanti, viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti.**consciousness, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1316]="*Te ca kho me, soṇa, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā, te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[1317]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1318]="*9. Nandikkhayasuttaṃ**The End of Relishing*";
P_HTM[1319]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1320]="*“Aniccaññeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu rūpaṃ aniccanti passati. Sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**“Mendicants, form really is impermanent. A mendicant sees that it is impermanent: that’s their right view.*";
P_HTM[1321]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.**Seeing rightly, they grow disillusioned.*";
P_HTM[1322]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo, rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[1323]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is freed, and is said to be well freed.*";
P_HTM[1324]="*Aniccaññeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vedanaṃ aniccanti passati. Sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[1325]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.* **";
P_HTM[1326]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo, rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[1327]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[1328]="*Aniccaññeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saññaṃ aniccanti passati … pe …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[1329]="*anicceyeva bhikkhave, bhikkhu saṅkhāre aniccāti passati. Sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**Choices …*";
P_HTM[1330]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.* **";
P_HTM[1331]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo, rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[1332]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[1333]="*Aniccaññeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu viññāṇaṃ aniccanti passati. Sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**Consciousness really is impermanent. A mendicant sees that it is impermanent: that’s their right view.*";
P_HTM[1334]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.**Seeing rightly, they grow disillusioned.*";
P_HTM[1335]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo, rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[1336]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ suvimuttanti vuccatī”ti.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is freed, and is said to be well freed.”*";
P_HTM[1337]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1338]="*10. Dutiyanandikkhayasuttaṃ**The End of Relishing (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1339]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1340]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, rūpāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**“Mendicants, properly attend to form. Truly see the impermanence of form.*";
P_HTM[1341]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasi karonto, rūpāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto rūpasmiṃ nibbindati.**When a mendicant does this, they grow disillusioned with form.*";
P_HTM[1342]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo, rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[1343]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is freed, and is said to be well freed.*";
P_HTM[1344]="*Vedanaṃ, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, vedanāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**Properly attend to feeling …*";
P_HTM[1345]="*Vedanaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasi karonto, vedanāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto vedanāya nibbindati.* **";
P_HTM[1346]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo, rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[1347]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[1348]="*Saññaṃ bhikkhave …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1349]="*saṅkhāre, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, saṅkhārāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**choices …*";
P_HTM[1350]="*Saṅkhāre, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasi karonto, saṅkhārāniccataṃ yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto saṅkhāresu nibbindati.* **";
P_HTM[1351]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo, rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[1352]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[1353]="*Viññāṇaṃ, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, viññāṇāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**consciousness. Truly see the impermanence of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1354]="*Viññāṇaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasi karonto, viññāṇāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto viññāṇasmiṃ nibbindati.**When a mendicant does this, they grow disillusioned with consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1355]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo, rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[1356]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ suvimuttanti vuccatī”ti.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is freed, and is said to be well freed.”*";
P_HTM[1357]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1358]="*Attadīpavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[1359]="*Attadīpā paṭipadā,* **";
P_HTM[1360]="*Dve ca honti aniccatā;* **";
P_HTM[1361]="*Samanupassanā khandhā,* **";
P_HTM[1362]="*Dve soṇā dve nandikkhayena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[1363]="*Mūlapaṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[1364]="*Nakulapitā anicco ca,* **";
P_HTM[1365]="*Bhāro natumhākena ca;* **";
P_HTM[1366]="*Attadīpena paññāso,* **";
P_HTM[1367]="*Paṭhamo tena pavuccatīti.* **";
P_HTM[1368]="*sn/sn22.053.xhtml==6. Upayavagga==6. Upayavaggo**Involvement*";
P_HTM[1369]="*1. Upayasuttaṃ**Involvement*";
P_HTM[1370]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1371]="*“Upayo, bhikkhave, avimutto, anupayo vimutto.**“Mendicants, if you’re involved, you’re not free. If you’re not involved, you’re free.*";
P_HTM[1372]="*Rūpupayaṃ vā, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭheyya, rūpārammaṇaṃ rūpappatiṭṭhaṃ nandūpasecanaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyya.**As long as consciousness remains, it would remain involved with form, supported by form, founded on form. And with a sprinkle of relishing, it would grow, increase, and mature.*";
P_HTM[1373]="*Vedanupayaṃ vā … pe …**Or consciousness would remain involved with feeling …*";
P_HTM[1374]="*saññupayaṃ vā … pe …**Or consciousness would remain involved with perception …*";
P_HTM[1375]="*saṅkhārupayaṃ vā, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭheyya, saṅkhārārammaṇaṃ saṅkhārappatiṭṭhaṃ nandūpasecanaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyya.**Or as long as consciousness remains, it would remain involved with choices, supported by choices, grounded on choices. And with a sprinkle of relishing, it would grow, increase, and mature.*";
P_HTM[1376]="*Yo, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadeyya:**Mendicants, suppose you say:*";
P_HTM[1377]="*‘ahamaññatra rūpā aññatra vedanāya aññatra saññāya aññatra saṅkhārehi viññāṇassa āgatiṃ vā gatiṃ vā cutiṃ vā upapattiṃ vā vuddhiṃ vā virūḷhiṃ vā vepullaṃ vā paññāpessāmī’ti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**‘Apart from form, feeling, perception, and choices, I will describe the coming and going of consciousness, its passing away and reappearing, its growth, increase, and maturity.’ That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[1378]="*Rūpadhātuyā ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno rāgo pahīno hoti.**If a mendicant has given up greed for the form element,*";
P_HTM[1379]="*Rāgassa pahānā vocchijjatārammaṇaṃ patiṭṭhā viññāṇassa na hoti.**the support is cut off, and there is no foundation for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1380]="*Vedanādhātuyā ce, bhikkhave …**If a mendicant has given up greed for the feeling element …*";
P_HTM[1381]="*saññādhātuyā ce, bhikkhave …**perception element …*";
P_HTM[1382]="*saṅkhāradhātuyā ce, bhikkhave …**choices element …*";
P_HTM[1383]="*viññāṇadhātuyā ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno rāgo pahīno hoti.**consciousness element,*";
P_HTM[1384]="*Rāgassa pahānā vocchijjatārammaṇaṃ patiṭṭhā viññāṇassa na hoti.**the support is cut off, and there is no foundation for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1385]="*Tadappatiṭṭhitaṃ viññāṇaṃ avirūḷhaṃ anabhisaṅkhacca vimuttaṃ.**Since that consciousness does not become established and does not grow, with no power to regenerate, it is freed.*";
P_HTM[1386]="*Vimuttattā ṭhitaṃ. Ṭhitattā santusitaṃ. Santusitattā na paritassati. Aparitassaṃ paccattaññeva parinibbāyati.**Being free, it’s stable. Being stable, it’s content. Being content, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1387]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1388]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1389]="*2. Bījasuttaṃ**A Seed*";
P_HTM[1390]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1391]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, bījajātāni.**“Mendicants, there are five kinds of plants propagated from seeds.*";
P_HTM[1392]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1393]="*Mūlabījaṃ, khandhabījaṃ, aggabījaṃ, phalubījaṃ, bījabījaññeva pañcamaṃ.**Plants propagated from roots, stems, cuttings, or joints; and those from regular seeds are the fifth.*";
P_HTM[1394]="*Imāni cassu, bhikkhave, pañca bījajātāni akhaṇḍāni apūtikāni avātātapahatāni sārādāni sukhasayitāni, pathavī ca nāssa, āpo ca nāssa;**Suppose these five kinds of plants propagated from seeds were intact, unspoiled, not weather-damaged, fertile, and well-kept. But there’s no soil or water.*";
P_HTM[1395]="*api numāni, bhikkhave, pañca bījajātāni vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyyun”ti?**Then would these five kinds of plants propagated from seeds reach growth, increase, and maturity?”*";
P_HTM[1396]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1397]="*“Imāni cassu, bhikkhave, pañca bījajātāni akhaṇḍāni … pe … sukhasayitāni, pathavī ca assa, āpo ca assa;**“Suppose these five kinds of plants propagated from seeds were intact, unspoiled, not weather-damaged, fertile, and well-kept. And there is soil and water.*";
P_HTM[1398]="*api numāni, bhikkhave, pañca bījajātāni vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyyun”ti?**Then would these five kinds of plants propagated from seeds reach growth, increase, and maturity?”*";
P_HTM[1399]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1400]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, pathavīdhātu, evaṃ catasso viññāṇaṭṭhitiyo daṭṭhabbā.**“The four grounds of consciousness should be seen as like the earth element.*";
P_HTM[1401]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, āpodhātu, evaṃ nandirāgo daṭṭhabbo.**Relishing and greed should be seen as like the water element.*";
P_HTM[1402]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, pañca bījajātāni, evaṃ viññāṇaṃ sāhāraṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**Consciousness with its fuel should be seen as like the five kinds of plants propagated from seeds.*";
P_HTM[1403]="*Rūpupayaṃ, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭheyya, rūpārammaṇaṃ rūpappatiṭṭhaṃ nandūpasecanaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyya.**As long as consciousness remains, it would remain involved with form, supported by form, grounded on form. And with a sprinkle of relishing, it would grow, increase, and mature.*";
P_HTM[1404]="*Vedanupayaṃ vā, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭheyya … pe …**Or consciousness would remain involved with feeling …*";
P_HTM[1405]="*saññupayaṃ vā, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭheyya … pe …**Or consciousness would remain involved with perception …*";
P_HTM[1406]="*saṅkhārupayaṃ vā, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭheyya, saṅkhārārammaṇaṃ saṅkhārappatiṭṭhaṃ nandūpasecanaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyya.**Or as long as consciousness remains, it would remain involved with choices, supported by choices, grounded on choices. And with a sprinkle of relishing, it would grow, increase, and mature.*";
P_HTM[1407]="*Yo, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadeyya:**Mendicants, suppose you say:*";
P_HTM[1408]="*‘ahamaññatra rūpā aññatra vedanāya aññatra saññāya aññatra saṅkhārehi viññāṇassa āgatiṃ vā gatiṃ vā cutiṃ vā upapattiṃ vā vuddhiṃ vā virūḷhiṃ vā vepullaṃ vā paññāpessāmī’ti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**‘Apart from form, feeling, perception, and choices, I will describe the coming and going of consciousness, its passing away and reappearing, its growth, increase, and maturity.’ That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[1409]="*Rūpadhātuyā ceva, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno rāgo pahīno hoti.**If a mendicant has given up greed for the form element,*";
P_HTM[1410]="*Rāgassa pahānā vocchijjatārammaṇaṃ patiṭṭhā viññāṇassa na hoti.**the support is cut off, and there is no foundation for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1411]="*Vedanādhātuyā ce …**If a mendicant has given up greed for the feeling element …*";
P_HTM[1412]="*saññādhātuyā ce …**perception element …*";
P_HTM[1413]="*saṅkhāradhātuyā ce …**choices element …*";
P_HTM[1414]="*viññāṇadhātuyā ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno rāgo pahīno hoti.**consciousness element,*";
P_HTM[1415]="*Rāgassa pahānā vocchijjatārammaṇaṃ patiṭṭhā viññāṇassa na hoti.**the support is cut off, and there is no foundation for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1416]="*Tadappatiṭṭhitaṃ viññāṇaṃ avirūḷhaṃ anabhisaṅkhacca vimuttaṃ.**Since that consciousness does not become established and does not grow, with no power to regenerate, it is freed.*";
P_HTM[1417]="*Vimuttattā ṭhitaṃ. Ṭhitattā santusitaṃ. Santusitattā na paritassati. Aparitassaṃ paccattaññeva parinibbāyati.**Being free, it’s stable. Being stable, it’s content. Being content, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1418]="*‘Khīṇā jāti … pe … nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended … there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1419]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1420]="*3. Udānasuttaṃ**An Inspired Saying*";
P_HTM[1421]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1422]="*Tatra kho bhagavā udānaṃ udānesi:**There the Buddha was inspired to exclaim:*";
P_HTM[1423]="*“‘no cassaṃ, no ca me siyā, nābhavissa, na me bhavissatī’ti—**“‘It might not be, and it might not be mine. It will not be, and it will not be mine.’*";
P_HTM[1424]="*evaṃ adhimuccamāno bhikkhu chindeyya orambhāgiyāni saṃyojanānī”ti.**A mendicant who makes such a resolution can cut off the five lower fetters.”*";
P_HTM[1425]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants asked the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1426]="*“yathā kathaṃ pana, bhante, ‘no cassaṃ, no ca me siyā, nābhavissa, na me bhavissatī’ti—**“But sir, how*";
P_HTM[1427]="*evaṃ adhimuccamāno bhikkhu chindeyya orambhāgiyāni saṃyojanānī”ti?**can a mendicant who makes such a resolution cut off the five lower fetters?”*";
P_HTM[1428]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī … pe …**“Mendicant, take an uneducated ordinary person who has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in their teaching. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in their teaching.*";
P_HTM[1429]="*sappurisadhamme avinīto rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[1430]="*Vedanaṃ …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[1431]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1432]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1433]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1434]="*So aniccaṃ rūpaṃ ‘aniccaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**They don’t truly understand form—which is impermanent—as impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1435]="*aniccaṃ vedanaṃ ‘aniccā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[1436]="*aniccaṃ saññaṃ ‘aniccā saññā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**perception …*";
P_HTM[1437]="*anicce saṅkhāre ‘aniccā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**choices …*";
P_HTM[1438]="*aniccaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘aniccaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is impermanent—as impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1439]="*Dukkhaṃ rūpaṃ ‘dukkhaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**They don’t truly understand form—which is suffering—as suffering.*";
P_HTM[1440]="*dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ …**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[1441]="*dukkhaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1442]="*dukkhe saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1443]="*dukkhaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘dukkhaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is suffering—as suffering.*";
P_HTM[1444]="*Anattaṃ rūpaṃ ‘anattā rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**They don’t truly understand form—which is not-self—as not-self.*";
P_HTM[1445]="*anattaṃ vedanaṃ ‘anattā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[1446]="*anattaṃ saññaṃ ‘anattā saññā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**perception …*";
P_HTM[1447]="*anatte saṅkhāre ‘anattā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**choices …*";
P_HTM[1448]="*anattaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘anattā viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is not-self—as not-self.*";
P_HTM[1449]="*Saṅkhataṃ rūpaṃ ‘saṅkhataṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti,**They don’t truly understand form—which is conditioned—as conditioned.*";
P_HTM[1450]="*saṅkhataṃ vedanaṃ …**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[1451]="*saṅkhataṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1452]="*saṅkhate saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1453]="*saṅkhataṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘saṅkhataṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is conditioned—as conditioned.*";
P_HTM[1454]="*Rūpaṃ vibhavissatīti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand that form will disappear.*";
P_HTM[1455]="*Vedanā vibhavissati …**They don’t truly understand that feeling …*";
P_HTM[1456]="*saññā vibhavissati …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1457]="*saṅkhārā vibhavissanti …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1458]="*viññāṇaṃ vibhavissatīti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness will disappear.*";
P_HTM[1459]="*Sutavā ca kho, bhikkhu, ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto**But an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[1460]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati … pe …**They don’t regard form as self …*";
P_HTM[1461]="*na vedanaṃ …**They don’t regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[1462]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1463]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1464]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati.**consciousness as self.*";
P_HTM[1465]="*So aniccaṃ rūpaṃ ‘aniccaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand form—which is impermanent—as impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1466]="*Aniccaṃ vedanaṃ …**They truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[1467]="*aniccaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1468]="*anicce saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1469]="*aniccaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘aniccaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness—which is impermanent—as impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1470]="*Dukkhaṃ rūpaṃ … pe … dukkhaṃ viññāṇaṃ …**They truly understand form … feeling … perception … choices … consciousness—which is suffering—as suffering.*";
P_HTM[1471]="*anattaṃ rūpaṃ … pe … anattaṃ viññāṇaṃ …**They truly understand form … feeling … perception … choices … consciousness—which is not-self—as not-self.*";
P_HTM[1472]="*saṅkhataṃ rūpaṃ … pe … saṅkhataṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘saṅkhataṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand form … feeling … perception … choices … consciousness—which is conditioned—as conditioned.*";
P_HTM[1473]="*Rūpaṃ vibhavissatīti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand that form will disappear.*";
P_HTM[1474]="*Vedanā …**They truly understand that feeling …*";
P_HTM[1475]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1476]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1477]="*viññāṇaṃ vibhavissatīti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness will disappear.*";
P_HTM[1478]="*So rūpassa vibhavā, vedanāya vibhavā, saññāya vibhavā, saṅkhārānaṃ vibhavā, viññāṇassa vibhavā, evaṃ kho, bhikkhu,**It’s because of the disappearance of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness that a mendicant who makes such a resolution—*";
P_HTM[1479]="*‘no cassaṃ, no ca me siyā, nābhavissa, na me bhavissatī’ti—**‘It might not be, and it might not be mine. It will not be, and it will not be mine’—*";
P_HTM[1480]="*evaṃ adhimuccamāno bhikkhu chindeyya orambhāgiyāni saṃyojanānī”ti.**can cut off the five lower fetters.”*";
P_HTM[1481]="*“Evaṃ adhimuccamāno, bhante, bhikkhu chindeyya orambhāgiyāni saṃyojanānī”ti.**“Sir, a mendicant who makes such a resolution can cut off the five lower fetters.*";
P_HTM[1482]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, jānato kathaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hotī”ti?**But how are they to know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life?”*";
P_HTM[1483]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, assutavā puthujjano atasitāye ṭhāne tāsaṃ āpajjati.**“Mendicant, an uneducated ordinary person worries about things that aren’t a worry.*";
P_HTM[1484]="*Tāso heso bhikkhu assutavato puthujjanassa:**For an uneducated ordinary person worries:*";
P_HTM[1485]="*‘no cassaṃ, no ca me siyā, nābhavissa, na me bhavissatī’ti.**‘It might not be, and it might not be mine. It will not be, and it will not be mine.’*";
P_HTM[1486]="*Sutavā ca kho, bhikkhu, ariyasāvako atasitāye ṭhāne na tāsaṃ āpajjati.**An educated noble disciple doesn’t worry about things that aren’t a worry.*";
P_HTM[1487]="*Na heso, bhikkhu, tāso sutavato ariyasāvakassa:**For an educated noble disciple doesn’t worry:*";
P_HTM[1488]="*‘no cassaṃ, no ca me siyā, nābhavissa, na me bhavissatī’ti.**‘It might not be, and it might not be mine. It will not be, and it will not be mine.’*";
P_HTM[1489]="*Rūpupayaṃ vā, bhikkhu, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭheyya, rūpārammaṇaṃ rūpappatiṭṭhaṃ nandūpasecanaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyya.**As long as consciousness remains, it would remain involved with form, supported by form, founded on form. And with a sprinkle of relishing, it would grow, increase, and mature.*";
P_HTM[1490]="*Vedanupayaṃ vā, bhikkhu …**Or consciousness would remain involved with feeling …*";
P_HTM[1491]="*saññupayaṃ vā, bhikkhu …**Or consciousness would remain involved with perception …*";
P_HTM[1492]="*saṅkhārupayaṃ vā, bhikkhu, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭheyya, saṅkhārārammaṇaṃ saṅkhārappatiṭṭhaṃ nandūpasecanaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyya.**Or consciousness would remain involved with choices, supported by choices, grounded on choices. And with a sprinkle of relishing, it would grow, increase, and mature.*";
P_HTM[1493]="*Yo, bhikkhu, evaṃ vadeyya:**Mendicants, suppose you say:*";
P_HTM[1494]="*‘ahamaññatra rūpā, aññatra vedanāya, aññatra saññāya, aññatra saṅkhārehi viññāṇassa āgatiṃ vā gatiṃ vā cutiṃ vā upapattiṃ vā vuddhiṃ vā virūḷhiṃ vā vepullaṃ vā paññāpessāmī’ti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**‘Apart from form, feeling, perception, and choices, I will describe the coming and going of consciousness, its passing away and reappearing, its growth, increase, and maturity.’ That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[1495]="*Rūpadhātuyā ce, bhikkhu, bhikkhuno rāgo pahīno hoti. Rāgassa pahānā vocchijjatārammaṇaṃ patiṭṭhā viññāṇassa na hoti.**If a mendicant has given up greed for the form element, the support is cut off, and there is no foundation for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1496]="*Vedanādhātuyā ce, bhikkhu, bhikkhuno …**If a mendicant has given up greed for the feeling element …*";
P_HTM[1497]="*saññādhātuyā ce, bhikkhu, bhikkhuno …**perception element …*";
P_HTM[1498]="*saṅkhāradhātuyā ce, bhikkhu, bhikkhuno …**choices element …*";
P_HTM[1499]="*viññāṇadhātuyā ce, bhikkhu, bhikkhuno rāgo pahīno hoti. Rāgassa pahānā vocchijjatārammaṇaṃ patiṭṭhā viññāṇassa na hoti.**consciousness element, the support is cut off, and there is no foundation for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1500]="*Tadappatiṭṭhitaṃ viññāṇaṃ avirūḷhaṃ anabhisaṅkhacca vimuttaṃ.**Since that consciousness does not become established and does not grow, with no power to regenerate, it is freed.*";
P_HTM[1501]="*Vimuttattā ṭhitaṃ. Ṭhitattā santusitaṃ. Santusitattā na paritassati. Aparitassaṃ paccattaññeva parinibbāyati.**Being free, it’s stable. Being stable, it’s content. Being content, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1502]="*‘Khīṇā jāti … pe … nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended … there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1503]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, jānato evaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hotī”ti.**The ending of the defilements is for one who knows and sees this.”*";
P_HTM[1504]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1505]="*4. Upādānaparipavattasuttaṃ**Perspectives*";
P_HTM[1506]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1507]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, upādānakkhandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1508]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1509]="*Rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**The grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1510]="*Yāvakīvañcāhaṃ, bhikkhave, ime pañcupādānakkhandhe catuparivaṭṭaṃ yathābhūtaṃ nābbhaññāsiṃ, neva tāvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddhoti paccaññāsiṃ.**As long as I didn’t truly understand these five grasping aggregates from four perspectives, I didn’t announce my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[1511]="*Yato ca khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, ime pañcupādānakkhandhe catuparivaṭṭaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, athāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke … pe …**But when I did truly understand these five grasping aggregates from four perspectives, I announced my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[1512]="*sadevamanussāya anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddhoti paccaññāsiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1513]="*Kathañca catuparivaṭṭaṃ?**And how are there four perspectives?*";
P_HTM[1514]="*Rūpaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, rūpasamudayaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, rūpanirodhaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ;**I directly knew form, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1515]="*vedanaṃ …**I directly knew feeling …*";
P_HTM[1516]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1517]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1518]="*viññāṇaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, viññāṇasamudayaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, viññāṇanirodhaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ.**consciousness, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1519]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ?**And what is form?*";
P_HTM[1520]="*Cattāro ca mahābhūtā catunnañca mahābhūtānaṃ upādāya rūpaṃ.**The four primary elements, and form derived from the four primary elements.*";
P_HTM[1521]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ.**This is called form.*";
P_HTM[1522]="*Āhārasamudayā rūpasamudayo;**Form originates from food.*";
P_HTM[1523]="*āhāranirodhā rūpanirodho.**When food ceases, form ceases.*";
P_HTM[1524]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo rūpanirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of form is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[1525]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[1526]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ rūpaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpanirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya rūpassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipannā, te suppaṭipannā.**Those ascetics and brahmins who have directly known form in this way—and its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation—and are practicing for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form: they are practicing well.*";
P_HTM[1527]="*Ye suppaṭipannā, te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye gādhanti.**Those who practice well have a firm footing in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[1528]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ rūpaṃ abhiññāya … pe … evaṃ rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya, rūpassa nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimuttā te suvimuttā.**Those ascetics and brahmins who have directly known form in this way—and its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation—and due to disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form, are freed by not grasping: they are well freed.*";
P_HTM[1529]="*Ye suvimuttā te kevalino.**Those who are well freed are consummate ones.*";
P_HTM[1530]="*Ye kevalino vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.**For consummate ones, there is no cycle of rebirths to be found.*";
P_HTM[1531]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, vedanā?**And what is feeling?*";
P_HTM[1532]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, vedanākāyā—**There are these six classes of feeling:*";
P_HTM[1533]="*cakkhusamphassajā vedanā, sotasamphassajā vedanā, ghānasamphassajā vedanā, jivhāsamphassajā vedanā, kāyasamphassajā vedanā, manosamphassajā vedanā.**feeling born of contact through the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1534]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, vedanā.**This is called feeling.*";
P_HTM[1535]="*Phassasamudayā vedanāsamudayo;**Feeling originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[1536]="*phassanirodhā vedanānirodho.**When contact ceases, feeling ceases.*";
P_HTM[1537]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of feelings is simply this noble eightfold path …*";
P_HTM[1538]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[1539]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ vedanaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ vedanāsamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ vedanānirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ vedanānirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya vedanāya nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipannā, te suppaṭipannā.* **";
P_HTM[1540]="*Ye suppaṭipannā, te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye gādhanti.* **";
P_HTM[1541]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ vedanaṃ abhiññāya … pe … evaṃ vedanānirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1542]="*vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1543]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, saññā?**And what is perception?*";
P_HTM[1544]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, saññākāyā—**There are these six classes of perception:*";
P_HTM[1545]="*rūpasaññā, saddasaññā, gandhasaññā, rasasaññā, phoṭṭhabbasaññā, dhammasaññā.**perceptions of sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1546]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saññā.**This is called perception.*";
P_HTM[1547]="*Phassasamudayā saññāsamudayo;**Perception originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[1548]="*phassanirodhā saññānirodho.**When contact ceases, perception ceases.*";
P_HTM[1549]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo saññānirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of perceptions is simply this noble eightfold path …*";
P_HTM[1550]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1551]="*vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1552]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, saṅkhārā?**And what are choices?*";
P_HTM[1553]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, cetanākāyā—**There are these six classes of intention:*";
P_HTM[1554]="*rūpasañcetanā, saddasañcetanā, gandhasañcetanā, rasasañcetanā, phoṭṭhabbasañcetanā, dhammasañcetanā.**intention regarding sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1555]="*Ime vuccanti, bhikkhave, saṅkhārā.**These are called choices.*";
P_HTM[1556]="*Phassasamudayā saṅkhārasamudayo;**Choices originate from contact.*";
P_HTM[1557]="*phassanirodhā saṅkhāranirodho.**When contact ceases, choices cease.*";
P_HTM[1558]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo saṅkhāranirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of choices is simply this noble eightfold path …*";
P_HTM[1559]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[1560]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ saṅkhāre abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhārasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhāranirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhāranirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya saṅkhārānaṃ nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipannā, te suppaṭipannā.* **";
P_HTM[1561]="*Ye suppaṭipannā, te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye gādhanti.* **";
P_HTM[1562]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ saṅkhāre abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhārasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhāranirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhāranirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya saṅkhārānaṃ nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimuttā, te suvimuttā.* **";
P_HTM[1563]="*Ye suvimuttā, te kevalino.* **";
P_HTM[1564]="*Ye kevalino vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1565]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ?**And what is consciousness?*";
P_HTM[1566]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, viññāṇakāyā—**There are these six classes of consciousness:*";
P_HTM[1567]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ, sotaviññāṇaṃ, ghānaviññāṇaṃ, jivhāviññāṇaṃ, kāyaviññāṇaṃ, manoviññāṇaṃ.**eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1568]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ.**This is called consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1569]="*Nāmarūpasamudayā viññāṇasamudayo;**Consciousness originates from name and form.*";
P_HTM[1570]="*nāmarūpanirodhā viññāṇanirodho.**When name and form cease, consciousness ceases.*";
P_HTM[1571]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo viññāṇanirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of consciousness is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[1572]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[1573]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ viññāṇaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇanirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya viññāṇassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipannā, te suppaṭipannā.**Those ascetics and brahmins who have directly known consciousness in this way—and its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation—and are practicing for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness: they are practicing well.*";
P_HTM[1574]="*Ye suppaṭipannā, te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye gādhanti.**Those who practice well have a firm footing in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[1575]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ viññāṇaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇanirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya viññāṇassa nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimuttā, te suvimuttā.**Those ascetics and brahmins who have directly known consciousness in this way—and its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation—and due to disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness, are freed by not grasping: they are well freed.*";
P_HTM[1576]="*Ye suvimuttā, te kevalino.**Those who are well freed are consummate ones.*";
P_HTM[1577]="*Ye kevalino vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāyā”ti.**For consummate ones, there is no cycle of rebirths to be found.”*";
P_HTM[1578]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1579]="*5. Sattaṭṭhānasuttaṃ**Seven Cases*";
P_HTM[1580]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1581]="*“Sattaṭṭhānakusalo, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tividhūpaparikkhī imasmiṃ dhammavinaye kevalī vusitavā uttamapurisoti vuccati.**“Mendicants, in this teaching and training a mendicant who is skilled in seven cases and who examines in three ways is called consummate, accomplished, a supreme person.*";
P_HTM[1582]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sattaṭṭhānakusalo hoti?**And how is a mendicant skilled in seven cases?*";
P_HTM[1583]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu rūpaṃ pajānāti, rūpasamudayaṃ pajānāti, rūpanirodhaṃ pajānāti, rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānāti;**It’s when a mendicant understands form, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1584]="*rūpassa assādaṃ pajānāti, rūpassa ādīnavaṃ pajānāti, rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ pajānāti;**They understand form’s gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[1585]="*vedanaṃ pajānāti …**They understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[1586]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1587]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1588]="*viññāṇaṃ pajānāti, viññāṇasamudayaṃ pajānāti, viññāṇanirodhaṃ pajānāti, viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānāti;**consciousness, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1589]="*viññāṇassa assādaṃ pajānāti, viññāṇassa ādīnavaṃ pajānāti, viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ pajānāti.**They understand consciousness’s gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[1590]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ?**And what is form?*";
P_HTM[1591]="*Cattāro ca mahābhūtā, catunnañca mahābhūtānaṃ upādāya rūpaṃ.**The four primary elements, and form derived from the four primary elements.*";
P_HTM[1592]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ.**This is called form.*";
P_HTM[1593]="*Āhārasamudayā rūpasamudayo;**Form originates from food.*";
P_HTM[1594]="*āhāranirodhā rūpanirodho.**When food ceases, form ceases.*";
P_HTM[1595]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo rūpanirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of form is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[1596]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[1597]="*Yaṃ rūpaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ—**The pleasure and happiness that arise from form: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[1598]="*ayaṃ rūpassa assādo.* **";
P_HTM[1599]="*Yaṃ rūpaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ—**That form is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[1600]="*ayaṃ rūpassa ādīnavo.* **";
P_HTM[1601]="*Yo rūpasmiṃ chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ—**Removing and giving up desire and greed for form: this is its escape.*";
P_HTM[1602]="*idaṃ rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1603]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ rūpaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpanirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya;**Those ascetics and brahmins who have directly known form in this way—and its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation;*";
P_HTM[1604]="*evaṃ rūpassa assādaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpassa ādīnavaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ abhiññāya rūpassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipannā, te suppaṭipannā.**its gratification, drawback, and escape—and are practicing for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form: they are practicing well.*";
P_HTM[1605]="*Ye suppaṭipannā, te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye gādhanti.**Those who practice well have a firm footing in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[1606]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ rūpaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpanirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya;**Those ascetics and brahmins who have directly known form in this way—and its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation;*";
P_HTM[1607]="*evaṃ rūpassa assādaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpassa ādīnavaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ abhiññāya rūpassa nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimuttā, te suvimuttā.**its gratification, drawback, and escape—and due to disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form, are freed by not grasping: they are well freed.*";
P_HTM[1608]="*Ye suvimuttā, te kevalino.**Those who are well freed are consummate ones.*";
P_HTM[1609]="*Ye kevalino vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.**For consummate ones, there is no cycle of rebirths to be found.*";
P_HTM[1610]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, vedanā?**And what is feeling?*";
P_HTM[1611]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, vedanākāyā—**There are these six classes of feeling:*";
P_HTM[1612]="*cakkhusamphassajā vedanā … pe …**feeling born of eye contact …*";
P_HTM[1613]="*manosamphassajā vedanā.**feeling born of mind contact.*";
P_HTM[1614]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, vedanā.**This is called feeling.*";
P_HTM[1615]="*Phassasamudayā vedanāsamudayo;**Feeling originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[1616]="*phassanirodhā vedanānirodho.**When contact ceases, feeling ceases.*";
P_HTM[1617]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of feelings is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[1618]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[1619]="*Yaṃ vedanaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ—**The pleasure and happiness that arise from feeling: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[1620]="*ayaṃ vedanāya assādo.* **";
P_HTM[1621]="*Yā vedanā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā—**That feeling is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[1622]="*ayaṃ vedanāya ādīnavo.* **";
P_HTM[1623]="*Yo vedanāya chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ—**Removing and giving up desire and greed for feeling: this is its escape. …*";
P_HTM[1624]="*idaṃ vedanāya nissaraṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1625]="*Ye hi, keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ vedanaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ vedanāsamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ vedanānirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ vedanānirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya;* **";
P_HTM[1626]="*evaṃ vedanāya assādaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ vedanāya ādīnavaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ vedanāya nissaraṇaṃ abhiññāya vedanāya nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipannā, te suppaṭipannā.* **";
P_HTM[1627]="*Ye suppaṭipannā, te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye gādhanti.* **";
P_HTM[1628]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ vedanaṃ abhiññāya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1629]="*vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1630]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, saññā?**And what is perception?*";
P_HTM[1631]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, saññākāyā—**There are these six classes of perception:*";
P_HTM[1632]="*rūpasaññā, saddasaññā, gandhasaññā, rasasaññā, phoṭṭhabbasaññā, dhammasaññā.**perceptions of sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1633]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saññā.**This is called perception.*";
P_HTM[1634]="*Phassasamudayā saññāsamudayo;**Perception originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[1635]="*phassanirodhā saññānirodho.**When contact ceases, perception ceases.*";
P_HTM[1636]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo saññānirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of perceptions is simply this noble eightfold path …*";
P_HTM[1637]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1638]="*vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1639]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, saṅkhārā?**And what are choices?*";
P_HTM[1640]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, cetanākāyā—**There are these six classes of intention:*";
P_HTM[1641]="*rūpasañcetanā … pe …**intention regarding sights …*";
P_HTM[1642]="*dhammasañcetanā.**intention regarding thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1643]="*Ime vuccanti, bhikkhave, saṅkhārā.**These are called choices.*";
P_HTM[1644]="*Phassasamudayā saṅkhārasamudayo;**Choices originate from contact.*";
P_HTM[1645]="*phassanirodhā saṅkhāranirodho.**When contact ceases, choices cease.*";
P_HTM[1646]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo saṅkhāranirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of choices is simply this noble eightfold path …*";
P_HTM[1647]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[1648]="*Yaṃ saṅkhāre paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[1649]="*ayaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ assādo.* **";
P_HTM[1650]="*Ye saṅkhārā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā—* **";
P_HTM[1651]="*ayaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ ādīnavo.* **";
P_HTM[1652]="*Yo saṅkhāresu chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[1653]="*idaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ nissaraṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1654]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ saṅkhāre abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhārasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhāranirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ saṅkhāranirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya … pe … saṅkhārānaṃ nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipannā te suppaṭipannā.* **";
P_HTM[1655]="*Ye suppaṭipannā, te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye gādhanti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1656]="*vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1657]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ?**And what is consciousness?*";
P_HTM[1658]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, viññāṇakāyā—**There are these six classes of consciousness:*";
P_HTM[1659]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ, sotaviññāṇaṃ, ghānaviññāṇaṃ, jivhāviññāṇaṃ, kāyaviññāṇaṃ, manoviññāṇaṃ.**eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1660]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ.**This is called consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1661]="*Nāmarūpasamudayā viññāṇasamudayo;**Consciousness originates from name and form.*";
P_HTM[1662]="*nāmarūpanirodhā viññāṇanirodho.**When name and form cease, consciousness ceases.*";
P_HTM[1663]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo viññāṇanirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of consciousness is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[1664]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[1665]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ—**The pleasure and happiness that arise from consciousness: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[1666]="*ayaṃ viññāṇassa assādo.* **";
P_HTM[1667]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ—**That consciousness is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[1668]="*ayaṃ viññāṇassa ādīnavo.* **";
P_HTM[1669]="*Yo viññāṇasmiṃ chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ—**Removing and giving up desire and greed for consciousness: this is its escape.*";
P_HTM[1670]="*idaṃ viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1671]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ viññāṇaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇanirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya;**Those ascetics and brahmins who have directly known consciousness in this way—and its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation;*";
P_HTM[1672]="*evaṃ viññāṇassa assādaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇassa ādīnavaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ abhiññāya viññāṇassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipannā, te suppaṭipannā.**its gratification, drawback, and escape—and are practicing for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness: they are practicing well.*";
P_HTM[1673]="*Ye suppaṭipannā, te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye gādhanti.**Those who practice well have a firm footing in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[1674]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā evaṃ viññāṇaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇasamudayaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇanirodhaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ abhiññāya;**Those ascetics and brahmins who have directly known consciousness in this way—and its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation;*";
P_HTM[1675]="*evaṃ viññāṇassa assādaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇassa ādīnavaṃ abhiññāya, evaṃ viññāṇassa nissaraṇaṃ abhiññāya viññāṇassa nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimuttā, te suvimuttā.**its gratification, drawback, and escape—and due to disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness, are freed by not grasping: they are well freed.*";
P_HTM[1676]="*Ye suvimuttā, te kevalino.**Those who are well freed are consummate ones.*";
P_HTM[1677]="*Ye kevalino vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya.**For consummate ones, there is no cycle of rebirths to be found.*";
P_HTM[1678]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sattaṭṭhānakusalo hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is skilled in seven cases.*";
P_HTM[1679]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tividhūpaparikkhī hoti?**And how does a mendicant examine in three ways?*";
P_HTM[1680]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu dhātuso upaparikkhati, āyatanaso upaparikkhati, paṭiccasamuppādaso upaparikkhati.**It’s when a mendicant examines the elements, sense fields, and dependent origination.*";
P_HTM[1681]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tividhūpaparikkhī hoti.**That’s how a mendicant examines in three ways.*";
P_HTM[1682]="*Sattaṭṭhānakusalo, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tividhūpaparikkhī, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye kevalī vusitavā ‘uttamapuriso’ti vuccatī”ti.**In this teaching and training, a mendicant who is skilled in seven cases and who examines in three ways is called consummate, accomplished, a supreme person.”*";
P_HTM[1683]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1684]="*6. Sammāsambuddhasuttaṃ**The Fully Awakened Buddha*";
P_HTM[1685]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1686]="*“Tathāgato, bhikkhave, arahaṃ sammāsambuddho rūpassa nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimutto sammāsambuddhoti vuccati.**“Mendicants, a Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha is freed by not grasping, due to disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form. They’re called a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1687]="*Bhikkhupi, bhikkhave, paññāvimutto rūpassa nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimutto paññāvimuttoti vuccati.**A mendicant freed by wisdom is also freed by not grasping, due to disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form. They’re called a mendicant freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1688]="*Tathāgato, bhikkhave, arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vedanāya nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimutto sammāsambuddhoti vuccati.**A Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha is freed by not grasping, due to disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding feeling …*";
P_HTM[1689]="*Bhikkhupi, bhikkhave, paññāvimutto vedanāya nibbidā … pe … paññāvimuttoti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[1690]="*Tathāgato, bhikkhave, arahaṃ sammāsambuddho saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1691]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1692]="*viññāṇassa nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimutto sammāsambuddhoti vuccati.**consciousness. They’re called a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1693]="*Bhikkhupi, bhikkhave, paññāvimutto viññāṇassa nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādā vimutto paññāvimuttoti vuccati.**A mendicant freed by wisdom is also freed by not grasping, due to disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness. They’re called a mendicant freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1694]="*Tatra kho, bhikkhave, ko viseso, ko adhippayāso, kiṃ nānākaraṇaṃ, tathāgatassa arahato sammāsambuddhassa paññāvimuttena bhikkhunā”ti?**What, then, is the difference between a Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, and a mendicant freed by wisdom?”*";
P_HTM[1695]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā bhagavaṃnettikā bhagavaṃpaṭisaraṇā. Sādhu vata, bhante, bhagavantaññeva paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho. Bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. He is our guide and our refuge. Sir, may the Buddha himself please clarify the meaning of this. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[1696]="*“Tena hi, bhikkhave, suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, mendicants, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[1697]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1698]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1699]="*“Tathāgato, bhikkhave, arahaṃ sammāsambuddho anuppannassa maggassa uppādetā, asañjātassa maggassa sañjanetā, anakkhātassa maggassa akkhātā maggaññū, maggavidū, maggakovido;**“A Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha gives rise to the unarisen path, gives birth to the unborn path, and explains the unexplained path. They know the path, understand the path, and are experts in the path.*";
P_HTM[1700]="*maggānugā ca, bhikkhave, etarahi sāvakā viharanti pacchā samannāgatā.**And now the disciples live following the path; they acquire it later.*";
P_HTM[1701]="*Ayaṃ kho, bhikkhave, viseso, ayaṃ adhippayāso, idaṃ nānākaraṇaṃ tathāgatassa arahato sammāsambuddhassa paññāvimuttena bhikkhunā”ti.**This is the difference between a Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, and a mendicant freed by wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[1702]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1703]="*7. Anattalakkhaṇasuttaṃ**The Characteristic of Not*";
P_HTM[1704]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā bārāṇasiyaṃ viharati isipatane migadāye.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana.*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Tatra kho bhagavā pañcavaggiye bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the group of five mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1706]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1707]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1708]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1709]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, anattā.**“Mendicants, form is not-self.*";
P_HTM[1710]="*Rūpañca hidaṃ, bhikkhave, attā abhavissa, nayidaṃ rūpaṃ ābādhāya saṃvatteyya, labbhetha ca rūpe:**For if form were self, it wouldn’t lead to affliction. And you could compel form:*";
P_HTM[1711]="*‘evaṃ me rūpaṃ hotu, evaṃ me rūpaṃ mā ahosī’ti.**‘May my form be like this! May it not be like that!’*";
P_HTM[1712]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ anattā, tasmā rūpaṃ ābādhāya saṃvattati, na ca labbhati rūpe:**But because form is not-self, it leads to affliction. And you can’t compel form:*";
P_HTM[1713]="*‘evaṃ me rūpaṃ hotu, evaṃ me rūpaṃ mā ahosī’ti.**‘May my form be like this! May it not be like that!’*";
P_HTM[1714]="*Vedanā anattā.**Feeling is not-self …*";
P_HTM[1715]="*Vedanā ca hidaṃ, bhikkhave, attā abhavissa, nayidaṃ vedanā ābādhāya saṃvatteyya, labbhetha ca vedanāya:* **";
P_HTM[1716]="*‘evaṃ me vedanā hotu, evaṃ me vedanā mā ahosī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1717]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, vedanā anattā, tasmā vedanā ābādhāya saṃvattati, na ca labbhati vedanāya:* **";
P_HTM[1718]="*‘evaṃ me vedanā hotu, evaṃ me vedanā mā ahosī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1719]="*Saññā anattā … pe …**Perception is not-self …*";
P_HTM[1720]="*saṅkhārā anattā.**Choices are not-self …*";
P_HTM[1721]="*Saṅkhārā ca hidaṃ, bhikkhave, attā abhavissaṃsu, nayidaṃ saṅkhārā ābādhāya saṃvatteyyuṃ, labbhetha ca saṅkhāresu:* **";
P_HTM[1722]="*‘evaṃ me saṅkhārā hontu, evaṃ me saṅkhārā mā ahesun’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1723]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, saṅkhārā anattā, tasmā saṅkhārā ābādhāya saṃvattanti, na ca labbhati saṅkhāresu:* **";
P_HTM[1724]="*‘evaṃ me saṅkhārā hontu, evaṃ me saṅkhārā mā ahesun’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1725]="*Viññāṇaṃ anattā.**Consciousness is not-self.*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Viññāṇañca hidaṃ, bhikkhave, attā abhavissa, nayidaṃ viññāṇaṃ ābādhāya saṃvatteyya, labbhetha ca viññāṇe:**For if consciousness were self, it wouldn’t lead to affliction. And you could compel consciousness:*";
P_HTM[1727]="*‘evaṃ me viññāṇaṃ hotu, evaṃ me viññāṇaṃ mā ahosī’ti.**‘May my consciousness be like this! May it not be like that!’*";
P_HTM[1728]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ anattā, tasmā viññāṇaṃ ābādhāya saṃvattati, na ca labbhati viññāṇe:**But because consciousness is not-self, it leads to affliction. And you can’t compel consciousness:*";
P_HTM[1729]="*‘evaṃ me viññāṇaṃ hotu, evaṃ me viññāṇaṃ mā ahosī’ti.**‘May my consciousness be like this! May it not be like that!’*";
P_HTM[1730]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[1731]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1732]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1733]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1734]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1735]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1736]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1737]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1738]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling permanent or impermanent?” …*";
P_HTM[1739]="*saññā …**“Is perception permanent or impermanent?” …*";
P_HTM[1740]="*saṅkhārā …**“Are choices permanent or impermanent?” …*";
P_HTM[1741]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**“Is consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1742]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1743]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1744]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1745]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1746]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1747]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1748]="*“Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, yaṃ kiñci rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ rūpaṃ: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**“So you should truly see any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1749]="*Yā kāci vedanā atītānāgatapaccuppannā ajjhattā vā bahiddhā vā … pe … yā dūre santike vā, sabbā vedanā: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**Any kind of feeling at all …*";
P_HTM[1750]="*Yā kāci saññā … pe …**Any kind of perception at all …*";
P_HTM[1751]="*ye keci saṅkhārā atītānāgatapaccuppannā ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā … pe … ye dūre santike vā, sabbe saṅkhārā: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**Any kind of choices at all …*";
P_HTM[1752]="*Yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**You should truly see any kind of consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1753]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi nibbindati, saññāyapi nibbindati, saṅkhāresupi nibbindati, viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1754]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1755]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1756]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1757]="*Attamanā pañcavaggiyā bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanduṃ.**Satisfied, the group of five mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1758]="*Imasmiñca pana veyyākaraṇasmiṃ bhaññamāne pañcavaggiyānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ anupādāya āsavehi cittāni vimucciṃsūti.**And while this discourse was being spoken, the minds of the group of five mendicants were freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1759]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1760]="*8. Mahālisuttaṃ**With Mahāli*";
P_HTM[1761]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1762]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[1763]="*Atha kho mahāli licchavi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahāli licchavi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahāli the Licchavi went up to the Buddha … and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1764]="*“Pūraṇo, bhante, kassapo evamāha:**“Sir, Pūraṇa Kassapa says this:*";
P_HTM[1765]="*‘natthi hetu natthi paccayo sattānaṃ saṅkilesāya;**‘There is no cause or condition for the corruption of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1766]="*ahetū appaccayā sattā saṅkilissanti.**Sentient beings are corrupted without cause or reason.*";
P_HTM[1767]="*Natthi hetu natthi paccayo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā;**There’s no cause or condition for the purification of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1768]="*ahetū appaccayā sattā visujjhantī’ti.**Sentient beings are purified without cause or reason.’*";
P_HTM[1769]="*Idha bhagavā kimāhā”ti?**What does the Buddha say about this?”*";
P_HTM[1770]="*“Atthi, mahāli, hetu atthi paccayo sattānaṃ saṅkilesāya;**“Mahāli, there is a cause and condition for the corruption of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1771]="*sahetū sappaccayā sattā saṅkilissanti.**Sentient beings are corrupted with cause and reason.*";
P_HTM[1772]="*Atthi, mahāli, hetu, atthi paccayo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā;**There is a cause and condition for the purification of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1773]="*sahetū sappaccayā sattā visujjhantī”ti.**Sentient beings are purified with cause and reason.”*";
P_HTM[1774]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, hetu katamo paccayo sattānaṃ saṅkilesāya;**“But sir, what is the cause and condition for the corruption of sentient beings?*";
P_HTM[1775]="*kathaṃ sahetū sappaccayā sattā saṅkilissantī”ti?**How are sentient beings corrupted with cause and reason?”*";
P_HTM[1776]="*“Rūpañca hidaṃ, mahāli, ekantadukkhaṃ abhavissa dukkhānupatitaṃ dukkhāvakkantaṃ anavakkantaṃ sukhena, nayidaṃ sattā rūpasmiṃ sārajjeyyuṃ.**“Mahāli, if form were exclusively painful—soaked and steeped in pain and not steeped in pleasure—sentient beings wouldn’t lust after it.*";
P_HTM[1777]="*Yasmā ca kho, mahāli, rūpaṃ sukhaṃ sukhānupatitaṃ sukhāvakkantaṃ anavakkantaṃ dukkhena, tasmā sattā rūpasmiṃ sārajjanti;**But because form is pleasurable—soaked and steeped in pleasure and not steeped in pain—sentient beings do lust after it.*";
P_HTM[1778]="*sārāgā saṃyujjanti; saṃyogā saṅkilissanti.**Since they lust after it, they’re caught up in it, and so they become corrupted.*";
P_HTM[1779]="*Ayaṃ kho, mahāli, hetu, ayaṃ paccayo sattānaṃ saṅkilesāya;**This is a cause and condition for the corruption of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1780]="*evaṃ sahetū sappaccayā sattā saṅkilissanti.**This is how sentient beings are corrupted with cause and reason.*";
P_HTM[1781]="*Vedanā ca hidaṃ, mahāli, ekantadukkhā abhavissa dukkhānupatitā dukkhāvakkantā anavakkantā sukhena, nayidaṃ sattā vedanāya sārajjeyyuṃ.**If feeling …*";
P_HTM[1782]="*Yasmā ca kho, mahāli, vedanā sukhā sukhānupatitā sukhāvakkantā anavakkantā dukkhena, tasmā sattā vedanāya sārajjanti;* **";
P_HTM[1783]="*sārāgā saṃyujjanti;* **";
P_HTM[1784]="*saṃyogā saṅkilissanti.* **";
P_HTM[1785]="*Ayampi kho, mahāli, hetu, ayaṃ paccayo sattānaṃ saṅkilesāya.* **";
P_HTM[1786]="*Evampi sahetū sappaccayā sattā saṅkilissanti.* **";
P_HTM[1787]="*Saññā ca hidaṃ, mahāli … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1788]="*saṅkhārā ca hidaṃ, mahāli, ekantadukkhā abhavissaṃsu dukkhānupatitā dukkhāvakkantā anavakkantā sukhena, nayidaṃ sattā saṅkhāresu sārajjeyyuṃ.**choices …*";
P_HTM[1789]="*Yasmā ca kho, mahāli, saṅkhārā sukhā sukhānupatitā sukhāvakkantā anavakkantā dukkhena, tasmā sattā saṅkhāresu sārajjanti;* **";
P_HTM[1790]="*sārāgā saṃyujjanti;* **";
P_HTM[1791]="*saṃyogā saṅkilissanti.* **";
P_HTM[1792]="*Ayampi kho, mahāli, hetu, ayaṃ paccayo sattānaṃ saṅkilesāya.* **";
P_HTM[1793]="*Evampi sahetū sappaccayā sattā saṅkilissanti.* **";
P_HTM[1794]="*Viññāṇañca hidaṃ, mahāli, ekantadukkhaṃ abhavissa dukkhānupatitaṃ dukkhāvakkantaṃ anavakkantaṃ sukhena, nayidaṃ sattā viññāṇasmiṃ sārajjeyyuṃ.**consciousness were exclusively painful—soaked and steeped in pain and not steeped in pleasure—sentient beings wouldn’t lust after it.*";
P_HTM[1795]="*Yasmā ca kho, mahāli, viññāṇaṃ sukhaṃ sukhānupatitaṃ sukhāvakkantaṃ anavakkantaṃ dukkhena, tasmā sattā viññāṇasmiṃ sārajjanti;**But because consciousness is pleasurable—soaked and steeped in pleasure and not steeped in pain—sentient beings do lust after it.*";
P_HTM[1796]="*sārāgā saṃyujjanti; saṃyogā saṅkilissanti.**Since they lust after it, they’re caught up in it, and so they become corrupted.*";
P_HTM[1797]="*Ayampi kho, mahāli, hetu ayaṃ paccayo sattānaṃ saṅkilesāya.**This is a cause and condition for the corruption of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1798]="*Evampi sahetū sappaccayā sattā saṅkilissantī”ti.**This is how sentient beings are corrupted with cause and reason.”*";
P_HTM[1799]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, hetu katamo paccayo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā;**“But sir, what is the cause and condition for the purification of sentient beings?*";
P_HTM[1800]="*kathaṃ sahetū sappaccayā sattā visujjhantī”ti?**How are sentient beings purified with cause and reason?”*";
P_HTM[1801]="*“Rūpañca hidaṃ, mahāli, ekantasukhaṃ abhavissa sukhānupatitaṃ sukhāvakkantaṃ anavakkantaṃ dukkhena, nayidaṃ sattā rūpasmiṃ nibbindeyyuṃ.**“Mahāli, if form were exclusively pleasurable—soaked and steeped in pleasure and not steeped in pain—sentient beings wouldn’t grow disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1802]="*Yasmā ca kho, mahāli, rūpaṃ dukkhaṃ dukkhānupatitaṃ dukkhāvakkantaṃ anavakkantaṃ sukhena, tasmā sattā rūpasmiṃ nibbindanti;**But because form is painful—soaked and steeped in pain and not steeped in pleasure—sentient beings do grow disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1803]="*nibbindaṃ virajjanti; virāgā visujjhanti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they are purified.*";
P_HTM[1804]="*Ayaṃ kho, mahāli, hetu, ayaṃ paccayo, sattānaṃ visuddhiyā.**This is a cause and condition for the purification of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1805]="*Evaṃ sahetū sappaccayā sattā visujjhanti.**This is how sentient beings are purified with cause and reason.*";
P_HTM[1806]="*Vedanā ca hidaṃ, mahāli, ekantasukhā abhavissa … pe …**If feeling …*";
P_HTM[1807]="*saññā ca hidaṃ, mahāli … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1808]="*saṅkhārā ca hidaṃ, mahāli, ekantasukhā abhavissaṃsu … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1809]="*viññāṇañca hidaṃ, mahāli, ekantasukhaṃ abhavissa sukhānupatitaṃ sukhāvakkantaṃ anavakkantaṃ dukkhena, nayidaṃ sattā viññāṇasmiṃ nibbindeyyuṃ.**consciousness were exclusively pleasurable—soaked and steeped in pleasure and not steeped in pain—sentient beings wouldn’t grow disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1810]="*Yasmā ca kho, mahāli, viññāṇaṃ dukkhaṃ dukkhānupatitaṃ dukkhāvakkantaṃ anavakkantaṃ sukhena, tasmā sattā viññāṇasmiṃ nibbindanti;**But because consciousness is painful—soaked and steeped in pain and not steeped in pleasure—sentient beings do grow disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1811]="*nibbindaṃ virajjanti; virāgā visujjhanti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they are purified.*";
P_HTM[1812]="*Ayaṃ kho, mahāli, hetu, ayaṃ paccayo, sattānaṃ visuddhiyā.**This is a cause and condition for the purification of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1813]="*Evampi sahetū sappaccayā sattā visujjhantī”ti.**This is how sentient beings are purified with cause and reason.”*";
P_HTM[1814]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1815]="*9. Ādittasuttaṃ**Burning*";
P_HTM[1816]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1817]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, ādittaṃ, vedanā ādittā, saññā ādittā, saṅkhārā ādittā, viññāṇaṃ ādittaṃ.**“Mendicants, form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are burning.*";
P_HTM[1818]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi … saññāyapi … saṅkhāresupi … viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1819]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1820]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1821]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1822]="*10. Niruttipathasuttaṃ**The Scope of Language*";
P_HTM[1823]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1824]="*“Tayome, bhikkhave, niruttipathā adhivacanapathā paññattipathā asaṅkiṇṇā asaṅkiṇṇapubbā, na saṅkīyanti, na saṅkīyissanti, appaṭikuṭṭhā samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**“Mendicants, there are these three scopes of language, terminology, and descriptions. They’re uncorrupted, as they have been since the beginning. They’re not being corrupted now, nor will they be. Sensible ascetics and brahmins don’t look down on them.*";
P_HTM[1825]="*Katame tayo?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1826]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ atītaṃ niruddhaṃ vipariṇataṃ ‘ahosī’ti tassa saṅkhā, ‘ahosī’ti tassa samaññā, ‘ahosī’ti tassa paññatti;**When form has passed, ceased, and perished, its designation, label, and description is ‘was’.*";
P_HTM[1827]="*na tassa saṅkhā ‘atthī’ti, na tassa saṅkhā ‘bhavissatī’ti.**It’s not ‘is’ or ‘will be’.*";
P_HTM[1828]="*Yā vedanā atītā niruddhā vipariṇatā ‘ahosī’ti tassā saṅkhā, ‘ahosī’ti tassā samaññā, ‘ahosī’ti tassā paññatti;**When feeling …*";
P_HTM[1829]="*na tassā saṅkhā ‘atthī’ti, na tassā saṅkhā ‘bhavissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1830]="*Yā saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1831]="*ye saṅkhārā atītā niruddhā vipariṇatā ‘ahesun’ti tesaṃ saṅkhā, ‘ahesun’ti tesaṃ samaññā, ‘ahesun’ti tesaṃ paññatti;**choices …*";
P_HTM[1832]="*na tesaṃ saṅkhā ‘atthī’ti, na tesaṃ saṅkhā ‘bhavissantī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1833]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ atītaṃ niruddhaṃ vipariṇataṃ, ‘ahosī’ti tassa saṅkhā, ‘ahosī’ti tassa samaññā, ‘ahosī’ti tassa paññatti;**consciousness has passed, ceased, and perished, its designation, label, and description is ‘was’.*";
P_HTM[1834]="*na tassa saṅkhā ‘atthī’ti, na tassa saṅkhā ‘bhavissatī’ti.**It’s not ‘is’ or ‘will be’.*";
P_HTM[1835]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ ajātaṃ apātubhūtaṃ, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassa saṅkhā, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassa samaññā, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassa paññatti;**When form is not yet born, and has not yet appeared, its designation, label, and description is ‘will be’.*";
P_HTM[1836]="*na tassa saṅkhā ‘atthī’ti, na tassa saṅkhā ‘ahosī’ti.**It’s not ‘is’ or ‘was’.*";
P_HTM[1837]="*Yā vedanā ajātā apātubhūtā, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassā saṅkhā, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassā samaññā, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassā paññatti;**When feeling …*";
P_HTM[1838]="*na tassā saṅkhā ‘atthī’ti, na tassā saṅkhā ‘ahosī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1839]="*Yā saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1840]="*ye saṅkhārā ajātā apātubhūtā, ‘bhavissantī’ti tesaṃ saṅkhā, ‘bhavissantī’ti tesaṃ samaññā, ‘bhavissantī’ti tesaṃ paññatti;**choices …*";
P_HTM[1841]="*na tesaṃ saṅkhā ‘atthī’ti, na tesaṃ saṅkhā ‘ahesun’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1842]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ ajātaṃ apātubhūtaṃ, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassa saṅkhā, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassa samaññā, ‘bhavissatī’ti tassa paññatti;**consciousness is not yet born, and has not yet appeared, its designation, label, and description is ‘will be’.*";
P_HTM[1843]="*na tassa saṅkhā ‘atthī’ti, na tassa saṅkhā ‘ahosī’ti.**It’s not ‘is’ or ‘was’.*";
P_HTM[1844]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ jātaṃ pātubhūtaṃ, ‘atthī’ti tassa saṅkhā, ‘atthī’ti tassa samaññā, ‘atthī’ti tassa paññatti;**When form has been born, and has appeared, its designation, label, and description is ‘is’.*";
P_HTM[1845]="*na tassa saṅkhā ‘ahosī’ti, na tassa saṅkhā ‘bhavissatī’ti.**It’s not ‘was’ or ‘will be’.*";
P_HTM[1846]="*Yā vedanā jātā pātubhūtā, ‘atthī’ti tassā saṅkhā, ‘atthī’ti tassā samaññā, ‘atthī’ti tassā paññatti;**When feeling …*";
P_HTM[1847]="*na tassā saṅkhā ‘ahosī’ti, na tassā saṅkhā ‘bhavissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1848]="*Yā saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1849]="*ye saṅkhārā jātā pātubhūtā, ‘atthī’ti tesaṃ saṅkhā, ‘atthī’ti tesaṃ samaññā, ‘atthī’ti tesaṃ paññatti;**choices …*";
P_HTM[1850]="*na tesaṃ saṅkhā ‘ahesun’ti, na tesaṃ saṅkhā, ‘bhavissantī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1851]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ jātaṃ pātubhūtaṃ, ‘atthī’ti tassa saṅkhā, ‘atthī’ti tassa samaññā, ‘atthī’ti tassa paññatti;**consciousness has been born, and has appeared, its designation, label, and description is ‘is’.*";
P_HTM[1852]="*na tassa saṅkhā ‘ahosī’ti, na tassa saṅkhā ‘bhavissatī’ti.**It’s not ‘was’ or ‘will be’.*";
P_HTM[1853]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, tayo niruttipathā adhivacanapathā paññattipathā asaṃkiṇṇā asaṃkiṇṇapubbā, na saṅkīyanti, na saṅkīyissanti, appaṭikuṭṭhā samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**These are the three scopes of language, terminology, and descriptions. They’re uncorrupted, as they have been since the beginning. They’re not being corrupted now, nor will they be. Sensible ascetics and brahmins don’t look down on them.*";
P_HTM[1854]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, ahesuṃ ukkalā vassabhaññā ahetukavādā akiriyavādā natthikavādā, tepime tayo niruttipathe adhivacanapathe paññattipathe na garahitabbaṃ nappaṭikkositabbaṃ amaññiṃsu.**Even those wanderers of the past, Vassa and Bhañña of Ukkalā, who taught the doctrines of no-cause, inaction, and nihilism, didn’t imagine that these three scopes of language should be criticized or rejected.*";
P_HTM[1855]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1856]="*Nindāghaṭṭanabyārosaupārambhabhayā”ti.**For fear of being blamed, criticized, and faulted.”*";
P_HTM[1857]="*Majjhimapaṇṇāsakassa upayavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[1858]="*Upayo bījaṃ udānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1859]="*Upādānaparivattaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1860]="*Sattaṭṭhānañca sambuddho,* **";
P_HTM[1861]="*Pañcamahāli ādittā;* **";
P_HTM[1862]="*Vaggo niruttipathena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[1863]="*sn/sn22.063.xhtml==7. Arahantavagga==7. Arahantavaggo**The Perfected Ones*";
P_HTM[1864]="*1. Upādiyamānasuttaṃ**When You Grasp*";
P_HTM[1865]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1866]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1867]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1868]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[1869]="*“Upādiyamāno kho, bhikkhu, baddho mārassa;**“When you grasp, mendicant, you’re bound by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1870]="*anupādiyamāno mutto pāpimato”ti.**Not grasping, you’re free from the Wicked One.”*";
P_HTM[1871]="*“Aññātaṃ bhagavā, aññātaṃ sugatā”ti.**“Understood, Blessed One! Understood, Holy One!”*";
P_HTM[1872]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsī”ti?**“But how do you see the detailed meaning of my brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[1873]="*“Rūpaṃ kho, bhante, upādiyamāno baddho mārassa;**“Sir, when you grasp form you’re bound by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1874]="*anupādiyamāno mutto pāpimato.**Not grasping, you’re free from the Wicked One.*";
P_HTM[1875]="*Vedanaṃ upādiyamāno baddho mārassa;**When you grasp feeling …*";
P_HTM[1876]="*anupādiyamāno mutto pāpimato.* **";
P_HTM[1877]="*Saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1878]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1879]="*viññāṇaṃ upādiyamāno baddho mārassa;**consciousness, you’re bound by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1880]="*anupādiyamāno mutto pāpimato.**Not grasping, you’re free from the Wicked One.*";
P_HTM[1881]="*Imassa khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**That’s how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.”*";
P_HTM[1882]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
P_HTM[1883]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsi.**It’s good that you understand the detailed meaning of what I’ve said in brief like this.*";
P_HTM[1884]="*Rūpaṃ kho, bhikkhu, upādiyamāno baddho mārassa;**When you grasp form you’re bound by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1885]="*anupādiyamāno mutto pāpimato.**Not grasping, you’re free from the Wicked One.*";
P_HTM[1886]="*Vedanaṃ …**When you grasp feeling …*";
P_HTM[1887]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1888]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1889]="*viññāṇaṃ upādiyamāno baddho mārassa;**consciousness, you’re bound by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1890]="*anupādiyamāno mutto pāpimato.**Not grasping, you’re free from the Wicked One.*";
P_HTM[1891]="*Imassa kho, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti.**This is how to understand the detailed meaning of what I said in brief.”*";
P_HTM[1892]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then that mendicant approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1893]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Then that mendicant, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[1894]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[1895]="*Aññataro ca pana so bhikkhu arahataṃ ahosīti.**And that mendicant became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[1896]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1897]="*2. Maññamānasuttaṃ**When You Identify*";
P_HTM[1898]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1899]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[1900]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena dhammaṃ desetu … pe … ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[1901]="*“Maññamāno kho, bhikkhu, baddho mārassa;**“When you identify, mendicant, you’re bound by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1902]="*amaññamāno mutto pāpimato”ti.**Not identifying, you’re free from the Wicked One.”*";
P_HTM[1903]="*“Aññātaṃ, bhagavā, aññātaṃ, sugatā”ti.**“Understood, Blessed One! Understood, Holy One!”*";
P_HTM[1904]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsī”ti?**“But how do you see the detailed meaning of my brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[1905]="*“Rūpaṃ kho, bhante, maññamāno baddho mārassa;**“Sir, when you identify with form you’re bound by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1906]="*amaññamāno mutto pāpimato.**Not identifying, you’re free from the Wicked One.*";
P_HTM[1907]="*Vedanaṃ …**When you identify with feeling …*";
P_HTM[1908]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1909]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1910]="*viññāṇaṃ maññamāno baddho mārassa;**consciousness, you’re bound by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1911]="*amaññamāno mutto pāpimato.**Not identifying, you’re free from the Wicked One.*";
P_HTM[1912]="*Imassa khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**That’s how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.”*";
P_HTM[1913]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
