P_HTM[2101]="*sn/sn22.073.xhtml==8. Khajjanīyavagga==8. Khajjanīyavaggo**Itchy*";
P_HTM[2102]="*1. Assādasuttaṃ**Gratification*";
P_HTM[2103]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2104]="*“Assutavā, bhikkhave, puthujjano rūpassa assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**“Mendicants, an uneducated ordinary person doesn’t truly understand the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[2105]="*Vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[2106]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2107]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices,*";
P_HTM[2108]="*viññāṇassa assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2109]="*Sutavā ca kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako rūpassa assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**An educated noble disciple does truly understand the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[2110]="*Vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[2111]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2112]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices,*";
P_HTM[2113]="*viññāṇassa assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānātī”ti.**and consciousness.”*";
P_HTM[2114]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2115]="*2. Samudayasuttaṃ**Origin*";
P_HTM[2116]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2117]="*“Assutavā, bhikkhave, puthujjano rūpassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**“Mendicants, an uneducated ordinary person doesn’t truly understand the origin, the ending, the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[2118]="*Vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[2119]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2120]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices,*";
P_HTM[2121]="*viññāṇassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2122]="*Sutavā ca kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako rūpassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**An educated noble disciple does truly understand the origin, the ending, the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[2123]="*Vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[2124]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2125]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices,*";
P_HTM[2126]="*viññāṇassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānātī”ti.**and consciousness.”*";
P_HTM[2127]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2128]="*3. Dutiyasamudayasuttaṃ**Origin (2nd)*";
P_HTM[2129]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2130]="*“Sutavā, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako rūpassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**“Mendicants, an educated noble disciple truly understands the origin, the ending, the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[2131]="*Vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[2132]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2133]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices,*";
P_HTM[2134]="*viññāṇassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānātī”ti.**and consciousness.”*";
P_HTM[2135]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2136]="*4. Arahantasuttaṃ**The Perfected Ones*";
P_HTM[2137]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2138]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ.**“Mendicants, form is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2139]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[2140]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[2141]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[2142]="*Vedanā …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[2143]="*saññā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[2144]="*saṅkhārā …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[2145]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**Consciousness is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2146]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[2147]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[2148]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[2149]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi … saññāyapi … saṅkhāresupi … viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2150]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[2151]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[2152]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, sattāvāsā, yāvatā bhavaggaṃ, ete aggā, ete seṭṭhā lokasmiṃ yadidaṃ arahanto”ti.**As far as there are abodes of sentient beings, even up until the pinnacle of existence, the perfected ones are the foremost and the best.”*";
P_HTM[2153]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2154]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[2155]="*“Sukhino vata arahanto,**“Oh! How happy are the perfected ones!*";
P_HTM[2156]="*taṇhā tesaṃ na vijjati;**Craving is not found in them,*";
P_HTM[2157]="*Asmimāno samucchinno,**the conceit ‘I am’ is cut off,*";
P_HTM[2158]="*mohajālaṃ padālitaṃ.**and the net of delusion is shattered.*";
P_HTM[2159]="*Anejaṃ te anuppattā,**They’ve attained imperturbability,*";
P_HTM[2160]="*cittaṃ tesaṃ anāvilaṃ;**their minds are unclouded,*";
P_HTM[2161]="*Loke anupalittā te,**nothing in the world clings to them,*";
P_HTM[2162]="*brahmabhūtā anāsavā.**they’ve become holy, undefiled.*";
P_HTM[2163]="*Pañcakkhandhe pariññāya,**Completely understanding the five aggregates,*";
P_HTM[2164]="*satta saddhammagocarā;**their domain is the seven good qualities.*";
P_HTM[2165]="*Pasaṃsiyā sappurisā,**Those good people are praiseworthy,*";
P_HTM[2166]="*puttā buddhassa orasā.**the Buddha’s rightful children.*";
P_HTM[2167]="*Sattaratanasampannā,**Endowed with the seven gems,*";
P_HTM[2168]="*Tīsu sikkhāsu sikkhitā;**and trained in the three trainings,*";
P_HTM[2169]="*Anuvicaranti mahāvīrā,**the great heroes live on,*";
P_HTM[2170]="*Pahīnabhayabheravā.**with fear and dread given up.*";
P_HTM[2171]="*Dasahaṅgehi sampannā,**Endowed with ten factors,*";
P_HTM[2172]="*mahānāgā samāhitā;**those giants have immersion.*";
P_HTM[2173]="*Ete kho seṭṭhā lokasmiṃ,**These are the best in the world,*";
P_HTM[2174]="*taṇhā tesaṃ na vijjati.**craving is not found in them.*";
P_HTM[2175]="*Asekhañāṇamuppannaṃ,**The master’s knowledge has arisen:*";
P_HTM[2176]="*antimoyaṃ samussayo;**‘This bag of bones is my last.’*";
P_HTM[2177]="*Yo sāro brahmacariyassa,**They are independent of others*";
P_HTM[2178]="*tasmiṃ aparapaccayā.**in the core of the spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[2179]="*Vidhāsu na vikampanti,**Unwavering in the face of discrimination,*";
P_HTM[2180]="*vippamuttā punabbhavā;**they’re freed from future lives.*";
P_HTM[2181]="*Dantabhūmimanuppattā,**They’ve reached the level of the tamed,*";
P_HTM[2182]="*te loke vijitāvino.**in the world, they’re the winners.*";
P_HTM[2183]="*Uddhaṃ tiriyaṃ apācīnaṃ,**Above, below, and all around,*";
P_HTM[2184]="*nandī tesaṃ na vijjati;**relishing is not found in them.*";
P_HTM[2185]="*Nadanti te sīhanādaṃ,**They roar their lion’s roar:*";
P_HTM[2186]="*buddhā loke anuttarā”ti.**‘The awakened are supreme in the world!’”*";
P_HTM[2187]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2188]="*5. Dutiyaarahantasuttaṃ**The Perfected Ones (2nd)*";
P_HTM[2189]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2190]="*“Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ.**“Mendicants, form is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2191]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[2192]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ tadanattā;**What’s suffering is not-self.*";
P_HTM[2193]="*yadanattā taṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti … pe … evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**And what’s not-self should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[2194]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi … saññāyapi … saṅkhāresupi … viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2195]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[2196]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[2197]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, sattāvāsā, yāvatā bhavaggaṃ, ete aggā, ete seṭṭhā lokasmiṃ yadidaṃ arahanto”ti.**As far as there are abodes of sentient beings, even up until the pinnacle of existence, the perfected ones are the foremost and the best.”*";
P_HTM[2198]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2199]="*6. Sīhasuttaṃ**The Lion*";
P_HTM[2200]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2201]="*“Sīho, bhikkhave, migarājā sāyanhasamayaṃ āsayā nikkhamati; āsayā nikkhamitvā vijambhati; vijambhitvā samantā catuddisā anuviloketi; samantā catuddisā anuviloketvā tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ nadati; tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ naditvā gocarāya pakkamati.**“Mendicants, towards evening the lion, king of beasts, emerges from his den, yawns, looks all around the four directions, and roars his lion’s roar three times. Then he sets out on the hunt.*";
P_HTM[2202]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā sīhassa migarañño nadato saddaṃ suṇanti; yebhuyyena bhayaṃ saṃvegaṃ santāsaṃ āpajjanti; bilaṃ bilāsayā pavisanti; dakaṃ dakāsayā pavisanti; vanaṃ vanāsayā pavisanti; ākāsaṃ pakkhino bhajanti.**And the animals who hear the roar of the lion, king of beasts, are typically filled with fear, awe, and terror. They return to their lairs, be they in a hole, the water, or a wood; and the birds take to the air.*";
P_HTM[2203]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, rañño nāgā gāmanigamarājadhānīsu, daḷhehi varattehi baddhā, tepi tāni bandhanāni sañchinditvā sampadāletvā bhītā muttakarīsaṃ cajamānā, yena vā tena vā palāyanti.**Even the royal elephants, bound with strong harness in the villages, towns, and capital cities, break apart their bonds, and urinate and defecate in terror as they flee here and there.*";
P_HTM[2204]="*Evaṃ mahiddhiko kho, bhikkhave, sīho migarājā tiracchānagatānaṃ pāṇānaṃ, evaṃ mahesakkho, evaṃ mahānubhāvo.**That’s how powerful is the lion, king of beasts, among animals, how illustrious and mighty.*";
P_HTM[2205]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yadā tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā. So dhammaṃ deseti:**In the same way, when a Realized One arises in the world—perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed—he teaches the Dhamma:*";
P_HTM[2206]="*‘iti rūpaṃ, iti rūpassa samudayo, iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo;**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[2207]="*iti vedanā …**Such is feeling …*";
P_HTM[2208]="*iti saññā …**Such is perception …*";
P_HTM[2209]="*iti saṅkhārā …**Such are choices …*";
P_HTM[2210]="*iti viññāṇaṃ, iti viññāṇassa samudayo, iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti.**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[2211]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, devā dīghāyukā vaṇṇavanto sukhabahulā uccesu vimānesu ciraṭṭhitikā tepi tathāgatassa dhammadesanaṃ sutvā yebhuyyena bhayaṃ saṃvegaṃ santāsaṃ āpajjanti:**Now, there are gods who are long-lived, beautiful, and very happy, living for ages in their divine palaces. When they hear this teaching by the Realized One, they’re typically filled with fear, awe, and terror.*";
P_HTM[2212]="*‘aniccāva kira, bho, mayaṃ samānā niccamhāti amaññimha.**‘Oh no! It turns out we’re impermanent, though we thought we were permanent!*";
P_HTM[2213]="*Addhuvāva kira, bho, mayaṃ samānā dhuvamhāti amaññimha.**It turns out we don’t last, though we thought we were everlasting!*";
P_HTM[2214]="*Asassatāva kira, bho, mayaṃ samānā sassatamhāti amaññimha.**It turns out we’re short-lived, though we thought we were eternal!*";
P_HTM[2215]="*Mayampi kira, bho, aniccā addhuvā asassatā sakkāyapariyāpannā’ti.**It turns out that we’re impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, and included within identity.’*";
P_HTM[2216]="*Evaṃ mahiddhiko kho, bhikkhave, tathāgato sadevakassa lokassa, evaṃ mahesakkho, evaṃ mahānubhāvo”ti.**That’s how powerful is the Realized One in the world with its gods, how illustrious and mighty.”*";
P_HTM[2217]="*Idamavoca bhagavā … pe …**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2218]="*etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[2219]="*“Yadā buddho abhiññāya,**“The Buddha, the teacher without a peer*";
P_HTM[2220]="*dhammacakkaṃ pavattayi;**in all the world with its gods,*";
P_HTM[2221]="*Sadevakassa lokassa,**rolls forth the Wheel of Dhamma*";
P_HTM[2222]="*satthā appaṭipuggalo.**from his own insight:*";
P_HTM[2223]="*Sakkāyañca nirodhañca,**identity, its cessation,*";
P_HTM[2224]="*sakkāyassa ca sambhavaṃ;**the origin of identity,*";
P_HTM[2225]="*Ariyañcaṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ,**and the noble eightfold path*";
P_HTM[2226]="*dukkhūpasamagāminaṃ.**that leads to the stilling of suffering.*";
P_HTM[2227]="*Yepi dīghāyukā devā,**And then the long-lived gods,*";
P_HTM[2228]="*vaṇṇavanto yasassino;**so beautiful and glorious,*";
P_HTM[2229]="*Bhītā santāsamāpāduṃ,**are afraid and full of terror,*";
P_HTM[2230]="*sīhassevitare migā.**like the other beasts when they hear a lion.*";
P_HTM[2231]="*Avītivattā sakkāyaṃ,**‘We haven’t transcended identity!*";
P_HTM[2232]="*aniccā kira bho mayaṃ;**It turns out we’re impermanent!’*";
P_HTM[2233]="*Sutvā arahato vākyaṃ,**So they say when they hear the word*";
P_HTM[2234]="*vippamuttassa tādino”ti.**of the perfected one, free and poised.”*";
P_HTM[2235]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2236]="*7. Khajjanīyasuttaṃ**Itchy*";
P_HTM[2237]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2238]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussaramānā anussaranti sabbete pañcupādānakkhandhe anussaranti etesaṃ vā aññataraṃ.**“Mendicants, whatever ascetics and brahmins recollect many kinds of past lives, all recollect the five grasping aggregates, or one of them.*";
P_HTM[2239]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[2240]="*‘Evaṃrūpo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti—**‘I had such form in the past.’*";
P_HTM[2241]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, anussaramāno rūpaṃyeva anussarati.**Recollecting thus, it’s only form that they recollect.*";
P_HTM[2242]="*‘Evaṃvedano ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti—**‘I had such feeling …*";
P_HTM[2243]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, anussaramāno vedanaṃyeva anussarati.* **";
P_HTM[2244]="*‘Evaṃsañño ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2245]="*‘evaṃsaṅkhāro ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2246]="*‘evaṃviññāṇo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti—**consciousness in the past.’*";
P_HTM[2247]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, anussaramāno viññāṇameva anussarati.**Recollecting thus, it’s only consciousness that they recollect.*";
P_HTM[2248]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, rūpaṃ vadetha?**And why do you call it form?*";
P_HTM[2249]="*Ruppatīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘rūpan’ti vuccati.**It’s deformed; that’s why it’s called ‘form’.*";
P_HTM[2250]="*Kena ruppati?**Deformed by what?*";
P_HTM[2251]="*Sītenapi ruppati, uṇhenapi ruppati, jighacchāyapi ruppati, pipāsāyapi ruppati, ḍaṃsamakasavātātapasarīsapasamphassenapi ruppati.**Deformed by cold, heat, hunger, and thirst, and deformed by the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and reptiles.*";
P_HTM[2252]="*Ruppatīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘rūpan’ti vuccati.**It’s deformed; that’s why it’s called ‘form’.*";
P_HTM[2253]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, vedanaṃ vadetha?**And why do you call it feeling?*";
P_HTM[2254]="*Vedayatīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘vedanā’ti vuccati.**It feels; that’s why it’s called ‘feeling’.*";
P_HTM[2255]="*Kiñca vedayati?**And what does it feel?*";
P_HTM[2256]="*Sukhampi vedayati, dukkhampi vedayati, adukkhamasukhampi vedayati.**It feels pleasure, pain, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[2257]="*Vedayatīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘vedanā’ti vuccati.**It feels; that’s why it’s called ‘feeling’.*";
P_HTM[2258]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, saññaṃ vadetha?**And why do you call it perception?*";
P_HTM[2259]="*Sañjānātīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘saññā’ti vuccati.**It perceives; that’s why it’s called ‘perception’.*";
P_HTM[2260]="*Kiñca sañjānāti?**And what does it perceive?*";
P_HTM[2261]="*Nīlampi sañjānāti, pītakampi sañjānāti, lohitakampi sañjānāti, odātampi sañjānāti.**It perceives blue, yellow, red, and white.*";
P_HTM[2262]="*Sañjānātīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘saññā’ti vuccati.**It perceives; that’s why it’s called ‘perception’.*";
P_HTM[2263]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, saṅkhāre vadetha?**And why do you call them choices?*";
P_HTM[2264]="*Saṅkhatamabhisaṅkharontīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘saṅkhārā’ti vuccati.**Choices produce conditioned phenomena; that’s why they’re called ‘choices’.*";
P_HTM[2265]="*Kiñca saṅkhatamabhisaṅkharonti?**And what are the conditioned phenomena that they produce?*";
P_HTM[2266]="*Rūpaṃ rūpattāya saṅkhatamabhisaṅkharonti, vedanaṃ vedanattāya saṅkhatamabhisaṅkharonti, saññaṃ saññattāya saṅkhatamabhisaṅkharonti, saṅkhāre saṅkhārattāya saṅkhatamabhisaṅkharonti, viññāṇaṃ viññāṇattāya saṅkhatamabhisaṅkharonti.**Form is a conditioned phenomenon; choices are what make it into form. Feeling is a conditioned phenomenon; choices are what make it into feeling. Perception is a conditioned phenomenon; choices are what make it into perception. Choices are conditioned phenomena; choices are what make them into choices. Consciousness is a conditioned phenomenon; choices are what make it into consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2267]="*Saṅkhatamabhisaṅkharontīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘saṅkhārā’ti vuccati.**Choices produce conditioned phenomena; that’s why they’re called ‘choices’.*";
P_HTM[2268]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, viññāṇaṃ vadetha?**And why do you call it consciousness?*";
P_HTM[2269]="*Vijānātīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘viññāṇan’ti vuccati.**It cognizes; that’s why it’s called ‘consciousness’.*";
P_HTM[2270]="*Kiñca vijānāti?**And what does it cognize?*";
P_HTM[2271]="*Ambilampi vijānāti, tittakampi vijānāti, kaṭukampi vijānāti, madhurampi vijānāti, khārikampi vijānāti, akhārikampi vijānāti, loṇikampi vijānāti, aloṇikampi vijānāti.**It cognizes sour, bitter, pungent, sweet, hot, mild, salty, and bland.*";
P_HTM[2272]="*Vijānātīti kho, bhikkhave, tasmā ‘viññāṇan’ti vuccati.**It cognizes; that’s why it’s called ‘consciousness’.*";
P_HTM[2273]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A noble disciple reflects on this:*";
P_HTM[2274]="*‘ahaṃ kho etarahi rūpena khajjāmi.**‘Currently I’m itched by form.*";
P_HTM[2275]="*Atītampāhaṃ addhānaṃ evameva rūpena khajjiṃ, seyyathāpi etarahi paccuppannena rūpena khajjāmi.**In the past I was also itched by form just like now.*";
P_HTM[2276]="*Ahañceva kho pana anāgataṃ rūpaṃ abhinandeyyaṃ, anāgatampāhaṃ addhānaṃ evameva rūpena khajjeyyaṃ, seyyathāpi etarahi paccuppannena rūpena khajjāmī’ti.**If I were to look forward to enjoying form in the future, I’d be itched by form in the future just as I am today.’*";
P_HTM[2277]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya atītasmiṃ rūpasmiṃ anapekkho hoti;**Reflecting like this they don’t worry about past form,*";
P_HTM[2278]="*anāgataṃ rūpaṃ nābhinandati;**they don’t look forward to enjoying future form,*";
P_HTM[2279]="*paccuppannassa rūpassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.**and they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present form.*";
P_HTM[2280]="*‘Ahaṃ kho etarahi vedanāya khajjāmi.**‘Currently I’m itched by feeling …*";
P_HTM[2281]="*Atītampāhaṃ addhānaṃ evameva vedanāya khajjiṃ, seyyathāpi etarahi paccuppannāya vedanāya khajjāmi.* **";
P_HTM[2282]="*Ahañceva kho pana anāgataṃ vedanaṃ abhinandeyyaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[2283]="*anāgatampāhaṃ addhānaṃ evameva vedanāya khajjeyyaṃ, seyyathāpi etarahi paccuppannāya vedanāya khajjāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2284]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya atītāya vedanāya anapekkho hoti;* **";
P_HTM[2285]="*anāgataṃ vedanaṃ nābhinandati;* **";
P_HTM[2286]="*paccuppannāya vedanāya nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2287]="*‘Ahaṃ kho etarahi saññāya khajjāmi … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2288]="*ahaṃ kho etarahi saṅkhārehi khajjāmi.**choices …*";
P_HTM[2289]="*Atītampāhaṃ addhānaṃ evameva saṅkhārehi khajjiṃ, seyyathāpi etarahi paccuppannehi saṅkhārehi khajjāmīti.* **";
P_HTM[2290]="*Ahañceva kho pana anāgate saṅkhāre abhinandeyyaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[2291]="*anāgatampāhaṃ addhānaṃ evameva saṅkhārehi khajjeyyaṃ, seyyathāpi etarahi paccuppannehi saṅkhārehi khajjāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2292]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya atītesu saṅkhāresu anapekkho hoti;* **";
P_HTM[2293]="*anāgate saṅkhāre nābhinandati;* **";
P_HTM[2294]="*paccuppannānaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2295]="*‘Ahaṃ kho etarahi viññāṇena khajjāmi.**consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2296]="*Atītampi addhānaṃ evameva viññāṇena khajjiṃ, seyyathāpi etarahi paccuppannena viññāṇena khajjāmi.**In the past I was also itched by consciousness just like now.*";
P_HTM[2297]="*Ahañceva kho pana anāgataṃ viññāṇaṃ abhinandeyyaṃ;**If I were to look forward to enjoying consciousness in the future, I’d be itched by consciousness in the future just as I am today.’*";
P_HTM[2298]="*anāgatampāhaṃ addhānaṃ evameva viññāṇena khajjeyyaṃ, seyyathāpi etarahi paccuppannena viññāṇena khajjāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2299]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya atītasmiṃ viññāṇasmiṃ anapekkho hoti;**Reflecting like this they don’t worry about past consciousness,*";
P_HTM[2300]="*anāgataṃ viññāṇaṃ nābhinandati;**they don’t look forward to enjoying future consciousness,*";
P_HTM[2301]="*paccuppannassa viññāṇassa nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.**and they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2302]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[2303]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2304]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2305]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[2306]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2307]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[2308]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[2309]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2310]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[2311]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2312]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2313]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2314]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2315]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[2316]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2317]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[2318]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[2319]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2320]="*“Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, yaṃ kiñci rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ rūpaṃ: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**“So you should truly see any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[2321]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**You should truly see any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[2322]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2323]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2324]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ … pe … yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[2325]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako apacināti, no ācināti;**This is called a noble disciple who gets rid of things and doesn’t accumulate them;*";
P_HTM[2326]="*pajahati, na upādiyati;**who gives things up and doesn’t grasp at them;*";
P_HTM[2327]="*visineti, na ussineti;**who discards things and doesn’t amass them;*";
P_HTM[2328]="*vidhūpeti, na sandhūpeti.**who dissipates things and doesn’t get clouded by them.*";
P_HTM[2329]="*Kiñca apacināti, no ācināti?**And what things do they get rid of and not accumulate?*";
P_HTM[2330]="*Rūpaṃ apacināti, no ācināti;**They get rid of form and don’t accumulate it.*";
P_HTM[2331]="*vedanaṃ …**They get rid of feeling …*";
P_HTM[2332]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2333]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2334]="*viññāṇaṃ apacināti, no ācināti.**consciousness and don’t accumulate it.*";
P_HTM[2335]="*Kiñca pajahati, na upādiyati?**And what things do they give up and not grasp?*";
P_HTM[2336]="*Rūpaṃ pajahati, na upādiyati;**They give up form and don’t grasp it.*";
P_HTM[2337]="*vedanaṃ …**They give up feeling …*";
P_HTM[2338]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2339]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2340]="*viññāṇaṃ pajahati, na upādiyati.**consciousness and don’t grasp it.*";
P_HTM[2341]="*Kiñca visineti, na ussineti?**And what things do they discard and not amass?*";
P_HTM[2342]="*Rūpaṃ visineti, na ussineti;**They discard form and don’t amass it.*";
P_HTM[2343]="*vedanaṃ …**They discard feeling …*";
P_HTM[2344]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2345]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2346]="*viññāṇaṃ visineti, na ussineti.**consciousness and don’t amass it.*";
P_HTM[2347]="*Kiñca vidhūpeti, na sandhūpeti?**And what things do they dissipate and not get clouded by?*";
P_HTM[2348]="*Rūpaṃ vidhūpeti, na sandhūpeti;**They dissipate form and don’t get clouded by it.*";
P_HTM[2349]="*vedanaṃ …**They dissipate feeling …*";
P_HTM[2350]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2351]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2352]="*viññāṇaṃ vidhūpeti, na sandhūpeti.**consciousness and don’t get clouded by it.*";
P_HTM[2353]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi … saññāyapi … saṅkhāresupi … viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2354]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[2355]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[2356]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu nevācināti na apacināti, apacinitvā ṭhito; neva pajahati na upādiyati, pajahitvā ṭhito; neva visineti na ussineti, visinetvā ṭhito; neva vidhūpeti na sandhūpeti vidhūpetvā ṭhito**This is called a mendicant who neither gets rid of things nor accumulates them, but remains after getting rid of them. They neither give things up nor grasp them, but remain after giving them up. They neither discard things nor amass them, but remain after discarding them. They neither dissipate things nor get clouded by them, but remain after dissipating them.*";
P_HTM[2357]="*Kiñca nevācināti na apacināti, apacinitvā ṭhito?**And what things do they neither get rid of nor accumulate, but remain after getting rid of them?*";
P_HTM[2358]="*Rūpaṃ nevācināti na apacināti, apacinitvā ṭhito;**They neither get rid of nor accumulate form, but remain after getting rid of it.*";
P_HTM[2359]="*vedanaṃ …**They neither get rid of nor accumulate feeling …*";
P_HTM[2360]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2361]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2362]="*viññāṇaṃ nevācināti na apacināti, apacinitvā ṭhito.**consciousness, but remain after getting rid of it.*";
P_HTM[2363]="*Kiñca neva pajahati na upādiyati, pajahitvā ṭhito?**And what things do they neither give up nor grasp, but remain after giving them up?*";
P_HTM[2364]="*Rūpaṃ neva pajahati na upādiyati, pajahitvā ṭhito;**They neither give up nor grasp form, but remain after giving it up.*";
P_HTM[2365]="*vedanaṃ …**They neither give up nor grasp feeling …*";
P_HTM[2366]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2367]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2368]="*viññāṇaṃ neva pajahati na upādiyati, pajahitvā ṭhito.**consciousness, but remain after giving it up.*";
P_HTM[2369]="*Kiñca neva visineti na ussineti, visinetvā ṭhito?**And what things do they neither discard nor amass, but remain after discarding them?*";
P_HTM[2370]="*Rūpaṃ neva visineti na ussineti, visinetvā ṭhito;**They neither discard nor amass form, but remain after discarding it.*";
P_HTM[2371]="*vedanaṃ …**They neither discard nor amass feeling …*";
P_HTM[2372]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2373]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2374]="*viññāṇaṃ neva visineti na ussineti, visinetvā ṭhito.**consciousness, but remain after discarding it.*";
P_HTM[2375]="*Kiñca neva vidhūpeti na sandhūpeti, vidhūpetvā ṭhito?**And what things do they neither dissipate nor get clouded by, but remain after dissipating them?*";
P_HTM[2376]="*Rūpaṃ neva vidhūpeti na sandhūpeti, vidhūpetvā ṭhito;**They neither dissipate nor get clouded by form, but remain after dissipating it.*";
P_HTM[2377]="*vedanaṃ …**They neither dissipate nor get clouded by feeling …*";
P_HTM[2378]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2379]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2380]="*viññāṇaṃ neva vidhūpeti na sandhūpeti, vidhūpetvā ṭhito.**consciousness, but remain after dissipating it.*";
P_HTM[2381]="*Evaṃvimuttacittaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuṃ saindā devā sabrahmakā sapajāpatikā ārakāva namassanti:**When a mendicant’s mind is freed like this, the gods together with Indra, Brahmā, and Pajāpati worship them from afar:*";
P_HTM[2382]="*‘Namo te purisājañña,**‘Homage to you, O thoroughbred!*";
P_HTM[2383]="*namo te purisuttama;**Homage to you, supreme among men!*";
P_HTM[2384]="*Yassa te nābhijānāma,**We don’t understand*";
P_HTM[2385]="*yampi nissāya jhāyasī’”ti.**the basis of your absorption.’”*";
P_HTM[2386]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2387]="*8. Piṇḍolyasuttaṃ**Beggars*";
P_HTM[2388]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[2389]="*Atha kho bhagavā kismiñcideva pakaraṇe bhikkhusaṅghaṃ paṇāmetvā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya kapilavatthuṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha, having dismissed the mendicant Saṅgha for some reason, robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Kapilavatthu for alms.*";
P_HTM[2390]="*Kapilavatthusmiṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena mahāvanaṃ tenupasaṅkami divāvihārāya.**He wandered for alms in Kapilavatthu. After the meal, on his return from alms-round, he went to the Great Wood,*";
P_HTM[2391]="*Mahāvanaṃ ajjhogāhetvā beluvalaṭṭhikāya mūle divāvihāraṃ nisīdi.**plunged deep into it, and sat at the root of a young wood apple tree for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[2392]="*Atha kho bhagavato rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Then as he was in private retreat this thought came to his mind,*";
P_HTM[2393]="*“mayā kho bhikkhusaṅgho pabāḷho.**“I’ve sent the mendicant Saṅgha away.*";
P_HTM[2394]="*Santettha bhikkhū navā acirapabbajitā adhunāgatā imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ.**But there are mendicants here who are junior, recently gone forth, newly come to this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[2395]="*Tesaṃ mamaṃ apassantānaṃ siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo.**Not seeing me they may change and fall apart.*";
P_HTM[2396]="*Seyyathāpi nāma vacchassa taruṇassa mātaraṃ apassantassa siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo;**If a young calf doesn’t see its mother it may change and fall apart. …*";
P_HTM[2397]="*evameva santettha bhikkhū navā acirapabbajitā adhunāgatā imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ tesaṃ mamaṃ apassantānaṃ siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo.* **";
P_HTM[2398]="*Seyyathāpi nāma bījānaṃ taruṇānaṃ udakaṃ alabhantānaṃ siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo;**Or if young seedlings don’t get water they may change and fall apart.*";
P_HTM[2399]="*evameva santettha … pe …**In the same way, there are mendicants here who are junior, recently gone forth, newly come to this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[2400]="*tesaṃ mamaṃ alabhantānaṃ dassanāya siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo.**Not seeing me they may change and fall apart.*";
P_HTM[2401]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yatheva mayā pubbe bhikkhusaṅgho anuggahito, evameva etarahi anuggaṇheyyaṃ bhikkhusaṅghan”ti.**Why don’t I support the mendicant Saṅgha now as I did in the past?”*";
P_HTM[2402]="*Atha kho brahmā sahampati bhagavato cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—brahmaloke antarahito bhagavato purato pāturahosi.**Then Brahmā Sahampati knew what the Buddha was thinking. As easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, he vanished from the Brahmā realm and reappeared in front of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2403]="*Atha kho brahmā sahampati ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He arranged his robe over one shoulder, raised his joined palms toward the Buddha, and said:*";
P_HTM[2404]="*“evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugata.**“That’s so true, Blessed One! That’s so true, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[2405]="*Bhagavatā, bhante, bhikkhusaṃgho pabāḷho.**The Buddha has sent the mendicant Saṅgha away.*";
P_HTM[2406]="*Santettha bhikkhū navā acirapabbajitā adhunāgatā imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ.**But there are mendicants who are junior, recently gone forth, newly come to this teaching and training. …*";
P_HTM[2407]="*Tesaṃ bhagavantaṃ apassantānaṃ siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo.* **";
P_HTM[2408]="*Seyyathāpi nāma vacchassa taruṇassa mātaraṃ apassantassa siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo;* **";
P_HTM[2409]="*evameva santettha bhikkhū navā acirapabbajitā adhunāgatā imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ tesaṃ bhagavantaṃ apassantānaṃ siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo.* **";
P_HTM[2410]="*Seyyathāpi nāma bījānaṃ taruṇānaṃ udakaṃ alabhantānaṃ siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo;* **";
P_HTM[2411]="*evameva santettha bhikkhū navā acirapabbajitā adhunāgatā imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ, tesaṃ bhagavantaṃ alabhantānaṃ dassanāya siyā aññathattaṃ siyā vipariṇāmo.* **";
P_HTM[2412]="*Abhinandatu, bhante, bhagavā bhikkhusaṃghaṃ;**May the Buddha be happy with the mendicant Saṅgha!*";
P_HTM[2413]="*abhivadatu, bhante, bhagavā bhikkhusaṃghaṃ.**May the Buddha welcome the mendicant Saṅgha!*";
P_HTM[2414]="*Yatheva bhagavatā pubbe bhikkhusaṃgho anuggahito, evameva etarahi anuggaṇhātu bhikkhusaṃghan”ti.**May the Buddha support the mendicant Saṅgha now as he did in the past!”*";
P_HTM[2415]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[2416]="*Atha kho brahmā sahampati bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyi.**Then Brahmā Sahampati, knowing that the Buddha had consented, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[2417]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena nigrodhārāmo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat and went to the Banyan Tree Monastery, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[2418]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā tathārūpaṃ iddhābhisaṅkhāraṃ abhisaṅkhāsi yathā te bhikkhū ekadvīhikāya sārajjamānarūpā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkameyyuṃ.**Then he used his psychic power to will that the mendicants would come to him timidly, alone or in pairs.*";
P_HTM[2419]="*Tepi bhikkhū ekadvīhikāya sārajjamānarūpā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinne kho te bhikkhū bhagavā etadavoca:**Those mendicants approached the Buddha timidly, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to them:*";
P_HTM[2420]="*“Antamidaṃ, bhikkhave, jīvikānaṃ yadidaṃ piṇḍolyaṃ.**“Mendicants, this relying on alms is an extreme way to live.*";
P_HTM[2421]="*Abhisāpoyaṃ, bhikkhave, lokasmiṃ piṇḍolo vicarasi pattapāṇīti.**The world curses you: ‘You beggar, walking bowl in hand!’*";
P_HTM[2422]="*Tañca kho etaṃ, bhikkhave, kulaputtā upenti atthavasikā, atthavasaṃ paṭicca;**Yet earnest and gentlemen take it up for a good reason.*";
P_HTM[2423]="*neva rājābhinītā, na corābhinītā, na iṇaṭṭā, na bhayaṭṭā, na ājīvikāpakatā;**Not because they’ve been forced to by kings or bandits, or because they’re in debt or threatened, or to earn a living.*";
P_HTM[2424]="*api ca kho otiṇṇāmha jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi dukkhotiṇṇā dukkhaparetā**But because they’re swamped by rebirth, old age, and death; by sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress. They’re swamped by suffering, mired in suffering.*";
P_HTM[2425]="*appeva nāma imassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa antakiriyā paññāyethāti.**And they think, ‘Hopefully I can find an end to this entire mass of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[2426]="*Evaṃ pabbajito cāyaṃ, bhikkhave, kulaputto.**That’s how this gentleman has gone forth.*";
P_HTM[2427]="*So ca hoti abhijjhālu kāmesu tibbasārāgo byāpannacitto paduṭṭhamanasaṅkappo muṭṭhassati asampajāno asamāhito vibbhantacitto pākatindriyo.**Yet they covet sensual pleasures; they’re infatuated, full of ill will and hateful intent. They are unmindful, lacking situational awareness and immersion, with straying mind and undisciplined faculties.*";
P_HTM[2428]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, chavālātaṃ ubhatopadittaṃ majjhe gūthagataṃ, neva gāme kaṭṭhatthaṃ pharati, nāraññe kaṭṭhatthaṃ pharati.**Suppose there was a firebrand for lighting a funeral pyre, burning at both ends, and smeared with dung in the middle. It couldn’t be used as timber either in the village or the wilderness.*";
P_HTM[2429]="*Tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi gihibhogā ca parihīno, sāmaññatthañca na paripūreti.**I say that person is just like this. They’ve missed out on the pleasures of the lay life, and haven’t fulfilled the goal of the ascetic life.*";
P_HTM[2430]="*Tayome, bhikkhave, akusalavitakkā—**There are these three unskillful thoughts.*";
P_HTM[2431]="*kāmavitakko, byāpādavitakko, vihiṃsāvitakko.**Sensual, malicious, and cruel thoughts.*";
P_HTM[2432]="*Ime ca bhikkhave, tayo akusalavitakkā kva aparisesā nirujjhanti?**And where do these three unskillful thoughts cease without anything left over?*";
P_HTM[2433]="*Catūsu vā satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittassa viharato animittaṃ vā samādhiṃ bhāvayato.**In those who meditate with their mind firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation; or who develop signless immersion.*";
P_HTM[2434]="*Yāvañcidaṃ, bhikkhave, alameva animitto samādhi bhāvetuṃ.**Just this much is quite enough motivation to develop signless immersion.*";
P_HTM[2435]="*Animitto, bhikkhave, samādhi bhāvito bahulīkato mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When signless immersion is developed and cultivated it is very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2436]="*Dvemā, bhikkhave, diṭṭhiyo—**There are these two views.*";
P_HTM[2437]="*bhavadiṭṭhi ca vibhavadiṭṭhi ca.**Views favoring continued existence and views favoring ending existence.*";
P_HTM[2438]="*Tatra kho, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A noble disciple reflects on this:*";
P_HTM[2439]="*‘atthi nu kho taṃ kiñci lokasmiṃ yamahaṃ upādiyamāno na vajjavā assan’ti?**‘Is there anything in the world that I could grasp without fault?’*";
P_HTM[2440]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[2441]="*‘natthi nu kho taṃ kiñci lokasmiṃ yamahaṃ upādiyamāno na vajjavā assaṃ.**‘There’s nothing in the world that I could grasp without fault.*";
P_HTM[2442]="*Ahañhi rūpaññeva upādiyamāno upādiyeyyaṃ vedanaññeva …**For in grasping I would grasp only at form, feeling,*";
P_HTM[2443]="*saññaññeva …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2444]="*saṅkhāreyeva viññāṇaññeva upādiyamāno upādiyeyyaṃ.**choices, or consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2445]="*Tassa me assa upādānapaccayā bhavo;**That grasping of mine would be a condition for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[2446]="*bhavapaccayā jāti;**Continued existence is a condition for rebirth.*";
P_HTM[2447]="*jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā sambhaveyyuṃ.**Rebirth is a condition that gives rise to old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[2448]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa samudayo assā’ti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering originates.*";
P_HTM[2449]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[2450]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2451]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2452]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[2453]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2454]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[2455]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[2456]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2457]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[2458]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2459]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2460]="*viññāṇaṃ … pe …**consciousness permanent or impermanent?” …*";
P_HTM[2461]="*tasmātiha, bhikkhave,**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[2462]="*evaṃ passaṃ …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[2463]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[2464]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2465]="*9. Pālileyyasuttaṃ**At Pārileyya*";
P_HTM[2466]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosambiyaṃ viharati ghositārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Kosambi, in Ghosita’s Monastery.*";
P_HTM[2467]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya kosambiṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Kosambi for alms.*";
P_HTM[2468]="*Kosambiyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto sāmaṃ senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya anāmantetvā upaṭṭhāke anapaloketvā bhikkhusaṃghaṃ eko adutiyo cārikaṃ pakkāmi.**After the meal, on his return from alms-round, he set his lodgings in order himself. Taking his bowl and robe, without informing his attendants or taking leave of the mendicant Saṅgha, he set out to go wandering alone, with no companion.*";
P_HTM[2469]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu acirapakkantassa bhagavato yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**Then, not long after the Buddha had left, one of the mendicants went to Venerable Ānanda and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[2470]="*“esāvuso ānanda, bhagavā sāmaṃ senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya anāmantetvā upaṭṭhāke anapaloketvā bhikkhusaṅghaṃ eko adutiyo cārikaṃ pakkanto”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2471]="*“Yasmiṃ, āvuso, samaye bhagavā sāmaṃ senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya anāmantetvā upaṭṭhāke anapaloketvā bhikkhusaṅghaṃ eko adutiyo cārikaṃ pakkamati, ekova bhagavā tasmiṃ samaye viharitukāmo hoti;**Ānanda said, “Reverend, when the Buddha leaves like this it means he wants to stay alone.*";
P_HTM[2472]="*na bhagavā tasmiṃ samaye kenaci anubandhitabbo hotī”ti.**At this time no-one should follow him.”*";
P_HTM[2473]="*Atha kho bhagavā anupubbena cārikaṃ caramāno yena pālileyyakaṃ tadavasari.**Then the Buddha, traveling stage by stage, arrived at Pārileyya,*";
P_HTM[2474]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā pālileyyake viharati bhaddasālamūle.**where he stayed at the root of a sacred sal tree.*";
P_HTM[2475]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then several mendicants went up to Venerable Ānanda and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[2476]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2477]="*“cirassutā kho no, āvuso ānanda, bhagavato sammukhā dhammī kathā;**“Reverend, it’s been a long time since we’ve heard a Dhamma talk from the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2478]="*icchāma mayaṃ, āvuso ānanda, bhagavato sammukhā dhammiṃ kathaṃ sotun”ti.**We wish to hear a Dhamma talk from the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2479]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando tehi bhikkhūhi saddhiṃ yena pālileyyakaṃ bhaddasālamūlaṃ yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Then Venerable Ānanda together with those mendicants went to Pārileyya to see the Buddha. They bowed and sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[2480]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinne kho te bhikkhū bhagavā dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi.**and the Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired them with a Dhamma talk.*";
P_HTM[2481]="*Tena kho pana samayena aññatarassa bhikkhuno evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Now at that time one of the monks had the thought,*";
P_HTM[2482]="*“kathaṃ nu kho jānato kathaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hotī”ti?**“How do you know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life?”*";
P_HTM[2483]="*Atha kho bhagavā tassa bhikkhuno cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha, knowing what that monk was thinking, addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2484]="*“vicayaso desito, bhikkhave, mayā dhammo;**“Mendicants, I’ve taught the Dhamma analytically.*";
P_HTM[2485]="*vicayaso desitā cattāro satipaṭṭhānā;**I’ve analytically taught the four kinds of mindfulness meditation,*";
P_HTM[2486]="*vicayaso desitā cattāro sammappadhānā;**the four right efforts,*";
P_HTM[2487]="*vicayaso desitā cattāro iddhipādā;**the four bases of psychic power,*";
P_HTM[2488]="*vicayaso desitāni pañcindriyāni;**the five faculties,*";
P_HTM[2489]="*vicayaso desitāni pañca balāni;**the five powers,*";
P_HTM[2490]="*vicayaso desitā sattabojjhaṅgā;**the seven awakening factors,*";
P_HTM[2491]="*vicayaso desito ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**and the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[2492]="*Evaṃ vicayaso desito, bhikkhave, mayā dhammo.**That’s how I’ve taught the Dhamma analytically.*";
P_HTM[2493]="*Evaṃ vicayaso desite kho, bhikkhave, mayā dhamme atha ca panidhekaccassa bhikkhuno evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Though I’ve taught the Dhamma analytically, still a certain mendicant present here has this thought:*";
P_HTM[2494]="*‘kathaṃ nu kho jānato kathaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hotī’ti?**‘How do you know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life?’*";
P_HTM[2495]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, jānato kathaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hoti?**And how, mendicants, do you know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life?*";
P_HTM[2496]="*Idha bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**Take an uneducated ordinary person who has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[2497]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati.**They regard form as self.*";
P_HTM[2498]="*Yā kho pana sā, bhikkhave, samanupassanā saṅkhāro so.**But that regarding is just a conditioned phenomenon.*";
P_HTM[2499]="*So pana saṅkhāro kiṃnidāno kiṃsamudayo kiṃjātiko kiṃpabhavo?**And what’s the source, origin, birthplace, and root of that conditioned phenomenon?*";
P_HTM[2500]="*Avijjāsamphassajena, bhikkhave, vedayitena phuṭṭhassa assutavato puthujjanassa uppannā taṇhā;**When an uneducated ordinary person is struck by feelings born of contact with ignorance, craving arises.*";
P_HTM[2501]="*tatojo so saṅkhāro.**That conditioned phenomenon is born from that.*";
P_HTM[2502]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sopi saṅkhāro anicco saṅkhato paṭiccasamuppanno.**So that conditioned phenomenon is impermanent, conditioned, and dependently originated.*";
P_HTM[2503]="*Sāpi taṇhā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.**And that craving,*";
P_HTM[2504]="*Sāpi vedanā, sopi phasso anicco saṅkhato paṭiccasamuppanno.**that feeling, that contact,*";
P_HTM[2505]="*Sāpi avijjā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.**and that ignorance are also impermanent, conditioned, and dependently originated.*";
P_HTM[2506]="*Evampi kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.**That’s how you should know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life.*";
P_HTM[2507]="*Na heva kho rūpaṃ attato samanupassati;**Perhaps they don’t regard form as self,*";
P_HTM[2508]="*api ca kho rūpavantaṃ attānaṃ samanupassati.**but they still regard self as possessing form.*";
P_HTM[2509]="*Yā kho pana sā, bhikkhave, samanupassanā saṅkhāro so.**But that regarding is just a conditioned phenomenon. …*";
P_HTM[2510]="*So pana saṅkhāro kiṃnidāno kiṃsamudayo kiṃjātiko kiṃpabhavo?* **";
P_HTM[2511]="*Avijjāsamphassajena, bhikkhave, vedayitena phuṭṭhassa assutavato puthujjanassa uppannā taṇhā;* **";
P_HTM[2512]="*tatojo so saṅkhāro.* **";
P_HTM[2513]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sopi saṅkhāro anicco saṅkhato paṭiccasamuppanno.* **";
P_HTM[2514]="*Sāpi taṇhā …* **";
P_HTM[2515]="*sāpi vedanā …* **";
P_HTM[2516]="*sopi phasso …* **";
P_HTM[2517]="*sāpi avijjā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.* **";
P_HTM[2518]="*Evampi kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2519]="*Na heva kho rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ attānaṃ samanupassati;**Perhaps they don’t regard form as self, or self as possessing form,*";
P_HTM[2520]="*api ca kho attani rūpaṃ samanupassati.**but they still regard form in self.*";
P_HTM[2521]="*Yā kho pana sā, bhikkhave, samanupassanā saṅkhāro so.**But that regarding is just a conditioned phenomenon. …*";
P_HTM[2522]="*So pana saṅkhāro kiṃnidāno kiṃsamudayo kiṃjātiko kiṃpabhavo?* **";
P_HTM[2523]="*Avijjāsamphassajena, bhikkhave, vedayitena phuṭṭhassa assutavato puthujjanassa uppannā taṇhā;* **";
P_HTM[2524]="*tatojo so saṅkhāro.* **";
P_HTM[2525]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sopi saṅkhāro anicco saṅkhato paṭiccasamuppanno.* **";
P_HTM[2526]="*Sāpi taṇhā …* **";
P_HTM[2527]="*sāpi vedanā …* **";
P_HTM[2528]="*sopi phasso …* **";
P_HTM[2529]="*sāpi avijjā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.* **";
P_HTM[2530]="*Evampi kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2531]="*Na heva kho rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ attānaṃ samanupassati, na attani rūpaṃ samanupassati;**Perhaps they don’t regard form as self, or self as possessing form, or form in self,*";
P_HTM[2532]="*api ca kho rūpasmiṃ attānaṃ samanupassati.**but they still regard self in form.*";
P_HTM[2533]="*Yā kho pana sā, bhikkhave, samanupassanā saṅkhāro so.**But that regarding is just a conditioned phenomenon. …*";
P_HTM[2534]="*So pana saṅkhāro kiṃnidāno kiṃsamudayo kiṃjātiko kiṃpabhavo?* **";
P_HTM[2535]="*Avijjāsamphassajena, bhikkhave, vedayitena phuṭṭhassa assutavato puthujjanassa uppannā taṇhā;* **";
P_HTM[2536]="*tatojo so saṅkhāro.* **";
P_HTM[2537]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sopi saṅkhāro anicco saṅkhato paṭiccasamuppanno.* **";
P_HTM[2538]="*Sāpi taṇhā …* **";
P_HTM[2539]="*sāpi vedanā …* **";
P_HTM[2540]="*sopi phasso …* **";
P_HTM[2541]="*sāpi avijjā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.* **";
P_HTM[2542]="*Evampi kho, bhikkhave, jānato … pe … āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2543]="*Na heva kho rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ attānaṃ, na attani rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ attānaṃ samanupassati;**Perhaps they don’t regard form as self, or self as possessing form, or form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[2544]="*api ca kho vedanaṃ attato samanupassati, api ca kho vedanāvantaṃ attānaṃ samanupassati, api ca kho attani vedanaṃ samanupassati, api ca kho vedanāya attānaṃ samanupassati;**But they regard feeling as self …*";
P_HTM[2545]="*api ca kho saññaṃ …**perception as self …*";
P_HTM[2546]="*api ca kho saṅkhāre attato samanupassati, api ca kho saṅkhāravantaṃ attānaṃ samanupassati, api ca kho attani saṅkhāre samanupassati, api ca kho saṅkhāresu attānaṃ samanupassati;**choices as self …*";
P_HTM[2547]="*api ca kho viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, api ca kho viññāṇavantaṃ attānaṃ, api ca kho attani viññāṇaṃ, api ca kho viññāṇasmiṃ attānaṃ samanupassati.**consciousness as self …*";
P_HTM[2548]="*Yā kho pana sā, bhikkhave, samanupassanā saṅkhāro so.**But that regarding is just a conditioned phenomenon.*";
P_HTM[2549]="*So pana saṅkhāro kiṃnidāno … pe … kiṃpabhavo?**And what’s the source of that conditioned phenomenon?*";
P_HTM[2550]="*Avijjāsamphassajena, bhikkhave, vedayitena phuṭṭhassa assutavato puthujjanassa uppannā taṇhā;**When an uneducated ordinary person is struck by feelings born of contact with ignorance, craving arises.*";
P_HTM[2551]="*tatojo so saṅkhāro.**That conditioned phenomenon is born from that.*";
P_HTM[2552]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sopi saṅkhāro anicco saṅkhato paṭiccasamuppanno.**So that conditioned phenomenon is impermanent, conditioned, and dependently originated.*";
P_HTM[2553]="*Sāpi taṇhā …**And that craving,*";
P_HTM[2554]="*sāpi vedanā …**that feeling,*";
P_HTM[2555]="*sopi phasso …**that contact,*";
P_HTM[2556]="*sāpi avijjā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.**and that ignorance are also impermanent, conditioned, and dependently originated.*";
P_HTM[2557]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.**That’s how you should know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life.*";
P_HTM[2558]="*Na heva kho rūpaṃ attato samanupassati,**Perhaps they don’t regard form*";
P_HTM[2559]="*na vedanaṃ attato samanupassati,**or feeling*";
P_HTM[2560]="*na saññaṃ …**or perception*";
P_HTM[2561]="*na saṅkhāre …**or choices*";
P_HTM[2562]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati;**or consciousness as self.*";
P_HTM[2563]="*api ca kho evaṃdiṭṭhi hoti:**Still, they have such a view:*";
P_HTM[2564]="*‘so attā so loko, so pecca bhavissāmi nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo’ti.**‘The self and the cosmos are one and the same. After passing away I will be permanent, everlasting, eternal, and imperishable.’*";
P_HTM[2565]="*Yā kho pana sā, bhikkhave, sassatadiṭṭhi saṅkhāro so.**But that eternalist view is just a conditioned phenomenon.*";
P_HTM[2566]="*So pana saṅkhāro kiṃnidāno … pe …**And what’s the source of that conditioned phenomenon? …*";
P_HTM[2567]="*evampi kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.**That’s how you should know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life.*";
P_HTM[2568]="*Na heva kho rūpaṃ attato samanupassati,**Perhaps they don’t regard form*";
P_HTM[2569]="*na vedanaṃ …**or feeling*";
P_HTM[2570]="*na saññaṃ …**or perception*";
P_HTM[2571]="*na saṅkhāre …**or choices*";
P_HTM[2572]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati;**or consciousness as self.*";
P_HTM[2573]="*nāpi evaṃdiṭṭhi hoti:**Nor do they have such a view:*";
P_HTM[2574]="*‘so attā so loko, so pecca bhavissāmi nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo’ti.**‘The self and the cosmos are one and the same. After passing away I will be permanent, everlasting, eternal, and imperishable.’*";
P_HTM[2575]="*Api ca kho evaṃdiṭṭhi hoti:**Still, they have such a view:*";
P_HTM[2576]="*‘no cassaṃ no ca me siyā nābhavissaṃ na me bhavissatī’ti.**‘I might not be, and it might not be mine. I will not be, and it will not be mine.’*";
P_HTM[2577]="*Yā kho pana sā, bhikkhave, ucchedadiṭṭhi saṅkhāro so.**But that annihilationist view is just a conditioned phenomenon.*";
P_HTM[2578]="*So pana saṅkhāro kiṃnidāno kiṃsamudayo kiṃjātiko kiṃpabhavo?**And what’s the source of that conditioned phenomenon? …*";
P_HTM[2579]="*Avijjāsamphassajena, bhikkhave, vedayitena phuṭṭhassa assutavato puthujjanassa uppannā taṇhā;* **";
P_HTM[2580]="*tatojo so saṅkhāro.* **";
P_HTM[2581]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sopi saṅkhāro anicco … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2582]="*evampi kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.**That’s how you should know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life.*";
P_HTM[2583]="*Na heva kho rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na vedanaṃ …**Perhaps they don’t regard form or feeling*";
P_HTM[2584]="*na saññaṃ …**or perception*";
P_HTM[2585]="*na saṅkhāre …**or choices*";
P_HTM[2586]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati … pe …**or consciousness as self.*";
P_HTM[2587]="*na viññāṇasmiṃ attato samanupassati, nāpi evaṃdiṭṭhi hoti:**Nor do they have such a view:*";
P_HTM[2588]="*‘so attā so loko, so pecca bhavissāmi nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo’ti;**‘The self and the cosmos are one and the same. After passing away I will be permanent, everlasting, eternal, and imperishable.’*";
P_HTM[2589]="*nāpi evaṃdiṭṭhi hoti:**Nor do they have such a view:*";
P_HTM[2590]="*‘no cassaṃ no ca me siyā nābhavissaṃ na me bhavissatī’ti;**‘I might not be, and it might not be mine. I will not be, and it will not be mine.’*";
P_HTM[2591]="*api ca kho kaṅkhī hoti vicikicchī aniṭṭhaṅgato saddhamme.**Still, they have doubts and uncertainties. They’re undecided about the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[2592]="*Yā kho pana sā, bhikkhave, kaṅkhitā vicikicchitā aniṭṭhaṅgatatā saddhamme saṅkhāro so.**That doubt and uncertainty, the indecision about the true teaching, is just a conditioned phenomenon.*";
P_HTM[2593]="*So pana saṅkhāro kiṃnidāno kiṃsamudayo kiṃjātiko kiṃpabhavo?**And what’s the source of that conditioned phenomenon?*";
P_HTM[2594]="*Avijjāsamphassajena, bhikkhave, vedayitena phuṭṭhassa assutavato puthujjanassa uppannā taṇhā;**When an uneducated ordinary person is struck by feelings born of contact with ignorance, craving arises.*";
P_HTM[2595]="*tatojo so saṅkhāro.**That conditioned phenomenon is born from that.*";
P_HTM[2596]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sopi saṅkhāro anicco saṅkhato paṭiccasamuppanno.**So that conditioned phenomenon is impermanent, conditioned, and dependently originated.*";
P_HTM[2597]="*Sāpi taṇhā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.**And that craving,*";
P_HTM[2598]="*Sāpi vedanā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.**that feeling,*";
P_HTM[2599]="*Sopi phasso anicco saṅkhato paṭiccasamuppanno.**that contact,*";
P_HTM[2600]="*Sāpi avijjā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā.**and that ignorance are also impermanent, conditioned, and dependently originated.*";
P_HTM[2601]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato anantarā āsavānaṃ khayo hotī”ti.**That’s how you should know and see in order to end the defilements in the present life.”*";
P_HTM[2602]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2603]="*10. Puṇṇamasuttaṃ**A Full Moon Night*";
P_HTM[2604]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother, together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants.*";
P_HTM[2605]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā tadahuposathe pannarase puṇṇāya puṇṇamāya rattiyā bhikkhusaṃghaparivuto ajjhokāse nisinno hoti.**Now, at that time it was the sabbath—the full moon on the fifteenth day—and the Buddha was sitting surrounded by the Saṅgha of monks.*";
P_HTM[2606]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then one of the mendicants got up from their seat, arranged their robe over one shoulder, raised their joined palms toward the Buddha, and said:*";
P_HTM[2607]="*“puccheyyāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ kiñcideva desaṃ, sace me bhagavā okāsaṃ karoti pañhassa veyyākaraṇāyā”ti?**“Sir, I’d like to ask the Buddha about a certain point, if you’d take the time to answer.”*";
P_HTM[2608]="*“Tena hi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sake āsane nisīditvā puccha yadākaṅkhasī”ti.**“Well then, mendicant, take your own seat and ask what you wish.”*";
P_HTM[2609]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu bhagavato paṭissutvā sake āsane nisīditvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” replied that mendicant. He took his seat and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2610]="*“ime nu kho, bhante, pañcupādānakkhandhā, seyyathidaṃ—**“Sir, are these the five grasping aggregates, that is:*";
P_HTM[2611]="*rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho”ti.**form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[2612]="*“Ime kho, bhikkhu, pañcupādānakkhandhā;**“Yes, they are,” replied the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2613]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2614]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā bhagavantaṃ uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. Then he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[2615]="*“Ime kho pana, bhante, pañcupādānakkhandhā kiṃmūlakā”ti?**“But sir, what is the root of these five grasping aggregates?”*";
P_HTM[2616]="*“Ime kho, bhikkhu, pañcupādānakkhandhā chandamūlakā”ti … pe …**“These five grasping aggregates are rooted in desire.” …*";
P_HTM[2617]="*taññeva nu kho, bhante, upādānaṃ te pañcupādānakkhandhā udāhu aññatra pañcahi upādānakkhandhehi upādānan”ti?**“But sir, is that grasping the exact same thing as the five grasping aggregates? Or is grasping one thing and the five grasping aggregates another?”*";
P_HTM[2618]="*“Na kho, bhikkhu, taññeva upādānaṃ te pañcupādānakkhandhā nāpi aññatra pañcahi upādānakkhandhehi upādānaṃ, api ca yo tattha chandarāgo taṃ tattha upādānan”ti.**“Neither. Rather, the desire and greed for them is the grasping there.”*";
P_HTM[2619]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant asked another question:*";
P_HTM[2620]="*“Siyā pana, bhante, pañcupādānakkhandhesu chandarāgavemattatā”ti?**“But sir, can there be different kinds of desire and greed for the five grasping aggregates?”*";
P_HTM[2621]="*“Siyā, bhikkhū”ti bhagavā avoca:**“There can,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2622]="*“idha, bhikkhu, ekaccassa evaṃ hoti:**“It’s when someone thinks:*";
P_HTM[2623]="*‘evaṃrūpo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃvedano siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃsañño siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃsaṅkhāro siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃviññāṇo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānan’ti.**‘In the future, may I be of such form, such feeling, such perception, such choices, or such consciousness!’*";
P_HTM[2624]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, siyā pañcupādānakkhandhesu chandarāgavemattatā”ti?**That’s how there can be different kinds of desire and greed for the five grasping aggregates.”*";
P_HTM[2625]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant asked another question:*";
P_HTM[2626]="*“Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, khandhānaṃ khandhādhivacanan”ti?**“Sir, what is the scope of the term ‘aggregates’ as applied to the aggregates?”*";
P_HTM[2627]="*“Yaṃ kiñci, bhikkhu, rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, ayaṃ vuccati rūpakkhandho.**“Any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: this is called the aggregate of form.*";
P_HTM[2628]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**Any kind of feeling at all …*";
P_HTM[2629]="*yā kāci saññā …**Any kind of perception at all …*";
P_HTM[2630]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**Any kind of choices at all …*";
P_HTM[2631]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, ayaṃ vuccati viññāṇakkhandho.**Any kind of consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: this is called the aggregate of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2632]="*Ettāvatā kho, bhikkhu, khandhānaṃ khandhādhivacanan”ti.**That’s the scope of the term ‘aggregates’ as applied to the aggregates.”*";
P_HTM[2633]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu … pe … apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant asked another question:*";
P_HTM[2634]="*“Ko nu kho, bhante, hetu ko paccayo rūpakkhandhassa paññāpanāya;**“What is the cause, sir, what is the reason why the aggregate of form is found?*";
P_HTM[2635]="*ko hetu ko paccayo vedanākkhandhassa paññāpanāya;**What is the cause, what is the reason why the aggregate of feeling …*";
P_HTM[2636]="*ko hetu ko paccayo saññākkhandhassa paññāpanāya;**perception …*";
P_HTM[2637]="*ko hetu ko paccayo saṅkhārakkhandhassa paññāpanāya;**choices …*";
P_HTM[2638]="*ko hetu ko paccayo viññāṇakkhandhassa paññāpanāyā”ti?**consciousness is found?”*";
P_HTM[2639]="*“Cattāro kho, bhikkhu, mahābhūtā hetu, cattāro mahābhūtā paccayo rūpakkhandhassa paññāpanāya.**“The four primary elements are the reason why the aggregate of form is found.*";
P_HTM[2640]="*Phasso hetu phasso paccayo vedanākkhandhassa paññāpanāya.**Contact is the reason why the aggregates of feeling,*";
P_HTM[2641]="*Phasso hetu phasso paccayo saññākkhandhassa paññāpanāya.**perception,*";
P_HTM[2642]="*Phasso hetu, phasso paccayo saṅkhārakkhandhassa paññāpanāya.**and choices are found.*";
P_HTM[2643]="*Nāmarūpaṃ hetu, nāmarūpaṃ paccayo viññāṇakkhandhassa paññāpanāyā”ti.**Name and form are the reasons why the aggregate of consciousness is found.”*";
P_HTM[2644]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu … pe … apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant asked another question:*";
P_HTM[2645]="*“Kathaṃ nu kho, bhante, sakkāyadiṭṭhi hotī”ti?**“Sir, how does identity view come about?”*";
P_HTM[2646]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**“It’s because an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[2647]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[2648]="*vedanaṃ …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[2649]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2650]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2651]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2652]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, sakkāyadiṭṭhi hotī”ti.**That’s how identity view comes about.”*";
P_HTM[2653]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu … pe … apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant … asked another question:*";
P_HTM[2654]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, sakkāyadiṭṭhi na hotī”ti?**“But sir, how does identity view not come about?”*";
P_HTM[2655]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto, sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto**It’s because an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[2656]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[2657]="*na vedanaṃ …**They don’t regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[2658]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2659]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2660]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā viññāṇaṃ, na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2661]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, sakkāyadiṭṭhi na hotī”ti.**That’s how identity view does not come about.”*";
P_HTM[2662]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu … pe … apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant … asked another question:*";
P_HTM[2663]="*“Ko nu kho, bhante, rūpassa assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ;**“Sir, what’s the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[2664]="*ko vedanāya …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[2665]="*ko saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2666]="*ko saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices,*";
P_HTM[2667]="*ko viññāṇassa assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan”ti?**and consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[2668]="*“Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, rūpaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ—ayaṃ rūpassa assādo.**“The pleasure and happiness that arise from form: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[2669]="*Yaṃ rūpaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ—ayaṃ rūpassa ādīnavo.**That form is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[2670]="*Yo rūpasmiṃ chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ—idaṃ rūpassa nissaraṇaṃ.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for form: this is its escape.*";
P_HTM[2671]="*Yaṃ vedanaṃ paṭicca …**The pleasure and happiness that arise from feeling …*";
P_HTM[2672]="*yaṃ saññaṃ paṭicca …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2673]="*ye saṅkhāre paṭicca …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2674]="*yaṃ viññāṇaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ—ayaṃ viññāṇassa assādo.**consciousness: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[2675]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ—ayaṃ viññāṇassa ādīnavo.**That consciousness is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[2676]="*Yo viññāṇasmiṃ chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ—idaṃ viññāṇassa nissaraṇan”ti.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for consciousness: this is its escape.”*";
P_HTM[2677]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā bhagavantaṃ uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. Then he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[2678]="*“Kathaṃ nu kho, bhante, jānato, kathaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayā na hontī”ti?**“Sir, how does one know and see so that there’s no ego, possessiveness, or underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli?”*";
P_HTM[2679]="*“Yaṃ kiñci, bhikkhu, rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ rūpaṃ: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passati.**“One truly sees any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[2680]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**They truly see any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[2681]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2682]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2683]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passati.**consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near, all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[2684]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, jānato evaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayā na hontī”ti.**That’s how to know and see so that there’s no ego, possessiveness, or underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli.”*";
P_HTM[2685]="*Tena kho pana samayena aññatarassa bhikkhuno evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Now at that time one of the mendicants had the thought:*";
P_HTM[2686]="*“iti kira bho rūpaṃ anattā, vedanā … saññā … saṅkhārā … viññāṇaṃ anattā;**“So it seems, good sir, that form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are not-self.*";
P_HTM[2687]="*anattakatāni kammāni kathamattānaṃ phusissantī”ti.**Then what self will the deeds done by not-self affect?”*";
P_HTM[2688]="*Atha kho bhagavā tassa bhikkhuno cetasā ceto parivitakkamaññāya bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha, knowing what that monk was thinking, addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2689]="*“Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati yaṃ idhekacco moghapuriso avidvā avijjāgato taṇhādhipateyyena cetasā satthusāsanaṃ atidhāvitabbaṃ maññeyya.**“It’s possible that some foolish person here—unknowing and ignorant, their mind dominated by craving—thinks they can overstep the teacher’s instructions. They think:*";
P_HTM[2690]="*‘Iti kira, bho, rūpaṃ anattā, vedanā … saññā … saṅkhārā … viññāṇaṃ anattā.**‘So it seems, good sir, that form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are not-self.*";
P_HTM[2691]="*Anattakatāni kammāni kathamattānaṃ phusissantī’ti?**Then what self will the deeds done by not-self affect?’*";
P_HTM[2692]="*Paṭipucchāvinītā kho me tumhe, bhikkhave, tatra tatra tesu tesu dhammesu.**Now, mendicants, you have been educated by me in questioning with regards to all these things in all such cases.*";
P_HTM[2693]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[2694]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2695]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2696]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[2697]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2698]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2699]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2700]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2701]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[2702]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2703]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[2704]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[2705]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2706]="*Tasmātiha … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[2707]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[2708]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[2709]="*“Dve khandhā taññeva siyaṃ,**“Two on the aggregates; exactly the same; and can there be;*";
P_HTM[2710]="*adhivacanañca hetunā;**on the term; and on the cause;*";
P_HTM[2711]="*Sakkāyena duve vuttā,**two questions on identity;*";
P_HTM[2712]="*assādaviññāṇakena ca;**gratification; and that with consciousness:*";
P_HTM[2713]="*Ete dasavidhā vuttā,**these are the ten questions*";
P_HTM[2714]="*hoti bhikkhu pucchāyā”ti.**the mendicant came to ask.”*";
P_HTM[2715]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2716]="*Khajjanīyavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[2717]="*Assādo dve samudayā,* **";
P_HTM[2718]="*arahantehi apare dve;* **";
P_HTM[2719]="*Sīho khajjanī piṇḍolyaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[2720]="*pālileyyena puṇṇamāti.* **";
P_HTM[2721]="*sn/sn22.083.xhtml==9. Theravagga==9. Theravaggo**Senior Mendicants*";
P_HTM[2722]="*1. Ānandasuttaṃ**With Ānanda*";
P_HTM[2723]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2724]="*Tatra kho āyasmā ānando bhikkhū āmantesi:**There Ānanda addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2725]="*“āvuso bhikkhave”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2726]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato ānandassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2727]="*Āyasmā ānando etadavoca:**Ānanda said this:*";
P_HTM[2728]="*“Puṇṇo nāma, āvuso, āyasmā mantāṇiputto amhākaṃ navakānaṃ sataṃ bahūpakāro hoti.**“Reverends, the venerable named Puṇṇa Mantāniputta was very helpful to me when I was just ordained.*";
P_HTM[2729]="*So amhe iminā ovādena ovadati:**He gave me this advice:*";
P_HTM[2730]="*‘upādāya, āvuso ānanda, asmīti hoti, no anupādāya.**‘Reverend Ānanda, the notion “I am” occurs because of grasping, not by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[2731]="*Kiñca upādāya asmīti hoti, no anupādāya?**Grasping what?*";
P_HTM[2732]="*Rūpaṃ upādāya asmīti hoti, no anupādāya.**The notion “I am” occurs because of grasping form,*";
P_HTM[2733]="*Vedanaṃ …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[2734]="*saññaṃ …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2735]="*saṅkhāre …**choices,*";
P_HTM[2736]="*viññāṇaṃ upādāya asmīti hoti, no anupādāya.**and consciousness, not by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[2737]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso ānanda, itthī vā puriso vā daharo yuvā maṇḍanakajātiko ādāse vā parisuddhe pariyodāte acche vā udakapatte sakaṃ mukhanimittaṃ paccavekkhamāno upādāya passeyya, no anupādāya;**Suppose there was a woman or man who was young, youthful, and fond of adornments, and they check their own reflection in a clean bright mirror or a clear bowl of water. They’d look because of grasping, not by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[2738]="*evameva kho, āvuso ānanda, rūpaṃ upādāya asmīti hoti, no anupādāya.**In the same way, the notion “I am” occurs because of grasping form,*";
P_HTM[2739]="*Vedanaṃ …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[2740]="*saññaṃ …**perception,*";
P_HTM[2741]="*saṅkhāre …**choices,*";
P_HTM[2742]="*viññāṇaṃ upādāya asmīti hoti, no anupādāya.**and consciousness, not by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[2743]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso ānanda,**What do you think, Reverend Ānanda?*";
P_HTM[2744]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā’ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?’*";
P_HTM[2745]="*‘Aniccaṃ, āvuso’.**‘Impermanent, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[2746]="*‘Vedanā …**‘Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[2747]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2748]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2749]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā’ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?’*";
P_HTM[2750]="*‘Aniccaṃ, āvuso’ … pe ….**‘Impermanent, reverend.’ …*";
P_HTM[2751]="*Tasmātiha … pe …**‘So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[2752]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[2753]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātīti.**They understand: “… there is no return to any state of existence.”’*";
P_HTM[2754]="*Puṇṇo nāma, āvuso, āyasmā mantāṇiputto amhākaṃ navakānaṃ sataṃ bahūpakāro hoti.**Reverends, the venerable named Puṇṇa Mantāniputta was very helpful to me when I was just ordained.*";
P_HTM[2755]="*So amhe iminā ovādena ovadati.**He gave me this advice.*";
P_HTM[2756]="*Idañca pana me āyasmato puṇṇassa mantāṇiputtassa dhammadesanaṃ sutvā dhammo abhisamito”ti.**And now that I’ve heard this teaching from Venerable Puṇṇa Mantāniputta, I’ve comprehended the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[2757]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2758]="*2. Tissasuttaṃ**With Tissa*";
P_HTM[2759]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2760]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā tisso bhagavato pitucchāputto sambahulānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ evamāroceti:**Now at that time Venerable Tissa, the Buddha’s paternal cousin, informed several mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2761]="*“api me, āvuso, madhurakajāto viya kāyo;**“Reverends, my body feels like it’s drugged. I’m disorientated, the teachings don’t inspire me, and dullness and drowsiness fill my mind. I live the spiritual life dissatisfied, and have doubts about the teachings.”*";
P_HTM[2762]="*disāpi me na pakkhāyanti;* **";
P_HTM[2763]="*dhammāpi maṃ na paṭibhanti;* **";
P_HTM[2764]="*thinamiddhañca me cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhati;* **";
P_HTM[2765]="*anabhirato ca brahmacariyaṃ carāmi;* **";
P_HTM[2766]="*hoti ca me dhammesu vicikicchā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2767]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[2768]="*“āyasmā, bhante, tisso bhagavato pitucchāputto sambahulānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ evamāroceti:* **";
P_HTM[2769]="*‘api me, āvuso, madhurakajāto viya kāyo;* **";
P_HTM[2770]="*disāpi me na pakkhāyanti;* **";
P_HTM[2771]="*dhammāpi maṃ na paṭibhanti;* **";
P_HTM[2772]="*thinamiddhañca me cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhati;* **";
P_HTM[2773]="*anabhirato ca brahmacariyaṃ carāmi;* **";
P_HTM[2774]="*hoti ca me dhammesu vicikicchā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2775]="*Atha kho bhagavā aññataraṃ bhikkhuṃ āmantesi:**So the Buddha said to a certain monk,*";
P_HTM[2776]="*“ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mama vacanena tissaṃ bhikkhuṃ āmantehī”ti.**“Please, mendicant, in my name tell the mendicant Tissa that the Teacher summons him.”*";
P_HTM[2777]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu bhagavato paṭissutvā yenāyasmā tisso tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ tissaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” that monk replied. He went to Tissa and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2778]="*“satthā taṃ, āvuso tissa, āmantetī”ti.**“Reverend Tissa, the teacher summons you.”*";
P_HTM[2779]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā tisso tassa bhikkhuno paṭissutvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ tissaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**“Yes, reverend,” Tissa replied. He went to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[2780]="*“saccaṃ kira tvaṃ, tissa, sambahulānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ evamārocesi:**“Is it really true, Tissa, that you informed several mendicants that*";
P_HTM[2781]="*‘api me, āvuso, madhurakajāto viya kāyo … pe …**your body feels like it’s drugged …*";
P_HTM[2782]="*hoti ca me dhammesu vicikicchā’”ti?**and you have doubts about the teachings?”*";
P_HTM[2783]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2784]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, tissa,**“What do you think, Tissa?*";
P_HTM[2785]="*rūpe avigatarāgassa avigatacchandassa avigatapemassa avigatapipāsassa avigatapariḷāhassa avigatataṇhassa, tassa rūpassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?**If you’re not rid of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for form, when that form decays and perishes, will it give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress?”*";
P_HTM[2786]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2787]="*“Sādhu sādhu, tissa.**“Good, good, Tissa!*";
P_HTM[2788]="*Evañhetaṃ, tissa, hoti.**That’s how it is, Tissa,*";
P_HTM[2789]="*Yathā taṃ rūpe avigatarāgassa …**when you’re not rid of greed for form.*";
P_HTM[2790]="*vedanāya …**If you’re not rid of greed for feeling …*";
P_HTM[2791]="*saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2792]="*saṅkhāresu avigatarāgassa … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2793]="*tesaṃ saṅkhārānaṃ vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2794]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[2795]="*“Sādhu sādhu, tissa.* **";
P_HTM[2796]="*Evañhetaṃ, tissa, hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2797]="*Yathā taṃ saṅkhāresu anigatarāgassa, viññāṇe avigatarāgassa avigatacchandassa avigatapemassa avigatapipāsassa avigatapariḷāhassa avigatataṇhassa, tassa viññāṇassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?**consciousness, when that consciousness decays and perishes, will it give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress?”*";
P_HTM[2798]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2799]="*“Sādhu sādhu, tissa.**“Good, good, Tissa!*";
P_HTM[2800]="*Evañhetaṃ, tissa, hoti.**That’s how it is, Tissa,*";
P_HTM[2801]="*Yathā taṃ viññāṇe avigatarāgassa.**when you’re not rid of greed for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2802]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, tissa,**What do you think, Tissa?*";
P_HTM[2803]="*rūpe vigatarāgassa vigatacchandassa vigatapemassa vigatapipāsassa vigatapariḷāhassa vigatataṇhassa, tassa rūpassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?**If you are rid of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for form, when that form decays and perishes, will it give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress?”*";
P_HTM[2804]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2805]="*“Sādhu sādhu, tissa.**“Good, good, Tissa!*";
P_HTM[2806]="*Evañhetaṃ, tissa, hoti.**That’s how it is, Tissa,*";
P_HTM[2807]="*Yathā taṃ rūpe vigatarāgassa …**when you are rid of greed for form …*";
P_HTM[2808]="*vedanāya …**feeling …*";
P_HTM[2809]="*saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2810]="*saṅkhāresu vigatarāgassa …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2811]="*viññāṇe vigatarāgassa vigatacchandassa vigatapemassa vigatapipāsassa vigatapariḷāhassa vigatataṇhassa tassa viññāṇassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2812]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[2813]="*“Sādhu sādhu, tissa.* **";
P_HTM[2814]="*Evañhetaṃ, tissa, hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2815]="*Yathā taṃ viññāṇe vigatarāgassa.**consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2816]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, tissa,**What do you think, Tissa?*";
P_HTM[2817]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2818]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2819]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[2820]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2821]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2822]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2823]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2824]="*“Tasmātiha … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[2825]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[2826]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[2827]="*Seyyathāpi, tissa, dve purisā—**Suppose, Tissa, there were two people.*";
P_HTM[2828]="*eko puriso amaggakusalo, eko puriso maggakusalo.**One was not skilled in the path, the other was.*";
P_HTM[2829]="*Tamenaṃ so amaggakusalo puriso amuṃ maggakusalaṃ purisaṃ maggaṃ puccheyya.**The one not skilled in the path would question the one skilled in the path,*";
P_HTM[2830]="*So evaṃ vadeyya:**who would reply:*";
P_HTM[2831]="*‘ehi, bho purisa, ayaṃ maggo.**‘Come, good man, this is the path.*";
P_HTM[2832]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gaccha.**Go down it a little,*";
P_HTM[2833]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi dvedhāpathaṃ, tattha vāmaṃ muñcitvā dakkhiṇaṃ gaṇhāhi.**and you’ll see a fork in the road. Ignore the left, and take the right-hand path.*";
P_HTM[2834]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gaccha.**Go a little further,*";
P_HTM[2835]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi tibbaṃ vanasaṇḍaṃ.**and you’ll see a dark forest grove.*";
P_HTM[2836]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gaccha.**Go a little further,*";
P_HTM[2837]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi mahantaṃ ninnaṃ pallalaṃ.**and you’ll see an expanse of low-lying marshes.*";
P_HTM[2838]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gaccha.**Go a little further,*";
P_HTM[2839]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi sobbhaṃ papātaṃ.**and you’ll see a large, steep cliff.*";
P_HTM[2840]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gaccha.**Go a little further,*";
P_HTM[2841]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi samaṃ bhūmibhāgaṃ ramaṇīyan’ti.**and you’ll see level, cleared parkland.’*";
P_HTM[2842]="*Upamā kho myāyaṃ, tissa, katā atthassa viññāpanāya.**I’ve made up this simile to make a point.*";
P_HTM[2843]="*Ayaṃ cevettha attho:**And this is what it means.*";
P_HTM[2844]="*‘puriso amaggakusalo’ti kho, tissa, puthujjanassetaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘A person who is not skilled in the path’ is a term for an ordinary uneducated person.*";
P_HTM[2845]="*‘Puriso maggakusalo’ti kho, tissa, tathāgatassetaṃ adhivacanaṃ arahato sammāsambuddhassa.**‘A person who is skilled in the path’ is a term for the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2846]="*‘Dvedhāpatho’ti kho, tissa, vicikicchāyetaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘A fork in the road’ is a term for doubt.*";
P_HTM[2847]="*‘Vāmo maggo’ti kho, tissa, aṭṭhaṅgikassetaṃ micchāmaggassa adhivacanaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—**‘The left-hand path’ is a term for the wrong eightfold path, that is,*";
P_HTM[2848]="*micchādiṭṭhiyā … pe … micchāsamādhissa.**wrong view … wrong immersion.*";
P_HTM[2849]="*‘Dakkhiṇo maggo’ti kho, tissa, ariyassetaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikassa maggassa adhivacanaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—**‘The right-hand path’ is a term for the noble eightfold path, that is,*";
P_HTM[2850]="*sammādiṭṭhiyā … pe … sammāsamādhissa.**right view … right immersion.*";
P_HTM[2851]="*‘Tibbo vanasaṇḍo’ti kho, tissa, avijjāyetaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘A dark forest grove’ is a term for ignorance.*";
P_HTM[2852]="*‘Mahantaṃ ninnaṃ pallalan’ti kho, tissa, kāmānametaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘An expanse of low-lying marshes’ is a term for sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[2853]="*‘Sobbho papāto’ti kho, tissa, kodhūpāyāsassetaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘A large, steep cliff’ is a term for anger and distress.*";
P_HTM[2854]="*‘Samo bhūmibhāgo ramaṇīyo’ti kho, tissa, nibbānassetaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘Level, cleared parkland’ is a term for extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[2855]="*Abhirama, tissa, abhirama, tissa.**Rejoice, Tissa, rejoice!*";
P_HTM[2856]="*Ahamovādena ahamanuggahena ahamanusāsaniyā”ti.**I’m here to advise you, to support you, and to teach you.”*";
P_HTM[2857]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2858]="*Attamano āyasmā tisso bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Tissa was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2859]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2860]="*3. Yamakasuttaṃ**With Yamaka*";
P_HTM[2861]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā sāriputto sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[2862]="*Tena kho pana samayena yamakassa nāma bhikkhuno evarūpaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ hoti:**Now at that time a mendicant called Yamaka had the following harmful misconception:*";
P_HTM[2863]="*“tathāhaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi, yathā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā”ti.**“As I understand the Buddha’s teaching, a mendicant who has ended the defilements is annihilated and destroyed when their body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death.”*";
P_HTM[2864]="*Assosuṃ kho sambahulā bhikkhū yamakassa kira nāma bhikkhuno evarūpaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ hoti:**Several mendicants heard about this.*";
P_HTM[2865]="*“tathāhaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi, yathā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2866]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū yenāyasmā yamako tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā yamakena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**They went to Yamaka and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[2867]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū āyasmantaṃ yamakaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2868]="*“Saccaṃ kira te, āvuso yamaka, evarūpaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ:**“Is it really true, Reverend Yamaka, that you have such a harmful misconception:*";
P_HTM[2869]="*‘tathāhaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi, yathā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā’”ti?**‘As I understand the Buddha’s teaching, a mendicant who has ended the defilements is annihilated and destroyed when their body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death.’”*";
P_HTM[2870]="*“Evaṃ khvāhaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi:**“Yes, reverends, that’s how I understand the Buddha’s teaching.”*";
P_HTM[2871]="*‘khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2872]="*“Mā, āvuso yamaka, evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi. Na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhācikkhanaṃ. Na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya:**“Don’t say that, Yamaka! Don’t misrepresent the Buddha, for misrepresentation of the Buddha is not good. And the Buddha would not say that.”*";
P_HTM[2873]="*‘khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2874]="*Evampi kho āyasmā yamako tehi bhikkhūhi vuccamāno tatheva taṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati:**But even though admonished by those mendicants, Yamaka obstinately stuck to that misconception and insisted on stating it.*";
P_HTM[2875]="*“tathāhaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi, yathā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2876]="*Yato kho te bhikkhū nāsakkhiṃsu āyasmantaṃ yamakaṃ etasmā pāpakā diṭṭhigatā vivecetuṃ, atha kho te bhikkhū uṭṭhāyāsanā yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When those mendicants were unable to dissuade Yamaka from that misconception, they got up from their seats and went to see Venerable Sāriputta. They told him what had happened, and said,*";
P_HTM[2877]="*“yamakassa nāma, āvuso sāriputta, bhikkhuno evarūpaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[2878]="*‘tathāhaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi yathā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2879]="*Sādhāyasmā sāriputto yena yamako bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**“May Venerable Sāriputta please go to the mendicant Yamaka out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[2880]="*Adhivāsesi kho āyasmā sāriputto tuṇhībhāvena.**Sāriputta consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[2881]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā yamako tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā yamakena saddhiṃ sammodi … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ yamakaṃ etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Sāriputta came out of retreat, went to Venerable Yamaka and exchanged greetings with him. Seated to one side he said to Yamaka:*";
P_HTM[2882]="*“Saccaṃ kira te, āvuso yamaka, evarūpaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ:**“Is it really true, Reverend Yamaka, that you have such a harmful misconception:*";
P_HTM[2883]="*‘tathāhaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi, yathā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā’”ti?**‘As I understand the Buddha’s teaching, a mendicant who has ended the defilements is annihilated and destroyed when their body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death.’”*";
P_HTM[2884]="*“Evaṃ khvāhaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi, yathā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā”ti.**“Yes, reverend, that’s how I understand the Buddha’s teaching.”*";
P_HTM[2885]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso yamaka,**“What do you think, Yamaka?*";
P_HTM[2886]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2887]="*“Aniccaṃ, āvuso”.**“Impermanent, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2888]="*“Vedanā niccā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[2889]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2890]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2891]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2892]="*“Aniccaṃ, āvuso”.**“Impermanent, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2893]="*“Tasmātiha … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[2894]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[2895]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[2896]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso yamaka,**What do you think, Reverend Yamaka?*";
P_HTM[2897]="*rūpaṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the Realized One as form?”*";
P_HTM[2898]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso” …**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2899]="*“vedanaṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**“Do you regard the Realized One as feeling …*";
P_HTM[2900]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso” …* **";
P_HTM[2901]="*“saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2902]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2903]="*viññāṇaṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[2904]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso”.**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2905]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso yamaka,**“What do you think, Reverend Yamaka?*";
P_HTM[2906]="*rūpasmiṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the Realized One as in form?”*";
P_HTM[2907]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso”.**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2908]="*“Aññatra rūpā tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**“Or do you regard the Realized One as distinct from form?”*";
P_HTM[2909]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso”.**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2910]="*“Vedanāya …**“Do you regard the Realized One as in feeling …*";
P_HTM[2911]="*aññatra vedanāya … pe …**or distinct from feeling …*";
P_HTM[2912]="*saññāya …**as in perception …*";
P_HTM[2913]="*aññatra saññāya …**or distinct from perception …*";
P_HTM[2914]="*saṅkhāresu …**as in choices …*";
P_HTM[2915]="*aññatra saṅkhārehi …**or distinct from choices …*";
P_HTM[2916]="*viññāṇasmiṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**as in consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[2917]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso”.**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2918]="*“Aññatra viññāṇā tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**“Or do you regard the Realized One as distinct from consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[2919]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso”.**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2920]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso yamaka,**“What do you think, Yamaka?*";
P_HTM[2921]="*rūpaṃ … vedanaṃ … saññaṃ … saṅkhāre … viññāṇaṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the Realized One as possessing form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[2922]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso”.**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2923]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso yamaka,**“What do you think, Yamaka?*";
P_HTM[2924]="*ayaṃ so arūpī … avedano … asaññī … asaṅkhāro … aviññāṇo tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the Realized One as one who is without form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[2925]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso”.**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2926]="*“Ettha ca te, āvuso yamaka, diṭṭheva dhamme saccato thetato tathāgate anupalabbhiyamāne, kallaṃ nu te taṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ:**“In that case, Reverend Yamaka, since you don’t acknowledge the Realized One as a genuine fact in the present life, is it appropriate to declare:*";
P_HTM[2927]="*‘tathāhaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi, yathā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā’”ti?**‘As I understand the Buddha’s teaching, a mendicant who has ended the defilements is annihilated and destroyed when their body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death.’?”*";
P_HTM[2928]="*“Ahu kho me taṃ, āvuso sāriputta, pubbe aviddasuno pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ;**“Reverend Sāriputta, in my ignorance, I used to have that misconception.*";
P_HTM[2929]="*idañca panāyasmato sāriputtassa dhammadesanaṃ sutvā tañceva pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ pahīnaṃ, dhammo ca me abhisamito”ti.**But now that I’ve heard the teaching from Venerable Sāriputta I’ve given up that misconception, and I’ve comprehended the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[2930]="*“Sace taṃ, āvuso yamaka, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Reverend Yamaka, suppose they were to ask you:*";
P_HTM[2931]="*‘yo so, āvuso yamaka, bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā kiṃ hotī’ti?**‘When their body breaks up, after death, what happens to a perfected one, who has ended the defilements?’*";
P_HTM[2932]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho tvaṃ, āvuso yamaka, kinti byākareyyāsī”ti?**How would you answer?”*";
P_HTM[2933]="*“Sace maṃ, āvuso, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Sir, if they were to ask this,*";
P_HTM[2934]="*‘yo so, āvuso yamaka, bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā kiṃ hotī’ti?* **";
P_HTM[2935]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhohaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ byākareyyaṃ:**I’d answer like this:*";
P_HTM[2936]="*‘rūpaṃ kho, āvuso, aniccaṃ.**‘Reverend, form is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2937]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[2938]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ taṃ niruddhaṃ tadatthaṅgataṃ.**What’s suffering has ceased and ended.*";
P_HTM[2939]="*Vedanā …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[2940]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2941]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2942]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**consciousness is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2943]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhaṃ;**What’s impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[2944]="*yaṃ dukkhaṃ taṃ niruddhaṃ tadatthaṅgatan’ti.**What’s suffering has ceased and ended.’*";
P_HTM[2945]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhohaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ byākareyyan”ti.**That’s how I’d answer such a question.”*";
P_HTM[2946]="*“Sādhu sādhu, āvuso yamaka.**“Good, good, Reverend Yamaka!*";
P_HTM[2947]="*Tena hāvuso yamaka, upamaṃ te karissāmi etasseva atthassa bhiyyoso mattāya ñāṇāya.**Well then, I shall give you a simile to make the meaning even clearer.*";
P_HTM[2948]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso yamaka, gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo;**Suppose there was a householder or householder’s son who was rich, with a lot of money and great wealth,*";
P_HTM[2949]="*so ca ārakkhasampanno.**and a bodyguard for protection.*";
P_HTM[2950]="*Tassa kocideva puriso uppajjeyya anatthakāmo ahitakāmo ayogakkhemakāmo jīvitā voropetukāmo.**Then along comes a person who wants to harm, injure, and threaten him, and take his life.*";
P_HTM[2951]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[2952]="*‘ayaṃ kho gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo;**‘This householder or householder’s son is rich, with a lot of money and great wealth,*";
P_HTM[2953]="*so ca ārakkhasampanno;**and a bodyguard for protection.*";
P_HTM[2954]="*nāyaṃ sukaro pasayha jīvitā voropetuṃ.**It won’t be easy to take his life by force.*";
P_HTM[2955]="*Yannūnāhaṃ anupakhajja jīvitā voropeyyan’ti.**Why don’t I get close to him, then take his life?’*";
P_HTM[2956]="*So taṃ gahapatiṃ vā gahapatiputtaṃ vā upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadeyya:**So he goes up to that householder or householder’s son and says:*";
P_HTM[2957]="*‘upaṭṭhaheyyaṃ taṃ, bhante’ti.**‘Sir, I would serve you.’*";
P_HTM[2958]="*Tamenaṃ so gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā upaṭṭhāpeyya.**Then they would serve that householder or householder’s son.*";
P_HTM[2959]="*So upaṭṭhaheyya pubbuṭṭhāyī pacchānipātī kiṃkārapaṭissāvī manāpacārī piyavādī.**They’d get up before him and go to bed after him, and be obliging, behaving nicely and speaking politely.*";
P_HTM[2960]="*Tassa so gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā mittatopi naṃ saddaheyya;**The householder or householder’s son would consider them as a friend*";
P_HTM[2961]="*suhajjatopi naṃ saddaheyya;**and companion,*";
P_HTM[2962]="*tasmiñca vissāsaṃ āpajjeyya.**and come to trust them.*";
P_HTM[2963]="*Yadā kho, āvuso, tassa purisassa evamassa:**But when that person realizes that*";
P_HTM[2964]="*‘saṃvissattho kho myāyaṃ gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā’ti, atha naṃ rahogataṃ viditvā tiṇhena satthena jīvitā voropeyya.**they’ve gained the trust of the householder or householder’s son, then, when they know he’s alone, they’d take his life with a sharp knife.*";
P_HTM[2965]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso yamaka,**What do you think, Yamaka?*";
P_HTM[2966]="*yadā hi so puriso amuṃ gahapatiṃ vā gahapatiputtaṃ vā upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ āha:**When that person went to the householder or householder’s son and offered to*";
P_HTM[2967]="*‘upaṭṭhaheyyaṃ taṃ, bhante’ti, tadāpi so vadhakova.**serve him, weren’t they a killer then,*";
P_HTM[2968]="*Vadhakañca pana santaṃ na aññāsi:**though he didn’t know that*";
P_HTM[2969]="*‘vadhako me’ti.**this was his killer?*";
P_HTM[2970]="*Yadāpi so upaṭṭhahati pubbuṭṭhāyī pacchānipātī kiṅkārapaṭissāvī manāpacārī piyavādī, tadāpi so vadhakova.**And when they got up before him and went to bed after him, being obliging, behaving nicely and speaking politely, weren’t they a killer then,*";
P_HTM[2971]="*Vadhakañca pana santaṃ na aññāsi:**though he didn’t know that*";
P_HTM[2972]="*‘vadhako me’ti.**this was his killer?*";
P_HTM[2973]="*Yadāpi naṃ rahogataṃ viditvā tiṇhena satthena jīvitā voropeti, tadāpi so vadhakova.**And when, knowing he was alone, they took his life with a sharp knife, weren’t they a killer then,*";
P_HTM[2974]="*Vadhakañca pana santaṃ na aññāsi:**though he didn’t know that*";
P_HTM[2975]="*‘vadhako me’”ti.**this was his killer?”*";
P_HTM[2976]="*“Evamāvuso”ti.**“Yes, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2977]="*“Evameva kho, āvuso, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**“In the same way, an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[2978]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[2979]="*Vedanaṃ …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[2980]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2981]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2982]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2983]="*So aniccaṃ rūpaṃ ‘aniccaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand form—which is impermanent—as impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2984]="*Aniccaṃ vedanaṃ ‘aniccā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[2985]="*Aniccaṃ saññaṃ ‘aniccā saññā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**perception …*";
P_HTM[2986]="*Anicce saṅkhāre ‘aniccā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**choices …*";
P_HTM[2987]="*Aniccaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘aniccaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is impermanent—as impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2988]="*Dukkhaṃ rūpaṃ ‘dukkhaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand form—which is suffering—as suffering.*";
P_HTM[2989]="*Dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ …**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[2990]="*dukkhaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2991]="*dukkhe saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2992]="*dukkhaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘dukkhaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is suffering—as suffering.*";
P_HTM[2993]="*Anattaṃ rūpaṃ ‘anattā rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand form—which is not-self—as not-self.*";
P_HTM[2994]="*Anattaṃ vedanaṃ …**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[2995]="*anattaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[2996]="*anatte saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[2997]="*anattaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘anattaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is not-self—as not-self.*";
P_HTM[2998]="*Saṅkhataṃ rūpaṃ ‘saṅkhataṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand form—which is conditioned—as conditioned.*";
P_HTM[2999]="*Saṅkhataṃ vedanaṃ …**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[3000]="*saṅkhataṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3001]="*saṅkhate saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3002]="*saṅkhataṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘saṅkhataṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is conditioned—as conditioned.*";
P_HTM[3003]="*Vadhakaṃ rūpaṃ ‘vadhakaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand form—which is a killer—as a killer.*";
P_HTM[3004]="*Vadhakaṃ vedanaṃ ‘vadhakā vedanā’ti …**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[3005]="*vadhakaṃ saññaṃ ‘vadhakā saññā’ti …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3006]="*vadhake saṅkhāre ‘vadhakā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**choices …*";
P_HTM[3007]="*Vadhakaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘vadhakaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness—which is a killer—as a killer.*";
P_HTM[3008]="*So rūpaṃ upeti upādiyati adhiṭṭhāti ‘attā me’ti.**They’re attracted to form, grasp it, and commit to the notion that it is ‘my self’.*";
P_HTM[3009]="*Vedanaṃ …**They’re attracted to feeling …*";
P_HTM[3010]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3011]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3012]="*viññāṇaṃ upeti upādiyati adhiṭṭhāti ‘attā me’ti.**consciousness, grasp it, and commit to the notion that it is ‘my self’.*";
P_HTM[3013]="*Tassime pañcupādānakkhandhā upetā upādinnā dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya saṃvattanti.**And when you’ve gotten involved with and grasped these five grasping aggregates, they lead to your lasting harm and suffering.*";
P_HTM[3014]="*Sutavā ca kho, āvuso, ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī … pe … sappurisadhamme suvinīto**An educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[3015]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ attānaṃ; na attani rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ attānaṃ.**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[3016]="*Na vedanaṃ …**They don’t regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[3017]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3018]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3019]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ attānaṃ;**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness,*";
P_HTM[3020]="*na attani viññāṇaṃ, na viññāṇasmiṃ attānaṃ.**consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3021]="*So aniccaṃ rūpaṃ ‘aniccaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand form—which is impermanent—as impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3022]="*Aniccaṃ vedanaṃ …**They truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[3023]="*aniccaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3024]="*anicce saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3025]="*aniccaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘aniccaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness—which is impermanent—as impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3026]="*Dukkhaṃ rūpaṃ ‘dukkhaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand form—which is suffering—as suffering.*";
P_HTM[3027]="*Dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ …**They truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[3028]="*dukkhaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3029]="*dukkhe saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3030]="*dukkhaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘dukkhaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness—which is suffering—as suffering.*";
P_HTM[3031]="*Anattaṃ rūpaṃ ‘anattā rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand form—which is not-self—as not-self.*";
P_HTM[3032]="*Anattaṃ vedanaṃ …**They truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[3033]="*anattaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3034]="*anatte saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3035]="*anattaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘anattā viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness—which is not-self—as not-self.*";
P_HTM[3036]="*Saṅkhataṃ rūpaṃ ‘saṅkhataṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand form—which is conditioned—as conditioned.*";
P_HTM[3037]="*Saṅkhataṃ vedanaṃ …**They truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[3038]="*saṅkhataṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3039]="*saṅkhate saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3040]="*saṅkhataṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘saṅkhataṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness—which is conditioned—as conditioned.*";
P_HTM[3041]="*Vadhakaṃ rūpaṃ ‘vadhakaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand form—which is a killer—as a killer.*";
P_HTM[3042]="*Vadhakaṃ vedanaṃ …**They truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[3043]="*vadhakaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3044]="*vadhake saṅkhāre ‘vadhakā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**choices …*";
P_HTM[3045]="*Vadhakaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘vadhakaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness—which is a killer—as a killer.*";
P_HTM[3046]="*So rūpaṃ na upeti, na upādiyati, nādhiṭṭhāti: ‘attā me’ti.**Not being attracted to form, they don’t grasp it, and commit to the notion that it is ‘my self’.*";
P_HTM[3047]="*Vedanaṃ …**Not being attracted to feeling …*";
P_HTM[3048]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3049]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3050]="*viññāṇaṃ na upeti, na upādiyati, nādhiṭṭhāti: ‘attā me’ti.**consciousness, they don't grasp it, and commit to the notion that it is ‘my self’.*";
P_HTM[3051]="*Tassime pañcupādānakkhandhā anupetā anupādinnā dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya saṃvattantī”ti.**And when you’re not attracted to and don’t grasp these five grasping aggregates, they lead to your lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[3052]="*“Evametaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, hoti yesaṃ āyasmantānaṃ tādisā sabrahmacārino anukampakā atthakāmā ovādakā anusāsakā.**“Reverend Sāriputta, this is how it is when you have such venerables as spiritual companions to advise and instruct you out of kindness and compassion.*";
P_HTM[3053]="*Idañca pana me āyasmato sāriputtassa dhammadesanaṃ sutvā anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan”ti.**And after hearing this teaching by Venerable Sāriputta, my mind is freed from the defilements by not grasping.”*";
P_HTM[3054]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3055]="*4. Anurādhasuttaṃ**With Anurādha*";
P_HTM[3056]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[3057]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā anurādho bhagavato avidūre araññakuṭikāyaṃ viharati.**Now at that time Venerable Anurādha was staying not far from the Buddha in a wilderness hut.*";
P_HTM[3058]="*Atha kho sambahulā aññatitthiyā paribbājakā yenāyasmā anurādho tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā anurādhena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then several wanderers who follow other paths went up to Venerable Anurādha and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3059]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te aññatitthiyā paribbājakā āyasmantaṃ anurādhaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3060]="*“yo so, āvuso anurādha, tathāgato uttamapuriso paramapuriso paramapattipatto, taṃ tathāgato imesu catūsu ṭhānesu paññāpayamāno paññāpeti:**“Reverend Anurādha, when a Realized One is describing a Realized One—a supreme person, highest of people, who has reached the highest point—they describe them in these four ways:*";
P_HTM[3061]="*‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā”ti?**After death, a Realized One exists, or doesn’t exist, or both exists and doesn’t exist, or neither exists nor doesn’t exist.”*";
P_HTM[3062]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā anurādho te aññatitthiye paribbājake etadavoca:**When they said this, Venerable Anurādha said to those wanderers:*";
P_HTM[3063]="*“yo so āvuso tathāgato uttamapuriso paramapuriso paramapattipatto taṃ tathāgato aññatra imehi catūhi ṭhānehi paññāpayamāno paññāpeti:**“Reverends, when a Realized One is describing a Realized One—a supreme person, highest of people, who has reached the highest point—they describe them other than these four ways:*";
P_HTM[3064]="*‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā”ti.**After death, a Realized One exists, or doesn’t exist, or both exists and doesn’t exist, or neither exists nor doesn’t exist.”*";
P_HTM[3065]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā āyasmantaṃ anurādhaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he said this, the wanderers said to him:*";
P_HTM[3066]="*“so cāyaṃ bhikkhu navo bhavissati acirapabbajito, thero vā pana bālo abyatto”ti.**“This mendicant must be junior, recently gone forth, or else a foolish, incompetent senior mendicant.”*";
P_HTM[3067]="*Atha kho aññatitthiyā paribbājakā āyasmantaṃ anurādhaṃ navavādena ca bālavādena ca apasādetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu.**Then, after rebuking Venerable Anurādha by calling him “junior” and “foolish”, the wanderers got up from their seats and left.*";
P_HTM[3068]="*Atha kho āyasmato anurādhassa acirapakkantesu tesu aññatitthiyesu paribbājakesu etadahosi:**Soon after they had left, Anurādha thought:*";
P_HTM[3069]="*“sace kho maṃ te aññatitthiyā paribbājakā uttariṃ pañhaṃ puccheyyuṃ.**“If those wanderers were to inquire further,*";
P_HTM[3070]="*Kathaṃ byākaramāno nu khvāhaṃ tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ vuttavādī ceva bhagavato assaṃ, na ca bhagavantaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkheyyaṃ, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākareyyaṃ, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgaccheyyā”ti?**how should I answer them so as to repeat what the Buddha has said, and not misrepresent him with an untruth? How should I explain in line with his teaching, so that there would be no legitimate grounds for rebuke and criticism?”*";
P_HTM[3071]="*Atha kho āyasmā anurādho yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā anurādho bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Anurādha went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him all that had happened.*";
P_HTM[3072]="*“idhāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato avidūre araññakuṭikāyaṃ viharāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3073]="*Atha kho, bhante, sambahulā aññatitthiyā paribbājakā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu … pe … maṃ etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3074]="*‘yo so, āvuso anurādha, tathāgato uttamapuriso paramapuriso paramapattipatto taṃ tathāgato imesu catūsu ṭhānesu paññāpayamāno paññāpeti—* **";
P_HTM[3075]="*hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, na hoti …* **";
P_HTM[3076]="*hoti ca na ca hoti, neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3077]="*Evaṃ vuttāhaṃ, bhante, te aññatitthiye paribbājake etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3078]="*“yo so, āvuso, tathāgato uttamapuriso paramapuriso paramapattipatto, taṃ tathāgato aññatra imehi catūhi ṭhānehi paññāpayamāno paññāpeti:* **";
P_HTM[3079]="*‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3080]="*‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[3081]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, te aññatitthiyā paribbājakā maṃ etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3082]="*‘so cāyaṃ bhikkhu na vo bhavissati acirapabbajito thero vā pana bālo abyatto’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3083]="*Atha kho maṃ, bhante, te aññatitthiyā paribbājakā navavādena ca bālavādena ca apasādetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3084]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, acirapakkantesu tesu aññatitthiyesu paribbājakesu etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[3085]="*‘sace kho maṃ te aññatitthiyā paribbājakā uttariṃ pañhaṃ puccheyyuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3086]="*Kathaṃ byākaramāno nu khvāhaṃ tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ vuttavādī ceva bhagavato assaṃ, na ca bhagavantaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkheyyaṃ, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākareyyaṃ, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgaccheyyā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3087]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, anurādha,**“What do you think, Anurādha?*";
P_HTM[3088]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3089]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3090]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[3091]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3092]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[3093]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[3094]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3095]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3096]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3097]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3098]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3099]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante” … pe …**“Impermanent, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[3100]="*tasmātiha … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[3101]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[3102]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti”.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3103]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, anurādha,**What do you think, Anurādha?*";
P_HTM[3104]="*rūpaṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the Realized One as form?”*";
P_HTM[3105]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3106]="*“Vedanaṃ …**“Do you regard the Realized One as feeling …*";
P_HTM[3107]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3108]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3109]="*viññāṇaṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[3110]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3111]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, anurādha,**“What do you think, Anurādha?*";
P_HTM[3112]="*rūpasmiṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the Realized One as in form?”*";
P_HTM[3113]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3114]="*“Aññatra rūpā tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**“Or do you regard the Realized One as distinct from form?”*";
P_HTM[3115]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3116]="*“Vedanāya … pe …**“Do you regard the Realized One as in feeling …*";
P_HTM[3117]="*aññatra vedanāya … pe …**or distinct from feeling …*";
P_HTM[3118]="*saññāya …**as in perception …*";
P_HTM[3119]="*aññatra saññāya …**or distinct from perception …*";
P_HTM[3120]="*saṅkhāresu …**as in choices …*";
P_HTM[3121]="*aññatra saṅkhārehi …**or distinct from choices …*";
P_HTM[3122]="*viññāṇasmiṃ …**as in consciousness …*";
P_HTM[3123]="*aññatra viññāṇā tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**or as distinct from consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[3124]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3125]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, anurādha,**“What do you think, Anurādha?*";
P_HTM[3126]="*rūpaṃ … vedanā … saññā … saṅkhārā … viññāṇaṃ tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the Realized One as possessing form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[3127]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3128]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, anurādha,**“What do you think, Anurādha?*";
P_HTM[3129]="*ayaṃ so arūpī … avedano … asaññī … asaṅkhāro … aviññāṇo tathāgatoti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the Realized One as one who is without form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[3130]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3131]="*“Ettha ca te, anurādha, diṭṭheva dhamme saccato thetato tathāgate anupalabbhiyamāne kallaṃ nu te taṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ:**“In that case, Anurādha, since you don’t acknowledge the Realized One as a genuine fact in the present life, is it appropriate to declare:*";
P_HTM[3132]="*‘yo so, āvuso, tathāgato uttamapuriso paramapuriso paramapattipatto taṃ tathāgato aññatra imehi catūhi ṭhānehi paññāpayamāno paññāpeti—**‘Reverends, when a Realized One is describing a Realized One—a supreme person, highest of people, who has reached the highest point—they describe them other than these four ways:*";
P_HTM[3133]="*hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā … na hoti … hoti ca na ca hoti … neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā’”ti?**After death, a Realized One exists, or doesn’t exist, or both exists and doesn’t exist, or neither exists nor doesn’t exist’?”*";
P_HTM[3134]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3135]="*“Sādhu sādhu, anurādha.**“Good, good, Anurādha!*";
P_HTM[3136]="*Pubbe cāhaṃ, anurādha, etarahi ca dukkhañceva paññapemi, dukkhassa ca nirodhan”ti.**In the past, as today, I describe suffering and the cessation of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[3137]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3138]="*5. Vakkalisuttaṃ**With Vakkali*";
P_HTM[3139]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[3140]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā vakkali kumbhakāranivesane viharati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time Venerable Vakkali was staying in a potter’s shed, and he was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3141]="*Atha kho āyasmā vakkali upaṭṭhāke āmantesi:**Then he addressed his carers,*";
P_HTM[3142]="*“etha tumhe, āvuso, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamatha; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatha:**“Please, reverends, go to the Buddha, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Say to him:*";
P_HTM[3143]="*‘vakkali, bhante, bhikkhu ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno, so bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatī’ti.**‘Sir, the mendicant Vakkali is sick, suffering, and gravely ill. He bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[3144]="*Evañca vadetha:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[3145]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, bhagavā yena vakkali bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.**‘Sir, please go to the mendicant Vakkali out of compassion.’”*";
P_HTM[3146]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato vakkalissa paṭissutvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**“Yes, reverend,” those monks replied. They did as he asked.*";
P_HTM[3147]="*“vakkali, bhante, bhikkhu ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno, so bhagavato pāde sirasā vandati;* **";
P_HTM[3148]="*evañca pana vadeti:* **";
P_HTM[3149]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, bhagavā yena vakkali bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3150]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[3151]="*Atha kho bhagavā nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yenāyasmā vakkali tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha robed up and, taking his bowl and robes, went to Venerable Vakkali.*";
P_HTM[3152]="*Addasā kho āyasmā vakkali bhagavantaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ. Disvāna mañcake samadhosi.**Venerable Vakkali saw the Buddha coming off in the distance and tried to rise on his cot.*";
P_HTM[3153]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ vakkaliṃ etadavoca:**But the Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[3154]="*“alaṃ, vakkali, mā tvaṃ mañcake samadhosi.**“It’s all right, Vakkali, don’t get up.*";
P_HTM[3155]="*Santimāni āsanāni paññattāni; tatthāhaṃ nisīdissāmī”ti.**There are some seats spread out, I will sit there.”*";
P_HTM[3156]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane. Nisajja kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ vakkaliṃ etadavoca:**He sat on the seat spread out and said to Vakkali,*";
P_HTM[3157]="*“kacci te, vakkali, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ, kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti, no abhikkamanti; paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no abhikkamo”ti?**“Vakkali, I hope you’re keeping well; I hope you’re alright. And I hope the pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[3158]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ; bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Sir, I’m not all right, I’m not getting by. My pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is apparent, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[3159]="*“Kacci te, vakkali, na kiñci kukkuccaṃ, na koci vippaṭisāro”ti?**“I hope you don’t have any remorse or regret?”*";
P_HTM[3160]="*“Taggha me, bhante, anappakaṃ kukkuccaṃ, anappako vippaṭisāro”ti.**“Indeed, sir, I have no little remorse and regret.”*";
P_HTM[3161]="*“Kacci pana taṃ, vakkali, attā sīlato na upavadatī”ti?**“I hope you have no reason to blame yourself when it comes to ethical conduct?”*";
P_HTM[3162]="*“Na kho maṃ, bhante, attā sīlato upavadatī”ti.**“No sir, I have no reason to blame myself when it comes to ethical conduct.”*";
P_HTM[3163]="*“No ce kira taṃ, vakkali, attā sīlato upavadati; atha kiñca te kukkuccaṃ ko ca vippaṭisāro”ti?**“In that case, Vakkali, why do you have remorse and regret?”*";
P_HTM[3164]="*“Cirapaṭikāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamitukāmo, natthi ca me kāyasmiṃ tāvatikā balamattā, yāvatāhaṃ bhagavantaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkameyyan”ti.**“For a long time I’ve wanted to go and see the Buddha, but I was physically too weak.”*";
P_HTM[3165]="*“Alaṃ, vakkali, kiṃ te iminā pūtikāyena diṭṭhena?**“Enough, Vakkali! Why would you want to see this rotten body?*";
P_HTM[3166]="*Yo kho, vakkali, dhammaṃ passati so maṃ passati;**One who sees the teaching sees me.*";
P_HTM[3167]="*yo maṃ passati so dhammaṃ passati.**One who sees me sees the teaching.*";
P_HTM[3168]="*Dhammañhi, vakkali, passanto maṃ passati;**Seeing the teaching, you see me.*";
P_HTM[3169]="*maṃ passanto dhammaṃ passati.**Seeing me, you see the teaching.*";
P_HTM[3170]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vakkali,**What do you think, Vakkali?*";
P_HTM[3171]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3172]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3173]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[3174]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3175]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[3176]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[3177]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3178]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3179]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3180]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3181]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3182]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante” … pe …**“Impermanent, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[3183]="*eso me attāti?* **";
P_HTM[3184]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[3185]="*“Tasmātiha … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[3186]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[3187]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[3188]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ vakkaliṃ iminā ovādena ovaditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā yena gijjhakūṭo pabbato tena pakkāmi.**And then, after giving Venerable Vakkali this advice, the Buddha got up from his seat and went to the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[3189]="*Atha kho āyasmā vakkali acirapakkantassa bhagavato upaṭṭhāke āmantesi:**Then Venerable Vakkali addressed his carers,*";
P_HTM[3190]="*“etha maṃ, āvuso, mañcakaṃ āropetvā yena isigilipassaṃ kāḷasilā tenupasaṅkamatha.**“Come on, reverends, lift my cot and take me to the Black Rock on the slopes of Isigili.*";
P_HTM[3191]="*Kathañhi nāma mādiso antaraghare kālaṃ kattabbaṃ maññeyyā”ti?**It’s unthinkable for one like me to die in an inhabited area!”*";
P_HTM[3192]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato vakkalissa paṭissutvā āyasmantaṃ vakkaliṃ mañcakaṃ āropetvā yena isigilipassaṃ kāḷasilā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu.**“Yes, reverend,” replied those mendicants, and did as he asked.*";
P_HTM[3193]="*Atha kho bhagavā tañca rattiṃ tañca divāvasesaṃ gijjhakūṭe pabbate vihāsi.**Meanwhile, the Buddha spent the rest of that night and day on Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[3194]="*Atha kho dve devatāyo abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇā kevalakappaṃ gijjhakūṭaṃ obhāsetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu … pe … ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu.**Then, late at night, two glorious deities, lighting up the entire Vulture’s Peak, went up to the Buddha, bowed, and stood to one side.*";
P_HTM[3195]="*Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho ekā devatā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**One deity said to him,*";
P_HTM[3196]="*“vakkali, bhante, bhikkhu vimokkhāya cetetī”ti.**“Sir, the mendicant Vakkali is intent on liberation!”*";
P_HTM[3197]="*Aparā devatā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**And another deity said to him,*";
P_HTM[3198]="*“so hi nūna, bhante, suvimutto vimuccissatī”ti.**“He’ll definitely be well-freed!”*";
P_HTM[3199]="*Idamavocuṃ tā devatāyo.**This is what those deities said.*";
P_HTM[3200]="*Idaṃ vatvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu.**Then they bowed and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right side, before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[3201]="*Atha kho bhagavā tassā rattiyā accayena bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then, when the night had passed, the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3202]="*“etha tumhe, bhikkhave, yena vakkali bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamatha; upasaṅkamitvā vakkaliṃ bhikkhuṃ evaṃ vadetha:**“Come, mendicants, go to the mendicant Vakkali and tell him:*";
P_HTM[3203]="*‘Suṇāvuso tvaṃ, vakkali, bhagavato vacanaṃ dvinnañca devatānaṃ.**‘Vakkali, hear the word of the Buddha and two deities.*";
P_HTM[3204]="*Imaṃ, āvuso, rattiṃ dve devatāyo abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇā kevalakappaṃ gijjhakūṭaṃ obhāsetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu.**Late last night, two glorious deities, lighting up the entire Vulture’s Peak, went up to the Buddha, bowed, and stood to one side.*";
P_HTM[3205]="*Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho, āvuso, ekā devatā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca—**One deity said to him,*";
P_HTM[3206]="*vakkali, bhante, bhikkhu vimokkhāya cetetīti.**“Sir, the mendicant Vakkali is intent on liberation!”*";
P_HTM[3207]="*Aparā devatā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca—**And another deity said to him,*";
P_HTM[3208]="*so hi nūna, bhante, suvimutto vimuccissatīti.**“He’ll definitely be well-freed!”*";
P_HTM[3209]="*Bhagavā ca taṃ, āvuso vakkali, evamāha—**And the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[3210]="*mā bhāyi, vakkali;**“Do not fear, Vakkali,*";
P_HTM[3211]="*mā bhāyi, vakkali.**do not fear!*";
P_HTM[3212]="*Apāpakaṃ te maraṇaṃ bhavissati, apāpikā kālakiriyā’”ti.**Your death will not be a bad one; your passing will not be a bad one.”’”*";
P_HTM[3213]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paṭissutvā yenāyasmā vakkali tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ vakkaliṃ etadavocuṃ:**“Yes, sir,” those monks replied. They went to Vakkali and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3214]="*“suṇāvuso vakkali, bhagavato vacanaṃ dvinnañca devatānan”ti.**“Vakkali, hear the word of the Buddha and two deities.”*";
P_HTM[3215]="*Atha kho āyasmā vakkali upaṭṭhāke āmantesi:**Then Vakkali addressed his carers,*";
P_HTM[3216]="*“etha maṃ, āvuso, mañcakā oropetha.**“Please, reverends, help me off my cot.*";
P_HTM[3217]="*Kathañhi nāma mādiso ucce āsane nisīditvā tassa bhagavato sāsanaṃ sotabbaṃ maññeyyā”ti.**It’s unthinkable for one like me to listen to the Buddha’s instructions sitting on a high seat.”*";
P_HTM[3218]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato vakkalissa paṭissutvā āyasmantaṃ vakkaliṃ mañcakā oropesuṃ.**“Yes, reverend,” replied those mendicants, and helped him off his cot.*";
P_HTM[3219]="*“Imaṃ, āvuso, rattiṃ dve devatāyo abhikkantāya rattiyā … pe … ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu.**They repeated what the Buddha had said.*";
P_HTM[3220]="*Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho, āvuso, ekā devatā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3221]="*‘vakkali, bhante, bhikkhu vimokkhāya cetetī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3222]="*Aparā devatā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3223]="*‘so hi nūna, bhante, suvimutto vimuccissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3224]="*Bhagavā ca taṃ, āvuso vakkali, evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[3225]="*‘mā bhāyi, vakkali;* **";
P_HTM[3226]="*mā bhāyi, vakkali.* **";
P_HTM[3227]="*Apāpakaṃ te maraṇaṃ bhavissati, apāpikā kālakiriyā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3228]="*“Tena hāvuso, mama vacanena bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatha:**Vakkali said, “Well then, reverends, in my name bow with your head to the Buddha’s feet. Say to him:*";
P_HTM[3229]="*‘vakkali, bhante, bhikkhu ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**‘Sir, the mendicant Vakkali is sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3230]="*So bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatī’ti.**He bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[3231]="*Evañca vadetha:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[3232]="*‘rūpaṃ aniccaṃ.**‘Form is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3233]="*Tāhaṃ, bhante, na kaṅkhāmi.**I have no doubt of that.*";
P_HTM[3234]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhanti na vicikicchāmi.**I’m certain that what is impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[3235]="*Yadaniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, natthi me tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vāti na vicikicchāmi.**And I’m certain that I have no desire or greed or fondness for what is impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[3236]="*Vedanā aniccā.**Feeling is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[3237]="*Tāhaṃ, bhante, na kaṅkhāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3238]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhanti na vicikicchāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3239]="*Yadaniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, natthi me tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vāti na vicikicchāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3240]="*Saññā …**Perception is impermanent …*";
P_HTM[3241]="*saṅkhārā aniccā.**Choices are impermanent …*";
P_HTM[3242]="*Tāhaṃ, bhante, na kaṅkhāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3243]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhanti na vicikicchāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3244]="*Yadaniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, natthi me tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vāti na vicikicchāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3245]="*Viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**Consciousness is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3246]="*Tāhaṃ, bhante, na kaṅkhāmi.**I have no doubt of that.*";
P_HTM[3247]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhanti na vicikicchāmi.**I’m certain that what is impermanent is suffering.*";
P_HTM[3248]="*Yadaniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, natthi me tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vāti na vicikicchāmī’”ti.**And I’m certain that I have no desire or greed or fondness for what is impermanent, suffering, and perishable.’”*";
P_HTM[3249]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato vakkalissa paṭissutvā pakkamiṃsu.**“Yes, reverend,” those monks replied, and left.*";
P_HTM[3250]="*Atha kho āyasmā vakkali acirapakkantesu tesu bhikkhūsu satthaṃ āharesi.**And then, not long after those mendicants had left, Venerable Vakkali slit his wrists.*";
P_HTM[3251]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then those senior mendicants went up to the Buddha and told him Vakkali’s message.*";
P_HTM[3252]="*“vakkali, bhante, bhikkhu ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno;* **";
P_HTM[3253]="*so bhagavato pāde sirasā vandati;* **";
P_HTM[3254]="*evañca vadeti:* **";
P_HTM[3255]="*‘rūpaṃ aniccaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3256]="*Tāhaṃ, bhante, na kaṅkhāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3257]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhanti na vicikicchāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3258]="*Yadaniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, natthi me tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vāti na vicikicchāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3259]="*Vedanā …* **";
P_HTM[3260]="*saññā …* **";
P_HTM[3261]="*saṅkhārā …* **";
P_HTM[3262]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3263]="*Tāhaṃ, bhante, na kaṅkhāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3264]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ dukkhanti na vicikicchāmi.* **";
P_HTM[3265]="*Yadaniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, natthi me tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vāti na vicikicchāmī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3266]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[3267]="*“āyāma, bhikkhave, yena isigilipassaṃ kāḷasilā tenupasaṅkamissāma;**“Come, mendicants, let’s go to the Black Rock on the slopes of Isigili,*";
P_HTM[3268]="*yattha vakkalinā kulaputtena satthamāharitan”ti.**where Vakkali, the gentleman, slit his wrists.”*";
P_HTM[3269]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[3270]="*Atha kho bhagavā sambahulehi bhikkhūhi saddhiṃ yena isigilipassaṃ kāḷasilā tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha together with several mendicants went to the Black Rock on the slopes of Isigili.*";
P_HTM[3271]="*Addasā kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ vakkaliṃ dūratova mañcake vivattakkhandhaṃ semānaṃ.**The Buddha saw Vakkali off in the distance lying on his cot, having cast off the aggregates.*";
P_HTM[3272]="*Tena kho pana samayena dhūmāyitattaṃ timirāyitattaṃ gacchateva purimaṃ disaṃ, gacchati pacchimaṃ disaṃ, gacchati uttaraṃ disaṃ, gacchati dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ, gacchati uddhaṃ disaṃ, gacchati adho disaṃ, gacchati anudisaṃ.**Now at that time a cloud of black smoke was moving east, west, north, south, above, below, and in-between.*";
P_HTM[3273]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**The Buddha said to the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[3274]="*“passatha no tumhe, bhikkhave, etaṃ dhūmāyitattaṃ timirāyitattaṃ gacchateva purimaṃ disaṃ … pe … gacchati anudisan”ti.**“Mendicants, do you see that cloud of black smoke moving east, west, north, south, above, below, and in-between?”*";
P_HTM[3275]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3276]="*“Eso kho, bhikkhave, māro pāpimā vakkalissa kulaputtassa viññāṇaṃ samanvesati:**“That’s Māra the Wicked searching for Vakkali’s consciousness, wondering:*";
P_HTM[3277]="*‘kattha vakkalissa kulaputtassa viññāṇaṃ patiṭṭhitan’ti?**‘Where is Vakkali’s consciousness established?’*";
P_HTM[3278]="*Appatiṭṭhitena ca, bhikkhave, viññāṇena vakkali kulaputto parinibbuto”ti.**But since his consciousness is not established, Vakkali is extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[3279]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3280]="*6. Assajisuttaṃ**With Assaji*";
P_HTM[3281]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[3282]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā assaji kassapakārāme viharati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time Venerable Assaji was staying in a monastery built by a Kassapa, and he was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3283]="*Atha kho āyasmā assaji upaṭṭhāke āmantesi:**Then he addressed his carers:*";
P_HTM[3284]="*“etha tumhe, āvuso, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamatha; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatha:**“Please, reverends, go to the Buddha, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Say to him:*";
P_HTM[3285]="*‘assaji, bhante, bhikkhu ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**‘Sir, the mendicant Assaji is sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3286]="*So bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatī’ti.**He bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[3287]="*Evañca vadetha:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[3288]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, bhagavā yena assaji bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.**‘Sir, please go to the mendicant Assaji out of compassion.’”*";
P_HTM[3289]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato assajissa paṭissutvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**“Yes, reverend,” those monks replied. They did as he asked.*";
P_HTM[3290]="*“assaji, bhante, bhikkhu ābādhiko … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3291]="*sādhu kira, bhante, bhagavā yena assaji bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3292]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[3293]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā assaji tenupasaṅkami.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat and went to Venerable Assaji.*";
P_HTM[3294]="*Addasā kho āyasmā assaji bhagavantaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.**Venerable Assaji saw the Buddha coming off in the distance,*";
P_HTM[3295]="*Disvāna mañcake samadhosi.**and tried to rise on his cot.*";
P_HTM[3296]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ assajiṃ etadavoca:**But the Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[3297]="*“alaṃ, assaji, mā tvaṃ mañcake samadhosi.**“It’s all right, Assaji, don’t get up.*";
P_HTM[3298]="*Santimāni āsanāni paññattāni, tatthāhaṃ nisīdissāmī”ti.**There are some seats spread out by others, I will sit there.”*";
P_HTM[3299]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane. Nisajja kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ assajiṃ etadavoca:**He sat on the seat spread out and said,*";
P_HTM[3300]="*“kacci te, assaji, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ … pe … paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no abhikkamo”ti?**“Assaji, I hope you’re keeping well; I hope you’re alright. And I hope the pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[3301]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ … pe … abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Sir, I’m not all right, I’m not getting by. My pain is terrible and growing, not fading, its growing is evident, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[3302]="*“Kacci te, assaji, na kiñci kukkuccaṃ na koci vippaṭisāro”ti?**“I hope you don’t have any remorse or regret?”*";
P_HTM[3303]="*“Taggha me, bhante, anappakaṃ kukkuccaṃ anappako vippaṭisāro”ti.**“Indeed, sir, I have no little remorse and regret.”*";
P_HTM[3304]="*“Kacci pana taṃ, assaji, attā sīlato na upavadatī”ti?**“I hope you have no reason to blame yourself when it comes to ethical conduct?”*";
P_HTM[3305]="*“Na kho maṃ, bhante, attā sīlato upavadatī”ti.**“No sir, I have no reason to blame myself when it comes to ethical conduct.”*";
P_HTM[3306]="*“No ce kira taṃ, assaji, attā sīlato upavadati, atha kiñca te kukkuccaṃ ko ca vippaṭisāro”ti?**“In that case, Assaji, why do you have remorse and regret?”*";
P_HTM[3307]="*“Pubbe khvāhaṃ, bhante, gelaññe passambhetvā passambhetvā kāyasaṅkhāre viharāmi, sohaṃ samādhiṃ nappaṭilabhāmi.**“Sir, before my time of illness I meditated having completely stilled the physical process. But now I can’t get immersion.*";
P_HTM[3308]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, taṃ samādhiṃ appaṭilabhato evaṃ hoti:**Since I can’t get immersion, I think:*";
P_HTM[3309]="*‘no cassāhaṃ parihāyāmī’”ti.**‘May I not decline!’”*";
P_HTM[3310]="*“Ye te, assaji, samaṇabrāhmaṇā samādhisārakā samādhisāmaññā tesaṃ taṃ samādhiṃ appaṭilabhataṃ evaṃ hoti:**“Assaji, there are ascetics and brahmins for whom samādhi is the essence, equating immersion with the ascetic life. They think:*";
P_HTM[3311]="*‘no cassu mayaṃ parihāyāmā’ti.**‘May we not decline!’*";
P_HTM[3312]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, assaji,**What do you think, Assaji?*";
P_HTM[3313]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3314]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante” … pe …**“Impermanent, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[3315]="*viññāṇaṃ … pe …**“Is consciousness permanent or impermanent?” …*";
P_HTM[3316]="*“tasmātiha … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[3317]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[3318]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātīti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3319]="*So sukhañce vedanaṃ vedayati, sā ‘aniccā’ti pajānāti. ‘Anajjhositā’ti pajānāti. ‘Anabhinanditā’ti pajānāti.**If they feel a pleasant feeling, they understand that it’s impermanent, that they’re not attached to it, and that they don’t relish it.*";
P_HTM[3320]="*Dukkhañce vedanaṃ vedayati, sā ‘aniccā’ti pajānāti. ‘Anajjhositā’ti pajānāti. ‘Anabhinanditā’ti pajānāti.**If they feel a painful feeling, they understand that it’s impermanent, that they’re not attached to it, and that they don’t relish it.*";
P_HTM[3321]="*Adukkhamasukhañce vedanaṃ vedayati, sā ‘aniccā’ti pajānāti … pe … ‘anabhinanditā’ti pajānāti.**If they feel a neutral feeling, they understand that it’s impermanent, that they’re not attached to it, and that they don’t relish it.*";
P_HTM[3322]="*So sukhañce vedanaṃ vedayati, visaṃyutto naṃ vedayati;**If they feel a pleasant feeling, they feel it detached.*";
P_HTM[3323]="*dukkhañce vedanaṃ vedayati, visaṃyutto naṃ vedayati;**If they feel a painful feeling, they feel it detached.*";
P_HTM[3324]="*adukkhamasukhañce vedanaṃ vedayati, visaṃyutto naṃ vedayati.**If they feel a neutral feeling, they feel it detached.*";
P_HTM[3325]="*So kāyapariyantikañce vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti. Jīvitapariyantikañce vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.**Feeling the end of the body approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of the body approaching.’ Feeling the end of life approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of life approaching.’*";
P_HTM[3326]="*‘Kāyassa bhedā uddhaṃ jīvitapariyādānā idheva sabbavedayitāni anabhinanditāni sītībhavissantī’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘When my body breaks up and my life is over, everything that’s felt, being no longer relished, will become cool right here.’*";
P_HTM[3327]="*Seyyathāpi, assaji, telañca paṭicca, vaṭṭiñca paṭicca, telappadīpo jhāyeyya;**Suppose an oil lamp depended on oil and a wick to burn.*";
P_HTM[3328]="*tasseva telassa ca vaṭṭiyā ca pariyādānā anāhāro nibbāyeyya.**As the oil and the wick are used up, it would be extinguished due to lack of fuel.*";
P_HTM[3329]="*Evameva kho, assaji, bhikkhu kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti. Jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.**In the same way, feeling the end of the body approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of the body approaching.’ Feeling the end of life approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of life approaching.’*";
P_HTM[3330]="*‘Kāyassa bhedā uddhaṃ jīvitapariyādānā idheva sabbavedayitāni anabhinanditāni sītībhavissantī’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘When my body breaks up and my life is over, everything that’s felt, being no longer relished, will become cool right here.’”*";
P_HTM[3331]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3332]="*7. Khemakasuttaṃ**With Khemaka*";
P_HTM[3333]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ sambahulā therā bhikkhū kosambiyaṃ viharanti ghositārāme.**At one time several senior mendicants were staying near Kosambi, in Ghosita’s Monastery.*";
P_HTM[3334]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā khemako badarikārāme viharati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time Venerable Khemaka was staying in the Jujube Tree Monastery, and he was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3335]="*Atha kho therā bhikkhū sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhitā āyasmantaṃ dāsakaṃ āmantesuṃ:**In the late afternoon those senior mendicants came out of retreat and addressed Venerable Dāsaka,*";
P_HTM[3336]="*“ehi tvaṃ, āvuso dāsaka, yena khemako bhikkhu tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā khemakaṃ bhikkhuṃ evaṃ vadehi:**“Please, Reverend Dāsaka, go to the mendicant Khemaka and say to him:*";
P_HTM[3337]="*‘therā taṃ, āvuso khemaka, evamāhaṃsu—**‘Reverend Khemaka, the seniors*";
P_HTM[3338]="*kacci te, āvuso, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ, kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti no abhikkamanti, paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no abhikkamo’”ti?**hope you’re keeping well; they hope you’re alright. They hope that your pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.’”*";
P_HTM[3339]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā dāsako therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ paṭissutvā yenāyasmā khemako tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ khemakaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, reverends,” replied Dāsaka. He went to Khemaka and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3340]="*“therā taṃ, āvuso khemaka, evamāhaṃsu:**“Reverend Khemaka, the seniors*";
P_HTM[3341]="*‘kacci te, āvuso, khamanīyaṃ … pe … no abhikkamo’”ti?**hope you’re keeping well; they hope you’re alright. They hope that your pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[3342]="*“Na me, āvuso, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ … pe … abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Reverend, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. My pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[3343]="*Atha kho āyasmā dāsako yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then Dāsaka went to those seniors and told them what had happened. They said,*";
P_HTM[3344]="*“khemako, āvuso, bhikkhu evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[3345]="*‘na me, āvuso, khamanīyaṃ … pe … abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no paṭikkamo’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3346]="*“Ehi tvaṃ, āvuso dāsaka, yena khemako bhikkhu tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā khemakaṃ bhikkhuṃ evaṃ vadehi:**“Please, Reverend Dāsaka, go to the mendicant Khemaka and say to him:*";
P_HTM[3347]="*‘therā taṃ, āvuso khemaka, evamāhaṃsu—**‘Reverend Khemaka, the seniors say that*";
P_HTM[3348]="*pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā vuttā bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—**these five grasping aggregates have been taught by the Buddha, that is:*";
P_HTM[3349]="*rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3350]="*Imesu āyasmā khemako pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu kiñci attaṃ vā attaniyaṃ vā samanupassatī’”ti?**Do you regard anything among these five grasping aggregates as self or as belonging to self?’”*";
P_HTM[3351]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā dāsako therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ paṭissutvā yenāyasmā khemako tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe …**“Yes, reverends,” replied Dāsaka. He relayed the message to Khemaka, who replied:*";
P_HTM[3352]="*therā taṃ, āvuso khemaka, evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[3353]="*“pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā vuttā bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[3354]="*rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.* **";
P_HTM[3355]="*Imesu āyasmā khemako pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu kiñci attaṃ vā attaniyaṃ vā samanupassatī”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3356]="*“Pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā vuttā bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—**“These five grasping aggregates have been taught by the Buddha, that is:*";
P_HTM[3357]="*rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3358]="*Imesu khvāhaṃ, āvuso, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu na kiñci attaṃ vā attaniyaṃ vā samanupassāmī”ti.**I do not regard anything among these five grasping aggregates as self or as belonging to self.”*";
P_HTM[3359]="*Atha kho āyasmā dāsako yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then Dāsaka went to those seniors and told them what had happened. They said:*";
P_HTM[3360]="*“khemako, āvuso, bhikkhu evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[3361]="*‘pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā vuttā bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[3362]="*rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.* **";
P_HTM[3363]="*Imesu khvāhaṃ, āvuso, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu na kiñci attaṃ vā attaniyaṃ vā samanupassāmī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3364]="*“Ehi tvaṃ, āvuso dāsaka, yena khemako bhikkhu tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā khemakaṃ bhikkhuṃ evaṃ vadehi:**“Please, Reverend Dāsaka, go to the mendicant Khemaka and say to him:*";
P_HTM[3365]="*‘therā taṃ, āvuso khemaka, evamāhaṃsu—**‘Reverend Khemaka, the seniors say that*";
P_HTM[3366]="*pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā vuttā bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—**these five grasping aggregates have been taught by the Buddha, that is:*";
P_HTM[3367]="*rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3368]="*No ce kirāyasmā khemako imesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu kiñci attaṃ vā attaniyaṃ vā samanupassati.**If, as it seems, Venerable Khemaka does not regard anything among these five grasping aggregates as self or as belonging to self,*";
P_HTM[3369]="*Tenahāyasmā khemako arahaṃ khīṇāsavo’”ti.**then he is a perfected one, with defilements ended.’”*";
P_HTM[3370]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā dāsako therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ paṭissutvā yenāyasmā khemako … pe …**“Yes, reverends,” replied Dāsaka. He relayed the message to Khemaka, who replied:*";
P_HTM[3371]="*therā taṃ, āvuso khemaka, evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[3372]="*“pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā vuttā bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[3373]="*rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho;* **";
P_HTM[3374]="*no ce kirāyasmā khemako imesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu kiñci attaṃ vā attaniyaṃ vā samanupassati, tenahāyasmā khemako arahaṃ khīṇāsavo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3375]="*“Pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā vuttā bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—**“These five grasping aggregates have been taught by the Buddha, that is:*";
P_HTM[3376]="*rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3377]="*Imesu khvāhaṃ, āvuso, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu na kiñci attaṃ vā attaniyaṃ vā samanupassāmi, na camhi arahaṃ khīṇāsavo;**I do not regard anything among these five grasping aggregates as self or as belonging to self, yet I am not a perfected one, with defilements ended.*";
P_HTM[3378]="*api ca me, āvuso, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu ‘asmī’ti adhigataṃ, ‘ayamahamasmī’ti na ca samanupassāmī”ti.**For when it comes to the five grasping aggregates I’m not rid of the conceit ‘I am’. But I don’t regard anything as ‘I am this’.”*";
P_HTM[3379]="*Atha kho āyasmā dāsako yena therā bhikkhū … pe …**Then Dāsaka went to those seniors and told them what had happened. They said:*";
P_HTM[3380]="*there bhikkhū etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3381]="*“khemako, āvuso, bhikkhu evamāha—* **";
P_HTM[3382]="*pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā vuttā bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[3383]="*rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.* **";
P_HTM[3384]="*Imesu khvāhaṃ, āvuso, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu na kiñci attaṃ vā attaniyaṃ vā samanupassāmi, na camhi arahaṃ khīṇāsavo;* **";
P_HTM[3385]="*api ca me, āvuso, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu ‘asmī’ti adhigataṃ, ‘ayamahamasmī’ti na ca samanupassāmī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3386]="*“Ehi tvaṃ, āvuso dāsaka, yena khemako bhikkhu tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā khemakaṃ bhikkhuṃ evaṃ vadehi:**“Please, Reverend Dāsaka, go to the mendicant Khemaka and say to him:*";
P_HTM[3387]="*‘therā taṃ, āvuso khemaka, evamāhaṃsu—**‘Reverend Khemaka, the seniors ask,*";
P_HTM[3388]="*yametaṃ, āvuso khemaka, asmīti vadesi, kimetaṃ asmīti vadesi?**when you say ‘I am’, what is it that you’re talking about?*";
P_HTM[3389]="*Rūpaṃ asmīti vadesi, aññatra rūpā asmīti vadesi,**Is it form or apart from form?*";
P_HTM[3390]="*vedanaṃ …**Is it feeling …*";
P_HTM[3391]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3392]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3393]="*viññāṇaṃ asmīti vadesi, aññatra viññāṇā asmīti vadesi.**consciousness, or apart from consciousness?*";
P_HTM[3394]="*Yametaṃ, āvuso khemaka, asmīti vadesi. Kimetaṃ asmīti vadesī’”ti?**When you say ‘I am’, what is it that you’re talking about?”*";
P_HTM[3395]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā dāsako therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ paṭissutvā yenāyasmā khemako tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ khemakaṃ etadavoca—**“Yes, reverends,” replied Dāsaka. He relayed the message to Khemaka, who replied:*";
P_HTM[3396]="*therā taṃ, āvuso khemaka, evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[3397]="*“yametaṃ, āvuso khemaka, ‘asmī’ti vadesi, kimetaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadesi?* **";
P_HTM[3398]="*Rūpaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadesi aññatra rūpā ‘asmī’ti vadesi?* **";
P_HTM[3399]="*Vedanaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[3400]="*saññaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[3401]="*saṅkhāre …* **";
P_HTM[3402]="*viññāṇaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadesi aññatra viññāṇā ‘asmī’ti vadesi?* **";
P_HTM[3403]="*Yametaṃ, āvuso khemaka, ‘asmī’ti vadesi, kimetaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadesī”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3404]="*“Alaṃ, āvuso dāsaka, kiṃ imāya sandhāvanikāya.**“Enough, Reverend Dāsaka! What’s the point in running back and forth?*";
P_HTM[3405]="*Āharāvuso, daṇḍaṃ;**Bring my staff,*";
P_HTM[3406]="*ahameva yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkamissāmī”ti.**I’ll go to see the senior mendicants myself.”*";
P_HTM[3407]="*Atha kho āyasmā khemako daṇḍamolubbha yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā therehi bhikkhūhi saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then Venerable Khemaka, leaning on a staff, went to those senior mendicants and exchanged greetings with them.*";
P_HTM[3408]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ khemakaṃ therā bhikkhū etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side. They said to him:*";
P_HTM[3409]="*“yametaṃ, āvuso khemaka, ‘asmī’ti vadesi, kimetaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadesi?**“Reverend Khemaka, when you say ‘I am’, what is it that you’re talking about?*";
P_HTM[3410]="*Rūpaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadesi, aññatra rūpā ‘asmī’ti vadesi?**Is it form or apart from form?*";
P_HTM[3411]="*Vedanaṃ …**Is it feeling …*";
P_HTM[3412]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3413]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3414]="*viññāṇaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadesi, aññatra viññāṇā ‘asmī’ti vadesi?**consciousness, or apart from consciousness?*";
P_HTM[3415]="*Yametaṃ, āvuso khemaka, ‘asmī’ti vadesi, kimetaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadesī”ti?**When you say ‘I am’, what is it that you’re talking about?”*";
P_HTM[3416]="*“Na khvāhaṃ, āvuso, rūpaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadāmi; napi aññatra rūpā ‘asmī’ti vadāmi.**“Reverends, I don’t say ‘I am’ with reference to form, or apart from form.*";
P_HTM[3417]="*Na vedanaṃ …**I don’t say ‘I am’ with reference to feeling …*";
P_HTM[3418]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3419]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3420]="*na viññāṇaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadāmi; napi aññatra viññāṇā ‘asmī’ti vadāmi.**consciousness, or apart from consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3421]="*Api ca me, āvuso, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu ‘asmī’ti adhigataṃ ‘ayamahamasmī’ti na ca samanupassāmi.**For when it comes to the five grasping aggregates I’m not rid of the conceit ‘I am’. But I don’t regard anything as ‘I am this’.*";
P_HTM[3422]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, uppalassa vā padumassa vā puṇḍarīkassa vā gandho.**It’s like the scent of a blue water lily, or a pink or white lotus.*";
P_HTM[3423]="*Yo nu kho evaṃ vadeyya: ‘pattassa gandho’ti vā ‘vaṇṇassa gandho’ti vā ‘kiñjakkhassa gandho’ti vā sammā nu kho so vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?**Would it be right to say that the scent belongs to the petals or the stalk or the pistil?”*";
P_HTM[3424]="*“No hetaṃ, āvuso”.**“No, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[3425]="*“Yathā kathaṃ, panāvuso, sammā byākaramāno byākareyyā”ti?**“Then, reverends, how should it be said?”*";
P_HTM[3426]="*“‘Pupphassa gandho’ti kho, āvuso, sammā byākaramāno byākareyyā”ti.**“It would be right to say that the scent belongs to the flower.”*";
P_HTM[3427]="*“Evameva khvāhaṃ, āvuso, na rūpaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadāmi, napi aññatra rūpā ‘asmī’ti vadāmi.**“In the same way, reverends, I don’t say ‘I am’ with reference to form, or apart from form.*";
P_HTM[3428]="*Na vedanaṃ …**I don’t say ‘I am’ with reference to feeling …*";
P_HTM[3429]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3430]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3431]="*na viññāṇaṃ ‘asmī’ti vadāmi, napi aññatra viññāṇā ‘asmī’ti vadāmi.**consciousness, or apart from consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3432]="*Api ca me, āvuso, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu ‘asmī’ti adhigataṃ ‘ayamahamasmī’ti na ca samanupassāmi.**For when it comes to the five grasping aggregates I’m not rid of the conceit ‘I am’. But I don’t regard anything as ‘I am this’.*";
P_HTM[3433]="*Kiñcāpi, āvuso, ariyasāvakassa pañcorambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni pahīnāni bhavanti, atha khvassa hoti: ‘yo ca pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu anusahagato asmīti māno, asmīti chando, asmīti anusayo asamūhato.**Although a noble disciple has given up the five lower fetters, they still have a lingering residue of the conceit ‘I am’, the desire ‘I am’, and the underlying tendency ‘I am’ which has not been eradicated.*";
P_HTM[3434]="*So aparena samayena pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassī viharati—**After some time they meditate observing rise and fall in the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[3435]="*iti rūpaṃ, iti rūpassa samudayo, iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo;**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[3436]="*iti vedanā …**Such is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3437]="*iti saññā …**Such is perception …*";
P_HTM[3438]="*iti saṅkhārā …**Such are choices …*";
P_HTM[3439]="*iti viññāṇaṃ, iti viññāṇassa samudayo, iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti.**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[3440]="*Tassimesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassino viharato yopissa hoti pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu anusahagato ‘asmī’ti, māno ‘asmī’ti, chando ‘asmī’ti anusayo asamūhato, sopi samugghātaṃ gacchati.**As they do so, that lingering residue is eradicated.*";
P_HTM[3441]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, vatthaṃ saṃkiliṭṭhaṃ malaggahitaṃ. Tamenaṃ sāmikā rajakassa anupadajjuṃ.**Suppose there was a cloth that was dirty and soiled, so the owners give it to a launderer.*";
P_HTM[3442]="*Tamenaṃ rajako ūse vā khāre vā gomaye vā sammadditvā acche udake vikkhāleti.**The launderer kneads it thoroughly with salt, lye, and cow dung, and rinses it in clear water.*";
P_HTM[3443]="*Kiñcāpi taṃ hoti vatthaṃ parisuddhaṃ pariyodātaṃ, atha khvassa hoti yeva anusahagato ūsagandho vā khāragandho vā gomayagandho vā asamūhato.**Although that cloth is clean and bright, it still has a lingering scent of salt, lye, or cow dung that had not been eradicated.*";
P_HTM[3444]="*Tamenaṃ rajako sāmikānaṃ deti. Tamenaṃ sāmikā gandhaparibhāvite karaṇḍake nikkhipanti.**The launderer returns it to its owners, who store it in a chest permeated with scent.*";
P_HTM[3445]="*Yopissa hoti anusahagato ūsagandho vā khāragandho vā gomayagandho vā asamūhato, sopi samugghātaṃ gacchati.**And that lingering scent would be eradicated.*";
P_HTM[3446]="*Evameva kho, āvuso, kiñcāpi ariyasāvakassa pañcorambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni pahīnāni bhavanti, atha khvassa hoti yeva pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu anusahagato ‘asmī’ti, māno ‘asmī’ti, chando ‘asmī’ti anusayo asamūhato.**In the same way, although a noble disciple has given up the five lower fetters, they still have a lingering residue of the conceit ‘I am’, the desire ‘I am’, and the underlying tendency ‘I am’ which has not been eradicated.*";
P_HTM[3447]="*So aparena samayena pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassī viharati.**After some time they meditate observing rise and fall in the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[3448]="*‘Iti rūpaṃ, iti rūpassa samudayo, iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo;**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[3449]="*iti vedanā …**Such is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3450]="*iti saññā …**Such is perception …*";
P_HTM[3451]="*iti saṅkhārā …**Such are choices …*";
P_HTM[3452]="*iti viññāṇaṃ, iti viññāṇassa samudayo, iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti.**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[3453]="*Tassa imesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassino viharato yopissa hoti pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu anusahagato ‘asmī’ti, māno ‘asmī’ti, chando ‘asmī’ti anusayo asamūhato, sopi samugghātaṃ gacchatī”ti.**As they do so, that lingering residue is eradicated.”*";
P_HTM[3454]="*Evaṃ vutte, therā bhikkhū āyasmantaṃ khemakaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he said this, the senior mendicants said to Venerable Khemaka,*";
P_HTM[3455]="*“na kho mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ khemakaṃ vihesāpekhā pucchimha, api cāyasmā khemako pahosi tassa bhagavato sāsanaṃ vitthārena ācikkhituṃ desetuṃ paññāpetuṃ paṭṭhapetuṃ vivarituṃ vibhajituṃ uttānīkātuṃ.**“We didn’t want to trouble Venerable Khemaka with our questions. But you’re capable of explaining, teaching, advocating, establishing, disclosing, analyzing, and clarifying the Buddha’s instructions in detail.*";
P_HTM[3456]="*Tayidaṃ āyasmatā khemakena tassa bhagavato sāsanaṃ vitthārena ācikkhitaṃ desitaṃ paññāpitaṃ paṭṭhapitaṃ vivaritaṃ vibhajitaṃ uttānīkatan”ti.**And that’s just what you’ve done.”*";
P_HTM[3457]="*Idamavoca āyasmā khemako.**That’s what Venerable Khemaka said.*";
P_HTM[3458]="*Attamanā therā bhikkhū āyasmato khemakassa bhāsitaṃ abhinanduṃ.**Satisfied, the senior mendicants were happy with what Venerable Khemaka said.*";
P_HTM[3459]="*Imasmiñca pana veyyākaraṇasmiṃ bhaññamāne saṭṭhimattānaṃ therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ anupādāya āsavehi cittāni vimucciṃsu, āyasmato khemakassa cāti.**And while this discourse was being spoken, the minds of sixty senior mendicants and of Venerable Khemaka were freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3460]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3461]="*8. Channasuttaṃ**With Channa*";
P_HTM[3462]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ sambahulā therā bhikkhū bārāṇasiyaṃ viharanti isipatane migadāye.**At one time several senior mendicants were staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana.*";
P_HTM[3463]="*Atha kho āyasmā channo sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito avāpuraṇaṃ ādāya vihārena vihāraṃ upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Channa came out of retreat. Taking a key, he went from dwelling to dwelling, going up to the senior mendicants and saying,*";
P_HTM[3464]="*“ovadantu maṃ āyasmanto therā, anusāsantu maṃ āyasmanto therā, karontu me āyasmanto therā dhammiṃ kathaṃ, yathāhaṃ dhammaṃ passeyyan”ti.**“May the venerable senior mendicants advise me and instruct me! May they give me a Dhamma talk so that I can see the teaching!”*";
P_HTM[3465]="*Evaṃ vutte, therā bhikkhū āyasmantaṃ channaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he said this, the senior mendicants said to Venerable Channa:*";
P_HTM[3466]="*“rūpaṃ kho, āvuso channa, aniccaṃ;**“Reverend Channa, form,*";
P_HTM[3467]="*vedanā aniccā;**feeling,*";
P_HTM[3468]="*saññā aniccā;**perception,*";
P_HTM[3469]="*saṅkhārā aniccā;**choices,*";
P_HTM[3470]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ.**and consciousness are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3471]="*Rūpaṃ anattā;**Form,*";
P_HTM[3472]="*vedanā …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[3473]="*saññā …**perception,*";
P_HTM[3474]="*saṅkhārā …**choices,*";
P_HTM[3475]="*viññāṇaṃ anattā.**and consciousness are not-self.*";
P_HTM[3476]="*Sabbe saṅkhārā aniccā;**All conditions are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3477]="*sabbe dhammā anattā”ti.**All things are not-self.”*";
P_HTM[3478]="*Atha kho āyasmato channassa etadahosi:**Then Venerable Channa thought,*";
P_HTM[3479]="*“mayhampi kho etaṃ evaṃ hoti:**“I too think in this way. …*";
P_HTM[3480]="*‘rūpaṃ aniccaṃ, vedanā …* **";
P_HTM[3481]="*saññā …* **";
P_HTM[3482]="*saṅkhārā …* **";
P_HTM[3483]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3484]="*rūpaṃ anattā, vedanā …* **";
P_HTM[3485]="*saññā …* **";
P_HTM[3486]="*saṅkhārā …* **";
P_HTM[3487]="*viññāṇaṃ anattā.* **";
P_HTM[3488]="*Sabbe saṅkhārā aniccā, sabbe dhammā anattā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3489]="*Atha ca pana me sabbasaṅkhārasamathe sabbūpadhipaṭinissagge taṇhākkhaye virāge nirodhe nibbāne cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati nādhimuccati.**And yet my mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided about the stilling of all activities, the letting go of all attachments, the ending of craving, fading away, cessation, extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3490]="*Paritassanā upādānaṃ uppajjati;**Anxiety and grasping arise.*";
P_HTM[3491]="*paccudāvattati mānasaṃ:**And the mind reverts to thinking:*";
P_HTM[3492]="*‘atha ko carahi me attā’ti?**‘So then who exactly is my self?’*";
P_HTM[3493]="*Na kho panevaṃ dhammaṃ passato hoti.**But that doesn’t happen for someone who sees the teaching.*";
P_HTM[3494]="*Ko nu kho me tathā dhammaṃ deseyya yathāhaṃ dhammaṃ passeyyan”ti.**Who can teach me the Dhamma so that I can see the teaching?”*";
P_HTM[3495]="*Atha kho āyasmato channassa etadahosi:**Then Venerable Channa thought,*";
P_HTM[3496]="*“ayaṃ kho āyasmā ānando kosambiyaṃ viharati ghositārāme satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ, pahoti ca me āyasmā ānando tathā dhammaṃ desetuṃ yathāhaṃ dhammaṃ passeyyaṃ;**“The Venerable Ānanda is staying near Kosambi, in Ghosita’s Monastery. He’s praised by the Buddha and esteemed by his sensible spiritual companions. He’s quite capable of teaching me the Dhamma so that I can see the teaching.*";
P_HTM[3497]="*atthi ca me āyasmante ānande tāvatikā vissaṭṭhi.**Since I have so much trust in Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[3498]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkameyyan”ti.**why don’t I go to see him?”*";
P_HTM[3499]="*Atha kho āyasmā channo senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena kosambī ghositārāmo yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodi … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā channo āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**Then Channa set his lodgings in order and, taking his bowl and robe, set out for Kosambi. He went to see Ānanda in Ghosita’s Monastery, exchanged greetings with him, and told him what had happened. Then he said,*";
P_HTM[3500]="*“Ekamidāhaṃ, āvuso ānanda, samayaṃ bārāṇasiyaṃ viharāmi isipatane migadāye.* **";
P_HTM[3501]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, āvuso, sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito avāpuraṇaṃ ādāya vihārena vihāraṃ upasaṅkamiṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3502]="*upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3503]="*‘ovadantu maṃ āyasmanto therā, anusāsantu maṃ āyasmanto therā, karontu me āyasmanto therā dhammiṃ kathaṃ yathāhaṃ dhammaṃ passeyyan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3504]="*Evaṃ vutte, maṃ, āvuso, therā bhikkhū etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3505]="*‘rūpaṃ kho, āvuso channa, aniccaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3506]="*vedanā …* **";
P_HTM[3507]="*saññā …* **";
P_HTM[3508]="*saṅkhārā …* **";
P_HTM[3509]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3510]="*rūpaṃ anattā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3511]="*viññāṇaṃ anattā.* **";
P_HTM[3512]="*Sabbe saṅkhārā aniccā, sabbe dhammā anattā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3513]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[3514]="*‘mayhampi kho etaṃ evaṃ hoti—* **";
P_HTM[3515]="*rūpaṃ aniccaṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3516]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ, rūpaṃ anattā, vedanā …* **";
P_HTM[3517]="*saññā …* **";
P_HTM[3518]="*saṅkhārā …* **";
P_HTM[3519]="*viññāṇaṃ anattā.* **";
P_HTM[3520]="*Sabbe saṅkhārā aniccā, sabbe dhammā anattā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3521]="*Atha ca pana me sabbasaṅkhārasamathe sabbūpadhipaṭinissagge taṇhākkhaye virāge nirodhe nibbāne cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati nādhimuccati.* **";
P_HTM[3522]="*Paritassanā upādānaṃ uppajjati;* **";
P_HTM[3523]="*paccudāvattati mānasaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3524]="*‘atha ko carahi me attā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3525]="*Na kho panevaṃ dhammaṃ passato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3526]="*Ko nu kho me tathā dhammaṃ deseyya yathāhaṃ dhammaṃ passeyyanti.* **";
P_HTM[3527]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[3528]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā ānando kosambiyaṃ viharati ghositārāme satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ, pahoti ca me āyasmā ānando tathā dhammaṃ desetuṃ yathāhaṃ dhammaṃ passeyyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3529]="*Atthi ca me āyasmante ānande tāvatikā vissaṭṭhi.* **";
P_HTM[3530]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkameyyan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3531]="*Ovadatu maṃ, āyasmā ānando;**“May Venerable Ānanda advise me and instruct me! May he give me a Dhamma talk so that I can see the teaching!”*";
P_HTM[3532]="*anusāsatu maṃ, āyasmā ānando;* **";
P_HTM[3533]="*karotu me, āyasmā ānando dhammiṃ kathaṃ yathāhaṃ dhammaṃ passeyyan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3534]="*“Ettakenapi mayaṃ āyasmato channassa attamanā api nāma taṃ āyasmā channo āvi akāsi khīlaṃ chindi.**“I’m already delighted with Venerable Channa. Hopefully you’ve opened yourself up and cut through your emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[3535]="*Odahāvuso channa, sotaṃ;**Listen well, Channa.*";
P_HTM[3536]="*bhabbosi dhammaṃ viññātun”ti.**You are capable of understanding the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[3537]="*Atha kho āyasmato channassa tāvatakeneva uḷāraṃ pītipāmojjaṃ uppajji:**Then right away Channa was filled with lofty rapture and joy,*";
P_HTM[3538]="*“bhabbo kirasmi dhammaṃ viññātun”ti.**“It seems I’m capable of understanding the teaching!”*";
P_HTM[3539]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso channa, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ kaccānagottaṃ bhikkhuṃ ovadantassa—**“Reverend Channa, I heard and learned in the presence of the Buddha his advice to the mendicant Kaccānagotta:*";
P_HTM[3540]="*dvayanissito khvāyaṃ, kaccāna, loko yebhuyyena atthitañceva natthitañca.**‘Kaccāna, this world mostly relies on the dual notions of existence and non-existence.*";
P_HTM[3541]="*Lokasamudayaṃ kho, kaccāna, yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato yā loke natthitā, sā na hoti.**But when you truly see the origin of the world with right understanding, you won’t have the notion of non-existence regarding the world.*";
P_HTM[3542]="*Lokanirodhaṃ kho, kaccāna, yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato yā loke atthitā, sā na hoti.**And when you truly see the cessation of the world with right understanding, you won’t have the notion of existence regarding the world.*";
P_HTM[3543]="*Upayupādānābhinivesavinibandho khvāyaṃ, kaccāna, loko yebhuyyena**The world is for the most part shackled to attraction, grasping, and insisting.*";
P_HTM[3544]="*taṃ cāyaṃ upayupādānaṃ cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayaṃ na upeti na upādiyati nādhiṭṭhāti ‘attā me’ti.**But if—when it comes to this attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendency—you don’t get attracted, grasp, and commit to the notion “my self”,*";
P_HTM[3545]="*Dukkhameva uppajjamānaṃ uppajjati, dukkhaṃ nirujjhamānaṃ nirujjhatīti na kaṅkhati na vicikicchati.**you’ll have no doubt or uncertainty that what arises is just suffering arising, and what ceases is just suffering ceasing.*";
P_HTM[3546]="*Aparappaccayā ñāṇamevassa ettha hoti.**Your knowledge about this is independent of others.*";
P_HTM[3547]="*Ettāvatā kho, kaccāna, sammādiṭṭhi hoti.**This is how right view is defined.*";
P_HTM[3548]="*Sabbamatthīti kho, kaccāna, ayameko anto.**“All exists”: this is one extreme.*";
P_HTM[3549]="*Sabbaṃ natthīti ayaṃ dutiyo anto.**“All doesn’t exist”: this is the second extreme.*";
P_HTM[3550]="*Ete te, kaccāna, ubho ante anupagamma majjhena tathāgato dhammaṃ deseti—**Avoiding these two extremes, the Realized One teaches by the middle way:*";
P_HTM[3551]="*avijjāpaccayā saṅkhārā;**“Ignorance is a condition for choices.*";
P_HTM[3552]="*saṅkhārapaccayā viññāṇaṃ … pe …**Choices are a condition for consciousness. …*";
P_HTM[3553]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa samudayo hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering originates.*";
P_HTM[3554]="*Avijjāya tveva asesavirāganirodhā saṅkhāranirodho … pe …**When ignorance fades away and ceases with nothing left over, choices cease. …*";
P_HTM[3555]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hotī”ti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering ceases.”’”*";
P_HTM[3556]="*“Evametaṃ, āvuso ānanda, hoti yesaṃ āyasmantānaṃ tādisā sabrahmacārayo anukampakā atthakāmā ovādakā anusāsakā.**“Reverend Ānanda, this is how it is when you have such venerables as spiritual companions to advise and instruct you out of kindness and compassion.*";
P_HTM[3557]="*Idañca pana me āyasmato ānandassa dhammadesanaṃ sutvā dhammo abhisamito”ti.**And now that I’ve heard this teaching from Venerable Ānanda, I’ve comprehended the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[3558]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3559]="*9. Rāhulasuttaṃ**Rāhula*";
P_HTM[3560]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3561]="*Atha kho āyasmā rāhulo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā rāhulo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Rāhula went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3562]="*“kathaṃ nu kho, bhante, jānato kathaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayā na hontī”ti?**“Sir, how does one know and see so that there’s no ego, possessiveness, or underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli?”*";
P_HTM[3563]="*“Yaṃ kiñci, rāhula, rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ rūpaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passati.**“Rāhula, one truly sees any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[3564]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**One truly sees any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[3565]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3566]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3567]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā … pe …**consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[3568]="*sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passati.* **";
P_HTM[3569]="*Evaṃ kho, rāhula, jānato evaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayā na hontī”ti.**That’s how to know and see so that there’s no ego, possessiveness, or underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli.”*";
P_HTM[3570]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3571]="*10. Dutiyarāhulasuttaṃ**Rāhula (2nd)*";
P_HTM[3572]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3573]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā rāhulo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, Rāhula said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3574]="*“kathaṃ nu kho, bhante, jānato kathaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānāpagataṃ mānasaṃ hoti vidhāsamatikkantaṃ santaṃ suvimuttan”ti?**“Sir, how does one know and see so that the mind is rid of ego, possessiveness, and conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli; and going beyond discrimination, it’s peaceful and well freed?”*";
P_HTM[3575]="*“Yaṃ kiñci, rāhula, rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā … pe … yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ rūpaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā anupādā vimutto hoti.**“Rāhula, when one truly sees any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self,’ one is freed by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3576]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**One truly sees any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[3577]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3578]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3579]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā anupādā vimutto hoti.**When one truly sees any kind of consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self,’ one is freed by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3580]="*Evaṃ kho, rāhula, jānato evaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānāpagataṃ mānasaṃ hoti vidhāsamatikkantaṃ santaṃ suvimuttan”ti.**That’s how to know and see so that the mind is rid of ego, possessiveness, and conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli; and going beyond discrimination, it’s peaceful and well freed.”*";
P_HTM[3581]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3582]="*Theravaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[3583]="*Ānando tisso yamako,* **";
P_HTM[3584]="*anurādho ca vakkali;* **";
P_HTM[3585]="*Assaji khemako channo,* **";
P_HTM[3586]="*rāhulā apare duve.* **";
P_HTM[3587]="*sn/sn22.093.xhtml==10. Pupphavagga==10. Pupphavaggo**Flowers*";
P_HTM[3588]="*1. Nadīsuttaṃ**A River*";
P_HTM[3589]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3590]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, nadī pabbateyyā ohārinī dūraṅgamā sīghasotā. Tassā ubhosu tīresu kāsā cepi jātā assu, te naṃ ajjholambeyyuṃ; kusā cepi jātā assu, te naṃ ajjholambeyyuṃ; pabbajā cepi jātā assu, te naṃ ajjholambeyyuṃ; bīraṇā cepi jātā assu, te naṃ ajjholambeyyuṃ; rukkhā cepi jātā assu, te naṃ ajjholambeyyuṃ. Tassā puriso sotena vuyhamāno kāse cepi gaṇheyya, te palujjeyyuṃ. So tatonidānaṃ anayabyasanaṃ āpajjeyya. Kuse cepi gaṇheyya, pabbaje cepi gaṇheyya, bīraṇe cepi gaṇheyya, rukkhe cepi gaṇheyya, te palujjeyyuṃ. So tatonidānaṃ anayabyasanaṃ āpajjeyya.**“Suppose, mendicants, there was a mountain river that flowed swiftly, going far, carrying all before it. If wild sugarcane, kusa grass, reeds, vetiver, or trees grew on either bank, they’d overhang the river. And if a person who was being swept along by the current grabbed the wild sugarcane, kusa grass, reeds, vetiver, or trees, it’d break off, and they’d come to ruin because of that.*";
P_HTM[3591]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**In the same way, an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[3592]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[3593]="*Tassa taṃ rūpaṃ palujjati.**But their form breaks off,*";
P_HTM[3594]="*So tatonidānaṃ anayabyasanaṃ āpajjati.**and they come to ruin because of that.*";
P_HTM[3595]="*Vedanaṃ …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[3596]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3597]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3598]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3599]="*Tassa taṃ viññāṇaṃ palujjati.**But their consciousness breaks off,*";
P_HTM[3600]="*So tatonidānaṃ anayabyasanaṃ āpajjati.**and they come to ruin because of that.*";
P_HTM[3601]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3602]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3603]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[3604]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[3605]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3606]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3607]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3608]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3609]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3610]="*“Tasmātiha … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[3611]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[3612]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[3613]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3614]="*2. Pupphasuttaṃ**Flowers*";
P_HTM[3615]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3616]="*“Nāhaṃ, bhikkhave, lokena vivadāmi, lokova mayā vivadati.**“Mendicants, I don’t argue with the world; it’s the world that argues with me.*";
P_HTM[3617]="*Na, bhikkhave, dhammavādī kenaci lokasmiṃ vivadati.**When your speech is in line with the teaching you don’t argue with anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[3618]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, natthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ, ahampi taṃ ‘natthī’ti vadāmi.**What the astute agree on as not existing, I too say does not exist.*";
P_HTM[3619]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, atthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ, ahampi taṃ ‘atthī’ti vadāmi.**What the astute agree on as existing, I too say exists.*";
P_HTM[3620]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, natthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ, yamahaṃ ‘natthī’ti vadāmi?**And what do the astute agree on as not existing, which I too say does not exist?*";
P_HTM[3621]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ natthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ; ahampi taṃ ‘natthī’ti vadāmi.**Form that is permanent, everlasting, eternal, and imperishable.*";
P_HTM[3622]="*Vedanā …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[3623]="*saññā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[3624]="*saṅkhārā …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[3625]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ natthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ; ahampi taṃ ‘natthī’ti vadāmi.**Consciousness that is permanent, everlasting, eternal, and imperishable.*";
P_HTM[3626]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, natthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ; ahampi taṃ ‘natthī’ti vadāmi.**This is what the astute agree on as not existing, which I too say does not exist.*";
P_HTM[3627]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, atthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ, yamahaṃ ‘atthī’ti vadāmi?**And what do the astute agree on as existing, which I too say exists?*";
P_HTM[3628]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ atthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ; ahampi taṃ ‘atthī’ti vadāmi.**Form that is impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[3629]="*Vedanā aniccā … pe …**Feeling … Perception … Choices …*";
P_HTM[3630]="*viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ atthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ; ahampi taṃ ‘atthī’ti vadāmi.**Consciousness that is impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[3631]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, atthisammataṃ loke paṇḍitānaṃ; ahampi taṃ ‘atthī’ti vadāmi.**This is what the astute agree on as existing, which I too say exists.*";
P_HTM[3632]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, loke lokadhammo, taṃ tathāgato abhisambujjhati abhisameti;**There is a temporal phenomenon in the world that the Realized One understands and comprehends.*";
P_HTM[3633]="*abhisambujjhitvā abhisametvā taṃ ācikkhati deseti paññapeti paṭṭhapeti vivarati vibhajati uttānīkaroti.**Then he explains, teaches, asserts, establishes, clarifies, analyzes, and reveals it.*";
P_HTM[3634]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, loke lokadhammo, taṃ tathāgato abhisambujjhati abhisameti, abhisambujjhitvā abhisametvā ācikkhati deseti paññapeti paṭṭhapeti vivarati vibhajati uttānīkaroti?**And what is that temporal phenomenon in the world?*";
P_HTM[3635]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, loke lokadhammo taṃ tathāgato abhisambujjhati abhisameti.**Form is a temporal phenomenon in the world that the Realized One understands and comprehends.*";
P_HTM[3636]="*Abhisambujjhitvā abhisametvā ācikkhati deseti paññapeti paṭṭhapeti vivarati vibhajati uttānīkaroti.**Then he explains, teaches, asserts, establishes, clarifies, analyzes, and reveals it.*";
P_HTM[3637]="*Yo, bhikkhave, tathāgatena evaṃ ācikkhiyamāne desiyamāne paññapiyamāne paṭṭhapiyamāne vivariyamāne vibhajiyamāne uttānīkariyamāne na jānāti na passati tamahaṃ, bhikkhave, bālaṃ puthujjanaṃ andhaṃ acakkhukaṃ ajānantaṃ apassantaṃ kinti karomi.**This being so, what can I do about a foolish ordinary person, blind and sightless, who does not know or see?*";
P_HTM[3638]="*Vedanā, bhikkhave, loke lokadhammo … pe …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[3639]="*saññā, bhikkhave …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[3640]="*saṅkhārā, bhikkhave …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[3641]="*viññāṇaṃ, bhikkhave, loke lokadhammo taṃ tathāgato abhisambujjhati abhisameti.**Consciousness is a temporal phenomenon in the world that the Realized One understands and comprehends.*";
P_HTM[3642]="*Abhisambujjhitvā abhisametvā ācikkhati deseti paññapeti paṭṭhapeti vivarati vibhajati uttānīkaroti.**Then he explains, teaches, asserts, establishes, clarifies, analyzes, and reveals it.*";
P_HTM[3643]="*Yo, bhikkhave, tathāgatena evaṃ ācikkhiyamāne desiyamāne paññapiyamāne paṭṭhapiyamāne vivariyamāne vibhajiyamāne uttānīkariyamāne na jānāti na passati tamahaṃ, bhikkhave, bālaṃ puthujjanaṃ andhaṃ acakkhukaṃ ajānantaṃ apassantaṃ kinti karomi.**This being so, what can I do about a foolish ordinary person, blind and sightless, who does not know or see?*";
P_HTM[3644]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uppalaṃ vā padumaṃ vā puṇḍarīkaṃ vā udake jātaṃ udake saṃvaḍḍhaṃ udakā accuggamma ṭhāti anupalittaṃ udakena;**Suppose there was a blue water lily, or a pink or white lotus. Though it sprouted and grew in the water, it would rise up above the water and stand with no water clinging to it.*";
P_HTM[3645]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, tathāgato loke jāto loke saṃvaḍḍho lokaṃ abhibhuyya viharati anupalitto lokenā”ti.**In the same way, though I was born and grew up in the world, I live having mastered the world, and the world does not cling to me.”*";
P_HTM[3646]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3647]="*3. Pheṇapiṇḍūpamasuttaṃ**A Lump of Foam*";
P_HTM[3648]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā ayujjhāyaṃ viharati gaṅgāya nadiyā tīre.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Ayojjhā on the bank of the Ganges river.*";
P_HTM[3649]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3650]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ayaṃ gaṅgā nadī mahantaṃ pheṇapiṇḍaṃ āvaheyya. Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso passeyya nijjhāyeyya yoniso upaparikkheyya. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyeyya, tucchakaññeva khāyeyya, asārakaññeva khāyeyya. Kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, pheṇapiṇḍe sāro?**“Mendicants, suppose this Ganges river was carrying along a big lump of foam. And a person with good eyesight would see it and contemplate it, examining it carefully. And it would appear to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in a lump of foam?*";
P_HTM[3651]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yaṃ kiñci rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ … pe … yaṃ dūre santike vā taṃ bhikkhu passati nijjhāyati yoniso upaparikkhati. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyati, tucchakaññeva khāyati, asārakaññeva khāyati. Kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, rūpe sāro?**In the same way, a mendicant sees and contemplates any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; near or far—examining it carefully. And it appears to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in form?*";
P_HTM[3652]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, saradasamaye thullaphusitake deve vassante udake udakapubbuḷaṃ uppajjati ceva nirujjhati ca. Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso passeyya nijjhāyeyya yoniso upaparikkheyya. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyeyya, tucchakaññeva khāyeyya, asārakaññeva khāyeyya. Kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, udakapubbuḷe sāro?**Suppose it was the time of autumn, when the rain was falling heavily, and a bubble on the water forms and pops right away. And a person with good eyesight would see it and contemplate it, examining it carefully. And it would appear to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in a water bubble?*";
P_HTM[3653]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yā kāci vedanā atītānāgatapaccuppannā … pe … yā dūre santike vā taṃ bhikkhu passati nijjhāyati yoniso upaparikkhati. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyati, tucchakaññeva khāyati, asārakaññeva khāyati. Kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, vedanāya sāro?**In the same way, a mendicant sees and contemplates any kind of feeling at all … examining it carefully. And it appears to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in feeling?*";
P_HTM[3654]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, gimhānaṃ pacchime māse ṭhite majjhanhike kāle marīcikā phandati. Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso passeyya nijjhāyeyya yoniso upaparikkheyya. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyeyya, tucchakaññeva khāyeyya … pe … kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, marīcikāya sāro?**Suppose that in the last month of summer, at noon, a shimmering mirage appears. And a person with good eyesight would see it and contemplate it, examining it carefully. And it would appear to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in a mirage?*";
P_HTM[3655]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yā kāci saññā … pe ….**In the same way, a mendicant sees and contemplates any kind of perception at all … examining it carefully. And it appears to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in perception?*";
P_HTM[3656]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso sāratthiko sāragavesī sārapariyesanaṃ caramāno tiṇhaṃ kuṭhāriṃ ādāya vanaṃ paviseyya. So tattha passeyya mahantaṃ kadalikkhandhaṃ ujuṃ navaṃ akukkukajātaṃ. Tamenaṃ mūle chindeyya; mūle chetvā agge chindeyya, agge chetvā pattavaṭṭiṃ vinibbhujeyya. So tassa pattavaṭṭiṃ vinibbhujanto pheggumpi nādhigaccheyya, kuto sāraṃ. Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso passeyya nijjhāyeyya yoniso upaparikkheyya. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyeyya, tucchakaññeva khāyeyya, asārakaññeva khāyeyya. Kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, kadalikkhandhe sāro?**Suppose there was a person in need of heartwood. Wandering in search of heartwood, they’d take a sharp axe and enter a forest. There they’d see a big banana tree, straight and young and grown free of defects. They’d cut it down at the base, cut off the top, and unroll the coiled sheaths. But they wouldn’t even find sapwood, much less heartwood. And a person with good eyesight would see it and contemplate it, examining it carefully. And it would appear to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in a banana tree?*";
P_HTM[3657]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ye keci saṅkhārā atītānāgatapaccuppannā … pe … ye dūre santike vā taṃ bhikkhu passati nijjhāyati yoniso upaparikkhati. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyati, tucchakaññeva khāyati, asārakaññeva khāyati. Kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, saṅkhāresu sāro?**In the same way, a mendicant sees and contemplates any kind of choices at all … examining them carefully. And they appear to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in choices?*";
P_HTM[3658]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, māyākāro vā māyākārantevāsī vā catumahāpathe māyaṃ vidaṃseyya. Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso passeyya nijjhāyeyya yoniso upaparikkheyya. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyeyya, tucchakaññeva khāyeyya, asārakaññeva khāyeyya. Kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, māyāya sāro?**Suppose a magician or their apprentice was to perform a magic trick at the crossroads. And a person with good eyesight would see it and contemplate it, examining it carefully. And it would appear to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in a magic trick?*";
P_HTM[3659]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ … pe … yaṃ dūre santike vā, taṃ bhikkhu passati nijjhāyati yoniso upaparikkhati. Tassa taṃ passato nijjhāyato yoniso upaparikkhato rittakaññeva khāyati, tucchakaññeva khāyati, asārakaññeva khāyati. Kiñhi siyā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe sāro?**In the same way, a mendicant sees and contemplates any kind of consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; near or far—examining it carefully. And it appears to them as completely void, hollow, and insubstantial. For what substance could there be in consciousness?*";
P_HTM[3660]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi … saññāyapi … saṅkhāresupi … viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3661]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti … pe …**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[3662]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti”.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[3663]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3664]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3665]="*“Pheṇapiṇḍūpamaṃ rūpaṃ,**“Form is like a lump of foam;*";
P_HTM[3666]="*vedanā bubbuḷūpamā;**feeling is like a bubble;*";
P_HTM[3667]="*Marīcikūpamā saññā,**perception seems like a mirage;*";
P_HTM[3668]="*saṅkhārā kadalūpamā;**choices like a banana tree;*";
P_HTM[3669]="*Māyūpamañca viññāṇaṃ,**and consciousness like a magic trick:*";
P_HTM[3670]="*desitādiccabandhunā.**so taught the Kinsman of the Sun.*";
P_HTM[3671]="*Yathā yathā nijjhāyati,**However you contemplate them,*";
P_HTM[3672]="*yoniso upaparikkhati;**examining them carefully,*";
P_HTM[3673]="*Rittakaṃ tucchakaṃ hoti,**they’re void and hollow*";
P_HTM[3674]="*yo naṃ passati yoniso.**when you look at them closely.*";
P_HTM[3675]="*Imañca kāyaṃ ārabbha,**Concerning this body,*";
P_HTM[3676]="*bhūripaññena desitaṃ;**he of vast wisdom has taught*";
P_HTM[3677]="*Pahānaṃ tiṇṇaṃ dhammānaṃ,**that when three things are given up,*";
P_HTM[3678]="*rūpaṃ passatha chaḍḍitaṃ.**you’ll see this form discarded.*";
P_HTM[3679]="*Āyu usmā ca viññāṇaṃ,**Vitality, warmth, and consciousness:*";
P_HTM[3680]="*yadā kāyaṃ jahantimaṃ;**when they leave the body,*";
P_HTM[3681]="*Apaviddho tadā seti,**it lies there tossed aside,*";
P_HTM[3682]="*parabhattaṃ acetanaṃ.**food for others, mindless.*";
P_HTM[3683]="*Etādisāyaṃ santāno,**Such is this process,*";
P_HTM[3684]="*māyāyaṃ bālalāpinī;**this illusion, cooed over by fools.*";
P_HTM[3685]="*Vadhako esa akkhāto,**It’s said to be a killer,*";
P_HTM[3686]="*sāro ettha na vijjati.**for no substance is found here.*";
P_HTM[3687]="*Evaṃ khandhe avekkheyya,**An energetic mendicant*";
P_HTM[3688]="*bhikkhu āraddhavīriyo;**should examine the aggregates like this,*";
P_HTM[3689]="*Divā vā yadi vā rattiṃ,**with situational awareness and mindfulness*";
P_HTM[3690]="*sampajāno paṭissato.**whether by day or by night.*";
P_HTM[3691]="*Jaheyya sabbasaṃyogaṃ,**They should give up all fetters,*";
P_HTM[3692]="*kareyya saraṇattano;**and make a refuge for themselves.*";
P_HTM[3693]="*Careyyādittasīsova,**They should live as though their head was on fire,*";
P_HTM[3694]="*patthayaṃ accutaṃ padan”ti.**aspiring to the imperishable state.”*";
P_HTM[3695]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3696]="*4. Gomayapiṇḍasuttaṃ**A Lump of Cow Dung*";
P_HTM[3697]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3698]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, that mendicant said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3699]="*“atthi nu kho, bhante, kiñci rūpaṃ yaṃ rūpaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati?**“Sir, is there any form at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever?*";
P_HTM[3700]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, kāci vedanā yā vedanā niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati?**Is there any feeling …*";
P_HTM[3701]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, kāci saññā yā saññā … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3702]="*atthi nu kho, bhante, keci saṅkhārā ye saṅkhārā niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti?**choices …*";
P_HTM[3703]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, kiñci viññāṇaṃ, yaṃ viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassatī”ti?**consciousness at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever?”*";
P_HTM[3704]="*“Natthi kho, bhikkhu, kiñci rūpaṃ, yaṃ rūpaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**“Mendicant, there is no form at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.*";
P_HTM[3705]="*Natthi kho, bhikkhu, kāci vedanā …**There’s no feeling …*";
P_HTM[3706]="*kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3707]="*keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3708]="*kiñci viññāṇaṃ, yaṃ viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassatī”ti.**consciousness at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.”*";
P_HTM[3709]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittaṃ gomayapiṇḍaṃ pāṇinā gahetvā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**Then the Buddha, picking up a lump of cow dung, said to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3710]="*“ettakopi kho, bhikkhu, attabhāvapaṭilābho natthi nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**“There’s not even this much of any incarnation that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.*";
P_HTM[3711]="*Ettako cepi, bhikkhu, attabhāvapaṭilābho abhavissa nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo, nayidaṃ brahmacariyavāso paññāyetha sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**If there were, this living of the spiritual life for the complete ending of suffering would not be found.*";
P_HTM[3712]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhu, ettakopi attabhāvapaṭilābho natthi nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo, tasmā brahmacariyavāso paññāyati sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**But since there isn’t, this living of the spiritual life for the complete ending of suffering is found.*";
P_HTM[3713]="*Bhūtapubbāhaṃ, bhikkhu, rājā ahosiṃ khattiyo muddhāvasitto.**Once upon a time I was an anointed aristocratic king.*";
P_HTM[3714]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu, rañño sato khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa caturāsītinagarasahassāni ahesuṃ kusāvatīrājadhānippamukhāni.**I had 84,000 cities, with the capital Kusāvatī the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3715]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu, rañño sato khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa caturāsītipāsādasahassāni ahesuṃ dhammapāsādappamukhāni.**I had 84,000 palaces, with the palace named Principle the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3716]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu, rañño sato khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa caturāsītikūṭāgārasahassāni ahesuṃ mahābyūhakūṭāgārappamukhāni.**I had 84,000 chambers, with the great foyer the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3717]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu, rañño sato khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa caturāsītipallaṅkasahassāni ahesuṃ dantamayāni sāramayāni sovaṇṇamayāni goṇakatthatāni paṭikatthatāni paṭalikatthatāni kadalimigapavarapaccattharaṇāni sauttaracchadāni ubhatolohitakūpadhānāni.**I had 84,000 couches made of ivory or heartwood or gold or silver, spread with woolen covers—shag-piled or embroidered with flowers—and spread with a fine deer hide, with a canopy above and red pillows at both ends.*";
P_HTM[3718]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu, rañño sato khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa caturāsītināgasahassāni ahesuṃ sovaṇṇālaṅkārāni sovaṇṇaddhajāni hemajālapaṭicchannāni uposathanāgarājappamukhāni.**I had 84,000 bull elephants with gold adornments and banners, covered with gold netting, with the royal bull elephant named Sabbath the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3719]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu, rañño sato khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa caturāsītiassasahassāni ahesuṃ sovaṇṇālaṅkārāni sovaṇṇaddhajāni hemajālapaṭicchannāni valāhakaassarājappamukhāni.**I had 84,000 horses with gold adornments and banners, covered with gold netting, with the royal steed named Thundercloud the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3720]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu, rañño sato khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa caturāsītirathasahassāni ahesuṃ sovaṇṇālaṅkārāni sovaṇṇaddhajāni hemajālapaṭicchannāni vejayantarathappamukhāni.**I had 84,000 chariots with gold adornments and banners, covered with gold netting, with the chariot named Triumph the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3721]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu, rañño sato khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa caturāsītimaṇisahassāni ahesuṃ maṇiratanappamukhāni.**I had 84,000 jewels, with the jewel-treasure the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3722]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu … pe … caturāsītiitthisahassāni ahesuṃ subhaddādevippamukhāni.**I had 84,000 women, with Queen Subhaddā the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3723]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu … pe … caturāsītikhattiyasahassāni ahesuṃ anuyantāni pariṇāyakaratanappamukhāni.**I had 84,000 aristocrat vassals, with the counselor-treasure the foremost.*";
P_HTM[3724]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu … pe … caturāsītidhenusahassāni ahesuṃ dukūlasandānāni kaṃsūpadhāraṇāni.**I had 84,000 milk cows with silken reins and bronze pails.*";
P_HTM[3725]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu … pe … caturāsītivatthakoṭisahassāni ahesuṃ khomasukhumāni koseyyasukhumāni kambalasukhumāni kappāsikasukhumāni.**I had 8,400,000,000 fine cloths of linen, silk, wool, and cotton.*";
P_HTM[3726]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhu … pe … caturāsītithālipākasahassāni ahesuṃ; sāyaṃ pātaṃ bhattābhihāro abhihariyittha.**I had 84,000 servings of food, which were presented to me as offerings in the morning and evening.*";
P_HTM[3727]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā nagarasahassānaṃ ekaññeva taṃ nagaraṃ hoti yamahaṃ tena samayena ajjhāvasāmi—kusāvatī rājadhānī.**Of those 84,000 cities, I only stayed in one, the capital Kusāvatī.*";
P_HTM[3728]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā pāsādasahassānaṃ ekoyeva so pāsādo hoti yamahaṃ tena samayena ajjhāvasāmi—dhammo pāsādo.**Of those 84,000 mansions, I only dwelt in one, the Palace of Principle.*";
P_HTM[3729]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā kūṭāgārasahassānaṃ ekaññeva taṃ kūṭāgāraṃ hoti yamahaṃ tena samayena ajjhāvasāmi—mahābyūhaṃ kūṭāgāraṃ.**Of those 84,000 chambers, I only dwelt in the great foyer.*";
P_HTM[3730]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā pallaṅkasahassānaṃ ekoyeva so pallaṅko hoti yamahaṃ tena samayena paribhuñjāmi—dantamayo vā sāramayo vā sovaṇṇamayo vā rūpiyamayo vā.**Of those 84,000 couches, I only used one, made of ivory or heartwood or gold or silver.*";
P_HTM[3731]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā nāgasahassānaṃ ekoyeva so nāgo hoti yamahaṃ tena samayena abhiruhāmi—uposatho nāgarājā.**Of those 84,000 bull elephants, I only rode one, the royal bull elephant named Sabbath.*";
P_HTM[3732]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā assasahassānaṃ ekoyeva so asso hoti yamahaṃ tena samayena abhiruhāmi—valāhako assarājā.**Of those 84,000 horses, I only rode one, the royal horse named Thundercloud.*";
P_HTM[3733]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā rathasahassānaṃ ekoyeva so ratho hoti yamahaṃ tena samayena abhiruhāmi—vejayanto ratho.**Of those 84,000 chariots, I only rode one, the chariot named Triumph.*";
P_HTM[3734]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā itthisahassānaṃ ekāyeva sā itthī hoti yā maṃ tena samayena paccupaṭṭhāti—khattiyānī vā velāmikā vā.**Of those 84,000 women, I was only served by one, a maiden of the aristocratic or merchant classes.*";
P_HTM[3735]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā vatthakoṭisahassānaṃ ekaññeva taṃ vatthayugaṃ hoti yamahaṃ tena samayena paridahāmi—khomasukhumaṃ vā koseyyasukhumaṃ vā kambalasukhumaṃ vā kappāsikasukhumaṃ vā.**Of those 8,400,000,000 cloths, I only wore one pair, made of fine linen, silk, wool, or cotton.*";
P_HTM[3736]="*Tesaṃ kho pana, bhikkhu, caturāsītiyā thālipākasahassānaṃ ekoyeva so thālipāko hoti yato nāḷikodanaparamaṃ bhuñjāmi tadupiyañca sūpeyyaṃ.**Of those 84,000 servings of food, I only had one, eating at most a serving of rice and suitable sauce.*";
P_HTM[3737]="*Iti kho, bhikkhu, sabbe te saṅkhārā atītā niruddhā vipariṇatā.**And so all those conditioned phenomena have passed, ceased, and perished.*";
P_HTM[3738]="*Evaṃ aniccā kho, bhikkhu, saṅkhārā.**So impermanent are conditions,*";
P_HTM[3739]="*Evaṃ addhuvā kho, bhikkhu, saṅkhārā.**so unstable are conditions,*";
P_HTM[3740]="*Evaṃ anassāsikā kho, bhikkhu, saṅkhārā.**so unreliable are conditions.*";
P_HTM[3741]="*Yāvañcidaṃ, bhikkhu, alameva sabbasaṅkhāresu nibbindituṃ, alaṃ virajjituṃ, alaṃ vimuccitun”ti.**This is quite enough for you to become disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding all conditions.”*";
P_HTM[3742]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3743]="*5. Nakhasikhāsuttaṃ**A Fingernail*";
P_HTM[3744]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3745]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, that mendicant said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3746]="*“atthi nu kho, bhante, kiñci rūpaṃ yaṃ rūpaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati?**“Sir, is there any form at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever?*";
P_HTM[3747]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, kāci vedanā yā vedanā niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati?**Is there any feeling …*";
P_HTM[3748]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, kāci saññā … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3749]="*keci saṅkhārā, ye saṅkhārā niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti?**choices …*";
P_HTM[3750]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, kiñci viññāṇaṃ, yaṃ viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassatī”ti?**consciousness at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever?”*";
P_HTM[3751]="*“Natthi kho, bhikkhu, kiñci rūpaṃ, yaṃ rūpaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**“Mendicant, there is no form at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.*";
P_HTM[3752]="*Natthi kho, bhikkhu, kāci vedanā …**There’s no feeling …*";
P_HTM[3753]="*kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3754]="*keci saṅkhārā … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3755]="*kiñci viññāṇaṃ, yaṃ viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassatī”ti.**consciousness at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.”*";
P_HTM[3756]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittaṃ nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsuṃ āropetvā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**Then the Buddha, picking up a little bit of dirt under his fingernail, addressed that mendicant:*";
P_HTM[3757]="*“ettakampi kho, bhikkhu, rūpaṃ natthi niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**“There’s not even this much of any form that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.*";
P_HTM[3758]="*Ettakañcepi, bhikkhu, rūpaṃ abhavissa niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ, nayidaṃ brahmacariyavāso paññāyetha sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**If there were, this living of the spiritual life for the complete ending of suffering would not be found.*";
P_HTM[3759]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhu, ettakampi rūpaṃ natthi niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ, tasmā brahmacariyavāso paññāyati sammā dukkhakkhayāya”.**But since there isn’t, this living of the spiritual life for the complete ending of suffering is found.*";
P_HTM[3760]="*Ettakāpi kho, bhikkhu, vedanā natthi niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**There’s not even this much of any feeling …*";
P_HTM[3761]="*Ettakā cepi, bhikkhu, vedanā abhavissa niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā, na yidaṃ brahmacariyavāso paññāyetha sammā dukkhakkhayāya.* **";
P_HTM[3762]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhu, ettakāpi vedanā natthi niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā, tasmā brahmacariyavāso paññāyati sammā dukkhakkhayāya.* **";
P_HTM[3763]="*Ettakāpi kho, bhikkhu, saññā natthi … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3764]="*ettakāpi kho, bhikkhu, saṅkhārā natthi niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti.**choices …*";
P_HTM[3765]="*Ettakā cepi, bhikkhu, saṅkhārā abhavissaṃsu niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā, na yidaṃ brahmacariyavāso paññāyetha sammā dukkhakkhayāya.* **";
P_HTM[3766]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhu, ettakāpi saṅkhārā natthi niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā, tasmā brahmacariyavāso paññāyati sammā dukkhakkhayāya.* **";
P_HTM[3767]="*Ettakampi kho, bhikkhu, viññāṇaṃ natthi niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**consciousness that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.*";
P_HTM[3768]="*Ettakampi kho, bhikkhu, viññāṇaṃ abhavissa niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ, na yidaṃ brahmacariyavāso paññāyetha sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**If there were, this living of the spiritual life for the complete ending of suffering would not be found.*";
P_HTM[3769]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhu, ettakampi viññāṇaṃ natthi niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ, tasmā brahmacariyavāso paññāyati sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**But since there isn’t, this living of the spiritual life for the complete ending of suffering is found.*";
P_HTM[3770]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, bhikkhu,**What do you think, mendicant?*";
P_HTM[3771]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3772]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3773]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3774]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3775]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3776]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3777]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante” … pe …**“Impermanent, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[3778]="*“tasmātiha … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[3779]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[3780]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[3781]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3782]="*6. Suddhikasuttaṃ**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[3783]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3784]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, that mendicant said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3785]="*“atthi nu kho, bhante, kiñci rūpaṃ, yaṃ rūpaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati?**“Sir, is there any form at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever?*";
P_HTM[3786]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, kāci vedanā … pe …**Is there any feeling …*";
P_HTM[3787]="*kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3788]="*keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3789]="*kiñci viññāṇaṃ, yaṃ viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassatī”ti?**consciousness at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever?”*";
P_HTM[3790]="*“Natthi kho, bhikkhu, kiñci rūpaṃ yaṃ rūpaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**“Mendicant, there is no form at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.*";
P_HTM[3791]="*Natthi kho, bhikkhu, kāci vedanā …**There’s no feeling …*";
P_HTM[3792]="*kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3793]="*keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3794]="*kiñci viññāṇaṃ, yaṃ viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhammaṃ sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassatī”ti.**consciousness at all that’s permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, and will last forever and ever.”*";
P_HTM[3795]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3796]="*7. Gaddulabaddhasuttaṃ**A Leash*";
P_HTM[3797]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3798]="*“Anamataggoyaṃ, bhikkhave, saṃsāro.**“Mendicants, transmigration has no known beginning.*";
P_HTM[3799]="*Pubbā koṭi na paññāyati avijjānīvaraṇānaṃ sattānaṃ taṇhāsaṃyojanānaṃ sandhāvataṃ saṃsarataṃ.**No first point is found of sentient beings roaming and transmigrating, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.*";
P_HTM[3800]="*Hoti so, bhikkhave, samayo yaṃ mahāsamuddo ussussati visussati na bhavati;**There comes a time when the ocean dries up and evaporates and is no more.*";
P_HTM[3801]="*na tvevāhaṃ, bhikkhave, avijjānīvaraṇānaṃ sattānaṃ taṇhāsaṃyojanānaṃ sandhāvataṃ saṃsarataṃ dukkhassa antakiriyaṃ vadāmi.**But still, I say, there is no making an end of suffering for sentient beings roaming and transmigrating, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.*";
P_HTM[3802]="*Hoti so, bhikkhave, samayo yaṃ sineru pabbatarājā ḍayhati vinassati na bhavati;**There comes a time when Sineru the king of mountains is burned up and destroyed, and is no more.*";
P_HTM[3803]="*na tvevāhaṃ, bhikkhave, avijjānīvaraṇānaṃ sattānaṃ taṇhāsaṃyojanānaṃ sandhāvataṃ saṃsarataṃ dukkhassa antakiriyaṃ vadāmi.**But still, I say, there is no making an end of suffering for sentient beings roaming and transmigrating, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.*";
P_HTM[3804]="*Hoti so, bhikkhave, samayo yaṃ mahāpathavī ḍayhati vinassati na bhavati;**There comes a time when the great earth is burned up and destroyed, and is no more.*";
P_HTM[3805]="*na tvevāhaṃ, bhikkhave, avijjānīvaraṇānaṃ sattānaṃ taṇhāsaṃyojanānaṃ sandhāvataṃ saṃsarataṃ dukkhassa antakiriyaṃ vadāmi.**But still, I say, there is no making an end of suffering for sentient beings roaming and transmigrating, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.*";
P_HTM[3806]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, sā gaddulabaddho daḷhe khīle vā thambhe vā upanibaddho tameva khīlaṃ vā thambhaṃ vā anuparidhāvati anuparivattati;**Suppose a dog on a leash was tethered to a strong post or pillar. It would just keep running and circling around that post or pillar.*";
P_HTM[3807]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī … pe …**In the same way, take an uneducated ordinary person who has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in their teaching. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in their teaching.*";
P_HTM[3808]="*sappurisadhamme avinīto rūpaṃ attato samanupassati … pe …**They regard form …*";
P_HTM[3809]="*vedanaṃ attato samanupassati …**feeling …*";
P_HTM[3810]="*saññaṃ attato samanupassati …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3811]="*saṅkhāre attato samanupassati …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3812]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3813]="*So rūpaññeva anuparidhāvati anuparivattati, vedanaññeva … pe … saññaññeva … saṅkhāreyeva … viññāṇaññeva anuparidhāvati anuparivattati.**They just keep running and circling around form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3814]="*So rūpaṃ anuparidhāvaṃ anuparivattaṃ, vedanaṃ … pe … saññaṃ … saṅkhāre … viññāṇaṃ anuparidhāvaṃ anuparivattaṃ, na parimuccati rūpamhā, na parimuccati vedanāya, na parimuccati saññāya, na parimuccati saṅkhārehi, na parimuccati viññāṇamhā, na parimuccati jātiyā jarāmaraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**Doing so, they’re not freed from form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness. They’re not freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[3815]="*‘Na parimuccati dukkhasmā’ti vadāmi.**They’re not freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[3816]="*Sutavā ca kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī … pe … sappurisadhamme suvinīto,**An educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[3817]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati … pe …**They don’t regard form …*";
P_HTM[3818]="*na vedanaṃ …**feeling …*";
P_HTM[3819]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3820]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3821]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā viññāṇaṃ, na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**or consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3822]="*So rūpaṃ nānuparidhāvati nānuparivattati, vedanaṃ … saññaṃ … saṅkhāre … viññāṇaṃ nānuparidhāvati nānuparivattati.**They don’t keep running and circling around form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3823]="*So rūpaṃ ananuparidhāvaṃ ananuparivattaṃ, vedanaṃ … saññaṃ … saṅkhāre … viññāṇaṃ ananuparidhāvaṃ ananuparivattaṃ; parimuccati rūpamhā, parimuccati vedanāya, parimuccati saññāya, parimuccati saṅkhārehi, parimuccati viññāṇamhā, parimuccati jātiyā jarāmaraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**By not doing so, they’re freed from form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness. They’re freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[3824]="*‘Parimuccati dukkhasmā’ti vadāmī”ti.**They’re freed from suffering, I say.”*";
P_HTM[3825]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3826]="*8. Dutiyagaddulabaddhasuttaṃ**A Leash (2nd)*";
P_HTM[3827]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3828]="*“Anamataggoyaṃ, bhikkhave, saṃsāro.**“Mendicants, transmigration has no known beginning.*";
P_HTM[3829]="*Pubbā koṭi na paññāyati avijjānīvaraṇānaṃ sattānaṃ taṇhāsaṃyojanānaṃ sandhāvataṃ saṃsarataṃ.**No first point is found of sentient beings roaming and transmigrating, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.*";
P_HTM[3830]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, sā gaddulabaddho daḷhe khīle vā thambhe vā upanibaddho. So gacchati cepi tameva khīlaṃ vā thambhaṃ vā upagacchati; tiṭṭhati cepi tameva khīlaṃ vā thambhaṃ vā upatiṭṭhati; nisīdati cepi tameva khīlaṃ vā thambhaṃ vā upanisīdati; nipajjati cepi tameva khīlaṃ vā thambhaṃ vā upanipajjati.**Suppose a dog on a leash was tethered to a strong post or pillar. Whether walking, standing, sitting, or lying down, it stays right beside that post or pillar.*";
P_HTM[3831]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano rūpaṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassati.**In the same way, an uneducated ordinary person regards form like this: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self.’*";
P_HTM[3832]="*Vedanaṃ …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[3833]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3834]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3835]="*viññāṇaṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassati.**consciousness like this: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self.’*";
P_HTM[3836]="*So gacchati cepi ime pañcupādānakkhandhe upagacchati;**When walking, they walk right beside the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[3837]="*tiṭṭhati cepi ime pañcupādānakkhandhe upatiṭṭhati;**When standing …*";
P_HTM[3838]="*nisīdati cepi ime pañcupādānakkhandhe upanisīdati;**sitting …*";
P_HTM[3839]="*nipajjati cepi ime pañcupādānakkhandhe upanipajjati.**lying down, they lie down right beside the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[3840]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, abhikkhaṇaṃ sakaṃ cittaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**So you should regularly check your own mind:*";
P_HTM[3841]="*‘dīgharattamidaṃ cittaṃ saṅkiliṭṭhaṃ rāgena dosena mohenā’ti.**‘For a long time this mind has been corrupted by greed, hate, and delusion.’*";
P_HTM[3842]="*Cittasaṅkilesā, bhikkhave, sattā saṅkilissanti;**Sentient beings are corrupted because the mind is corrupted.*";
P_HTM[3843]="*cittavodānā sattā visujjhanti.**Sentient beings are purified because the mind is purified.*";
P_HTM[3844]="*Diṭṭhaṃ vo, bhikkhave, caraṇaṃ nāma cittan”ti?**Mendicants, have you seen the picture called ‘Conduct’?”*";
P_HTM[3845]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3846]="*“Tampi kho, bhikkhave, caraṇaṃ nāma cittaṃ citteneva cittitaṃ. Tenapi kho, bhikkhave, caraṇena cittena cittaññeva cittataraṃ.**“That picture was elaborated by the mind, but the mind is even more elaborate than that.*";
P_HTM[3847]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, abhikkhaṇaṃ sakaṃ cittaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**So you should regularly check your own mind:*";
P_HTM[3848]="*‘dīgharattamidaṃ cittaṃ saṅkiliṭṭhaṃ rāgena dosena mohenā’ti.**‘For a long time this mind has been corrupted by greed, hate, and delusion.’*";
P_HTM[3849]="*Cittasaṅkilesā, bhikkhave, sattā saṅkilissanti;**Sentient beings are corrupted because the mind is corrupted.*";
P_HTM[3850]="*cittavodānā sattā visujjhanti.**Sentient beings are purified because the mind is purified.*";
P_HTM[3851]="*Nāhaṃ, bhikkhave, aññaṃ ekanikāyampi samanupassāmi evaṃ cittaṃ yathayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā.**I don’t see see any other order of beings as elaborate as the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[3852]="*tepi kho, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā citteneva cittitā, tehipi kho, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatehi pāṇehi cittaññeva cittataraṃ.**The creatures in the animal realm were elaborated by the mind, but the mind is even more elaborate than that.*";
P_HTM[3853]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, abhikkhaṇaṃ sakaṃ cittaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**So you should regularly check your own mind:*";
P_HTM[3854]="*‘dīgharattamidaṃ cittaṃ saṅkiliṭṭhaṃ rāgena dosena mohenā’ti.**‘For a long time this mind has been corrupted by greed, hate, and delusion.’*";
P_HTM[3855]="*Cittasaṅkilesā, bhikkhave, sattā saṅkilissanti;**Sentient beings are corrupted because the mind is corrupted.*";
P_HTM[3856]="*cittavodānā sattā visujjhanti.**Sentient beings are purified because the mind is purified.*";
P_HTM[3857]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, rajako vā cittakārako vā rajanāya vā lākhāya vā haliddiyā vā nīliyā vā mañjiṭṭhāya vā suparimaṭṭhe phalake vā bhittiyā vā dussapaṭṭe vā itthirūpaṃ vā purisarūpaṃ vā abhinimmineyya sabbaṅgapaccaṅgiṃ;**Suppose an artist or painter had some dye, red lac, turmeric, indigo, or rose madder. And on a polished plank or a wall or a canvas they’d create the image of a woman or a man, complete in all its various parts.*";
P_HTM[3858]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano rūpaññeva abhinibbattento abhinibbatteti, vedanaññeva … pe … saññaññeva … saṅkhāreyeva … viññāṇaññeva abhinibbattento abhinibbatteti.**In the same way, when an uneducated ordinary person creates a future life, all they create is form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3859]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3860]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3861]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3862]="*“Vedanā …**“Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3863]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[3864]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[3865]="*viññāṇaṃ … pe …**consciousness permanent or impermanent?” …*";
P_HTM[3866]="*“tasmātiha, bhikkhave … pe …**“So you should truly see …*";
P_HTM[3867]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[3868]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[3869]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3870]="*9. Vāsijaṭasuttaṃ**The Adze*";
P_HTM[3871]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3872]="*“Jānato ahaṃ, bhikkhave, passato āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi, no ajānato no apassato.**“Mendicants, I say that the ending of defilements is for one who knows and sees, not for one who does not know or see.*";
P_HTM[3873]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, jānato kiṃ passato āsavānaṃ khayo hoti?**For one who knows and sees what?*";
P_HTM[3874]="*‘Iti rūpaṃ, iti rūpassa samudayo, iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo;**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[3875]="*iti vedanā …**Such is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3876]="*iti saññā …**Such is perception …*";
P_HTM[3877]="*iti saṅkhārā …**Such are choices …*";
P_HTM[3878]="*iti viññāṇaṃ, iti viññāṇassa samudayo, iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti—**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[3879]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.**The ending of the defilements is for one who knows and sees this.*";
P_HTM[3880]="*Bhāvanānuyogaṃ ananuyuttassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno viharato kiñcāpi evaṃ icchā uppajjeyya:**When a mendicant is not committed to development, they might wish:*";
P_HTM[3881]="*‘aho vata me anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimucceyyā’ti, atha khvassa neva anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuccati.**‘If only my mind was freed from the defilements by not grasping!’ Even so, their mind is not freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3882]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3883]="*‘Abhāvitattā’ tissa vacanīyaṃ.**It’s because they’re undeveloped.*";
P_HTM[3884]="*Kissa abhāvitattā?**Undeveloped in what?*";
P_HTM[3885]="*Abhāvitattā catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ, abhāvitattā catunnaṃ sammappadhānānaṃ, abhāvitattā catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ, abhāvitattā pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ, abhāvitattā pañcannaṃ balānaṃ, abhāvitattā sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ, abhāvitattā ariyassa aṭṭhaṅgikassa maggassa.**Undeveloped in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[3886]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, kukkuṭiyā aṇḍāni aṭṭha vā dasa vā dvādasa vā.**Suppose there was a chicken with eight or ten or twelve eggs.*";
P_HTM[3887]="*Tānassu kukkuṭiyā na sammā adhisayitāni, na sammā pariseditāni, na sammā paribhāvitāni.**But she had not properly sat on them to keep them warm and incubated.*";
P_HTM[3888]="*Kiñcāpi tassā kukkuṭiyā evaṃ icchā uppajjeyya:**That chicken might wish:*";
P_HTM[3889]="*‘aho vata me kukkuṭapotakā pādanakhasikhāya vā mukhatuṇḍakena vā aṇḍakosaṃ padāletvā sotthinā abhinibbhijjeyyun’ti,**‘If only my chicks could break out of the eggshell with their claws and beak and hatch safely!’*";
P_HTM[3890]="*atha kho abhabbāva te kukkuṭapotakā pādanakhasikhāya vā mukhatuṇḍakena vā aṇḍakosaṃ padāletvā sotthinā abhinibbhijjituṃ.**But they can’t break out and hatch safely.*";
P_HTM[3891]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3892]="*Tathā hi pana, bhikkhave, kukkuṭiyā aṇḍāni aṭṭha vā dasa vā dvādasa vā;**Because that chicken with eight or ten or twelve eggs*";
P_HTM[3893]="*tāni kukkuṭiyā na sammā adhisayitāni, na sammā pariseditāni, na sammā paribhāvitāni.**has not properly sat on them to keep them warm and incubated.*";
P_HTM[3894]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhāvanānuyogaṃ ananuyuttassa bhikkhuno viharato kiñcāpi evaṃ icchā uppajjeyya:**In the same way, when a mendicant is not committed to development, they might wish:*";
P_HTM[3895]="*‘aho vata me anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimucceyyā’ti, atha khvassa neva anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuccati.**‘If only my mind was freed from the defilements by not grasping!’ Even so, their mind is not freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3896]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3897]="*‘Abhāvitattā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**It’s because they’re undeveloped.*";
P_HTM[3898]="*Kissa abhāvitattā?**Undeveloped in what?*";
P_HTM[3899]="*Abhāvitattā catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ … pe … aṭṭhaṅgikassa maggassa.**Undeveloped in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[3900]="*Bhāvanānuyogaṃ anuyuttassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno viharato kiñcāpi na evaṃ icchā uppajjeyya:**When a mendicant is committed to development, they might not wish:*";
P_HTM[3901]="*‘aho vata me anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimucceyyā’ti, atha khvassa anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuccati.**‘If only my mind was freed from the defilements by not grasping!’ Even so, their mind is freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3902]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3903]="*‘Bhāvitattā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**It’s because they’re developed.*";
P_HTM[3904]="*Kissa bhāvitattā?**Developed in what?*";
P_HTM[3905]="*Bhāvitattā catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ, bhāvitattā catunnaṃ sammappadhānānaṃ, bhāvitattā catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ, bhāvitattā pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ, bhāvitattā pañcannaṃ balānaṃ, bhāvitattā sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ, bhāvitattā ariyassa aṭṭhaṅgikassa maggassa.**Developed in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[3906]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, kukkuṭiyā aṇḍāni aṭṭha vā dasa vā dvādasa vā.**Suppose there was a chicken with eight or ten or twelve eggs.*";
P_HTM[3907]="*Tānassu kukkuṭiyā sammā adhisayitāni, sammā pariseditāni, sammā paribhāvitāni.**And she properly sat on them to keep them warm and incubated.*";
P_HTM[3908]="*Kiñcāpi tassā kukkuṭiyā na evaṃ icchā uppajjeyya:**That chicken might not wish:*";
P_HTM[3909]="*‘aho vata me kukkuṭapotakā pādanakhasikhāya vā mukhatuṇḍakena vā aṇḍakosaṃ padāletvā sotthinā abhinibbhijjeyyun’ti,**‘If only my chicks could break out of the eggshell with their claws and beak and hatch safely!’*";
P_HTM[3910]="*atha kho bhabbāva te kukkuṭapotakā pādanakhasikhāya vā mukhatuṇḍakena vā aṇḍakosaṃ padāletvā sotthinā abhinibbhijjituṃ.**But still they can break out and hatch safely.*";
P_HTM[3911]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3912]="*Tathā hi pana, bhikkhave, kukkuṭiyā aṇḍāni aṭṭha vā dasa vā dvādasa vā;**Because that chicken with eight or ten or twelve eggs*";
P_HTM[3913]="*tānassu kukkuṭiyā sammā adhisayitāni, sammā pariseditāni, sammā paribhāvitāni.**properly sat on them to keep them warm and incubated.*";
P_HTM[3914]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhāvanānuyogaṃ anuyuttassa bhikkhuno viharato kiñcāpi na evaṃ icchā uppajjeyya:**In the same way, when a mendicant is committed to development, they might not wish:*";
P_HTM[3915]="*‘aho vata me anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimucceyyā’ti, atha khvassa anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuccati.**‘If only my mind was freed from the defilements by not grasping!’ Even so, their mind is freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3916]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3917]="*‘Bhāvitattā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**It’s because they’re developed.*";
P_HTM[3918]="*Kissa bhāvitattā?**Developed in what?*";
P_HTM[3919]="*Bhāvitattā catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ … pe … bhāvitattā ariyassa aṭṭhaṅgikassa maggassa.**Developed in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[3920]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, palagaṇḍassa vā palagaṇḍantevāsissa vā vāsijaṭe dissanteva aṅgulipadāni dissati aṅguṭṭhapadaṃ.**Suppose a carpenter or their apprentice sees the marks of his fingers and thumb on the handle of his adze.*";
P_HTM[3921]="*No ca khvassa evaṃ ñāṇaṃ hoti:**They don’t know*";
P_HTM[3922]="*‘ettakaṃ vata me ajja vāsijaṭassa khīṇaṃ, ettakaṃ hiyyo, ettakaṃ pare’ti.**how much of the handle was worn away today, how much yesterday, and how much previously.*";
P_HTM[3923]="*Atha khvassa khīṇe khīṇantveva ñāṇaṃ hoti.**They just know what has been worn away.*";
P_HTM[3924]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhāvanānuyogaṃ anuyuttassa bhikkhuno viharato kiñcāpi na evaṃ ñāṇaṃ hoti:**In the same way, when a mendicant is committed to development, they don’t know*";
P_HTM[3925]="*‘ettakaṃ vata me ajja āsavānaṃ khīṇaṃ, ettakaṃ hiyyo, ettakaṃ pare’ti, atha khvassa khīṇe khīṇantveva ñāṇaṃ hoti.**how much of the defilements were worn away today, how much yesterday, and how much previously. They just know what has been worn away.*";
P_HTM[3926]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, sāmuddikāya nāvāya vettabandhanabaddhāya vassamāsāni udake pariyādāya hemantikena thalaṃ ukkhittāya vātātapaparetāni vettabandhanāni. Tāni pāvusakena meghena abhippavuṭṭhāni appakasireneva paṭippassambhanti pūtikāni bhavanti;**Suppose there was a sea-faring ship bound together with ropes. For six months they deteriorated in the water. Then in the cold season it was hauled up on dry land, where the ropes were weathered by wind and sun. When the clouds soaked it with rain, the ropes would readily collapse and rot away.*";
P_HTM[3927]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhāvanānuyogaṃ anuyuttassa bhikkhuno viharato appakasireneva saṃyojanāni paṭippassambhanti pūtikāni bhavantī”ti.**In the same way, when a mendicant is committed to development their fetters readily collapse and rot away.”*";
P_HTM[3928]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3929]="*10. Aniccasaññāsuttaṃ**The Perception of Impermanence*";
P_HTM[3930]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3931]="*“Aniccasaññā, bhikkhave, bhāvitā bahulīkatā sabbaṃ kāmarāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ rūparāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ bhavarāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ avijjaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**“Mendicants, when the perception of impermanence is developed and cultivated it eliminates all desire for sensual pleasures, for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, and for rebirth in a future life. It eliminates all ignorance and eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3932]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, saradasamaye kassako mahānaṅgalena kasanto sabbāni mūlasantānakāni sampadālento kasati;**In the autumn, a farmer ploughing with a large plough shears through all the root networks.*";
P_HTM[3933]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā sabbaṃ kāmarāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ rūparāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ bhavarāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ avijjaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3934]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, pabbajalāyako pabbajaṃ lāyitvā agge gahetvā odhunāti niddhunāti nicchoṭeti;**A reed-cutter, having cut the reeds, grabs them at the top and shakes them down, shakes them about, and shakes them off.*";
P_HTM[3935]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā sabbaṃ kāmarāgaṃ pariyādiyati … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3936]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ambapiṇḍiyā vaṇṭacchinnāya yāni tattha ambāni vaṇṭapaṭibandhāni sabbāni tāni tadanvayāni bhavanti;**When the stalk of a bunch of mangoes is cut, all the mangoes attached to the stalk will follow along.*";
P_HTM[3937]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā bhāvitā … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3938]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, kūṭāgārassa yā kāci gopānasiyo sabbā tā kūṭaṅgamā kūṭaninnā kūṭasamosaraṇā, kūṭaṃ tāsaṃ aggamakkhāyati;**The rafters of a bungalow all lean to the peak, slope to the peak, and meet at the peak, so the peak is said to be the topmost of them all.*";
P_HTM[3939]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā bhāvitā … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3940]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ye keci mūlagandhā kāḷānusārigandho tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati;**Of all kinds of fragrant root, spikenard is said to be the best.*";
P_HTM[3941]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3942]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ye keci sāragandhā, lohitacandanaṃ tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati;**Of all kinds of fragrant heartwood, red sandalwood is said to be the best.*";
P_HTM[3943]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3944]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ye keci pupphagandhā, vassikaṃ tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati;**Of all kinds of fragrant flower, jasmine is said to be the best.*";
P_HTM[3945]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3946]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ye keci kuṭṭarājāno, sabbete rañño cakkavattissa anuyantā bhavanti, rājā tesaṃ cakkavatti aggamakkhāyati;**All lesser kings are vassals of a wheel-turning monarch, so the wheel-turning monarch is said to be the foremost of them all.*";
P_HTM[3947]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3948]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yā kāci tārakarūpānaṃ pabhā, sabbā tā candimappabhāya kalaṃ nāgghanti soḷasiṃ, candappabhā tāsaṃ aggamakkhāyati;**The radiance of all the stars is not worth a sixteenth part of the moon’s radiance, so the moon’s radiance is said to be the best of them all.*";
P_HTM[3949]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3950]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, saradasamaye viddhe vigatavalāhake deve ādicco nataṃ abbhussakkamāno, sabbaṃ ākāsagataṃ tamagataṃ abhivihacca bhāsate ca tapate ca virocate ca;**After the rainy season the sky is clear and cloudless. And when the sun rises, it dispels all the darkness from the sky as it shines and glows and radiates.*";
P_HTM[3951]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā sabbaṃ kāmarāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ rūparāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ bhavarāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ avijjaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati.**In the same way, when the perception of impermanence is developed and cultivated it eliminates all desire for sensual pleasures, for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, and for rebirth in a future life. It eliminates all ignorance and eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[3952]="*Kathaṃ bhāvitā ca, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā kathaṃ bahulīkatā sabbaṃ kāmarāgaṃ pariyādiyati … pe … sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanati?**And how is the perception of impermanence developed and cultivated so that … it eradicates all conceit ‘I am’?*";
P_HTM[3953]="*‘Iti rūpaṃ, iti rūpassa samudayo, iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo;**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[3954]="*iti vedanā …**Such is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3955]="*iti saññā …**Such is perception …*";
P_HTM[3956]="*iti saṅkhārā …**Such are choices …*";
P_HTM[3957]="*iti viññāṇaṃ, iti viññāṇassa samudayo, iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti—**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[3958]="*evaṃ bhāvitā kho, bhikkhave, aniccasaññā evaṃ bahulīkatā sabbaṃ kāmarāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ rūparāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ bhavarāgaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ avijjaṃ pariyādiyati, sabbaṃ asmimānaṃ samūhanatī”ti.**That’s how the perception of impermanence is developed and cultivated so that it eliminates all desire for sensual pleasures, for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, and for rebirth in a future life. That’s how it eliminates all ignorance and eradicates all conceit ‘I am’.”*";
P_HTM[3959]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3960]="*Pupphavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[3961]="*Nadī pupphañca pheṇañca,* **";
P_HTM[3962]="*gomayañca nakhāsikhaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3963]="*Suddhikaṃ dve ca gaddulā,* **";
P_HTM[3964]="*vāsījaṭaṃ aniccatāti.* **";
P_HTM[3965]="*Majjhimapaṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[3966]="*Upayo arahanto ca,* **";
P_HTM[3967]="*khajjanī therasavhayaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3968]="*Pupphavaggena paṇṇāsa,* **";
P_HTM[3969]="*dutiyo tena vuccatīti.* **";
P_HTM[3970]="*sn/sn22.103.xhtml==11. Antavagga==11. Antavaggo**Sides*";
P_HTM[3971]="*1. Antasuttaṃ**Sides*";
P_HTM[3972]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3973]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, antā.**“Mendicants, there are these four sides.*";
P_HTM[3974]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3975]="*Sakkāyanto, sakkāyasamudayanto, sakkāyanirodhanto, sakkāyanirodhagāminippaṭipadanto.**The side of identity, the side of the origin of identity, the side of the cessation of identity, and the side of the practice that leads to the cessation of identity.*";
P_HTM[3976]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyanto?**And what is the side of identity?*";
P_HTM[3977]="*Pañcupādānakkhandhātissa vacanīyaṃ.**It should be said: the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[3978]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[3979]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho—**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3980]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sakkāyanto.**This is called the side of identity.*";
P_HTM[3981]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyasamudayanto?**And what is the side of the origin of identity?*";
P_HTM[3982]="*Yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobhavikā nandirāgasahagatā tatratatrābhinandinī, seyyathidaṃ—**It’s the craving that leads to future lives, mixed up with relishing and greed, taking pleasure in various different realms. That is,*";
P_HTM[3983]="*kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā.**craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[3984]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sakkāyasamudayanto.**This is called the side of the origin of identity.*";
P_HTM[3985]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodhanto?**And what is the side of the cessation of identity?*";
P_HTM[3986]="*Yo tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodho cāgo paṭinissaggo mutti anālayo—**It’s the fading away and cessation of that very same craving with nothing left over; giving it away, letting it go, releasing it, and not adhering to it.*";
P_HTM[3987]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodhanto.**This is called the side of the cessation of identity.*";
P_HTM[3988]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodhagāminippaṭipadanto?**And what is the side of the practice that leads to the cessation of identity?*";
P_HTM[3989]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[3990]="*Seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[3991]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodhagāminippaṭipadanto.**This is called the side of the practice that leads to the cessation of identity.*";
P_HTM[3992]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro antā”ti.**These are the four sides.”*";
P_HTM[3993]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3994]="*2. Dukkhasuttaṃ**Suffering*";
P_HTM[3995]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3996]="*“Dukkhañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi dukkhasamudayañca dukkhanirodhañca dukkhanirodhagāminiñca paṭipadaṃ.**“Mendicants, I will teach you suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[3997]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[3998]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ?**And what is suffering?*";
P_HTM[3999]="*Pañcupādānakkhandhātissa vacanīyaṃ.**It should be said: the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[4000]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4001]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4002]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ.**This is called suffering.*";
P_HTM[4003]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, dukkhasamudayo?**And what is the origin of suffering?*";
P_HTM[4004]="*Yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobhavikā … pe … vibhavataṇhā—**It’s the craving that leads to future lives, mixed up with relishing and greed, looking for enjoyment anywhere it can. That is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[4005]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhasamudayo.**This is called the origin of suffering.*";
P_HTM[4006]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodho?**And what is the cessation of suffering?*";
P_HTM[4007]="*Yo tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodho cāgo paṭinissaggo mutti anālayo—**It’s the fading away and cessation of that very same craving with nothing left over; giving it away, letting it go, releasing it, and not adhering to it.*";
P_HTM[4008]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodho.**This is called the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[4009]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**And what is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering?*";
P_HTM[4010]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[4011]="*Seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[4012]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā”ti.**This is called the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[4013]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4014]="*3. Sakkāyasuttaṃ**Identity*";
P_HTM[4015]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4016]="*“Sakkāyañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi sakkāyasamudayañca sakkāyanirodhañca sakkāyanirodhagāminiñca paṭipadaṃ.**“Mendicants, I will teach you identity, the origin of identity, the cessation of identity, and the practice that leads to the cessation of identity.*";
P_HTM[4017]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[4018]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyo?**And what is identity?*";
P_HTM[4019]="*Pañcupādānakkhandhātissa vacanīyaṃ.**It should be said: the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[4020]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4021]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4022]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sakkāyo.**This is called identity.*";
P_HTM[4023]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyasamudayo?**And what is the origin of identity?*";
P_HTM[4024]="*Yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobhavikā … pe …**It’s the craving that leads to future lives, mixed up with relishing and greed, looking for enjoyment anywhere it can. That is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[4025]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sakkāyasamudayo.**This is called the origin of identity.*";
P_HTM[4026]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodho?**And what is the cessation of identity?*";
P_HTM[4027]="*Yo tassāyeva taṇhāya … pe …**It’s the fading away and cessation of that very same craving with nothing left over; giving it away, letting it go, releasing it, and not clinging to it.*";
P_HTM[4028]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodho.**This is called the cessation of identity.*";
P_HTM[4029]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**And what is the practice that leads to the cessation of identity?*";
P_HTM[4030]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[4031]="*Seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[4032]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sakkāyanirodhagāminī paṭipadā”ti.**This is called the practice that leads to the cessation of identity.”*";
P_HTM[4033]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4034]="*4. Pariññeyyasuttaṃ**Should Be Completely Understood*";
P_HTM[4035]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4036]="*“Pariññeyye ca, bhikkhave, dhamme desessāmi pariññañca pariññātāviñca puggalaṃ.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the things that should be completely understood, complete understanding, and the person who has completely understood.*";
P_HTM[4037]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[4038]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, pariññeyyā dhammā?**And what things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[4039]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, pariññeyyo dhammo.**Form,*";
P_HTM[4040]="*Vedanā … pe …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[4041]="*saññā …**perception,*";
P_HTM[4042]="*saṅkhārā …**choices,*";
P_HTM[4043]="*viññāṇaṃ pariññeyyo dhammo.**and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4044]="*Ime vuccanti, bhikkhave, pariññeyyā dhammā.**These are called the things that should be completely understood.*";
P_HTM[4045]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, pariññā?**And what is complete understanding?*";
P_HTM[4046]="*Rāgakkhayo, dosakkhayo, mohakkhayo—**The ending of greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[4047]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, pariññā.**This is called complete understanding.*";
P_HTM[4048]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, pariññātāvī puggalo?**And what is the person who has completely understood?*";
P_HTM[4049]="*Arahātissa vacanīyaṃ.**It should be said: a perfected one,*";
P_HTM[4050]="*Yvāyaṃ āyasmā evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto—**the venerable of such and such name and clan.*";
P_HTM[4051]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, pariññātāvī puggalo”ti.**This is called the person who has completely understood.”*";
P_HTM[4052]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4053]="*5. Samaṇasuttaṃ**Ascetics (1st)*";
P_HTM[4054]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4055]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, upādānakkhandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[4056]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4057]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4058]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ gratification, drawback, and escape …*";
P_HTM[4059]="*pajānanti, sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**There are ascetics and brahmins who do truly understand …”*";
P_HTM[4060]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4061]="*6. Dutiyasamaṇasuttaṃ**Ascetics (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4062]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4063]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, upādānakkhandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[4064]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4065]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4066]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape … Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin …*";
P_HTM[4067]="*pajānanti, sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**There are ascetics and brahmins who do truly understand … Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[4068]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4069]="*7. Sotāpannasuttaṃ**A Stream*";
P_HTM[4070]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4071]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, upādānakkhandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[4072]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4073]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4074]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A noble disciple comes to truly understand these five grasping aggregates’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4075]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyano”ti.**Such a noble disciple is called a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[4076]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4077]="*8. Arahantasuttaṃ**A Perfected One*";
P_HTM[4078]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4079]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, upādānakkhandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[4080]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4081]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4082]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imesaṃ pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto hoti.**A mendicant comes to be freed by not grasping after truly understanding these five grasping aggregates’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4083]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto”ti.**Such a mendicant is called a perfected one, with defilements ended, who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own true goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment.”*";
P_HTM[4084]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4085]="*9. Chandappahānasuttaṃ**Giving Up Desire*";
P_HTM[4086]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4087]="*“Rūpe, bhikkhave, yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā, taṃ pajahatha.**“Mendicants, you should give up any desire, greed, relishing, and craving for form.*";
P_HTM[4088]="*Evaṃ taṃ rūpaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati ucchinnamūlaṃ tālāvatthukataṃ anabhāvaṃkataṃ āyatiṃ anuppādadhammaṃ.**Thus that form will be given up, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated, and unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[4089]="*Vedanāya … pe …**You should give up any desire, greed, relishing, and craving for feeling …*";
P_HTM[4090]="*saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4091]="*saṅkhāresu …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4092]="*viññāṇe yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā, taṃ pajahatha.**consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4093]="*Evaṃ taṃ viññāṇaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati ucchinnamūlaṃ tālāvatthukataṃ anabhāvaṃkataṃ āyatiṃ anuppādadhamman”ti.**Thus that consciousness will be given up, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated, and unable to arise in the future.”*";
P_HTM[4094]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4095]="*10. Dutiyachandappahānasuttaṃ**Giving Up Desire (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4096]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4097]="*“Rūpe, bhikkhave, yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā ye upayupādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā, te pajahatha.**“Mendicants, you should give up any desire, greed, relishing, and craving for form; and any attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[4098]="*Evaṃ taṃ rūpaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati ucchinnamūlaṃ … pe …**Thus that form will be given up, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated, and unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[4099]="*vedanāya …**You should give up any desire, greed, relishing, and craving for feeling …*";
P_HTM[4100]="*saññāya …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4101]="*saṅkhāresu yo chando … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4102]="*evaṃ te saṅkhārā pahīnā bhavissanti ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṃkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[4103]="*Viññāṇe yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā ye upayupādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā, te pajahatha.**consciousness; and any attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[4104]="*Evaṃ taṃ viññāṇaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati ucchinnamūlaṃ tālāvatthukataṃ anabhāvaṃkataṃ āyatiṃ anuppādadhamman”ti.**Thus that consciousness will be given up, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated, and unable to arise in the future.”*";
P_HTM[4105]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4106]="*Antavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[4107]="*Anto dukkhañca sakkāyo,* **";
P_HTM[4108]="*pariññeyyā samaṇā duve;* **";
P_HTM[4109]="*Sotāpanno arahā ca,* **";
P_HTM[4110]="*duve ca chandappahānāti.* **";
P_HTM[4111]="*sn/sn22.113.xhtml==12. Dhammakathikavagga==12. Dhammakathikavaggo**A Dhamma speaker*";
P_HTM[4112]="*1. Avijjāsuttaṃ**Ignorance*";
P_HTM[4113]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4114]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe …**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha*";
P_HTM[4115]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him:*";
P_HTM[4116]="*“‘avijjā, avijjā’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘ignorance’.*";
P_HTM[4117]="*Katamā nu kho, bhante, avijjā;**What is ignorance?*";
P_HTM[4118]="*kittāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is an ignorant person defined?”*";
P_HTM[4119]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, assutavā puthujjano rūpaṃ nappajānāti, rūpasamudayaṃ nappajānāti, rūpanirodhaṃ nappajānāti, rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānāti;**“Mendicant, it’s when an uneducated ordinary person doesn’t understand form, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4120]="*vedanaṃ nappajānāti …**They don’t understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[4121]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4122]="*saṅkhāre nappajānāti … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4123]="*viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4124]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, avijjā;**This is called ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4125]="*ettāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti.**And this is how an ignorant person is defined.”*";
P_HTM[4126]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4127]="*2. Vijjāsuttaṃ**Knowledge*";
P_HTM[4128]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4129]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, that mendicant said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[4130]="*“‘vijjā, vijjā’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘knowledge’.*";
P_HTM[4131]="*Katamā nu kho, bhante, vijjā;**What is knowledge?*";
P_HTM[4132]="*kittāvatā ca vijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is a knowledgeable person defined?”*";
P_HTM[4133]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpaṃ pajānāti, rūpasamudayaṃ … rūpanirodhaṃ … rūpanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānāti.**“Mendicant, it’s when an educated noble disciple understands form, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4134]="*Vedanaṃ …**They understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[4135]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4136]="*saṅkhāre pajānāti … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4137]="*viññāṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4138]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, vijjā;**This is called knowledge.*";
P_HTM[4139]="*ettāvatā ca vijjāgato hotī”ti.**And this is how a knowledgeable person is defined.”*";
P_HTM[4140]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4141]="*3. Dhammakathikasuttaṃ**A Dhamma speaker*";
P_HTM[4142]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4143]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, that mendicant said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[4144]="*“‘dhammakathiko, dhammakathiko’ti, bhante, vuccati;**“Sir, they speak of a ‘Dhamma speaker’.*";
P_HTM[4145]="*kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, dhammakathiko hotī”ti?**How is a Dhamma speaker defined?”*";
P_HTM[4146]="*“Rūpassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya dhammaṃ deseti ‘dhammakathiko bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**“Mendicant, if a mendicant teaches Dhamma for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who speaks on Dhamma’.*";
P_HTM[4147]="*Rūpassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti, ‘dhammānudhammappaṭipanno bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**If they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who practices in line with the teaching’.*";
P_HTM[4148]="*Rūpassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādāvimutto hoti, ‘diṭṭhadhammanibbānappatto bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**If they’re freed by not grasping by disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who has attained extinguishment in this very life’.*";
P_HTM[4149]="*Vedanāya ce, bhikkhu … pe …**If a mendicant teaches Dhamma for disillusionment with feeling …*";
P_HTM[4150]="*saññāya ce, bhikkhu …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4151]="*saṅkhārānañce, bhikkhu …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4152]="*viññāṇassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya dhammaṃ deseti, ‘dhammakathiko bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**consciousness, for its fading away and cessation, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who speaks on Dhamma’.*";
P_HTM[4153]="*Viññāṇassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti, ‘dhammānudhammappaṭipanno bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**If they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who practices in line with the teaching’.*";
P_HTM[4154]="*Viññāṇassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādāvimutto hoti, ‘diṭṭhadhammanibbānappatto bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti.**If they’re freed by not grasping by disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who has attained extinguishment in this very life’.”*";
P_HTM[4155]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4156]="*4. Dutiyadhammakathikasuttaṃ**A Dhamma speaker (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4157]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4158]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, that mendicant said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[4159]="*“‘dhammakathiko, dhammakathiko’ti, bhante, vuccati;**“Sir, they speak of a ‘Dhamma speaker’.*";
P_HTM[4160]="*kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, dhammakathiko hoti;**How is a Dhamma speaker defined?*";
P_HTM[4161]="*kittāvatā dhammānudhammappaṭipanno hoti, kittāvatā diṭṭhadhammanibbānappatto hotī”ti?**How is a mendicant who practices in line with the teaching defined? And how is a mendicant who has attained extinguishment in this very life defined?”*";
P_HTM[4162]="*“Rūpassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya dhammaṃ deseti, ‘dhammakathiko bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**“Mendicant, if a mendicant teaches Dhamma for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who speaks on Dhamma’.*";
P_HTM[4163]="*Rūpassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti, ‘dhammānudhammappaṭipanno bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**If they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who practices in line with the teaching’.*";
P_HTM[4164]="*Rūpassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādāvimutto hoti, ‘diṭṭhadhammanibbānappatto bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**If they’re freed by not grasping by disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding form, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who has attained extinguishment in this very life’.*";
P_HTM[4165]="*Vedanāya ce, bhikkhu … pe …**If a mendicant teaches Dhamma for disillusionment with feeling …*";
P_HTM[4166]="*saññāya ce, bhikkhu …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4167]="*saṅkhārānañce, bhikkhu …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4168]="*viññāṇassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya dhammaṃ deseti, ‘dhammakathiko bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**consciousness, for its fading away and cessation, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who speaks on Dhamma’.*";
P_HTM[4169]="*Viññāṇassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti, ‘dhammānudhammappaṭipanno bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**If they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who practices in line with the teaching’.*";
P_HTM[4170]="*Viññāṇassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādāvimutto hoti, ‘diṭṭhadhammanibbānappatto bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti.**If they’re freed by not grasping by disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding consciousness, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who has attained extinguishment in this very life’.”*";
P_HTM[4171]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4172]="*5. Bandhanasuttaṃ**Shackles*";
P_HTM[4173]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4174]="*“Idha, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī … pe … sappurisadhamme avinīto**“Mendicants, take an uneducated ordinary person who has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[4175]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[4176]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano rūpabandhanabaddho santarabāhirabandhanabaddho atīradassī apāradassī, baddho jīyati baddho mīyati baddho asmā lokā paraṃ lokaṃ gacchati.**They’re called an uneducated ordinary person who is bound to form, inside and out. They see neither the near shore nor the far shore. They’re born in bonds and die in bonds, and in bonds they go from this world to the next.*";
P_HTM[4177]="*Vedanaṃ attato samanupassati … pe … vedanāya vā attānaṃ.**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[4178]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano vedanābandhanabaddho santarabāhirabandhanabaddho atīradassī apāradassī, baddho jīyati baddho mīyati baddho asmā lokā paraṃ lokaṃ gacchati.* **";
P_HTM[4179]="*Saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4180]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4181]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati … pe …**consciousness as self.*";
P_HTM[4182]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano viññāṇabandhanabaddho santarabāhirabandhanabaddho atīradassī apāradassī, baddho jīyati baddho mīyati baddho asmā lokā paraṃ lokaṃ gacchati.**They’re called an uneducated ordinary person who is bound to consciousness, inside and out. They see neither the near shore nor the far shore. They’re born in bonds and die in bonds, and in bonds they go from this world to the next.*";
P_HTM[4183]="*Sutavā ca kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī … pe … sappurisadhamme suvinīto**An educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[4184]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ; na attani vā rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[4185]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako na rūpabandhanabaddho, na santarabāhirabandhanabaddho, tīradassī, pāradassī; ‘parimutto so dukkhasmā’ti vadāmi.**They’re called an educated noble disciple who is not bound to form, inside or out. They see the near shore and the far shore. They’re exempt from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[4186]="*Na vedanaṃ attato … pe …**They don’t regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[4187]="*na saññaṃ attato … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4188]="*na saṅkhāre attato … pe …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4189]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati … pe …**consciousness as self.*";
P_HTM[4190]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako na viññāṇabandhanabaddho, na santarabāhirabandhanabaddho, tīradassī, pāradassī, ‘parimutto so dukkhasmā’ti vadāmī”ti.**They’re called an educated noble disciple who is not bound to consciousness, inside or out. They see the near shore and the far shore. They’re exempt from suffering, I say.”*";
P_HTM[4191]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4192]="*6. Paripucchitasuttaṃ**Questioning*";
P_HTM[4193]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4194]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[4195]="*rūpaṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassathā”ti?**Do you regard form like this: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[4196]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[4197]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhave.**“Good, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[4198]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**Form should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[4199]="*Vedanaṃ …**Do you regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[4200]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4201]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4202]="*viññāṇaṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassathā”ti?**consciousness like this: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[4203]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[4204]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhave.**“Good, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[4205]="*Viññāṇaṃ, bhikkhave, ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ … pe …**Consciousness should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[4206]="*evaṃ passaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[4207]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[4208]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4209]="*7. Dutiyaparipucchitasuttaṃ**Questioning (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4210]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4211]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[4212]="*rūpaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassathā”ti?**Do you regard form like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’?”*";
P_HTM[4213]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[4214]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhave.**“Good, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[4215]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**Form should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[4216]="*Vedanaṃ …**Do you regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[4217]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4218]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4219]="*viññāṇaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassathā”ti?**consciousness like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’?”*";
P_HTM[4220]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[4221]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhave.**“Good, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[4222]="*Viññāṇaṃ, bhikkhave, ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ …**Consciousness should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[4223]="*evaṃ … pe …**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[4224]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[4225]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4226]="*8. Saṃyojaniyasuttaṃ**Things Prone To Being Fettered*";
P_HTM[4227]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4228]="*“Saṃyojaniye ca, bhikkhave, dhamme desessāmi saṃyojanañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the things that are prone to being fettered, and the fetter.*";
P_HTM[4229]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[4230]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, saṃyojaniyā dhammā, katamaṃ saṃyojanaṃ?**What are the things that are prone to being fettered? And what is the fetter?*";
P_HTM[4231]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, saṃyojaniyo dhammo;**Form is something that’s prone to being fettered.*";
P_HTM[4232]="*yo tattha chandarāgo, taṃ tattha saṃyojanaṃ.**The desire and greed for it is the fetter.*";
P_HTM[4233]="*Vedanā … pe …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[4234]="*saññā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[4235]="*saṅkhārā …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[4236]="*viññāṇaṃ saṃyojaniyo dhammo;**Consciousness is something that’s prone to being fettered.*";
P_HTM[4237]="*yo tattha chandarāgo, taṃ tattha saṃyojanaṃ.**The desire and greed for it is the fetter.*";
P_HTM[4238]="*Ime vuccanti, bhikkhave, saṃyojaniyā dhammā, idaṃ saṃyojanan”ti.**These are called the things that are prone to being fettered, and this is the fetter.”*";
P_HTM[4239]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4240]="*9. Upādāniyasuttaṃ**Things Prone To Being Grasped*";
P_HTM[4241]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4242]="*“Upādāniye ca, bhikkhave, dhamme desessāmi upādānañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the things that are prone to being grasped, and the grasping.*";
P_HTM[4243]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[4244]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, upādāniyā dhammā, katamaṃ upādānaṃ?**What are the things that are prone to being grasped? And what is the grasping?*";
P_HTM[4245]="*Rūpaṃ, bhikkhave, upādāniyo dhammo,**Form is something that’s prone to being grasped.*";
P_HTM[4246]="*yo tattha chandarāgo, taṃ tattha upādānaṃ.**The desire and greed for it is the grasping.*";
P_HTM[4247]="*Vedanā … pe …**Feeling …*";
P_HTM[4248]="*saññā …**Perception …*";
P_HTM[4249]="*saṅkhārā …**Choices …*";
P_HTM[4250]="*viññāṇaṃ upādāniyo dhammo;**Consciousness is something that’s prone to being grasped.*";
P_HTM[4251]="*yo tattha chandarāgo, taṃ tattha upādānaṃ.**The desire and greed for it is the grasping.*";
P_HTM[4252]="*Ime vuccanti, bhikkhave, upādāniyā dhammā, idaṃ upādānan”ti.**These are called the things that are prone to being grasped, and this is the grasping.”*";
P_HTM[4253]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4254]="*10. Sīlavantasuttaṃ**An Ethical Mendicant*";
P_HTM[4255]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahākoṭṭhiko bārāṇasiyaṃ viharanti isipatane migadāye.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta and Venerable Mahākoṭṭhita were staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana.*";
P_HTM[4256]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahākoṭṭhiko sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami … pe … etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Mahākoṭṭhita came out of retreat, went to Venerable Sāriputta, and said:*";
P_HTM[4257]="*“sīlavatāvuso, sāriputta, bhikkhunā katame dhammā yoniso manasikātabbā”ti?**“Reverend Sāriputta, what things should an ethical mendicant properly attend to?”*";
P_HTM[4258]="*“Sīlavatāvuso, koṭṭhika, bhikkhunā pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato dukkhato rogato gaṇḍato sallato aghato ābādhato parato palokato suññato anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**“Reverend Koṭṭhita, an ethical mendicant should properly attend to the five grasping aggregates as impermanent, as suffering, as diseased, as an abscess, as a dart, as misery, as an affliction, as alien, as falling apart, as empty, as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4259]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4260]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4261]="*Sīlavatāvuso, koṭṭhika, bhikkhunā ime pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato dukkhato rogato gaṇḍato sallato aghato ābādhato parato palokato suññato anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**An ethical mendicant should properly attend to these five grasping aggregates as impermanent, as suffering, as diseased, as an abscess, as a dart, as misery, as an affliction, as alien, as falling apart, as empty, as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4262]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati yaṃ sīlavā bhikkhu ime pañcupādānakkhandhe aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi karonto sotāpattiphalaṃ sacchikareyyā”ti.**It’s possible that an ethical mendicant who regards the five grasping aggregates in this way will realize the fruit of stream-entry.”*";
P_HTM[4263]="*“Sotāpannena panāvuso sāriputta, bhikkhunā katame dhammā yoniso manasi kātabbā”ti?**“But Reverend Sāriputta, what things should a mendicant stream-enterer properly attend to?”*";
P_HTM[4264]="*“Sotāpannenapi kho, āvuso koṭṭhika, bhikkhunā ime pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**“A mendicant stream-enterer should properly attend to these five grasping aggregates as impermanent … as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4265]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati yaṃ sotāpanno bhikkhu ime pañcupādānakkhandhe aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi karonto sakadāgāmiphalaṃ sacchikareyyā”ti.**It’s possible that a mendicant stream-enterer who regards the five grasping aggregates in this way will realize the fruit of once-return.”*";
P_HTM[4266]="*“Sakadāgāminā panāvuso sāriputta, bhikkhunā katame dhammā yoniso manasi kātabbā”ti?**“But Reverend Sāriputta, what things should a mendicant once-returner properly attend to?”*";
P_HTM[4267]="*“Sakadāgāmināpi kho, āvuso koṭṭhika, bhikkhunā ime pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**“A mendicant once-returner should properly attend to these five grasping aggregates as impermanent … as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4268]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati yaṃ sakadāgāmī bhikkhu ime pañcupādānakkhandhe aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi karonto anāgāmiphalaṃ sacchikareyyā”ti.**It’s possible that a mendicant once-returner who regards the five grasping aggregates in this way will realize the fruit of non-return.”*";
P_HTM[4269]="*“Anāgāminā panāvuso sāriputta, bhikkhunā katame dhammā yoniso manasi kātabbā”ti?**“But Reverend Sāriputta, what things should a mendicant non-returner properly attend to?”*";
P_HTM[4270]="*“Anāgāmināpi kho, āvuso koṭṭhika, bhikkhunā ime pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**“A mendicant non-returner should properly attend to these five grasping aggregates as impermanent … as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4271]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati yaṃ anāgāmī bhikkhu ime pañcupādānakkhandhe aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi karonto arahattaṃ sacchikareyyā”ti.**It’s possible that a mendicant non-returner who regards the five grasping aggregates in this way will realize perfection.”*";
P_HTM[4272]="*“Arahatā panāvuso sāriputta, katame dhammā yoniso manasi kātabbā”ti?**“But Reverend Sāriputta, what things should a perfected one properly attend to?”*";
P_HTM[4273]="*“Arahatāpi kho, āvuso koṭṭhika, ime pañcupādānakkhandhe aniccato dukkhato rogato gaṇḍato sallato aghato ābādhato parato palokato suññato anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**“Reverend Koṭṭhita, a perfected one should properly attend to the five grasping aggregates as impermanent, as suffering, as diseased, as an abscess, as a dart, as misery, as an affliction, as alien, as falling apart, as empty, as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4274]="*Natthi, khvāvuso, arahato uttari karaṇīyaṃ katassa vā paticayo;**A perfected one has nothing more to do, and nothing that needs improvement.*";
P_HTM[4275]="*api ca ime dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya ceva saṃvattanti satisampajaññāya cā”ti.**Still, these things, when developed and cultivated, lead to blissful meditation in the present life, and also to mindfulness and situational awareness.”*";
P_HTM[4276]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4277]="*11. Sutavantasuttaṃ**Educated*";
P_HTM[4278]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahākoṭṭhiko bārāṇasiyaṃ viharanti isipatane migadāye.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta and Venerable Mahākoṭṭhita were staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana.*";
P_HTM[4279]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahākoṭṭhiko sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe … etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Mahākoṭṭhita came out of retreat, went to Venerable Sāriputta, bowed, sat down to one side, and said:*";
P_HTM[4280]="*“Sutavatāvuso sāriputta, bhikkhunā katame dhammā yoniso manasi kātabbā”ti?**“Reverend Sāriputta, what things should an educated mendicant properly attend to?”*";
P_HTM[4281]="*“Sutavatāvuso koṭṭhika, bhikkhunā pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**“An educated mendicant should properly attend to these five grasping aggregates as impermanent … as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4282]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4283]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is, the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4284]="*Sutavatāvuso koṭṭhika, bhikkhunā ime pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**An educated mendicant should properly attend to these five grasping aggregates as impermanent … as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4285]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati—yaṃ sutavā bhikkhu ime pañcupādānakkhandhe aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi karonto sotāpattiphalaṃ sacchikareyyā”ti.**It’s possible that an educated mendicant who regards the five grasping aggregates in this way will realize the fruit of stream-entry.”*";
P_HTM[4286]="*“Sotāpannena panāvuso sāriputta, bhikkhunā katame dhammā yoniso manasi kātabbā”ti?**“But Reverend Sāriputta, what things should a mendicant stream-enterer properly attend to?”*";
P_HTM[4287]="*“Sotāpannenapi kho āvuso koṭṭhika, bhikkhunā ime pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**“A mendicant stream-enterer should properly attend to these five grasping aggregates as impermanent … as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4288]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati—yaṃ sotāpanno bhikkhu ime pañcupādānakkhandhe aniccato … pe … anattato yoniso manasi karonto sakadāgāmiphalaṃ … pe …**It’s possible that a mendicant stream-enterer who regards the five grasping aggregates in this way will realize the fruit of once-return.” …*";
P_HTM[4289]="*anāgāmiphalaṃ … pe …**“It’s possible that a mendicant once-returner who regards the five grasping aggregates in this way will realize the fruit of non-return.” …*";
P_HTM[4290]="*arahattaphalaṃ sacchikareyyā”ti.**“It’s possible that a mendicant non-returner who regards the five grasping aggregates in this way will realize the fruit of perfection.” …*";
P_HTM[4291]="*“Arahatā panāvuso sāriputta, katame dhammā yoniso manasi kātabbā”ti?**“But Reverend Sāriputta, what things should a perfected one properly attend to?”*";
P_HTM[4292]="*“Arahatāpi khvāvuso koṭṭhika, ime pañcupādānakkhandhā aniccato dukkhato rogato gaṇḍato sallato aghato ābādhato parato palokato suññato anattato yoniso manasi kātabbā.**“Reverend Koṭṭhita, a perfected one should properly attend to the five grasping aggregates as impermanent, as suffering, as diseased, as an abscess, as a dart, as misery, as an affliction, as alien, as falling apart, as empty, as not-self.*";
P_HTM[4293]="*Natthi, khvāvuso, arahato uttari karaṇīyaṃ, katassa vā paticayo;**A perfected one has nothing more to do, and nothing that needs improvement.*";
P_HTM[4294]="*api ca kho ime dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya ceva saṃvattanti satisampajaññāya cā”ti.**Still, these things, when developed and cultivated, lead to blissful meditation in the present life, and also to mindfulness and situational awareness.”*";
P_HTM[4295]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4296]="*12. Kappasuttaṃ**With Kappa*";
P_HTM[4297]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4298]="*Atha kho āyasmā kappo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā kappo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Kappa went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[4299]="*“kathaṃ nu kho, bhante, jānato kathaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayā na hontī”ti?**“Sir, how does one know and see so that there’s no ego, possessiveness, or underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli?”*";
P_HTM[4300]="*“Yaṃ kiñci, kappa, rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ rūpaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passati.**“Kappa, one truly sees any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[4301]="*Yā kāci vedanā … pe …**One truly sees any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[4302]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4303]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4304]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passati.**consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[4305]="*Evaṃ kho, kappa, jānato evaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayā na hontī”ti.**That’s how to know and see so that there’s no ego, possessiveness, or underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli.”*";
P_HTM[4306]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4307]="*13. Dutiyakappasuttaṃ**With Kappa (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4308]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4309]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā kappo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, Venerable Kappa said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[4310]="*“kathaṃ nu kho, bhante, jānato kathaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānāpagataṃ mānasaṃ hoti vidhā samatikkantaṃ santaṃ suvimuttan”ti?**“Sir, how does one know and see so that the mind is rid of ego, possessiveness, and conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli; and going beyond discrimination, it’s peaceful and well freed?”*";
P_HTM[4311]="*“Yaṃ kiñci, kappa, rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ … pe … sabbaṃ rūpaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā anupādāvimutto hoti.**“Kappa, one is freed by not grasping having truly seen any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[4312]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**One is freed by not grasping having truly seen any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[4313]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4314]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4315]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā, sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā anupādāvimutto hoti.**consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[4316]="*Evaṃ kho, kappa, jānato evaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānāpagataṃ mānasaṃ hoti vidhā samatikkantaṃ santaṃ suvimuttan”ti.**That’s how to know and see so that the mind is rid of ego, possessiveness, and conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli; and going beyond discrimination, it’s peaceful and well freed.”*";
P_HTM[4317]="*Terasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4318]="*Dhammakathikavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[4319]="*Avijjā vijjā dve kathikā,* **";
P_HTM[4320]="*Bandhanā paripucchitā duve;* **";
P_HTM[4321]="*Saṃyojanaṃ upādānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[4322]="*Sīlaṃ sutavā dve ca kappenāti.* **";
P_HTM[4323]="*sn/sn22.126.xhtml==13. Avijjāvagga==13. Avijjāvaggo**Ignorance*";
P_HTM[4324]="*1. Samudayadhammasuttaṃ**Liable To Originate*";
P_HTM[4325]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4326]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[4327]="*“‘avijjā, avijjā’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘ignorance’.*";
P_HTM[4328]="*Katamā nu kho, bhante, avijjā;**What is ignorance?*";
P_HTM[4329]="*kittāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is an ignorant person defined?”*";
P_HTM[4330]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, assutavā puthujjano samudayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘samudayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**“Mendicant, it’s when an uneducated ordinary person doesn’t truly understand form, which is liable to originate, as form which is liable to originate.*";
P_HTM[4331]="*vayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘vayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**They don’t truly understand form, which is liable to vanish, as form which is liable to vanish.*";
P_HTM[4332]="*samudayavayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand form, which is liable to originate and vanish, as form which is liable to originate and vanish.*";
P_HTM[4333]="*Samudayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ ‘samudayadhammā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[4334]="*vayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ ‘vayadhammā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;* **";
P_HTM[4335]="*samudayavayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[4336]="*Samudayadhammaṃ saññaṃ … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4337]="*samudayadhamme saṅkhāre ‘samudayadhammā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**choices …*";
P_HTM[4338]="*vayadhamme saṅkhāre ‘vayadhammā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;* **";
P_HTM[4339]="*samudayavayadhamme saṅkhāre ‘samudayavayadhammā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[4340]="*Samudayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘samudayadhammaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**consciousness, which is liable to originate, as consciousness which is liable to originate.*";
P_HTM[4341]="*vayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘vayadhammaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**They don’t truly understand consciousness, which is liable to vanish, as consciousness which is liable to vanish.*";
P_HTM[4342]="*samudayavayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand consciousness, which is liable to originate and vanish, as consciousness which is liable to originate and vanish.*";
P_HTM[4343]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, avijjā;**This is called ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4344]="*ettāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti.**And this is how an ignorant person is defined.”*";
P_HTM[4345]="*Evaṃ vutte, so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, the mendicant said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[4346]="*“‘vijjā, vijjā’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘knowledge’.*";
P_HTM[4347]="*Katamā nu kho, bhante, vijjā;**What is knowledge?*";
P_HTM[4348]="*kittāvatā ca vijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is a knowledgeable person defined?”*";
P_HTM[4349]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, sutavā ariyasāvako samudayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘samudayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**“Mendicant, it’s when an educated noble disciple truly understands form, which is liable to originate, as form which is liable to originate.*";
P_HTM[4350]="*vayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘vayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand form, which is liable to vanish, as form which is liable to vanish.*";
P_HTM[4351]="*samudayavayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand form, which is liable to originate and vanish, as form which is liable to originate and vanish.*";
P_HTM[4352]="*Samudayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ ‘samudayadhammā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[4353]="*vayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ ‘vayadhammā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;* **";
P_HTM[4354]="*samudayavayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[4355]="*Samudayadhammaṃ saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4356]="*samudayadhamme saṅkhāre ‘samudayadhammā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**choices …*";
P_HTM[4357]="*vayadhamme saṅkhāre ‘vayadhammā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;* **";
P_HTM[4358]="*samudayavayadhamme saṅkhāre ‘samudayavayadhammā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[4359]="*Samudayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘samudayadhammaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**consciousness, which is liable to originate, as consciousness which is liable to originate.*";
P_HTM[4360]="*vayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘vayadhammaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand consciousness, which is liable to vanish, as consciousness which is liable to vanish.*";
P_HTM[4361]="*samudayavayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand consciousness, which is liable to originate and vanish, as consciousness which is liable to originate and vanish.*";
P_HTM[4362]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, vijjā;**This is called knowledge.*";
P_HTM[4363]="*ettāvatā ca vijjāgato hotī”ti.**And this is how a knowledgeable person is defined.”*";
P_HTM[4364]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4365]="*2. Dutiyasamudayadhammasuttaṃ**Liable To Originate (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4366]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahākoṭṭhiko bārāṇasiyaṃ viharanti isipatane migadāye.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta and Venerable Mahākoṭṭhita were staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana. …*";
P_HTM[4367]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahākoṭṭhiko sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā mahākoṭṭhiko āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:**Mahākoṭṭhita said to Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[4368]="*“‘avijjā, avijjā’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘ignorance’.*";
P_HTM[4369]="*Katamā nu kho, āvuso, avijjā;**What is ignorance?*";
P_HTM[4370]="*kittāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is an ignorant person defined?”*";
P_HTM[4371]="*“Idhāvuso assutavā puthujjano samudayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘samudayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti; vayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ … pe … ‘samudayavayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**“Reverend, it’s when an uneducated ordinary person doesn’t truly understand form, which is liable to originate … liable to vanish … liable to originate and vanish, as form which is liable to originate and vanish.*";
P_HTM[4372]="*Samudayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ … pe … vayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ … pe … ‘samudayavayadhammā vedanā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**They don’t truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[4373]="*Samudayadhammaṃ saññaṃ … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4374]="*samudayadhamme saṅkhāre … pe … vayadhamme saṅkhāre … pe … samudayavayadhamme saṅkhāre ‘samudayavayadhammā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**choices …*";
P_HTM[4375]="*Samudayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ … pe … samudayavayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**consciousness, which is liable to originate … liable to vanish … liable to originate and vanish, as consciousness which is liable to originate and vanish.*";
P_HTM[4376]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, āvuso, avijjā;**This is called ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4377]="*ettāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti.**And this is how an ignorant person is defined.”*";
P_HTM[4378]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4379]="*3. Tatiyasamudayadhammasuttaṃ**Liable To Originate (3rd)*";
P_HTM[4380]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahākoṭṭhiko bārāṇasiyaṃ viharanti isipatane migadāye … pe …**At one time Venerable Sāriputta and Venerable Mahākoṭṭhita were staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana. …*";
P_HTM[4381]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā mahākoṭṭhiko āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:**Mahākoṭṭhita said to Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[4382]="*“‘vijjā, vijjā’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘knowledge’.*";
P_HTM[4383]="*Katamā nu kho, āvuso, vijjā;**What is knowledge?*";
P_HTM[4384]="*kittāvatā ca vijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is a knowledgeable person defined?”*";
P_HTM[4385]="*“Idhāvuso, sutavā ariyasāvako samudayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘samudayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti; vayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ … pe … samudayavayadhammaṃ rūpaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammaṃ rūpan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**“Reverend, it’s when an educated noble disciple truly understands form, which is liable to originate … liable to vanish … liable to originate and vanish, as form which is liable to originate and vanish.*";
P_HTM[4386]="*samudayadhammaṃ vedanaṃ … pe … samudayavayadhammā vedanā …**They truly understand feeling …*";
P_HTM[4387]="*samudayadhammaṃ saññaṃ … pe …**perception …*";
P_HTM[4388]="*samudayadhamme saṅkhāre … vayadhamme saṅkhāre … samudayavayadhamme saṅkhāre ‘samudayavayadhammā saṅkhārā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**choices …*";
P_HTM[4389]="*Samudayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ … vayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ … samudayavayadhammaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘samudayavayadhammaṃ viññāṇan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**consciousness, which is liable to originate … liable to vanish … liable to originate and vanish, as consciousness which is liable to originate and vanish.*";
P_HTM[4390]="*Ayaṃ vuccatāvuso, vijjā;**This is called knowledge.*";
P_HTM[4391]="*ettāvatā ca vijjāgato hotī”ti.**And this is how a knowledgeable person is defined.”*";
P_HTM[4392]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4393]="*4. Assādasuttaṃ**Gratification*";
P_HTM[4394]="*Bārāṇasiyaṃ viharanti isipatane migadāye … pe …**At Benares.*";
P_HTM[4395]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā mahākoṭṭhiko āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:**Mahākoṭṭhita said to Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[4396]="*“‘avijjā, avijjā’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘ignorance’.*";
P_HTM[4397]="*Katamā nu kho, āvuso, avijjā;**What is ignorance?*";
P_HTM[4398]="*kittāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is an ignorant person defined?”*";
P_HTM[4399]="*“Idhāvuso assutavā puthujjano rūpassa assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**“Reverend, an uneducated ordinary person doesn’t truly understand the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[4400]="*Vedanāya … pe …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[4401]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
P_HTM[4402]="*saṅkhārānaṃ …**choices,*";
P_HTM[4403]="*viññāṇassa assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4404]="*Ayaṃ vuccatāvuso, avijjā;**This is called ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4405]="*ettāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti.**And this is how an ignorant person is defined.”*";
P_HTM[4406]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4407]="*5. Dutiyaassādasuttaṃ**Gratification (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4408]="*Bārāṇasiyaṃ viharanti isipatane migadāye … pe …**At Benares.*";
P_HTM[4409]="*“‘vijja, vijjā’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘knowledge’.*";
P_HTM[4410]="*Katamā nu kho, āvuso, vijjā;**What is knowledge?*";
P_HTM[4411]="*kittāvatā ca vijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is a knowledgeable person defined?”*";
P_HTM[4412]="*“Idhāvuso, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpassa assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**“Reverend, an educated noble disciple truly understands the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[4413]="*Vedanāya … pe …**feeling,*";
P_HTM[4414]="*saññāya …**perception,*";
